    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nAndhra Pradesh is a state located in the southeastern coastal region of India. It has a long coastline along the Bay of Bengal to the east. It is bordered by the states of Tamil Nadu to the south, Karnataka to the west, Telangana to the northwest, Chhattisgarh to the north, and Odisha to the northeast. The enclave of Yanam, part of the union territory of Puducherry, is situated within the state's Godavari delta.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Andhra Pradesh is defined by the Eastern Ghats and the coastal plains along the Bay of Bengal. The Eastern Ghats are a discontinuous range of mountains running parallel to the coast, broken by major river valleys. The highest peak in the state is Arma Konda. The state is drained by two major rivers, the Godavari and the Krishna, which form large, fertile deltas before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. Another significant river is the Penna in the southern part of the state. The coastline stretches for about 974 kilometers, making it the second longest mainland coastline in India after Gujarat. Important natural bodies include Kolleru Lake, one of the largest freshwater lakes in India, and Pulicat Lake, a large brackish water lagoon situated near the border with Tamil Nadu. Protected areas include the Sri Venkateswara National Park and the Papikonda National Park.\n\n## Climate\nAndhra Pradesh experiences a tropical climate, which varies slightly depending on the elevation and distance from the coast. The state has three main seasons: summer, monsoon, and winter. Summers, lasting from March to June, are typically hot and humid, with temperatures frequently exceeding 40 degrees Celsius in the coastal plains. The southwest monsoon brings the majority of the state's rainfall between June and September. The coastal regions also receive significant precipitation from the northeast monsoon between October and December. During this period, coastal areas are vulnerable to cyclones originating in the Bay of Bengal, which bring heavy rains. Winters are mild and pleasant, lasting from December to February.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Andhra Pradesh is primarily driven by agriculture, manufacturing, and information technology. The fertile deltas of the Godavari and Krishna rivers make the state a major producer of rice. Other significant crops include cotton, sugarcane, mangoes, and tobacco. Aquaculture is also a major industry along the coast. Visakhapatnam is the largest city and the commercial hub of the state, featuring a major seaport, a steel plant, and a growing IT sector. Amaravati is the administrative center and the planned capital city, situated on the banks of the Krishna River. Other major cities include Vijayawada, a major trading and transportation hub, and Guntur, known for its chili, cotton, and tobacco exports. Tirupati is a major urban center driven by religious tourism.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a long history, having been ruled by various dynasties including the Satavahanas, the Eastern Chalukyas, the Vijayanagara Empire, and the Qutb Shahis. During the British colonial period, much of the area was part of the Madras Presidency. Andhra Pradesh was formed in 1956 as the first state in India created on a linguistic basis, uniting Telugu-speaking areas. In 2014, the northwestern portion of the state was separated to form the new state of Telangana. Telugu is the official and most widely spoken language. The state is known for its classical dance form, Kuchipudi, and its distinct cuisine, which is characterized by its use of spices and tamarind. The Venkateswara Temple in Tirupati is one of the most visited religious sites in the world.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Amaravati\n* Approximate area: 162,970 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 49,500,000\n* Largest city: Visakhapatnam\n* Signature features: The Eastern Ghats, extensive coastline along the Bay of Bengal, and the Venkateswara Temple in Tirupati",
