    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nBihar is a landlocked state located in the eastern region of India. It shares a significant international border with Nepal to the north. Domestically, it is bordered by the Indian states of Uttar Pradesh to the west, West Bengal to the east, and Jharkhand to the south. The state of Jharkhand was carved out of Bihar's southern territory in the year 2000. Bihar is completely landlocked, and the nearest major seaport is located in Kolkata, West Bengal.\n\n## Physical features\nBihar is primarily a vast, fertile plain divided into two unequal halves by the Ganges River, which flows from west to east through the middle of the state. The North Bihar Plains are drained by several major tributaries originating in the Himalayas, including the Gandak, Koshi, Bagmati, and Kamla rivers. These rivers are prone to shifting their courses and frequently cause severe flooding during the monsoon season. The Koshi River is historically known as the \"Sorrow of Bihar\" due to its devastating floods. The South Bihar Plains are narrower and drained by rivers like the Son, Punpun, and Phalgu, which originate in the central Indian plateaus. The state lacks significant mountain ranges, but the Someshwar Fort range of the Shiwalik Hills touches the northwestern corner in the West Champaran district. Valmiki National Park, located in this northwestern region, is the only national park in the state and serves as a vital tiger reserve.\n\n## Climate\nBihar experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by three distinct seasons. The hot summer season lasts from March to mid-June, with daytime temperatures often exceeding 40 degrees Celsius in May. The southwest monsoon season follows from mid-June to September. This period brings heavy rainfall that sustains the region's agriculture but also triggers widespread flooding in the northern plains. The winter season, from November to February, is generally mild and dry, with nighttime temperatures dropping to around 10 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Bihar is heavily dependent on agriculture, supported by the deep alluvial soils of the Gangetic plain. Farmers primarily cultivate rice, wheat, maize, pulses, and sugarcane. Bihar is also a major producer of fruits like litchi, mango, and guava, with the Muzaffarpur region being particularly famous for its Shahi litchis. Industrial development is relatively limited, a situation exacerbated by the 2000 bifurcation that transferred most of the region's mineral wealth and heavy industry to Jharkhand. Today, industries focus on food processing, dairy, and textiles. Patna is the administrative center and the largest city, situated on the southern bank of the Ganges. Other major cities include Gaya, Bhagalpur, and Muzaffarpur. Bhagalpur is known as the \"Silk City\" due to its traditional tussar silk production.\n\n## History & culture\nBihar has a rich historical legacy as a center of power, learning, and religion in ancient India. It was the seat of the Magadha Empire, which included the Maurya and Gupta dynasties. Ancient Patna, known as Pataliputra, served as the capital of these vast empires. Bihar is the birthplace of both Buddhism and Jainism. Bodh Gaya is the site where Gautama Buddha is said to have attained enlightenment under the Bodhi Tree, and the Mahabodhi Temple complex there is a UNESCO World Heritage site. Lord Mahavira, the twenty-fourth Tirthankara of Jainism, was born in Vaishali. Nalanda and Vikramashila were home to ancient universities that attracted scholars from across Asia. The state is also known for its distinct regional languages, including Bhojpuri, Maithili, and Magahi, as well as traditional art forms like Madhubani painting.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Patna\n* Approximate area: 94,163 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 104 million\n* Signature features: Ganges River plains, birthplace of Buddhism, Mahabodhi Temple, Madhubani art",
