    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nArunachal Pradesh is the northeasternmost state of India. It shares international borders with Bhutan to the west, the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the north and northeast, and Myanmar to the east and southeast. To the south, it borders the Indian states of Assam and Nagaland. The political status of the state is disputed by the People's Republic of China, which claims most of the territory as South Tibet.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Arunachal Pradesh is dominated by the Himalayan mountain system. The terrain is highly rugged, featuring deep river valleys and high peaks. The highest peak in the state is Kangto, which reaches an elevation of roughly 7,060 meters. Along the eastern border with Myanmar lie the Patkai hills, which form a natural barrier. The state is intersected by several major rivers that originate in the Himalayas and flow southward into the Brahmaputra River basin. The Brahmaputra itself enters the state from Tibet, where it is known locally as the Siang or Dihang River. Other significant rivers include the Kameng, Subansiri, Dibang, and Lohit. The region is heavily forested and contains significant biodiversity, protected in areas like Namdapha National Park and Mouling National Park.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Arunachal Pradesh varies significantly with elevation. Low-altitude areas near the Assam border experience a humid subtropical climate, characterized by hot summers and mild winters. As the elevation increases, the climate transitions to a temperate zone. In the highest altitudes of the Greater Himalayas, the state experiences an alpine or tundra climate, where areas remain snow-covered throughout the year. The state receives heavy precipitation during the southwest monsoon season, which lasts from May to September. Annual rainfall averages roughly 2,000 to 5,000 millimeters, making it one of the wettest regions in India.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Arunachal Pradesh is primarily agrarian. Traditional shifting cultivation, known locally as jhum, is widely practiced alongside settled agriculture. Major crops include rice, maize, millet, wheat, pulses, sugarcane, and ginger. The state also produces horticultural crops like apples and oranges. Forestry was historically a major economic driver, but logging is now strictly regulated to preserve the environment. The steep mountainous terrain and abundant water resources give the state significant hydroelectric power potential, leading to the development of several dam projects. Itanagar is the administrative center and the largest city. Other notable urban centers include Pasighat, Tawang, Ziro, and Roing. Tourism is a growing industry, centered around wildlife sanctuaries and cultural heritage sites.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has been historically inhabited by numerous indigenous groups speaking Tibeto-Burman languages. During the British colonial period, the area was administered as the North-East Frontier Agency. Following the Sino-Indian War of 1962, which saw military conflict in the region, the Indian government moved to integrate the area more closely. It was designated as a Union Territory in 1972 and achieved full statehood in 1987. The population is highly diverse, comprising roughly 26 major tribes and over 100 sub-tribes, including the Nyishi, Apatani, Adi, Monpa, and Mishmi. Religious practices are varied, encompassing indigenous faiths such as Donyi-Polo, Tibetan Buddhism, and Christianity. The state is home to the Tawang Monastery, which is the largest Buddhist monastery in India and a major center of Tibetan Buddhism.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Itanagar\n* Approximate area: 83,743 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.38 million\n* Largest city: Itanagar\n* Signature features: Tawang Monastery, Namdapha National Park, the easternmost point of India",
