    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nChhattisgarh is a landlocked state located in the central and eastern part of India. It shares its borders with seven other Indian states. To the northwest lies Madhya Pradesh, the state from which Chhattisgarh was carved out. Uttar Pradesh borders it to the north, while Jharkhand is situated to the northeast. The eastern boundary is shared with Odisha. To the south, Chhattisgarh borders Telangana and a small portion of Andhra Pradesh, and Maharashtra lies to the west. The state occupies a strategic position connecting northern and southern India.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Chhattisgarh is diverse, characterized by plains, plateaus, and extensive forested hills. The central part of the state is dominated by the fertile Mahanadi River basin, which forms a broad plain. The northern region is part of the Chota Nagpur Plateau, featuring rugged terrain and hills. The southern part of the state encompasses the Bastar plateau, which is heavily forested and drained by the Indravati River, a major tributary of the Godavari River. Chhattisgarh has significant forest cover, encompassing roughly forty percent of its total land area. Notable protected areas include Indravati National Park and Kanger Valley National Park, which preserve regional flora and fauna.\n\n## Climate\nChhattisgarh experiences a tropical climate with three primary seasons. The summer season lasts from April to mid-June and is characterized by high temperatures that frequently exceed 40 degrees Celsius. The southwest monsoon arrives in mid-June and lasts until October, bringing the majority of the annual rainfall to the region. The central plains receive moderate rainfall, while the northern and southern hilly regions receive heavier precipitation. The winter season, from November to February, is generally mild and dry, with cooler temperatures prevailing in the elevated northern and southern districts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Chhattisgarh is heavily driven by mining, agriculture, and energy production. The state is exceptionally rich in mineral resources, producing significant quantities of coal, iron ore, bauxite, and dolomite. This mineral wealth supports a large industrial sector, most notably the Bhilai Steel Plant, which is one of the largest steel manufacturing facilities in India. Korba is a major hub for electricity generation, earning the state a reputation as the power hub of the country. Agriculture is also a vital economic activity. The central plains are highly productive for rice cultivation, leading to the region being called the rice bowl of central India. Raipur is the administrative center and largest city, serving as a major commercial and educational hub. Other significant cities include Bhilai, Bilaspur, and Durg.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region that is now Chhattisgarh was historically known as Dakshina Kosala and has been mentioned in ancient Indian texts. For much of its modern history, the area was administered as part of the Central Provinces and Berar under British rule, and later as part of the state of Madhya Pradesh after India gained independence. Chhattisgarh was officially established as an independent state on November 1, 2000, to provide better governance for its distinct cultural and demographic identity. The state has a large indigenous tribal population, particularly in the northern and southern districts. Prominent tribal groups include the Gond, Halba, and Baiga communities. The local culture is noted for its traditional dance forms, such as Panthi and Raut Nacha, as well as unique handicrafts like Bastar Dhokra, a traditional method of bell metal casting.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Raipur\n* Approximate area: 135,192 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 29 million\n* Largest city: Raipur\n* Signature features: Extensive mineral deposits and steel production, large indigenous tribal population, and heavy forest cover.",
