    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nHaryana is a landlocked state situated in the northern region of India. It shares its borders with Punjab and Himachal Pradesh to the north, and Rajasthan to the west and south. The river Yamuna defines its eastern border with Uttar Pradesh. Haryana also surrounds the National Capital Territory of Delhi on three sides, forming its northern, western, and southern boundaries. This proximity to the national capital heavily influences the geographic and economic development of the state.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Haryana consists primarily of the flat, fertile lands of the Indo-Gangetic Plain. The state features two major hill ranges. The Shivalik Hills rise in the northeast, characterized by deciduous forests and uneven terrain. In the south, the residual Aravalli Range appears as scattered, low rocky hills. The Yamuna River is the only major perennial river, flowing along the eastern boundary. The seasonal Ghaggar-Hakra River flows through the northern and western parts of the state. Haryana lacks a coastline. Protected natural areas include Sultanpur National Park, known for migratory bird species, and Kalesar National Park in the Shivalik foothills, which provides habitat for leopards and various avian species.\n\n## Climate\nHaryana experiences a continental climate that ranges from semi-arid in the southwest to sub-humid in the northeast. The state has distinct seasons, including a very hot summer, a monsoon season, and a cool winter. Summer temperatures from April to June frequently exceed forty degrees Celsius. The southwest monsoon arrives in July and lasts through September, delivering the majority of the annual precipitation. The northeastern districts near the Shivalik Hills receive the highest rainfall, while the southwestern areas bordering Rajasthan receive the least. Winters, lasting from November to February, are generally cool and dry, with occasional frost in January.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Haryana relies heavily on both agriculture and manufacturing. It was a primary site for the Green Revolution in India, making it a leading producer of wheat and rice. The state is also highly industrialized. Gurugram is a major financial and technology center, hosting numerous multinational corporations and serving as a hub for the information technology sector. Faridabad is the largest city by population and a significant industrial center known for manufacturing tractors, motorcycles, and auto parts. Panipat is recognized for its textile and carpet industries. Other important urban centers include Rohtak, Hisar, and Ambala.\n\n## History & culture\nHaryana was established as a separate state on November 1, 1966, when it was carved out of the former state of East Punjab based on linguistic lines, separating the Hindi-speaking areas from the Punjabi-speaking regions. The region has deep historical roots, containing several sites of the ancient Indus Valley Civilization, such as Rakhigarhi. It is also the traditional setting for the epic Mahabharata, with the Kurukshetra region identified as the site of its central conflict. The city of Panipat hosted three pivotal battles in 1526, 1556, and 1761 that shaped the course of Indian history. The local culture is deeply tied to its agricultural heritage, with traditional music, dance, and festivals like Teej and Lohri reflecting agrarian cycles. The state is also recognized for producing a large number of successful athletes in wrestling and boxing.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Chandigarh\n* Approximate area: 44,212 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 28,000,000\n* Largest city: Faridabad\n* Signature features: Surrounds Delhi on three sides, historic site of the battles of Panipat, major agricultural and industrial contributor to the Indian economy",
