    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nGujarat is located on the western coast of India. It shares an international border with Pakistan to the northwest. Domestically, it is bordered by the Indian states of Rajasthan to the northeast, Madhya Pradesh to the east, and Maharashtra to the southeast. To the south, it borders the union territory of Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu. The state has a long coastline along the Arabian Sea to the west and southwest, which includes the Gulf of Kutch and the Gulf of Khambhat.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Gujarat is diverse, featuring peninsulas, salt marshes, and river plains. The state is divided into three main geographical regions. The Saurashtra peninsula, also known as Kathiawar, forms a large hilly region in the southwest. The Rann of Kutch, located in the northwest, is a vast seasonal salt marsh that divides into the Great Rann and the Little Rann. The mainland region in the east and south consists of fertile river plains. Major rivers flowing through Gujarat include the Narmada, Tapti, Mahi, and Sabarmati. The Gir Forest National Park, located in the Saurashtra region, is the only natural habitat of the Asiatic lion. The state also features low mountain ranges, including the Aravalli, Vindhya, Satpura, and Sahyadri ranges, which extend into its eastern and southern borders.\n\n## Climate\nGujarat experiences a diverse climate, ranging from arid in the northwest to tropical wet and dry in the south. The state generally has three main seasons: summer, monsoon, and winter. Summers, lasting from March to May, are extremely hot and dry, with temperatures frequently exceeding forty degrees Celsius. The southwest monsoon brings rain from June to September. Rainfall is highly uneven, with the southern districts receiving heavy precipitation while the Kutch region receives very little, making it prone to drought. Winters, from November to February, are mild and dry, providing a comfortable climate across most of the state.\n\n## Economy & cities\nGujarat is one of the most industrialized states in India. Its economy is heavily driven by manufacturing, petroleum refining, chemicals, and pharmaceuticals. The Jamnagar Refinery, operated by Reliance Industries, is the largest oil refinery complex in the world. The state is also a major producer of cotton, groundnuts, and dairy products, being the birthplace of the Amul dairy cooperative. Surat is a global hub for diamond cutting and polishing, as well as a major center for textile manufacturing. Ahmedabad is the largest city and a major commercial hub, historically known for its textile mills. Gandhinagar serves as the administrative center and is a planned city located just north of Ahmedabad. Other significant cities include Vadodara, known for its chemical and engineering industries, and Rajkot, a center for automotive components.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a long history dating back to the Indus Valley Civilization, with significant archaeological sites such as Lothal and Dholavira. Lothal is noted for having one of the world's earliest known docks. Throughout its history, Gujarat was ruled by various dynasties, including the Mauryas, Guptas, Chalukyas, and the Delhi Sultanate, before becoming part of the Mughal Empire and later falling under British colonial rule. The modern state of Gujarat was formed in 1960 when the Bombay State was split along linguistic lines into Gujarat and Maharashtra. Gujarati is the official language and is widely spoken. The state is known for its traditional arts, including Garba and Dandiya Raas folk dances, which are prominently performed during the Navratri festival. It is also the birthplace of Mahatma Gandhi, who led the Indian independence movement.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Gandhinagar\n* Approximate area: 196,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 60 million\n* Largest city: Ahmedabad\n* Signature features: The Rann of Kutch salt marsh, sole home of the Asiatic lion in Gir Forest, and the Jamnagar oil refinery.",
    "summary": "Gujarat is a highly industrialized state on the western coast of India, bordered by Pakistan and the Arabian Sea. It is characterized by diverse physical features including the Saurashtra peninsula, the Rann of Kutch salt marsh, and fertile river plains. The state is a major economic hub known for its petroleum refining, diamond polishing, and historical significance as a center of the Indus Valley Civilization.",
