    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nJharkhand is a landlocked state located in the eastern part of India. It shares its northern border with Bihar, the state from which it was separated in the year 2000. To the east, Jharkhand is bordered by West Bengal. The state of Odisha lies to the south, while Chhattisgarh is situated to the west. Additionally, Jharkhand shares a short border with Uttar Pradesh in its northwest corner.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Jharkhand is defined largely by the Chota Nagpur Plateau, a rugged and forested region that covers most of the state. This plateau is the source of several major rivers, including the Damodar, Subarnarekha, North Koel, and South Koel rivers. The highest point in the state is Parasnath Hill, which reaches an elevation of 1,365 meters and is a prominent pilgrimage site. The state lacks a coastline. Much of the land is covered by dense forests, which support diverse wildlife. Betla National Park and Dalma Wildlife Sanctuary are notable protected areas that house elephants, tigers, and various deer species. Jharkhand is particularly famous for its vast mineral reserves. The region contains significant deposits of coal, iron ore, copper, uranium, mica, and bauxite.\n\n## Climate\nJharkhand experiences a tropical climate with three distinct seasons. The summer season begins in March and lasts until mid-June, bringing hot and dry conditions. During this time, maximum temperatures frequently exceed 35 degrees Celsius and can reach up to 40 degrees Celsius in the lower plains. The southwest monsoon arrives in June and continues through October, providing the majority of the annual rainfall. The winter season runs from November to February. Winters are generally cool and pleasant, with average temperatures dropping to about 10 degrees Celsius, though higher elevations on the plateau can experience colder nights.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Jharkhand is heavily dependent on mining and heavy industry, driven by its abundant mineral resources. The state is one of the leading producers of coal and iron ore in India. Major industrial centers include Jamshedpur, which is home to one of the largest steel plants in the country operated by Tata Steel. Bokaro Steel City is another major industrial hub, while Dhanbad is widely recognized as the coal capital of India. Ranchi serves as the administrative center and has a growing sector in manufacturing and information technology. Outside the urban industrial zones, a large portion of the population relies on agriculture, with rice being the primary crop cultivated during the monsoon season.\n\n## History & culture\nJharkhand was established as a separate state on November 15, 2000, following a prolonged movement to carve out the tribal-dominated southern districts of Bihar. The state has a rich cultural heritage shaped by its large indigenous population, collectively known as Adivasis. Major tribal groups include the Santhal, Munda, Oraon, and Ho communities. Hindi is the official language, but numerous regional and tribal languages are spoken, including Santali, Bengali, Urdu, Mundari, and Kurukh. Traditional festivals such as Sarhul, which celebrates the spring season and the Sal tree, and Karma, an agricultural festival, are central to the local culture. The region is also known for its traditional folk dances, metal crafts, and ancient rock art.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Ranchi\n* Approximate area: 79,710 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 33 million\n* Largest city: Jamshedpur\n* Signature features: The mineral-rich Chota Nagpur Plateau, extensive coal and steel industries, and a strong Adivasi cultural heritage.",
    "summary": "Jharkhand is a landlocked state in eastern India, situated primarily on the mineral-rich Chota Nagpur Plateau. Carved out of southern Bihar in 2000, it is heavily industrialized with major steel and coal centers like Jamshedpur and Dhanbad. The state is also defined by its extensive forests and the rich cultural heritage of its indigenous Adivasi communities.",
