    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nHimachal Pradesh is a state located in the northern part of India, situated primarily within the western Himalayas. It shares borders with the union territories of Jammu and Kashmir and Ladakh to the north. To the west, it is bordered by the state of Punjab, while Haryana lies to the southwest. Uttarakhand is located to the southeast, and a very small border is shared with Uttar Pradesh to the south. Additionally, Himachal Pradesh shares an international border with the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the east.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is defined by its rugged, mountainous terrain. The elevation increases from west to east and from south to north. The landscape is divided into three main topographical regions. The Shivalik range forms the southern foothills. The lesser Himalayas occupy the central region, and the Great Himalayas and Zanskar range dominate the northern and eastern sections. Reo Purgyil is the highest mountain peak in the state. Five major rivers flow through the region, which are the Chenab, Ravi, Beas, Sutlej, and Yamuna. These rivers are fed by snowmelt and glaciers. The state also features high-altitude lakes such as Chandra Taal and Prashar Lake. Protected areas include the Great Himalayan National Park, which is a UNESCO World Heritage site, and Pin Valley National Park.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Himachal Pradesh varies significantly depending on the elevation. The southern low tracts experience a subtropical climate with hot summers and mild winters. The mid-elevation areas, including cities like Shimla, have a temperate climate with warm summers and cool, snowy winters. The high northern and eastern mountains experience a cold alpine and glacial climate, remaining under snow for much of the year. The state receives heavy monsoon rains from July to September. However, the trans-Himalayan districts of Lahaul and Spiti lie in a rain shadow, resulting in a cold desert environment that receives very little precipitation.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAgriculture and horticulture form the backbone of the local economy. Himachal Pradesh is widely known for its large-scale apple production, alongside the cultivation of stone fruits, wheat, and maize. Hydroelectric power is another major industry, as the state utilizes its fast-flowing rivers to generate electricity that is exported to neighboring states. Tourism is a vital economic driver, drawing visitors to hill stations like Shimla, Manali, Dalhousie, and Dharamshala. Shimla serves as the administrative center and the largest city. Other notable urban centers include Solan, Mandi, and Kullu. Industrial manufacturing, particularly pharmaceuticals, is concentrated in border towns like Baddi.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has been inhabited since prehistoric times by various indigenous tribes. Historically, the area was divided into numerous small princely states ruled by local chieftains and Rajput kings. In the early nineteenth century, the Gurkha kingdom expanded into the region, which eventually led to the Anglo-Gurkha War. The British East India Company defeated the Gurkhas and took control of the hill states. Shimla later became the summer capital of British India. Following Indian independence in 1947, the region was organized as a Chief Commissioner's Province, later becoming a Union Territory. Himachal Pradesh achieved full statehood in 1971. The culture is a blend of Hindu traditions and Tibetan Buddhism. Dharamshala is notable for hosting the Dalai Lama and the headquarters of the Central Tibetan Administration.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Shimla (summer), Dharamshala (winter)\n* Approximate area: 55,673 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 6.8 million\n* Largest city: Shimla\n* Signature features: Himalayan hill stations, extensive apple orchards, Tibetan Buddhist centers in Dharamshala",
