    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nKarnataka is located in the southwestern region of India. It is bordered by the Arabian Sea to the west, Goa to the northwest, Maharashtra to the north, Telangana to the northeast, Andhra Pradesh to the east, Tamil Nadu to the southeast, and Kerala to the south. It is the largest state in South India by area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is divided into three primary geographic zones. The coastal region, known as Karavali, runs along the Arabian Sea. The hilly Malenadu region comprises the Western Ghats, a mountain range that runs parallel to the coast and is recognized for its high biodiversity. The highest peak in Karnataka is Mullayanagiri, located in the Baba Budan Giri range of the Western Ghats. To the east of the Western Ghats lies the Bayalu Seeme region, which is a vast, undulating plateau that forms part of the larger Deccan Plateau. Major rivers include the Krishna and its tributaries in the north, and the Kaveri in the south. Both rivers flow eastward into the Bay of Bengal. The state also features notable waterfalls, such as Jog Falls on the Sharavati River. Prominent national parks include Bandipur and Nagarhole, which are significant habitats for tigers and Asian elephants.\n\n## Climate\nKarnataka experiences a tropical climate with distinct seasons. The year is divided into the summer season from March to May, the monsoon season from June to September, and the winter season from October to February. The coastal and Malenadu regions receive heavy rainfall during the southwest monsoon, often exceeding thousands of millimeters annually. In contrast, the eastern plateau region, or Bayalu Seeme, is semi-arid and receives significantly less precipitation, making it prone to droughts. Temperatures vary by elevation and region, with the coastal plains remaining hot and humid year-round, while the elevated plateau and Western Ghats experience milder, more temperate conditions.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Karnataka is one of the largest in India, driven by a mix of agriculture, manufacturing, and services. The state is a major hub for the information technology sector, biotechnology, and aerospace industries. Bengaluru, the administrative center and largest city, is often referred to as the Silicon Valley of India due to its concentration of technology companies and research institutions. Other major cities include Mysuru, known for tourism and traditional industries, Mangaluru, a major port city on the Arabian Sea, and Hubballi-Dharwad, a commercial and industrial center in the northern part of the state. Agriculture remains a vital sector, with Karnataka being the largest producer of coffee, raw silk, and sandalwood in India.\n\n## History & culture\nKarnataka has a long history, having been ruled by several prominent ancient and medieval empires. The Chalukya, Rashtrakuta, and Hoysala dynasties left significant architectural legacies, including the rock-cut temples of Badami and the stone temples of Belur and Halebidu. The Vijayanagara Empire, which peaked in the sixteenth century, established its capital at Hampi, the ruins of which are now a UNESCO World Heritage site. The region was later governed by the Wadiyar dynasty of the Kingdom of Mysore, as well as by Hyder Ali and Tipu Sultan, before coming under British suzerainty. The official language is Kannada, a Dravidian language with an extensive literary tradition. The state is also known for Carnatic music and traditional dance forms like Yakshagana.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Bengaluru\n* Approximate area: 191,791 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 61 million\n* Signature features: Information technology hub, Western Ghats biodiversity, ruins of Hampi",
    "summary": "Karnataka is a southwestern Indian state known for its diverse geography, ranging from the Arabian Sea coastline and the biodiverse Western Ghats to the semi-arid Deccan Plateau. Its economy is driven by a mix of agriculture, particularly coffee and silk production, and a massive information technology sector centered in Bengaluru. The state also features a rich cultural heritage highlighted by the Kannada language and historic sites like the ruins of Hampi.",
