    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nMadhya Pradesh is a landlocked state located in central India. Its name translates to \"Central Province\" in Hindi. It shares borders with five other Indian states. To the northeast lies Uttar Pradesh, while Chhattisgarh is situated to the southeast. Maharashtra borders the state to the south, Gujarat to the west, and Rajasthan to the northwest. Prior to the year 2000, Madhya Pradesh was the largest state in India by area, but it became the second largest after the southeastern portion was separated to form the new state of Chhattisgarh.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Madhya Pradesh is defined by plateaus, mountain ranges, and major river basins. The state is primarily situated on the Malwa Plateau in the west and the Bundelkhand region in the north. Two prominent mountain ranges, the Vindhya Range and the Satpura Range, run east to west through the state. These ranges act as a divide between northern and southern India. The Narmada River flows westward between the Vindhya and Satpura ranges, eventually emptying into the Arabian Sea. Other significant rivers include the Tapti, which also flows west, and the Chambal, Son, and Betwa rivers, which flow north to join the Ganges and Yamuna river systems. The state contains extensive forest cover, housing several national parks such as Kanha National Park, Bandhavgarh National Park, and Pench National Park, which are known for their Bengal tiger populations.\n\n## Climate\nMadhya Pradesh experiences a subtropical climate with three distinct seasons. The summer season lasts from March to June and is characterized by hot and dry conditions, with temperatures often exceeding forty degrees Celsius in May. The monsoon season begins in June and continues through September, bringing the majority of the annual rainfall to the state. The southwestern monsoon winds deliver heavier precipitation to the eastern and southern parts of the state, while the western and northern regions receive less rain. The winter season runs from November to February, offering cool and dry weather, with average temperatures ranging from ten to twenty-five degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Madhya Pradesh relies heavily on agriculture, mining, and manufacturing. The state is a major producer of soybeans, wheat, pulses, and garlic. It also possesses substantial mineral reserves, including diamonds, copper, and coal. The Panna district is particularly noted for its diamond mines. Industrial sectors include textiles, automobiles, and pharmaceuticals. Bhopal serves as the administrative center and is known for its lakes and the tragic 1984 gas leak incident. Indore is the largest city and the commercial hub of the state, recognized for its cleanliness and food processing industries. Other major cities include Gwalior, noted for its historic fort, and Jabalpur, an important military and industrial center located near the Narmada River.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a long history of human habitation, evidenced by the prehistoric rock shelters at Bhimbetka, which feature ancient cave paintings. Throughout history, the area was ruled by various dynasties, including the Mauryas, Guptas, and Marathas. During the British colonial period, the region was administered as the Central Provinces and Berar, along with several princely states. Madhya Pradesh is home to diverse cultural traditions and a large indigenous tribal population, including the Bhil and Gond communities. The state contains three UNESCO World Heritage sites. These are the Khajuraho Group of Monuments, famous for their intricate sculptures, the Buddhist Monuments at Sanchi, and the Rock Shelters of Bhimbetka.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Bhopal\n* Approximate area: 308,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 72 million\n* Largest city: Indore\n* Signature features: Extensive tiger reserves, Khajuraho temples, Narmada River valley",
    "summary": "Madhya Pradesh is a large, landlocked state in central India known for its extensive forests, tiger reserves, and historical sites. Its geography is defined by the Vindhya and Satpura mountain ranges and the westward-flowing Narmada River. The state has an agriculture- and mining-based economy, with Bhopal serving as its administrative center and Indore as its commercial hub.",
