    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nMizoram is a landlocked state located in the northeastern region of India. It shares international borders with Myanmar to the east and south, and Bangladesh to the west. Domestically, it is bordered by the Indian states of Tripura to the northwest, Assam to the north, and Manipur to the northeast. It is one of the \"Seven Sister States\" of northeastern India.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Mizoram is dominated by rolling hills, steep terrain, and deep river valleys. The state is part of the Patkai range system. The highest peak is Phawngpui, also known as the Blue Mountain, which reaches an elevation of roughly 2,157 meters. The state is drained by several rivers that flow either northward into the Barak River system or southward. Major rivers include the Tlawng, Tuirial, and the Kaladan, which is known locally as the Chhimtuipui. Natural lakes include Palak Dil, the largest lake in the state. Protected areas include Murlen National Park and Phawngpui National Park, which preserve the region's rich biodiversity and dense bamboo forests.\n\n## Climate\nMizoram experiences a mild, subtropical climate. Temperatures remain relatively moderate throughout the year, avoiding the extreme heat found in other parts of India. Winter temperatures generally range from 11 to 21 degrees Celsius, while summer temperatures hover between 20 and 30 degrees Celsius. The state receives heavy rainfall during the southwest monsoon season, which typically lasts from May to September. This abundant precipitation supports dense vegetation but can also trigger landslides in the steep hilly areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mizoram is primarily agrarian. A significant portion of the population relies on agriculture, with traditional slash-and-burn farming, known as jhum cultivation, still practiced alongside more settled horticulture. Key agricultural products include bamboo, ginger, mustard, sesame, and various fruits. Sericulture, or silk production, is also an important rural industry. The industrial sector is small and largely focused on handloom textiles, handicrafts, and agro-processing. Aizawl is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the commercial and cultural hub of the state. Other notable urban centers include Lunglei in the south, Champhai near the Myanmar border, and Kolasib in the north.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was historically inhabited by various Mizo tribes who migrated into the area over several centuries. During the late nineteenth century, the British annexed the territory, administering it as the Lushai Hills district of Assam. Following India's independence, the Mizo National Front led a movement for self-determination. This culminated in the Mizoram Peace Accord of 1986. Consequently, Mizoram was elevated from a Union Territory to a full state of India in 1987. The culture is deeply rooted in tribal traditions and community life. The majority of the population practices Christianity, a result of missionary work in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. Mizoram is known for its high literacy rate and traditional arts, most notably the Cheraw, a rhythmic dance performed using bamboo staves.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Aizawl\n* Approximate area: 21,081 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.1 million\n* Largest city: Aizawl\n* Signature features: High literacy rate, dense bamboo forests, and the traditional Cheraw bamboo dance.",
    "summary": "Mizoram is a hilly, landlocked state in northeastern India known for its dense bamboo forests and high literacy rate. Its economy is largely agricultural, and its administrative center and largest city is Aizawl. The state shares international borders with Myanmar and Bangladesh and became a full Indian state in 1987 following a historic peace accord.",
