    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nManipur is a state located in the northeastern region of India. It is one of the Seven Sister States of the northeast. The state shares domestic borders with Nagaland to the north, Assam to the west, and Mizoram to the south. To the east and south, Manipur shares an international border with Myanmar, specifically abutting the Sagaing Region and Chin State.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Manipur is distinctly divided into two main regions, which are the central Imphal Valley and the rugged hills that surround it. The Imphal Valley accounts for roughly ten percent of the total land area but accommodates the vast majority of the population. The surrounding hills are part of the Patkai and Arakan mountain ranges. Mount Tenapu, also known as Mount Iso, is the highest peak in the state.\n\nThe state features several important river systems. The Barak River originates in the northern hills and flows westward into Assam. The Manipur River flows southward through the central valley and eventually enters Myanmar. A prominent geographical feature in the central valley is Loktak Lake. It is the largest freshwater lake in northeastern India and is recognized for its phumdis, which are floating islands of decomposing plant matter and soil. Keibul Lamjao National Park is situated on these phumdis and serves as the only floating national park in the world. This park is the last natural refuge of the endangered sangai, a subspecies of brow-antlered deer.\n\n## Climate\nManipur experiences a climate that ranges from subtropical to temperate, largely depending on elevation. The central valley has a relatively moderate climate, while the surrounding hill regions are noticeably cooler. The state receives substantial rainfall from the southwest monsoon, with the wettest months occurring between May and October. Winters are generally dry and cool, and frost can occur in the higher elevations. Summers are warm, but extreme heat is rare due to the altitude and frequent monsoon precipitation.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Manipur is primarily agrarian. Agriculture and forestry provide the main sources of livelihood for the population. Rice is the staple crop and is cultivated extensively throughout the Imphal Valley. Farmers also grow maize, pulses, sugarcane, and mustard. Handlooms and handicrafts represent significant cottage industries, producing traditional textiles and bamboo products.\n\nImphal is the administrative center and the largest city in the state. It functions as the primary commercial, educational, and cultural hub. Other notable urban centers include Churachandpur, Thoubal, Kakching, and Ukhrul. Large-scale industrial development is limited by the remote location and rugged terrain. However, cross-border trade with Myanmar through the border town of Moreh is an important component of the local economy.\n\n## History & culture\nManipur existed as an independent kingdom for centuries before becoming a princely state under British paramountcy in 1891. During World War II, it was the site of major military engagements. The Battle of Imphal in 1944 was a turning point where British and Indian forces stopped the Japanese advance into the Indian subcontinent. After India gained independence, Manipur was integrated into the Republic of India in 1949 and achieved full statehood in 1972.\n\nThe population of Manipur is ethnically diverse. The Meitei people form the majority and primarily live in the Imphal Valley. The surrounding hills are inhabited by various indigenous tribes, predominantly belonging to the Naga and Kuki-Zo groups. Manipuri, also known as Meiteilon, is the official language and serves as a lingua franca across different communities.\n\nThe state has a rich cultural heritage. It is the birthplace of Manipuri dance, which is one of the major classical dance forms of India, characterized by gentle movements and Vaishnavite themes. Additionally, the region is credited with the origin of modern polo, a sport derived from the traditional local game known as sagol kangjei.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Imphal\n* Approximate area: 22,327 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.8 million\n* Largest city: Imphal\n* Signature features: Loktak Lake and its floating phumdis, origin of modern polo, Manipuri classical dance",
    "summary": "Manipur is a state in northeastern India characterized by its central Imphal Valley surrounded by rugged mountain ranges. Its economy is largely agrarian, supplemented by traditional handlooms and cross-border trade with neighboring Myanmar. The state is noted for its rich cultural heritage, including Manipuri classical dance, the origin of modern polo, and the unique floating islands of Loktak Lake.",
