    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nRajasthan is located in the northwestern part of India. It is the largest state in the country by total area. The state shares an international border with Pakistan to the west and northwest, specifically abutting the provinces of Sindh and Punjab. Domestically, Rajasthan is bordered by the Indian states of Punjab to the north, Haryana and Uttar Pradesh to the northeast, Madhya Pradesh to the southeast, and Gujarat to the southwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Rajasthan is largely defined by the Thar Desert and the Aravalli Range. The Aravalli Range runs diagonally across the state from the southwest to the northeast, effectively dividing Rajasthan into two distinct geographic zones. The region to the west and northwest of the Aravallis is predominantly arid and encompasses the Thar Desert, also known as the Great Indian Desert. This area features shifting sand dunes and sparse vegetation. The Luni River is the only significant river in this western expanse, eventually draining into the Rann of Kutch in neighboring Gujarat.\n\nEast and southeast of the Aravalli Range, the terrain is more fertile and features broader river valleys. The Chambal River, along with its major tributary the Banas River, drains this eastern region. Rajasthan also contains several important wildlife reserves. Ranthambore National Park is a prominent tiger reserve, and Keoladeo National Park is a major wetland habitat for migratory birds.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Rajasthan ranges from arid to semi-arid. The western desert regions experience extreme temperature fluctuations. Summer temperatures frequently exceed 45 degrees Celsius, while winter nights can drop to near freezing. Rainfall in the west is minimal and highly erratic. The eastern and southeastern regions experience a slightly milder climate and receive more consistent precipitation. Most of the state's rainfall occurs during the southwest monsoon season, which lasts from July to September.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Rajasthan relies heavily on agriculture, mining, and tourism. Despite water scarcity, farmers cultivate crops such as wheat, barley, pulses, cotton, and oilseeds. The Indira Gandhi Canal provides essential irrigation to the northwestern desert districts, supporting agricultural output. Rajasthan is also rich in mineral resources, leading the country in the production of zinc, copper, marble, and limestone.\n\nTourism is a major economic sector, driven by the state's historical architecture and wildlife. Jaipur is the administrative center and largest city, widely recognized for its pink-hued historical buildings. Other major urban centers include Jodhpur, Udaipur, Kota, and Bikaner. Kota serves as a significant industrial and educational center situated along the banks of the Chambal River.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically referred to as Rajputana, the region was governed for centuries by various Rajput clans. These rulers constructed massive hill forts and palaces, many of which are now designated as UNESCO World Heritage sites. Throughout its history, the region experienced periods of conflict and strategic alliances with the Delhi Sultanate, the Mughal Empire, and the British East India Company. Following India's independence in 1947, the numerous princely states of Rajputana were gradually integrated to form the modern state of Rajasthan. The local culture is characterized by distinct folk music, traditional dances such as the Ghoomar, and the production of brightly colored textiles and handicrafts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Jaipur\n* Approximate area: 342,239 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: roughly 68 million to 80 million\n* Largest city: Jaipur\n* Signature features: Thar Desert, Aravalli Range, historic Rajput hill forts, Ranthambore National Park",
    "summary": "Rajasthan is India's largest state by area, located in the northwestern part of the country along the border with Pakistan. Its geography is defined by the arid Thar Desert in the west and the Aravalli Range, which separates the desert from the more fertile eastern river valleys. The state has a diverse economy driven by agriculture, mining, and a robust tourism industry centered around its historic Rajput forts and palaces.",
