    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nTripura is a state located in the northeastern part of India. It is almost entirely surrounded by the neighboring country of Bangladesh, which borders it to the north, south, and west. To the east, Tripura shares domestic borders with the Indian states of Assam and Mizoram. It is a landlocked state and is geographically isolated from the rest of India, connected only by a narrow strip of land through Assam.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Tripura is characterized by a series of parallel hill ranges running from north to south, alternating with narrow valleys. The major hill ranges include the Boromura, Atharamura, Longtharai, Shakhan, and Jampui hills. The highest point in the state is Betling Shib, located in the Jampui hill range. Several rivers originate in these hills and flow outward into Bangladesh. The major rivers include the Gomati, Manu, Khowai, and Haora. The state has significant forest cover, featuring tropical evergreen and moist deciduous forests. Protected areas include the Clouded Leopard National Park and the Rajbari National Park, which support diverse flora and fauna.\n\n## Climate\nTripura experiences a tropical savanna climate, characterized by distinct seasons including a warm summer, a heavy monsoon period, and a mild winter. The monsoon season lasts from June to September and brings heavy rainfall to the region, which often leads to flooding in the river valleys. Humidity remains high throughout the year. Temperatures during the summer months can reach roughly 35 degrees Celsius, while winter temperatures typically range between 10 and 20 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Tripura is primarily agrarian. Rice is the major crop, cultivated extensively in the plains and valleys. The state is also a major producer of natural rubber, ranking second in India behind Kerala. Other significant agricultural products include tea, pineapples, and jackfruit. The industrial sector is relatively small, focusing on brick manufacturing, tea processing, and traditional cottage industries like bamboo and cane handicrafts. Tripura also has significant reserves of natural gas, which are utilized for power generation. Agartala is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the commercial and cultural hub. Other notable urban centers include Udaipur, Dharmanagar, and Kailashahar.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore its integration into the Republic of India, the region was the independent Twipra Kingdom, ruled for centuries by the Manikya dynasty. The princely state officially merged with India in 1949 and was designated as a full state in 1972. The population is diverse, comprising a majority of Bengali people alongside numerous indigenous communities, the largest being the Tripuri people. Kokborok and Bengali are the official languages. The cultural heritage of the state is visible in its historical architecture and archaeological sites. Notable landmarks include the Ujjayanta Palace in Agartala, the Neermahal water palace situated in the middle of Lake Rudrasagar, and the ancient rock carvings at Unakoti.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Agartala\n* Approximate area: 10,491 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.6 million\n* Largest city: Agartala\n* Signature features: Extensive bamboo and cane handicrafts, Neermahal water palace, second-largest natural rubber producer in India",
    "summary": "Tripura is a landlocked state in northeastern India that is almost entirely surrounded by Bangladesh. Its geography features parallel north-to-south hill ranges, river valleys, and a tropical savanna climate that supports significant natural rubber and agricultural production. Formerly an independent kingdom ruled by the Manikya dynasty, the state is now known for its diverse Bengali and indigenous cultures, as well as landmarks like the Neermahal water palace.",
