    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nTelangana is a landlocked state located in the south-central region of India, situated on the high Deccan Plateau. It serves as a geographic and cultural bridge between North and South India. The state shares its borders with Maharashtra to the north and northwest, Chhattisgarh to the northeast, Karnataka to the west, and Andhra Pradesh to the south and east. Telangana was carved out of the northwestern part of Andhra Pradesh in 2014, making it the youngest state in the Republic of India at the time of its formation.\n\n## Physical features\nSituated entirely on the Deccan Plateau, the terrain of Telangana consists mostly of hills, mountain ranges, and thick forests. The average elevation of the plateau in this region ranges from about 400 to 600 meters above sea level. The state is drained by two major rivers, the Godavari and the Krishna, which flow from west to east. The Godavari flows through the northern districts, while the Krishna forms parts of the southern border. Other notable rivers include the Musi River, which flows through Hyderabad, as well as the Manjira and Tungabhadra rivers. The region features red sandy soils and black soils, which support various types of vegetation. Telangana is home to several protected areas, including the Kawal Tiger Reserve, the Amrabad Tiger Reserve, and the Kasu Brahmananda Reddy National Park. Man-made lakes, such as Hussain Sagar and Osman Sagar, are also prominent features of the landscape.\n\n## Climate\nTelangana experiences a semi-arid climate characterized by predominantly hot and dry conditions. The state has three main seasons: summer from March to May, the southwest monsoon from June to September, and winter from October to February. Summers are extremely hot, with daytime temperatures frequently exceeding 40 degrees Celsius. The southwest monsoon brings the majority of the state's annual rainfall, which averages about 700 to 900 millimeters. Because Telangana is located in the rain shadow of the Western Ghats, it is historically prone to dry spells and droughts. Winters are generally mild, dry, and pleasant, with temperatures rarely dropping below 15 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Telangana is driven by agriculture, information technology, and pharmaceuticals. Hyderabad is a major global hub for the IT industry and hosts numerous multinational technology companies in its HITEC City district. The city is also a center for biotechnology and pharmaceuticals, anchored by the Genome Valley research cluster. Agriculture relies heavily on irrigation from the Godavari and Krishna rivers. The Kaleshwaram Lift Irrigation Project, a massive infrastructure initiative on the Godavari River, provides water for farming and drinking. Major crops include cotton, rice, maize, and mangoes. Mining is another crucial sector, with the Singareni Collieries Company extracting coal in the Godavari river basin. Hyderabad is the administrative center and the largest city. Other significant urban centers include Warangal, Nizamabad, Karimnagar, and Khammam.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a rich history, having been ruled by major powers such as the Satavahanas, the Kakatiyas, the Delhi Sultanate, the Bahmani Sultanate, and the Golconda Sultanate. The Kakatiya dynasty left a lasting legacy through its architecture, including the Ramappa Temple, which is a recognized World Heritage site. In the 18th century, the region became part of the princely state of Hyderabad under the Nizams, who ruled until India gained independence. The princely state was integrated into India in 1948. Telangana was merged with Andhra State in 1956 to form Andhra Pradesh. Following a prolonged regional movement citing economic and cultural marginalization, Telangana was officially formed as a separate state on June 2, 2014. The local culture is a blend of Persian traditions introduced by the Nizams and South Indian Telugu traditions. Telugu and Urdu are the principal languages. The state is known for unique regional festivals such as Bathukamma and Bonalu.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Hyderabad\n* Approximate area: 112,077 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 35 million\n* Largest city: Hyderabad\n* Signature features: Charminar monument, Golconda Fort, HITEC City technology hub",
