    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nUttar Pradesh is a landlocked state located in the northern region of India. It shares an international border with Nepal to the north. Within India, it is bordered by the state of Uttarakhand to the northwest, which was carved out of Uttar Pradesh in the year 2000. It also shares borders with Himachal Pradesh to the northwest, Haryana, Rajasthan, and the National Capital Territory of Delhi to the west. To the south, it is bounded by Madhya Pradesh, while Chhattisgarh and Jharkhand lie to the southeast. The state of Bihar borders Uttar Pradesh to the east.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Uttar Pradesh is dominated by the vast Indo-Gangetic Plain, which covers the majority of the state. This plain is characterized by highly fertile alluvial soils deposited by the river systems. The northernmost edge of the state transitions into the Bhabar and Terai regions, which are marshy and forested foothills of the Himalayas. In the south, the landscape rises into the Vindhya Range and the Bundelkhand plateau, featuring older, harder rock formations and more rugged terrain.\n\nThe state is defined by its extensive river network. The Ganges and the Yamuna are the most prominent rivers, flowing from the northwest to the southeast. They meet at the Triveni Sangam in the city of Prayagraj. Other significant rivers include the Gomti, the Ghaghara, the Betwa, and the Ken. Dudhwa National Park, located in the Terai region, is the primary protected wildlife reserve in the state, known for its populations of Bengal tigers and swamp deer.\n\n## Climate\nUttar Pradesh experiences a humid subtropical climate with three distinct seasons. The summer season lasts from March to May and is characterized by extreme heat, with temperatures frequently exceeding 40 degrees Celsius. Dry, hot winds known as the Loo blow across the plains during this time. The southwest monsoon arrives in June and lasts through September, bringing the majority of the annual precipitation. The eastern parts of the state generally receive more rainfall than the western regions. The winter season, from December to February, is cool and dry, with temperatures occasionally dropping below 5 degrees Celsius in the northern and western districts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Uttar Pradesh is heavily reliant on agriculture. The fertile plains make it one of the largest producers of food grains in India. Major crops include wheat, rice, sugarcane, potatoes, and lentils. The state also has a significant industrial sector. Kanpur is a major center for the leather and textile industries. Sugar processing is a widespread industry throughout the agricultural belts. The western region, particularly the cities of Noida and Greater Noida, has developed into a major hub for information technology, electronics, and manufacturing due to its proximity to Delhi. Lucknow serves as the administrative center and is a major hub for commerce and governance. Other important cities include Agra, Varanasi, Meerut, and Prayagraj.\n\n## History & culture\nUttar Pradesh has been a central region in the history of the Indian subcontinent. It was a focal point for ancient Vedic culture and the site of several powerful ancient empires, including the Mauryan and Gupta dynasties. The state contains Sarnath, the location where the Buddha delivered his first sermon. During the medieval period, the region was ruled by the Delhi Sultanate and the Mughal Empire, which left a lasting architectural legacy. Under British rule, the region was administered as the United Provinces.\n\nThe state is a major center for Indian arts, including classical Hindustani music and the Kathak dance form. It is also famous for Awadhi cuisine. Varanasi, situated on the banks of the Ganges, is one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world and a central pilgrimage site for Hindus. Agra is globally recognized as the home of the Taj Mahal, a UNESCO World Heritage site constructed by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Lucknow\n* Approximate area: 240,928 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 240 million\n* Signature features: Home to the Taj Mahal in Agra, the ancient city of Varanasi, and the confluence of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers.",
