    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nUttarakhand is a state located in the northern part of India. It shares international borders with the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the north and Nepal to the east. Within India, it is bordered by the state of Uttar Pradesh to the south and Himachal Pradesh to the west and northwest. The state occupies a strategic position along the Himalayan mountain range. There is a localized territorial dispute with Nepal regarding the Kalapani region in the easternmost part of the state, which both nations claim and map as their own territory.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Uttarakhand is dominated by the Himalayas. The state is traditionally divided into two mountainous regions known as the Garhwal Himalayas in the west and the Kumaon Himalayas in the east. Nanda Devi is the highest peak in the state and the second highest mountain located entirely within India, reaching an elevation of about 7,816 meters. The state contains the sources of two of India's major rivers. The Gangotri Glacier feeds the Bhagirathi River, which joins the Alaknanda River to form the Ganges. The Yamunotri Glacier is the source of the Yamuna River. The southern edge of the state transitions into the Bhabar and Terai regions, which are lower foothills and plains. Notable protected areas include Jim Corbett National Park, which is known for its Bengal tiger population, and the Valley of Flowers National Park, an alpine valley recognized for its endemic flora.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Uttarakhand varies significantly depending on the elevation. The southern plains and lower foothills experience a subtropical climate with hot summers and mild winters. As the elevation increases into the middle Himalayas, the climate becomes temperate, featuring warm summers and cold winters with regular snowfall. The highest peaks remain covered in snow year-round and experience a harsh alpine climate. The state receives the majority of its annual precipitation during the southwest monsoon season, which lasts from July to September. This heavy rainfall frequently causes landslides and floods in the steep mountain valleys.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Uttarakhand relies heavily on tourism, agriculture, and hydroelectric power. Tourism is driven by both ecological destinations and religious pilgrimage sites. Agriculture is concentrated in the southern plains and terraced mountain slopes, producing crops such as wheat, basmati rice, soybeans, and apples. The state also generates significant hydroelectricity, utilizing infrastructure like the Tehri Dam on the Bhagirathi River. Dehradun serves as the winter capital and administrative center, while Gairsain was designated as the summer capital in 2020. Other major cities include Haridwar and Rishikesh, which are prominent religious centers along the Ganges, as well as Roorkee, known for its engineering institutions, and Haldwani in the Kumaon region.\n\n## History & culture\nUttarakhand was established as the twenty-seventh state of India on November 9, 2000. It was created by separating the northwestern mountainous districts from the state of Uttar Pradesh. The state was originally named Uttaranchal, but the name was officially changed to Uttarakhand in 2007 to reflect the historical name of the region. The culture is heavily influenced by Hindu traditions, and the state is often referred to as the Land of the Gods due to its numerous temples. The population is primarily composed of Garhwali and Kumaoni communities, each with distinct dialects, music, and festivals.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Dehradun (winter) and Gairsain (summer)\n* Approximate area: 53,483 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 10.1 million\n* Largest city: Dehradun\n* Signature features: Source of the Ganges and Yamuna rivers, Char Dham Hindu pilgrimage sites, and Nanda Devi mountain peak.",
