    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nTamil Nadu is located in the southernmost part of the Indian subcontinent. It is bordered by the Indian Ocean to the south, the Bay of Bengal to the east, and the Arabian Sea to the southwest. It shares domestic land borders with the states of Kerala to the west, Karnataka to the northwest, and Andhra Pradesh to the north. The state also surrounds the Puducherry and Karaikal districts of the Union Territory of Puducherry along the eastern coast. The southernmost tip of the Indian mainland, Cape Comorin, is located in the coastal town of Kanyakumari in Tamil Nadu.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Tamil Nadu is broadly divided into the eastern coastal plains and the hilly regions of the north and west. The Western Ghats run along the western border with Kerala, featuring prominent peaks such as Doddabetta in the Nilgiri Hills. The Eastern Ghats are a discontinuous range of hills that run through the northern parts of the state. The central region consists of a dry plateau. The Kaveri River is the longest and most significant river in Tamil Nadu, originating in Karnataka and flowing eastward to form a large delta before emptying into the Bay of Bengal. Other notable rivers include the Palar, Vaigai, and Thamirabarani. The state features diverse ecosystems, including the Gulf of Mannar Marine National Park and the Mudumalai National Park, which protect coastal reefs and inland tiger habitats.\n\n## Climate\nTamil Nadu experiences a tropical wet and dry climate, though its rainfall pattern is distinct from much of the rest of India. The state relies heavily on the northeast monsoon, which brings the majority of its annual rainfall between October and December. The southwest monsoon, which provides rain to most of India from June to September, yields less precipitation in Tamil Nadu because the state is located in the rain shadow of the Western Ghats. Coastal areas experience high humidity year-round, while the inland plains are characterized by high temperatures during the summer months of April and May. The hill stations in the Western Ghats, such as Ooty and Kodaikanal, maintain cooler, temperate climates throughout the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTamil Nadu has one of the largest state economies in India, driven by manufacturing, services, and agriculture. The state is a major hub for the automobile industry, with numerous manufacturing plants located around Chennai. The textile industry is heavily concentrated in cities like Coimbatore and Tiruppur, while information technology and software services are prominent in Chennai. Agriculture remains vital, with rice, sugarcane, and cotton being primary crops. Chennai is the administrative center and largest city, situated on the Coromandel Coast. Other major urban centers include Coimbatore, Madurai, Tiruchirappalli, and Salem. The state also operates major seaports in Chennai, Ennore, and Thoothukudi.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a continuous cultural history that spans over two millennia. It was ruled by three major ancient Tamil dynasties: the Cheras, Cholas, and Pandyas. These empires built extensive trade networks across the Indian Ocean and constructed large-scale stone temples. The Brihadisvara Temple in Thanjavur and the Shore Temple in Mahabalipuram are recognized as UNESCO World Heritage sites. The Tamil language is one of the oldest surviving classical languages in the world and serves as the foundation of the state's cultural identity. Traditional arts, including the classical dance form Bharatanatyam and Carnatic music, originated in this region and remain central to its cultural life.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Chennai\n* Approximate area: 130,058 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 72,000,000\n* Largest city: Chennai\n* Signature features: Dravidian temple architecture, automobile manufacturing hub, classical Tamil language, Coromandel Coast",
    "summary": "Tamil Nadu is a southern Indian state known for its distinct cultural heritage, ancient Dravidian temples, and the classical Tamil language. Its geography ranges from the Coromandel Coast along the Bay of Bengal to the peaks of the Western Ghats, which place much of the state in a rain shadow. The state has a robust economy driven by automobile manufacturing, textiles, and information technology, centered largely around its capital city, Chennai.",
