    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nSikkim is a landlocked state located in the northeastern part of India. It is situated entirely within the Himalayan mountain range. The state shares international borders with the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the north and northeast, Bhutan to the east, and Nepal to the west. To the south, it shares a domestic border with the Indian state of West Bengal. The region is strategically significant due to its proximity to the Siliguri Corridor, a narrow strip of land in neighboring West Bengal that connects the northeastern states to the rest of India.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Sikkim is defined by its dramatic mountainous terrain. The state is home to Kangchenjunga, which is the highest mountain peak in India and the third highest in the world, situated on the western border with Nepal. The landscape features steep valleys, alpine meadows, and extensive glaciers, including the Zemu Glacier. The Teesta River serves as the primary waterway, flowing from north to south and dividing the state. The Rangeet River is its most significant tributary. A large portion of the state is protected by Khangchendzonga National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site that preserves the high-altitude ecosystems and diverse flora and fauna of the region.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Sikkim varies drastically depending on the elevation. The southern, lower-altitude regions experience a subtropical climate. As the elevation increases toward the north, the climate transitions into a temperate zone, and eventually into a cold alpine or tundra climate in the highest northern reaches. The high-altitude peaks remain permanently covered in snow. The state receives heavy rainfall during the Indian monsoon season, which typically lasts from May to October. This intense precipitation frequently leads to landslides in the steep river valleys.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Sikkim relies heavily on agriculture and tourism. The state is known for its production of large cardamom, ginger, oranges, and tea. In recent years, Sikkim transitioned its entire agricultural sector to organic farming, becoming the first state in India to achieve this status. Tourism is driven by the natural landscape and the presence of prominent Buddhist monasteries. Additionally, the steep gradients of the Teesta River and its tributaries support a growing hydroelectric power industry. Gangtok is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the primary hub for commerce and government. Other notable towns include Namchi, Pelling, Mangan, and Geyzing.\n\n## History & culture\nSikkim was historically an independent Buddhist kingdom ruled by the Namgyal dynasty, known as the Chogyals, beginning in the seventeenth century. It became a princely state under British paramountcy in the nineteenth century. Following the independence of India in 1947, Sikkim continued as a protectorate of India. In 1975, following political unrest and a referendum, the monarchy was abolished, and Sikkim officially integrated into India as its twenty-second state. The population is diverse, consisting primarily of Nepali, Bhutia, and Lepcha ethnic groups. Nepali serves as the primary lingua franca. Hinduism and Vajrayana Buddhism are the major religions, and the state is dotted with historically significant monastic centers like the Rumtek Monastery and the Pemayangtse Monastery.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Gangtok\n* Approximate area: 7,096 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 690,000\n* Largest city: Gangtok\n* Signature features: Kangchenjunga mountain, Khangchendzonga National Park, first fully organic state in India",
