    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nChandigarh is a union territory located in the northern part of India. It is situated near the foothills of the Sivalik range of the Himalayas. The territory is bordered by the state of Punjab to the north, west, and south, and by the state of Haryana to the east. Chandigarh holds a unique political and administrative position in India because it serves as the joint capital for both the states of Punjab and Haryana, while remaining directly administered by the federal government as a union territory.\n\n## Physical features\nThe union territory covers a small geographical area characterized by flat, fertile plains that gently slope from northeast to southwest. It sits at an average elevation of about 321 meters above sea level. Chandigarh is bounded by two seasonal rivulets that originate in the Sivalik Hills. The Sukhna Choe flows along the eastern boundary, and the Patiala Ki Rao flows along the western boundary. A major geographical landmark within the territory is Sukhna Lake. This is an artificial reservoir created in 1958 by damming the Sukhna Choe, and it serves as a prominent wetland habitat for migratory birds. The surrounding landscape includes patches of protected forest, such as the Sukhna Wildlife Sanctuary, which supports species like the sambar deer and Indian peafowl.\n\n## Climate\nChandigarh experiences a humid subtropical climate, characterized by extreme seasonal variations in temperature. Summers last from mid-April to June and are typically very hot, with temperatures often exceeding 40 degrees Celsius. The monsoon season occurs from July to September, bringing the majority of the territory's annual rainfall through the southwest monsoon winds. Winters, lasting from late November to February, are mild to cool, with occasional ground frost and temperatures that can drop to near freezing at night. Western disturbances occasionally bring winter rain.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Chandigarh is primarily driven by the tertiary sector, with a strong emphasis on government services, education, healthcare, and information technology. The territory has a high per capita income compared to the national average. Industrial activity is concentrated in designated zones and includes the manufacturing of pharmaceuticals, machine tools, and electrical appliances. The Rajiv Gandhi Chandigarh Technology Park has attracted numerous multinational software and technology firms. As a union territory, Chandigarh is essentially a single-city administration, though it forms the core of the larger Chandigarh Capital Region, often called the Tricity, which includes the neighboring satellite cities of Mohali in Punjab and Panchkula in Haryana.\n\n## History & culture\nFollowing the partition of India in 1947, the former British province of Punjab was divided, leaving the Indian state of Punjab without a capital. The Indian government commissioned the construction of a new, planned city to serve this purpose. The master plan was developed by the Swiss-French architect Le Corbusier, who organized the city into a grid of self-contained sectors. In 1966, the state of Punjab was reorganized along linguistic lines into the modern states of Punjab and Haryana. Chandigarh was made a union territory to serve as the shared capital. Cultural landmarks include the Capitol Complex, which is a UNESCO World Heritage site, and the Rock Garden, a large sculpture garden built entirely from industrial and home waste by artist Nek Chand.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: Union Territory\n* Administrative center: Chandigarh\n* Approximate area: 114 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.1 million\n* Largest city: Chandigarh\n* Signature features: Master-planned grid layout by Le Corbusier, Capitol Complex, Rock Garden, joint capital of Punjab and Haryana.",
