    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nDadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu is a union territory located in western India. It is a fragmented territory consisting of four distinct geographical entities. Daman is a small enclave on the southern coast of the state of Gujarat, bordering the Arabian Sea. Diu is an island situated off the southern coast of Gujarat's Kathiawar Peninsula, separated from the mainland by a narrow tidal creek. Dadra and Nagar Haveli are landlocked regions situated between the states of Gujarat to the north and Maharashtra to the south. Dadra is a small enclave completely surrounded by Gujarat, while Nagar Haveli is a larger tract wedged between Gujarat and Maharashtra.\n\n## Physical features\nThe physical geography of the union territory varies across its distinct districts. Daman is characterized by a flat coastal plain intersected by the Daman Ganga River, which flows into the Arabian Sea. The coastline features sandy beaches, such as Jampore and Devka. Diu is a low-lying island with limestone cliffs, rocky coves, and sandy beaches like Nagoa Beach. The terrain of Dadra and Nagar Haveli is more rugged and undulating, rising toward the foothills of the Western Ghats in the east. The Daman Ganga River also flows through Nagar Haveli, where the Madhuban Dam creates a large reservoir. The region contains forest cover, particularly in the eastern parts of Nagar Haveli, which supports local wildlife sanctuaries.\n\n## Climate\nThe union territory experiences a tropical savanna climate. The year is divided into three main seasons. The summer season lasts from March to May and is characterized by high temperatures and humidity, particularly in the coastal areas of Daman and Diu. The monsoon season occurs from June to September, bringing heavy rainfall from the southwest monsoon winds. Dadra and Nagar Haveli generally receive more rainfall than the coastal enclaves due to their proximity to the Western Ghats. The winter season, from November to February, is mild and dry, with comfortable temperatures.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of the union territory relies heavily on manufacturing. For many years, the region benefited from tax exemptions granted by the central government, which attracted numerous industrial facilities. Major manufacturing sectors include plastics, textiles, chemicals, and electronics. Agriculture also plays a role, particularly in Dadra and Nagar Haveli, where farmers cultivate rice, wheat, and pulses. Tourism is another major economic sector, centered on the beaches of Diu and Daman, as well as the Portuguese heritage sites. Daman serves as the administrative center of the union territory. Silvassa, located in Nagar Haveli, is the largest city and serves as a major industrial hub. Diu town is the primary settlement on Diu island.\n\n## History & culture\nThe territories comprising this union territory share a history of Portuguese colonial rule. The Portuguese acquired Diu in 1535 and Daman in 1559, incorporating them into the Portuguese State of India. Dadra and Nagar Haveli were acquired by the Portuguese in the late eighteenth century. Following the independence of India, pro-Indian forces took control of Dadra and Nagar Haveli in 1954. Daman and Diu remained under Portuguese control until December 1961, when the Indian military annexed them during Operation Vijay. In 2020, the two separate union territories were merged into a single administrative unit. The local culture is a blend of Gujarati, Maharashtrian, and Portuguese influences. The indigenous Warli people form a large part of the population in Dadra and Nagar Haveli, known for their distinct traditional paintings.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: Union territory\n* Administrative center: Daman\n* Approximate area: 603 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 586,000\n* Largest city: Silvassa\n* Signature features: Fragmented geography across western India, historic Portuguese colonial architecture, Warli indigenous culture",
