    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nJammu and Kashmir is a union territory located in the northern part of the Indian subcontinent, situated primarily in the western Himalayas. It is bordered by the Indian union territory of Ladakh to the east and the Indian states of Himachal Pradesh and Punjab to the south. To the west and north, it shares a border with Pakistan. The region is part of the larger Kashmir territory, which has been the subject of a territorial dispute among India, Pakistan, and China since 1947.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Jammu and Kashmir is defined by high mountain ranges and deep valleys. The Pir Panjal Range separates the Jammu region from the Kashmir Valley. The Kashmir Valley itself is a large, fertile basin situated between the Pir Panjal and the main Himalayas. Major rivers flowing through the territory include the Jhelum, which meanders through the Kashmir Valley, as well as the Chenab, Ravi, and Tawi rivers in the Jammu region. The territory contains several prominent lakes, including Dal Lake in Srinagar and Wular Lake, which is one of the largest freshwater lakes in Asia. Dachigam National Park is a notable protected area, known for sheltering the endangered Kashmir stag or hangul.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Jammu and Kashmir varies significantly depending on elevation and geographic location. The southern Jammu region experiences a subtropical climate characterized by hot summers, a distinct monsoon season from July to September, and cool winters. In contrast, the Kashmir Valley has a temperate climate. Summers in the valley are mild and pleasant, while winters are cold and bring heavy snowfall. Unlike much of India, the Kashmir Valley receives a significant portion of its precipitation during the winter and spring months due to weather systems known as western disturbances, rather than relying solely on the summer monsoon.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Jammu and Kashmir is largely agrarian, with a strong emphasis on horticulture. The region is a major producer of apples, walnuts, cherries, and almonds. The town of Pampore is particularly famous for cultivating high-quality saffron. Handicrafts also form a vital part of the economy, with artisans producing Pashmina shawls, hand-knotted carpets, and intricate wood carvings. Tourism is another major economic driver. Visitors are drawn to leisure destinations like Gulmarg and Pahalgam, as well as major pilgrimage sites such as the Mata Vaishno Devi shrine in Jammu and the Amarnath Cave in the Himalayas. Srinagar is the largest city and serves as the summer administrative center. Jammu serves as the winter administrative center. Other significant towns include Anantnag, Baramulla, and Udhampur.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the region was an important center for Hinduism and Buddhism before becoming heavily influenced by Islam starting in the fourteenth century. It was ruled by various powers, including the Mughal Empire, the Afghan Durrani Empire, and the Sikh Empire. In 1846, it became a princely state under the Dogra dynasty. The ruler of this state acceded to India in 1947. In August 2019, the Parliament of India passed legislation that reorganized the former state into two separate union territories, Jammu and Kashmir, and Ladakh. The culture is highly diverse. The Kashmir Valley is predominantly Muslim and the primary language is Kashmiri. The Jammu region is predominantly Hindu and the primary language is Dogri.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: Union Territory\n* Administrative center: Srinagar (summer), Jammu (winter)\n* Approximate area: 42,241 square kilometers (administered area)\n* Approximate population: 12.2 million\n* Largest city: Srinagar\n* Signature features: Dal Lake houseboats, saffron cultivation, Pir Panjal mountain range",
    "summary": "Jammu and Kashmir is a union territory in northern India, characterized by the high peaks of the Himalayas and the fertile Kashmir Valley. Its economy relies heavily on agriculture, horticulture, and tourism, with distinct cultural and climatic differences between the Jammu region and the Kashmir Valley. In 2019, it was reorganized from a state into a union territory, with Srinagar serving as its summer capital and Jammu as its winter capital.",
