    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nWest Bengal is a state located in the eastern region of India. It is uniquely positioned as the only Indian state that extends from the Himalayas in the north to the Bay of Bengal in the south. The state shares international borders with three countries. Bangladesh lies to the east, Nepal to the northwest, and Bhutan to the northeast. Domestically, West Bengal is bordered by five Indian states. It shares boundaries with Odisha to the southwest, Jharkhand and Bihar to the west, Sikkim to the north, and Assam to the northeast. The narrow Siliguri Corridor connects the main body of India to the northeastern states.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of West Bengal is diverse, encompassing high mountain peaks, flat river plains, and coastal ecosystems. The northernmost area contains the Darjeeling Himalayan hill region. This area includes Sandakphu, which at roughly 3,636 meters is the highest peak in the state. South of the mountains lie the Terai and Dooars regions, which are transition zones characterized by dense forests and rolling foothills. The central and southern portions of the state are dominated by the Ganges delta. The Ganges River divides into several distributaries, with the Hooghly River flowing south through the state. Other major rivers include the Teesta, Torsa, and Damodar. The southernmost coastal region features the Sundarbans. This vast mangrove forest is a UNESCO World Heritage site and provides a critical habitat for the Bengal tiger and saltwater crocodiles.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of West Bengal varies significantly depending on elevation and proximity to the coast. The southern and central plains experience a tropical wet and dry climate, while the northern mountainous regions have a subtropical highland climate. The year is generally divided into four seasons. Summer lasts from March to June, bringing hot and humid conditions to the plains. The southwest monsoon arrives in June and lasts through September, delivering the majority of the annual rainfall. The coastal regions and the Ganges delta are highly susceptible to severe cyclones that form in the Bay of Bengal, particularly during the pre-monsoon and post-monsoon periods. Winters are mild in the plains but can be quite cold in the northern Himalayan region.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of West Bengal is supported by agriculture, manufacturing, and the service sector. The state is a leading agricultural producer in India, cultivating large quantities of rice, potatoes, and jute. The northern districts are famous globally for producing Darjeeling tea. The western region, particularly around the cities of Asansol and Durgapur, contains rich coal deposits and forms a major industrial belt focused on steel production and heavy engineering. Kolkata is the administrative center and the largest city. It serves as a major port and the primary commercial and financial hub of eastern India. Other important cities include Howrah, which is connected to Kolkata by the iconic Howrah Bridge, and Siliguri, which functions as a critical transport and logistics hub for the region.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region of Bengal has a long history, having been ruled by various ancient and medieval empires including the Mauryas, Guptas, and Palas. In the late seventeenth century, the British East India Company established a trading post at Calcutta. The city grew rapidly and served as the capital of British India until 1911. In 1947, the partition of India divided the Bengal province along religious lines. The predominantly Hindu western section became the Indian state of West Bengal, and the predominantly Muslim eastern section became East Pakistan, which later gained independence as Bangladesh. The state is noted for its rich literary, artistic, and cinematic heritage. It is the home of prominent historical figures such as Nobel laureate Rabindranath Tagore and filmmaker Satyajit Ray. The annual Durga Puja festival is a major cultural event in the state.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Kolkata\n* Approximate area: 88,752 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 91 million\n* Largest city: Kolkata\n* Signature features: The Sundarbans mangrove forest, Darjeeling tea, and the Hooghly River",
    "summary": "West Bengal is an eastern Indian state that stretches from the Himalayas in the north to the Bay of Bengal in the south. Its economy relies on agriculture, including rice and Darjeeling tea, alongside industrial and service sectors centered around its capital, Kolkata. The state is known for its rich cultural history and diverse geography, which includes the Sundarbans mangrove forest.",
