    "mainNotes": "## Location within India\nLakshadweep is a union territory of India located in the Laccadive Sea, off the southwestern coast of the Indian subcontinent. It is situated roughly 200 to 440 kilometers off the Malabar Coast of the state of Kerala. The nearest major mainland city is Kochi in Kerala, which serves as the primary gateway to the islands. Lakshadweep is the smallest union territory in India by both area and population. It shares maritime borders with the Maldives to the south, separated by the Eight Degree Channel.\n\n## Physical features\nThe territory is an archipelago consisting of 36 islands, which include 12 atolls, three reefs, and five submerged banks. The islands are broadly divided into three main subgroups. The Amindivi Islands lie to the north, the Laccadive Islands are situated in the center, and Minicoy Island is located to the far south, separated from the rest of the archipelago by the Nine Degree Channel. The total land area is very small, and the terrain is entirely flat with no mountains, hills, or freshwater rivers. The islands are formed of coral reefs and sand banks. The soils are highly porous and derived from coral limestone. Pitti Island is an important breeding ground for sea turtles and pelagic birds and has been declared a bird sanctuary. The surrounding lagoons provide extensive marine habitats.\n\n## Climate\nLakshadweep experiences a tropical monsoon climate. The weather is warm and highly humid throughout the year, closely mirroring the climate of the neighboring state of Kerala. Temperatures typically range from 22 to 33 degrees Celsius. The islands receive significant rainfall from the southwest monsoon, which generally lasts from late May through September. The pre-monsoon months of April and May are the hottest. Cyclonic storms occasionally form in the Arabian Sea during the post-monsoon season, bringing high winds and heavy rainfall to the archipelago.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Lakshadweep is primarily based on agriculture and fishing. Coconut is the dominant crop, and the extraction of coir fiber from coconut husks is a major local industry. Fishing, particularly for skipjack tuna, is another crucial economic activity. Tourism is a growing sector, though it is strictly regulated by the government to protect the fragile coral ecology and local culture. Visitors require special permits to enter the islands. Kavaratti is the administrative center and one of the most populated islands. Andrott is the largest island by area and population. Agatti Island hosts the only airport in the territory, connecting the archipelago to Kochi. Other notable inhabited islands include Minicoy, Amini, and Kalpeni.\n\n## History & culture\nArchaeological evidence suggests early Buddhist settlements existed on the islands. According to local tradition, Islam was introduced in the seventh century by an Arab saint named Ubaidullah. The islands were later controlled by the Chola Empire and the Kingdom of Kannur. In the sixteenth century, the Portuguese established a brief presence before being expelled. Control eventually passed to the Arakkal kingdom, then to Tipu Sultan of Mysore, and finally to the British East India Company in the late eighteenth century. Following Indian independence, the islands were organized into a union territory in 1956. The population is predominantly Muslim. The culture and language are closely tied to Kerala, with Malayalam being the most widely spoken language. However, the people of Minicoy Island speak Mahl, a dialect of the Maldivian language, reflecting strong historical and cultural ties to the Maldives.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: India\n* Subdivision type: Union territory\n* Administrative center: Kavaratti\n* Approximate area: 32 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 64,000\n* Largest city: Andrott\n* Signature features: Coral atolls, extensive coconut groves, coir production, and the unique Mahl-speaking population of Minicoy.",
    "summary": "Lakshadweep is a small Indian union territory located in the Laccadive Sea off the coast of Kerala. It consists of 36 coral islands and atolls known for their coconut agriculture, tuna fishing, and strictly regulated tourism. While most of the predominantly Muslim population speaks Malayalam, the southernmost island of Minicoy has strong cultural ties to the Maldives.",
