    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nIowa is located in the Midwestern region of the United States. It is bordered by six states. Minnesota lies to the north, Wisconsin and Illinois are to the east, Missouri is to the south, and Nebraska and South Dakota are to the west. The eastern boundary is defined entirely by the Mississippi River, while the western boundary is defined by the Missouri River and the Big Sioux River.\n\n## Physical features\nIowa is characterized by rolling plains and low hills. The state is situated entirely within the Interior Plains of North America. The landscape is generally divided into several landform regions, including the Des Moines Lobe, which is relatively flat and features rich glacial soils. The Loess Hills run along the western edge of the state, formed by windblown silt deposits from the end of the last ice age. The Driftless Area in the northeastern corner of the state features steep hills, deep valleys, and limestone bluffs, as it was bypassed by recent glacial advances. Major rivers include the Des Moines River, the Cedar River, and the Iowa River, all of which flow generally southeast to join the Mississippi River. Natural lakes are concentrated in the northwest, including Spirit Lake and the Okoboji lakes.\n\n## Climate\nIowa experiences a humid continental climate. This climate type is marked by significant seasonal temperature variations. Winters are typically cold and snowy, with average January temperatures often dropping below freezing. Summers are warm and humid, with average July temperatures frequently exceeding eighty degrees Fahrenheit. Precipitation is generally concentrated in the spring and summer months, providing necessary moisture for the agricultural sector. The state is located in a region prone to severe weather, including thunderstorms and tornadoes, particularly during the spring and early summer.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Iowa is heavily reliant on agriculture, manufacturing, and financial services. Iowa is consistently a leading producer of corn, soybeans, pork, and eggs in the United States. The state is also a major producer of ethanol and other biofuels. Beyond agriculture, manufacturing sectors include food processing, heavy machinery, and chemicals. Des Moines, the administrative center and largest city, is a major hub for the insurance and financial services industries. Other significant cities include Cedar Rapids, known for its large corn-processing industry, Davenport, which is part of the Quad Cities metropolitan area on the Mississippi River, and Iowa City, home to the University of Iowa.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European settlement, the region was inhabited by various Native American groups, including the Ioway, Sauk, and Meskwaki. French explorers Jacques Marquette and Louis Jolliet were among the first Europeans to document the area in 1673. The United States acquired the territory as part of the Louisiana Purchase in 1803. Iowa was admitted to the Union as the twenty-ninth state in 1846. The culture of the state is deeply tied to its agricultural heritage, which is celebrated annually at the Iowa State Fair in Des Moines. The state also holds a prominent position in the United States political system due to the Iowa caucuses, which traditionally serve as the first major electoral event in the presidential nominating process.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Des Moines\n* Approximate area: 56,273 square miles\n* Approximate population: 3.2 million\n* Largest city: Des Moines\n* Signature features: Leading producer of corn and pork, the Loess Hills, the Iowa caucuses",
