    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nIdaho is located in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States. It is landlocked and shares borders with six states and one Canadian province. To the north, it shares a short international border with British Columbia, Canada. To the east, it is bordered by Montana and Wyoming. Utah and Nevada lie to the south, while Oregon and Washington form the western border. The western boundary is partially defined by the Snake River, which runs through Hells Canyon.\n\n## Physical features\nIdaho is characterized by mountainous terrain and large areas of wilderness. The Rocky Mountains cover much of the state, with notable sub-ranges including the Bitterroot Range along the Montana border, the Sawtooth Range in central Idaho, and the Tetons extending near the Wyoming border. The highest point is Borah Peak, reaching 12,662 feet in the Lost River Range. The southern portion of the state is dominated by the Snake River Plain, a wide depression that arcs across the region. This plain was formed by volcanic activity and features geological sites like Craters of the Moon National Monument and Preserve, containing large lava fields. The state is forested in the panhandle and contains lakes such as Lake Coeur d'Alene and Pend Oreille. The Salmon River carves through the central mountains, creating deep canyons and providing habitats for fish and wildlife.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Idaho varies significantly depending on elevation and region. The state generally experiences a continental climate, but the western parts receive maritime influence from the Pacific Ocean. The northern panhandle has a wetter climate with cold, snowy winters and warm, moderately dry summers. Central Idaho's mountainous regions experience long, cold winters with heavy snowfall and short, mild summers. The southern Snake River Plain is more arid, featuring a semi-arid steppe climate. Here, summers are hot and dry, while winters are cold with relatively low precipitation. Temperature inversions are common in the valleys during winter, trapping cold air and fog for extended periods.\n\n## Economy & cities\nIdaho has an economy historically rooted in agriculture, mining, and forestry, which have diversified into technology and manufacturing. The Snake River Plain is an agricultural center reliant on irrigation. The state is the leading producer of potatoes in the United States and grows quantities of wheat, sugar beets, and alfalfa. The technology sector has expanded in the capital, Boise, which hosts semiconductor and electronics manufacturing facilities. Tourism and outdoor recreation are important economic sectors, drawing visitors to ski resorts like Sun Valley and national forests. Boise is the largest city and the administrative center, located in the southwestern part of the state. Other major cities include Meridian and Nampa in the Boise metropolitan area, Idaho Falls and Pocatello in the east, and Coeur d'Alene in the northern panhandle.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Shoshone, Bannock, and Nez Perce, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. The Lewis and Clark Expedition crossed the area in 1805, which opened the region to fur trappers and missionaries. The discovery of gold in the 1860s led to an influx of miners and the establishment of the Idaho Territory in 1863. Idaho was admitted as the 43rd state in 1890. The state maintains a cultural emphasis on outdoor activities, including hunting, fishing, and hiking. Basque immigrants settled in the region during the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries to work as shepherds, and Boise now holds one of the largest Basque populations in the United States.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Boise\n* Approximate area: 83,569 square miles\n* Approximate population: 1.9 million\n* Signature features: Snake River Plain, Craters of the Moon, potato agriculture, Rocky Mountains",
    "summary": "Idaho is a landlocked state in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States, known for its rugged Rocky Mountain terrain and the expansive Snake River Plain. Its economy relies heavily on agriculture, particularly potato production, as well as a growing technology sector centered around the capital city of Boise. The state features vast wilderness areas that support significant outdoor recreation and forestry industries.",
