    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nLouisiana is located in the Deep South region of the South Central United States. It is bordered by Texas to the west, Arkansas to the north, and Mississippi to the east. The southern boundary of the state is formed by the Gulf of Mexico. The Mississippi River defines a significant portion of its eastern border with the state of Mississippi.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Louisiana is largely defined by its low elevation and its relationship with water. The state is divided into two broad geographical regions, which are the uplands of the north and the alluvial region along the coast and the Mississippi River. The alluvial region includes low swamp lands, coastal marshlands, beaches, and barrier islands. The Mississippi River Delta is a dominant feature in the southeast, characterized by a complex network of distributaries, bayous, and wetlands. Lake Pontchartrain is a large brackish estuary located near the coast. The northern and western parts of the state feature the Gulf Coastal Plain, which consists of low rolling hills and pine forests. Driskill Mountain, located in the north-central part of the state, is the highest natural point at an elevation of about 535 feet. Major rivers besides the Mississippi include the Red River, the Ouachita River, and the Atchafalaya River.\n\n## Climate\nLouisiana has a humid subtropical climate. The state experiences long, hot, and humid summers, along with short and relatively mild winters. Precipitation is abundant throughout the year, with the southern coastal regions generally receiving more rainfall than the northern areas. The state is highly vulnerable to tropical cyclones and hurricanes, which frequently strike the Gulf Coast between June and November. These storms often bring heavy rainfall, storm surges, and high winds, significantly impacting the coastal wetlands and inland communities.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Louisiana is heavily reliant on its natural resources. The state is a major producer of crude oil and natural gas, with extensive drilling operations located both onshore and offshore in the Gulf of Mexico. Petroleum and coal products manufacturing, along with chemical manufacturing, are primary industrial sectors. Agriculture also plays a vital role, with major crops including soybeans, sugarcane, rice, and cotton. The state is a leading producer of seafood, particularly crawfish, shrimp, and oysters. The Port of South Louisiana, located along the Mississippi River, is one of the largest volume shipping ports in the Western Hemisphere. Baton Rouge is the administrative center and a major industrial hub. New Orleans is the largest city and serves as a primary center for maritime trade, tourism, and healthcare. Other significant cities include Shreveport, Lafayette, and Lake Charles.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European settlement, the area was inhabited by various Indigenous peoples, including the Chitimacha, Choctaw, and Caddo. French explorers claimed the region in the late seventeenth century, naming it after King Louis XIV. It became a French colony and later a Spanish colony before reverting to French control. The United States acquired the territory in 1803 through the Louisiana Purchase. Louisiana was admitted as the eighteenth state in 1812. The state has a distinct cultural heritage shaped by French, Spanish, African, and Native American influences. This is most evident in the Creole and Cajun cultures of the southern parishes. The legal system is unique within the United States, as it is based on civil law derived from French and Spanish codes rather than English common law.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Baton Rouge\n* Approximate area: 52,000 square miles\n* Approximate population: 4.6 million\n* Largest city: New Orleans\n* Signature features: Mississippi River Delta, Cajun and Creole culture, bayous and coastal wetlands, extensive petroleum and natural gas industries",
