    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nMichigan is located in the Great Lakes region of the upper Midwestern United States. It is the only state to consist of two peninsulas, the Lower Peninsula and the Upper Peninsula. The state shares land borders with Ohio and Indiana to the south, and Wisconsin to the west along the Upper Peninsula. It shares extensive water boundaries with the Canadian province of Ontario to the north and east, as well as water boundaries with Illinois and Minnesota.\n\n## Physical features\nThe Lower Peninsula is shaped roughly like a mitten and is generally flat with rolling hills in the north. The Upper Peninsula is more rugged and heavily forested, featuring the Porcupine Mountains and the Huron Mountains. Mount Arvon is the highest point in the state, located in the Huron Mountains. Michigan borders four of the five Great Lakes, which are Lake Superior, Lake Michigan, Lake Huron, and Lake Erie. The state has the longest freshwater coastline of any political subdivision in the world. Major rivers include the Grand River, which is the longest in the state, the Detroit River, the Saginaw River, and the Escanaba River. Isle Royale National Park is located in Lake Superior and is known for its isolated wilderness.\n\n## Climate\nMichigan experiences a continental climate. The southern and central parts of the Lower Peninsula have a hot-summer humid continental climate, while the northern Lower Peninsula and the entire Upper Peninsula have a warm-summer humid continental climate. Winters are cold and snowy, particularly in areas affected by lake-effect snow from Lake Michigan and Lake Superior. Summers are generally warm to hot and humid. Precipitation is relatively well distributed throughout the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Michigan is highly diversified but is most historically associated with the automotive industry. The major American automobile manufacturers are headquartered in the Detroit metropolitan area. Other significant economic sectors include advanced manufacturing, agriculture, forestry, and tourism. Michigan is a leading producer of tart cherries, apples, and blueberries. Detroit is the largest city and serves as a major cultural and economic hub. Grand Rapids is the second-largest city, known for furniture manufacturing and healthcare. Lansing is the administrative center, located in the central Lower Peninsula. Other notable cities include Ann Arbor, home to the University of Michigan, and Flint.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Anishinaabe tribes such as the Ojibwe, Odawa, and Potawatomi, inhabited the region for thousands of years before European contact. French explorers arrived in the seventeenth century and established fur trading posts. The area passed to British control after the French and Indian War and became part of the United States following the American Revolutionary War. Michigan was admitted as the twenty-sixth state in 1837. During the twentieth century, the state became a global center for the automotive industry, which attracted a large influx of workers during the Great Migration. Culturally, Michigan is known for its contributions to popular music, particularly the Motown sound that originated in Detroit in the 1960s.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Lansing\n* Approximate area: 96,716 square miles (250,493 square kilometers)\n* Approximate population: 10 million\n* Largest city: Detroit\n* Signature features: Two distinct peninsulas, borders four of the five Great Lakes, historic center of the American automotive industry",
    "summary": "Michigan is a Midwestern state in the Great Lakes region, uniquely composed of the Lower and Upper Peninsulas. It is known for having the longest freshwater coastline in the world and serving as the historic hub of the American automotive industry. The state features a diverse economy, extensive forests, and major urban centers like Detroit and Grand Rapids.",
