    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nMaryland is located in the Mid-Atlantic region of the United States. It shares borders with Pennsylvania to the north, Delaware to the east, and both Virginia and West Virginia to the south and west. The eastern edge of the state also meets the Atlantic Ocean. The District of Columbia, which serves as the national capital, sits along Maryland's southwestern border. This federal district was formed from land originally ceded by Maryland along the banks of the Potomac River.\n\n## Physical features\nMaryland features diverse physical geography. The state is often divided into three main topographical regions. The Atlantic Coastal Plain covers the eastern and southern parts of the state. This plain is bisected by the Chesapeake Bay, creating the Eastern Shore and the Western Shore. The central Piedmont plateau features rolling hills separated from the Coastal Plain by the Atlantic Seaboard fall line. Western Maryland is dominated by the Appalachian Mountains, which include the Blue Ridge Mountains and the Allegheny Mountains. The highest point in the state is Hoye-Crest on Backbone Mountain, reaching roughly 3,360 feet above sea level. Major waterways include the Potomac River, which forms the long southern border, and the Susquehanna River, which flows into the northern tip of the Chesapeake Bay. Assateague Island is a notable barrier island on the Atlantic coast.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Maryland varies significantly depending on elevation and proximity to water. The eastern and central regions, including Baltimore and Annapolis, experience a humid subtropical climate. These areas have hot, humid summers and mild to cool winters. In contrast, the higher elevations of western Maryland feature a humid continental climate, characterized by milder summers and colder winters with substantial snowfall. Precipitation is distributed fairly evenly throughout the year across the state, averaging about 40 to 45 inches annually. The coastal and bay areas are occasionally impacted by tropical storms and nor'easters, which can bring heavy rain and high winds.\n\n## Economy & cities\nMaryland has a diversified economy benefiting from its proximity to the federal government in Washington, D.C. Major industries include defense contracting, aerospace, biotechnology, and cybersecurity. Federal agencies such as the National Institutes of Health and the National Security Agency are headquartered in the state. The Port of Baltimore is an economic engine, handling large volumes of automobile and roll-on/roll-off cargo. Agriculture remains a vital industry, with poultry farming dominating the Eastern Shore. The Chesapeake Bay supports a commercial fishing industry known for Maryland blue crabs and oysters. Baltimore is the largest city and a major industrial center. Other significant population centers include Columbia, Germantown, Silver Spring, and Frederick. Annapolis serves as the administrative center and is home to the United States Naval Academy.\n\n## History & culture\nMaryland was one of the original Thirteen Colonies. It was founded in 1632 by George Calvert, Lord Baltimore, who intended the colony to be a refuge for English Catholics. During the War of 1812, the successful defense of Fort McHenry in Baltimore inspired Francis Scott Key to write the poem that became the national anthem. During the American Civil War, Maryland remained in the Union as a border state. The Battle of Antietam, fought near Sharpsburg in 1862, was the bloodiest single-day battle in American military history. Maryland culture is closely tied to the Chesapeake Bay, reflected in local culinary traditions featuring blue crabs and Old Bay seasoning. The state flag is distinctive, displaying the heraldic banners of the Calvert and Crossland families.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Annapolis\n* Approximate area: 12,407 square miles\n* Approximate population: 6.1 million\n* Largest city: Baltimore\n* Signature features: Chesapeake Bay, blue crabs, Fort McHenry, United States Naval Academy",
    "summary": "Maryland is a Mid-Atlantic state known for its diverse geography, ranging from the Appalachian Mountains in the west to the Chesapeake Bay in the east. Its economy is heavily influenced by its proximity to Washington, D.C., supporting major defense, aerospace, and biotechnology industries. The state is rich in early American history and is culturally associated with its maritime traditions and blue crab harvests.",
