    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nMississippi is located in the southeastern region of the United States. It is bordered by Tennessee to the north, Alabama to the east, the Gulf of Mexico to the south, and Louisiana and Arkansas to the west. The Mississippi River defines its entire western boundary, separating it from Louisiana and Arkansas.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is characterized by low-lying plains and is divided into two major geographic regions: the Mississippi Alluvial Plain and the Gulf Coastal Plain. The Mississippi Alluvial Plain, commonly known as the Delta, is a narrow strip of land in the northwest that is extremely flat and features highly fertile soil deposited by the Mississippi River. The Gulf Coastal Plain covers the rest of the state and includes rolling hills, pine forests, and prairie lands. The highest point in the state is Woodall Mountain, which reaches an elevation of 806 feet in the northeastern corner. Major rivers include the Mississippi, the Pearl, the Big Black, and the Yazoo. The southern coastline along the Gulf of Mexico is relatively short but includes several bays and barrier islands, such as Ship Island and Horn Island, which are part of the Gulf Islands National Seashore.\n\n## Climate\nMississippi experiences a humid subtropical climate. Summers are long, hot, and humid, while winters are short and mild. Average temperatures in July range from the low to mid-nineties Fahrenheit, and January temperatures typically hover in the forties and fifties. The state receives abundant precipitation throughout the year, averaging about fifty to sixty-five inches annually. Mississippi is prone to severe weather, including thunderstorms, tornadoes, and hurricanes. Hurricanes frequently impact the southern coastal region during the late summer and fall, bringing heavy rainfall and storm surges.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mississippi is historically rooted in agriculture, though it has diversified into manufacturing, forestry, and services. The state is a leading producer of cotton, soybeans, poultry, and farm-raised catfish. Manufacturing sectors include automotive production, aerospace, and shipbuilding, particularly at the Ingalls Shipbuilding facility in Pascagoula. The state also has a significant gambling and tourism industry centered around coastal cities like Biloxi and Gulfport, as well as Tunica in the north. Jackson is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a hub for government, healthcare, and education. Other notable cities include Hattiesburg, Southaven, and Meridian.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the area was inhabited by indigenous peoples, including the Choctaw, Chickasaw, and Natchez. French explorers established the first permanent European settlement at Ocean Springs in 1699. Mississippi became the twentieth state to join the United States in 1817. The state played a central role in the American Civil War and the subsequent Civil Rights Movement of the mid-twentieth century. Culturally, Mississippi is widely recognized for its contributions to American music. It is known as the birthplace of the blues, with deep roots in the Mississippi Delta region. The state has also produced numerous prominent authors, such as William Faulkner, Eudora Welty, and Richard Wright.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Jackson\n* Approximate area: 48,430 square miles\n* Approximate population: 2.9 million\n* Largest city: Jackson\n* Signature features: The Mississippi River, birthplace of the blues, Gulf Islands National Seashore, extensive catfish farming",
    "summary": "Mississippi is a southeastern US state bordered by the Mississippi River to the west and the Gulf of Mexico to the south. Its economy relies on agriculture, manufacturing, and coastal tourism, while its geography features the flat, fertile Delta and rolling pine forests. The state is historically significant for its role in the Civil Rights Movement and is widely celebrated as the birthplace of blues music.",
