    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nMissouri is located in the Midwestern region of the United States. It is a landlocked state bordered by eight other states. Its neighbors include Iowa to the north, Illinois, Kentucky, and Tennessee to the east, Arkansas to the south, and Oklahoma, Kansas, and Nebraska to the west. The state is strategically positioned at the confluence of the two longest rivers in the United States, the Missouri and the Mississippi. The Mississippi River forms the entirety of its eastern border.\n\n## Physical features\nMissouri is divided into two major geographic regions. The northern and western parts of the state consist of the Dissected Till Plains and the Osage Plains, which feature rolling hills and fertile agricultural land. The southern half is dominated by the Ozark Mountains, a forested highland region characterized by steep hills, deep valleys, and extensive karst topography. Missouri is often called the Cave State due to the presence of thousands of caves, including Onondaga Cave and Meramec Caverns. The highest point in the state is Taum Sauk Mountain, reaching an elevation of roughly 1,772 feet. The Missouri River flows eastward through the center of the state, joining the Mississippi River just north of St. Louis. Major lakes include the Lake of the Ozarks and Table Rock Lake, both created by damming rivers in the Ozark region.\n\n## Climate\nMissouri has a humid continental climate in the northern half and a humid subtropical climate in the southern half. Summers are typically hot and humid, while winters are cold with moderate snowfall. The state experiences frequent precipitation throughout the year. Because it is located in the interior of the continent, Missouri is subject to extreme temperatures and severe weather. This includes thunderstorms and tornadoes, particularly during the spring months, as the state lies within the region known as Tornado Alley.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Missouri is diverse, relying on agriculture, manufacturing, and services. Agricultural outputs include soybeans, corn, cattle, and hogs. Manufacturing sectors produce aerospace equipment, transportation equipment, and chemicals. Missouri is also a leading producer of lead, with the Viburnum Trend being one of the most productive lead mining districts in the world. St. Louis and Kansas City are the major economic hubs. St. Louis is known for biotechnology, healthcare, and brewing. Kansas City has a strong presence in finance, telecommunications, and federal government operations. Other significant cities include Springfield, which serves as a commercial center for the Ozarks, and Columbia, home to the University of Missouri. Tourism is also a major industry, particularly in the Ozarks region and the city of Branson.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Osage and Missouria, inhabited the region for thousands of years before European contact. French explorers arrived in the late seventeenth century, establishing settlements such as Ste. Genevieve. The United States acquired the territory in 1803 as part of the Louisiana Purchase. Missouri was admitted to the Union in 1821 as a slave state following the Missouri Compromise. During the American Civil War, Missouri was a border state that remained in the Union but experienced significant internal conflict and guerrilla warfare. The state played a central role in westward expansion, serving as the starting point for the Oregon, Santa Fe, and California trails. This history is commemorated by the Gateway Arch in St. Louis. Culturally, Missouri has strong traditions in music, particularly ragtime, jazz, and blues, which flourished in St. Louis and Kansas City. The state is also the birthplace of author Mark Twain, whose novels captured life along the Mississippi River.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Jefferson City\n* Approximate area: 69,700 square miles\n* Approximate population: 6.1 million\n* Largest city: Kansas City\n* Signature features: The Gateway Arch, the Ozark Mountains, extensive cave systems, and a major role in westward expansion",
    "summary": "Missouri is a Midwestern state defined by its position along the Mississippi and Missouri rivers and its diverse geography, which ranges from northern plains to the southern Ozark Mountains. Historically serving as the starting point for westward expansion, the state now features a diverse economy anchored by major urban centers like Kansas City and St. Louis.",
