    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nMontana is located in the northwestern region of the United States. It shares a long international border to the north with the Canadian provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan. Within the United States, Montana is bordered by North Dakota and South Dakota to the east, Wyoming to the south, and Idaho to the west and southwest. It is the fourth largest state in the country by area.\n\n## Physical features\nMontana is divided into two distinct topographic regions. The western third of the state contains numerous mountain ranges that are part of the Rocky Mountains. Prominent ranges include the Bitterroot Range along the Idaho border, the Lewis Range, and the Absaroka Range. Granite Peak is the highest point, reaching 12,807 feet. The eastern two-thirds of Montana consist of the Great Plains, characterized by rolling prairie, badlands, and isolated island ranges. The Missouri River forms in southwestern Montana at the confluence of the Jefferson, Madison, and Gallatin rivers. The Yellowstone River flows through the southern and eastern parts of the state before joining the Missouri River. The western region is drained by the Clark Fork and Flathead rivers, which flow toward the Pacific Ocean. Montana is also home to Glacier National Park in the northwest and a small portion of Yellowstone National Park in the south. Flathead Lake is the largest natural freshwater lake in the western United States.\n\n## Climate\nMontana experiences a diverse continental climate due to its large size and varying elevations. The western mountainous region receives more precipitation and experiences milder winters and cooler summers compared to the eastern plains. The eastern plains have a semi-arid climate with cold, harsh winters and hot summers. Precipitation in the east is generally sparse and falls primarily during the late spring and early summer. The Continental Divide acts as a barrier to moisture from the Pacific Ocean, creating a rain shadow effect over the eastern plains. Winter temperatures can drop significantly, especially when Arctic air masses move south from Canada. Chinook winds, which are warm and dry, frequently blow down the eastern slopes of the Rocky Mountains during winter, causing rapid temperature increases.\n\n## Economy & cities\nMontana's economy is historically rooted in agriculture, mining, and timber. Agriculture remains a major industry, with the eastern plains supporting extensive cattle ranching and dryland wheat farming. Other significant crops include barley, sugar beets, and hay. The state has an extensive mining history, extracting resources such as copper, gold, silver, coal, and oil. Tourism is a growing sector, driven by visitors to Glacier and Yellowstone national parks, as well as outdoor recreation activities like hunting, fishing, and skiing. Healthcare, government, and technology are increasingly important to the modern economy. Billings is the largest city in Montana and serves as a major economic and medical hub for the region. Missoula and Bozeman host the state's largest public universities. Great Falls and Butte are historically significant industrial and mining centers. Helena serves as the administrative center.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples have inhabited the region for thousands of years. Present-day Native American tribes in Montana include the Crow, Cheyenne, Blackfeet, Assiniboine, Gros Ventre, Salish, and Kootenai. The Lewis and Clark Expedition explored the area in 1805 and 1806, mapping the Missouri and Yellowstone rivers. Gold discoveries in the 1860s brought a rapid influx of prospectors and established early mining camps. Montana became a United States territory in 1864 and achieved statehood in 1889. The late nineteenth century saw the rise of large-scale copper mining, particularly in Butte. The culture of Montana is influenced by its agricultural and frontier heritage, often associated with cowboy culture, rodeo events, and a strong emphasis on outdoor recreation and conservation.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Helena\n* Approximate area: 147,040 square miles\n* Approximate population: 1.1 million\n* Largest city: Billings\n* Signature features: Glacier National Park, Rocky Mountains, Great Plains, Yellowstone River",
    "summary": "Montana is a large state in the northwestern United States, characterized by the Rocky Mountains in the west and the Great Plains in the east. Its economy relies on agriculture, mining, and a growing tourism industry centered around its expansive natural parks. Helena serves as the state capital, while Billings is its largest city and primary economic hub.",
