    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nNew Hampshire is located in the New England region of the northeastern United States. It is bordered by Massachusetts to the south, Vermont to the west, Maine and the Atlantic Ocean to the east, and the Canadian province of Quebec to the north. The Connecticut River forms the entirety of its western border with Vermont.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is characterized by its mountainous terrain, extensive forests, and a short coastline. The White Mountains, a subrange of the Appalachian Mountains, dominate the northern and central parts of the state. Mount Washington is the highest peak in the northeastern United States at 6,288 feet and is known for its extreme weather conditions. The state has a heavily forested landscape, covering roughly 84 percent of its land area. Major rivers include the Merrimack River, which flows south through the center of the state, and the Connecticut River. The state also features numerous lakes, with Lake Winnipesaukee being the largest. The Atlantic coastline is the shortest of any coastal state in the country, measuring about 18 miles.\n\n## Climate\nNew Hampshire experiences a humid continental climate. This climate features warm, humid summers and long, cold, and snowy winters. Precipitation is distributed fairly evenly throughout the year. The northern and mountainous regions experience colder temperatures and heavier snowfall compared to the southern and coastal areas. Mount Washington frequently records hurricane-force winds and some of the lowest wind chill temperatures in the country. Coastal areas have slightly milder winters and cooler summers due to the moderating influence of the Atlantic Ocean.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of New Hampshire transitions from historical textile and shoemaking industries to modern sectors such as smart manufacturing, technology, and healthcare. Tourism is a major economic driver, drawing visitors for skiing, hiking, and fall foliage viewing. The state has no general sales tax or personal income tax, which influences its economic environment and attracts retail trade from neighboring states. Manchester is the largest city and serves as a major commercial hub. Concord is the administrative center and state capital. Other significant cities include Nashua, which is part of the high-tech corridor, and Portsmouth, a historic seaport city on the Atlantic coast.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Abenaki and Pennacook tribes, inhabited the region for thousands of years before European contact. English and French explorers arrived in the early seventeenth century. New Hampshire became one of the original thirteen colonies that revolted against British rule during the American Revolution. It was the first colony to establish a government independent of Great Britain and the ninth state to ratify the United States Constitution. Culturally, the state is known for its early presidential primary, which plays a significant role in the American electoral process. The state motto, \"Live Free or Die,\" reflects a strong tradition of independence and local autonomy.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Concord\n* Approximate area: 9,349 square miles\n* Approximate population: 1.4 million\n* Largest city: Manchester\n* Signature features: Mount Washington, White Mountains, first-in-the-nation presidential primary, \"Live Free or Die\" motto",
    "summary": "New Hampshire is a New England state known for its extensive forests, the rugged White Mountains, and a short Atlantic coastline. Its economy relies on technology, healthcare, and tourism, supported by a lack of general sales and personal income taxes. The state holds historical significance as one of the original thirteen colonies and plays a prominent role in modern politics with its early presidential primary.",
