    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nNevada is located in the western region of the United States. It is bordered by Oregon to the northwest, Idaho to the northeast, California to the west, Arizona to the southeast, and Utah to the east. The state is entirely landlocked.\n\n## Physical features\nNevada lies almost entirely within the Great Basin, a massive desert region characterized by basin and range topography. This landscape features numerous north-south mountain ranges separated by flat valleys. Prominent mountain ranges include the Sierra Nevada on the western edge, the Ruby Mountains, and the Snake Range, which is home to Great Basin National Park. Boundary Peak is the highest point in the state. The southern portion of Nevada transitions into the Mojave Desert. Major bodies of water include Lake Tahoe, which the state shares with California, and Lake Mead, a large reservoir formed by the Hoover Dam on the Colorado River. The Humboldt River is the longest river entirely within the state, flowing through the northern Great Basin before emptying into the Humboldt Sink.\n\n## Climate\nNevada is the driest state in the United States. The climate is predominantly arid and semi-arid. The Sierra Nevada creates a strong rain shadow effect, blocking moisture from the Pacific Ocean. Summers are generally hot, particularly in the southern Mojave Desert region where temperatures frequently exceed one hundred degrees Fahrenheit. Winters can be bitterly cold in the northern and central parts of the state, with significant snowfall occurring in the higher mountain elevations. Precipitation is sparse statewide, averaging less than ten inches annually in many areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Nevada is heavily dependent on tourism, entertainment, and gaming. Las Vegas is the primary economic hub, attracting millions of visitors annually to its casino resorts and conventions. Mining is another major industry, and Nevada is one of the largest producers of gold in the world. The state also mines silver, copper, and lithium. Agriculture is limited by the arid climate, but cattle ranching and alfalfa hay production occur in areas with access to irrigation. Las Vegas is the largest city, followed by Henderson and North Las Vegas, which are all located in the southern part of the state. Reno is a major urban center in the northwest, historically known as a gaming destination before the rise of Las Vegas. Carson City serves as the administrative center and is an independent city not part of any county.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Washoe, Northern Paiute, Southern Paiute, and Western Shoshone, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. Spanish explorers were the first Europeans to enter the area, naming it Nevada, which translates to snow-covered in Spanish. The region became part of Mexico before being ceded to the United States in 1848 following the Mexican-American War. The discovery of the Comstock Lode, a major silver deposit, in 1859 led to a population boom and the establishment of Virginia City. Nevada was admitted as the thirty-sixth state in 1864 during the American Civil War, earning it the nickname the Battle Born State. The state is also widely known as the Silver State due to the historical importance of its mining industry. In the twentieth century, the legalization of gambling in 1931 and the construction of the Hoover Dam transformed the state economy, leading to the rapid growth of Las Vegas. The state is also known for the Nevada Test Site, where nuclear weapons testing occurred during the Cold War.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Carson City\n* Approximate area: 110,572 square miles\n* Approximate population: 3.1 million\n* Largest city: Las Vegas\n* Signature features: Extensive casino and entertainment industry, Great Basin topography, large-scale gold and silver mining.",
    "summary": "Nevada is a landlocked state in the western United States known for its arid climate and basin and range topography. Its economy is heavily driven by the tourism, gaming, and mining industries, with Las Vegas serving as the primary commercial hub. Historically shaped by the silver mining boom of the Comstock Lode, the state is now defined by its vast desert landscapes and large entertainment centers.",
