    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nNew Jersey is located in the Mid-Atlantic region of the Northeastern United States. It is bordered on the north and east by New York. The Atlantic Ocean forms its eastern, southeastern, and southern borders. The Delaware River forms its western border, separating New Jersey from Pennsylvania to the west and Delaware to the southwest. The state is situated strategically between the major metropolitan areas of New York City and Philadelphia.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of New Jersey is divided into four distinct physical regions. The Ridge and Valley Appalachian region occupies the northwestern corner, featuring the Kittatinny Mountains and the Delaware Water Gap, where the Delaware River cuts through the ridges. High Point, located in this region, is the highest elevation in the state at 1,803 feet. To the southeast lies the Highlands, a belt of rugged hills, forests, and lakes, including Lake Hopatcong. Further south and east is the Piedmont plateau, which contains the majority of the state's population and industrial centers, as well as the Palisades, a line of steep cliffs along the western side of the lower Hudson River. The largest region is the Atlantic Coastal Plain, covering the southern and eastern parts of the state. This area includes the Pine Barrens, a vast expanse of sandy soil and pine forests, and the Jersey Shore, which features barrier islands, bays, and beaches along the Atlantic Ocean.\n\n## Climate\nNew Jersey experiences two main climate types. The southern, central, and eastern parts of the state have a humid subtropical climate, while the northwestern part has a humid continental climate. Summers are typically hot and humid, with average high temperatures in July ranging from the low to mid-eighties Fahrenheit. Winters are cold, with average January lows often dropping below freezing. Precipitation is relatively evenly distributed throughout the year. Coastal areas experience milder winters and cooler summers due to the moderating influence of the Atlantic Ocean, though they are also susceptible to coastal storms and occasional hurricanes during the late summer and autumn months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of New Jersey is highly diversified, with major sectors including pharmaceuticals, biotechnology, information technology, financial services, and logistics. The state is a major hub for pharmaceutical research and manufacturing. Agriculture also plays a role, with the state producing significant quantities of cranberries, blueberries, tomatoes, and bell peppers. Tourism is a major economic driver, particularly along the Jersey Shore and in Atlantic City, which is known for its casinos and boardwalk. Trenton serves as the administrative center, located on the Delaware River. Newark is the largest city, housing a major international airport and serving as a center for transportation and corporate headquarters. Other significant cities include Jersey City, known for its financial district along the Hudson River, Paterson, and Elizabeth.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the area was inhabited by the Lenape Native Americans. Dutch and Swedish colonists established the first European settlements in the early seventeenth century. The English took control of the region in 1664, naming it the Province of New Jersey. During the American Revolutionary War, New Jersey was the site of numerous pivotal battles, including the Battle of Trenton and the Battle of Princeton, earning it the nickname the Crossroads of the Revolution. In the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, the state became a major center for the Industrial Revolution, heavily driven by manufacturing in cities like Paterson and Trenton. Culturally, New Jersey is known for its diverse population, its contributions to American music, and its extensive diner culture.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Trenton\n* Approximate area: 8,722 square miles\n* Approximate population: 9.3 million\n* Largest city: Newark\n* Signature features: The Jersey Shore, the Pine Barrens, and a dense concentration of pharmaceutical industries.",
    "summary": "New Jersey is a Mid-Atlantic state situated between the major metropolitan areas of New York City and Philadelphia. It features diverse geography ranging from the Appalachian ridges in the northwest to the Pine Barrens and sandy beaches of the Atlantic Coastal Plain. The state has a highly developed economy driven by pharmaceuticals, logistics, and coastal tourism, with Trenton serving as its capital and Newark as its largest city.",
