    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nNorth Carolina is located in the southeastern region of the United States. It is bordered by Virginia to the north, the Atlantic Ocean to the east, South Carolina and Georgia to the south, and Tennessee to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is divided into three primary geographic regions: the Coastal Plain, the Piedmont, and the Appalachian Mountains. The Coastal Plain occupies the eastern 45 percent of the state. It features the Outer Banks, a string of barrier islands separated from the mainland by sounds such as the Pamlico Sound and Albemarle Sound. The Piedmont region lies in the middle of the state, characterized by rolling hills and a higher elevation. The western part of the state contains the Appalachian Mountains, specifically the Blue Ridge and Great Smoky Mountains. Mount Mitchell, located in the Black Mountains, is the highest peak in North America east of the Mississippi River at 6,684 feet. Major rivers include the Cape Fear, Neuse, Roanoke, and Yadkin rivers. The state also contains the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, which it shares with Tennessee.\n\n## Climate\nNorth Carolina experiences a humid subtropical climate across most of its area. The coastal and Piedmont regions have hot, humid summers and mild winters. The Appalachian Mountains in the west have a subtropical highland climate, which brings cooler temperatures year-round and significant snowfall during the winter months. The state receives abundant precipitation, which is relatively well distributed throughout the year. The coastal areas are vulnerable to Atlantic hurricanes and tropical storms, which frequently make landfall or brush the coastline during the late summer and autumn.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of North Carolina is diverse, transitioning from historical reliance on tobacco, textiles, and furniture to modern sectors such as technology, finance, and biotechnology. The Research Triangle Park, located between Raleigh, Durham, and Chapel Hill, is a major center for high-tech research and development. Charlotte is a major national financial hub, housing the headquarters of large banking institutions. Agriculture remains significant, with the state being a leading producer of tobacco, sweet potatoes, poultry, and pork. Major cities include Charlotte, the largest city, followed by Raleigh, Greensboro, Durham, and Winston-Salem. The coastal regions also support a large tourism and commercial fishing industry.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Cherokee, Tuscarora, and Catawba, inhabited the region for thousands of years before European contact. North Carolina was established as a royal colony in 1729 and was one of the original Thirteen Colonies that declared independence from Great Britain. It was the site of the first English attempt at colonization in North America, the Roanoke Colony, which disappeared in the late sixteenth century. During the American Civil War, North Carolina seceded from the Union in 1861 and provided significant manpower to the Confederate army. In 1903, the Wright brothers achieved the first successful powered flight at Kitty Hawk on the Outer Banks. The state has a notable cultural history, particularly in traditional music genres such as bluegrass and old-time string bands, and is known for its distinct styles of barbecue.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Raleigh\n* Approximate area: 53,819 square miles\n* Approximate population: 10.8 million\n* Largest city: Charlotte\n* Signature features: The Outer Banks, Research Triangle Park, Mount Mitchell, Wright brothers' first flight",
