    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nNew York is located in the Northeastern region of the United States. It shares international borders with the Canadian provinces of Ontario to the northwest and Quebec to the north. Domestically, it is bordered by Vermont, Massachusetts, and Connecticut to the east. To the south, it shares borders with New Jersey and Pennsylvania. New York also has a maritime border with Rhode Island east of Long Island. The state features coastlines along the Atlantic Ocean to the southeast and two Great Lakes, Lake Erie and Lake Ontario, to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of New York encompasses coastal plains, mountain ranges, and large inland bodies of water. The Adirondack Mountains dominate the northeastern part of the state, featuring Mount Marcy, the highest point in New York at 5,344 feet. South of the Adirondacks, the Appalachian Highlands extend through the central and southern regions, including the Catskill Mountains. The state is defined by several major river systems. The Hudson River flows southward from the Adirondacks to the Atlantic Ocean, forming a major navigable waterway. The Mohawk River cuts an east-west valley that historically enabled transportation across the Appalachian barrier. Other significant water bodies include the Finger Lakes in the central region and the Saint Lawrence River, which forms part of the northern border with Canada. Niagara Falls, located on the Niagara River, is a major geological feature and hydroelectric power source.\n\n## Climate\nMost of New York experiences a humid continental climate, characterized by four distinct seasons. Winters are generally cold and snowy, particularly in the northern and western parts of the state. The areas adjacent to Lake Erie and Lake Ontario frequently receive heavy lake-effect snow during the winter months. Summers are warm and humid. The southeastern portion of the state, including New York City and Long Island, transitions into a humid subtropical climate. This region experiences milder winters and hotter summers compared to the upstate regions, moderated slightly by the proximity to the Atlantic Ocean. Precipitation is relatively well distributed throughout the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nNew York has one of the largest economies in the United States, driven by finance, technology, manufacturing, and agriculture. New York City is a global financial hub, home to the New York Stock Exchange. The state also has a growing technology sector, often referred to as Silicon Alley in New York City and Tech Valley in the Capital Region. Upstate New York relies on manufacturing, education, and agriculture. The state is a leading producer of dairy products, apples, and wine. Albany serves as the administrative center, located along the Hudson River. New York City is the largest city in the state. Other major cities include Buffalo on Lake Erie, Rochester on Lake Ontario, and Syracuse in the central part of the state.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the region was inhabited by Algonquian and Iroquoian-speaking Indigenous peoples, including the Haudenosaunee Confederacy. Dutch colonists established the first European settlements in the early seventeenth century, founding New Amsterdam on Manhattan Island and Fort Orange near present-day Albany. The English took control of the territory in 1664, renaming it New York. The state played a central role in the American Revolution, hosting the pivotal Battle of Saratoga. The completion of the Erie Canal in 1825 transformed the state into a commercial powerhouse by connecting the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean. New York has historically served as a primary entry point for immigrants to the United States, symbolized by Ellis Island.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Albany\n* Approximate area: 54,555 square miles\n* Approximate population: 19.5 million\n* Largest city: New York City\n* Signature features: Niagara Falls, Statue of Liberty, Adirondack Mountains",
    "summary": "New York is a diverse Northeastern state known for its global financial hub, New York City, and significant natural features like the Adirondack Mountains and Niagara Falls. Its history as a major entry point for immigrants and a commercial powerhouse was heavily shaped by the Erie Canal and the Hudson River. Today, the state maintains a massive economy driven by finance, technology, manufacturing, and agriculture.",
