    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\n\nNorth Dakota is situated in the Upper Midwest and Great Plains regions of the United States, near the geographic center of the North American continent. It shares an international border with the Canadian provinces of Saskatchewan and Manitoba to the north. Domestically, it is bordered by Minnesota to the east, South Dakota to the south, and Montana to the west. The Red River of the North forms the entirety of the eastern boundary with Minnesota.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe state is generally divided into three major geographic regions from east to west. The Red River Valley in the east is extremely flat and fertile, formed by the ancient glacial Lake Agassiz. Moving westward, the Drift Prairie features rolling hills, shallow lakes, and sloughs carved by glacial activity. The westernmost region is the Missouri Plateau, which is part of the broader Great Plains. This area is higher in elevation and includes the Badlands, a rugged landscape shaped by wind and water erosion. The highest point in the state is White Butte, located within the Badlands. Major waterways include the Missouri River, which flows through the western part of the state. The Missouri River is impounded by the Garrison Dam, creating Lake Sakakawea, which is one of the largest human-made lakes in the United States. Theodore Roosevelt National Park preserves a significant portion of the Badlands environment.\n\n## Climate\n\nNorth Dakota experiences a continental climate, characterized by extreme temperature variations between seasons. Winters are long, cold, and snowy, with frequent blizzards and subzero temperatures. January temperatures often drop well below freezing. Summers are warm to hot, with occasional severe thunderstorms, and July temperatures can frequently exceed ninety degrees Fahrenheit. Precipitation is relatively light and decreases from east to west. The eastern part of the state receives more moisture, which supports intensive agriculture, while the western part is semi-arid.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nAgriculture is a primary driver of the North Dakota economy. The state is a leading national producer of wheat, soybeans, canola, flaxseed, and honey. Energy production is another major economic sector. North Dakota holds significant oil reserves in the Bakken formation in the west, making it one of the top oil-producing states in the country. Coal mining and wind energy generation are also important industries. In addition to agriculture and energy, the state has a growing technology sector, particularly in drone research and aviation, centered around Grand Forks. Bismarck is the administrative center, located on the Missouri River. Fargo is the largest city, situated in the southeast on the Red River, and serves as a major commercial, educational, and healthcare hub. Other significant cities include Grand Forks, Minot, and Williston.\n\n## History & culture\n\nIndigenous peoples, including the Mandan, Hidatsa, Arikara, Dakota, and Ojibwe, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. European exploration began in the eighteenth century, primarily driven by the fur trade. The Lewis and Clark Expedition wintered in central North Dakota in 1804 and 1805, where they built Fort Mandan and met Sacagawea. The region was organized as the Dakota Territory in 1861. The arrival of the Northern Pacific and Great Northern railroads in the late nineteenth century spurred rapid settlement, largely facilitated by the Homestead Act. North Dakota was admitted to the Union as the thirty-ninth state in 1889. The culture of the state is heavily influenced by its agricultural roots as well as the Scandinavian and German heritage of many early European settlers.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Bismarck\n* Approximate area: 70,700 square miles (183,000 square kilometers)\n* Approximate population: 780,000\n* Largest city: Fargo\n* Signature features: Theodore Roosevelt National Park, the Badlands, Bakken oil formation, extensive wheat and canola fields",
    "summary": "North Dakota is a Midwestern and Great Plains state known for its vast agricultural output and significant energy production from the Bakken formation. Its geography ranges from the flat, fertile Red River Valley in the east to the rugged Badlands in the west. The state features a continental climate with extreme temperature variations and has a rich history shaped by Indigenous cultures and nineteenth-century railroad expansion.",
