    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nOregon is located in the Pacific Northwest region of the western United States. It is bordered by Washington to the north, Idaho to the east, Nevada to the southeast, and California to the south. The Pacific Ocean forms its entire western boundary. The Columbia River defines much of its northern border with Washington, while the Snake River forms a significant portion of its eastern border with Idaho.\n\n## Physical features\nOregon has a diverse geography that includes a rugged coastline, dense forests, high deserts, and prominent mountain ranges. The Coast Range runs parallel to the Pacific Ocean, featuring temperate rainforests and steep cliffs. Further inland, the Cascade Range bisects the state from north to south. This volcanic range includes Mount Hood, which is the highest peak in the state at 11,249 feet, as well as Crater Lake, the deepest lake in the United States, located in a collapsed volcanic caldera. East of the Cascades lies the Columbia Plateau and the High Desert, a vast expanse of arid land characterized by sagebrush steppes, volcanic rock formations, and internal drainage basins. The Willamette Valley, situated between the Coast Range and the Cascades, is a fertile lowland where the majority of the state population resides.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Oregon varies significantly depending on the region and elevation. The coastal areas and the Willamette Valley experience a Mediterranean climate with oceanic influences. These western regions receive abundant rainfall during the winter months and have relatively dry, warm summers. The Cascade Range receives heavy winter precipitation, much of it falling as snow, which sustains glaciers and provides water for the lower valleys. East of the Cascade Range, the climate is semi-arid to arid. The High Desert region experiences greater temperature extremes, with hot summers, cold winters, and significantly less precipitation due to the rain shadow effect created by the mountains.\n\n## Economy & cities\nOregon has a mixed economy driven by agriculture, technology, manufacturing, and natural resources. The Willamette Valley is a major agricultural hub, producing hazelnuts, berries, grass seed, and wine grapes. The state is a leading producer of timber and wood products, though the technology sector has grown substantially. The area around Portland, known as the Silicon Forest, hosts numerous high-tech companies and semiconductor manufacturing facilities. Portland is the largest city in the state, serving as a major economic and cultural center with a significant inland port on the Willamette River. Salem, located south of Portland in the Willamette Valley, is the administrative center. Other notable cities include Eugene, home to the University of Oregon, and Bend, a rapidly growing city in the central high desert known for outdoor recreation.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Chinook, Bannock, and Klamath, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. European exploration began in the sixteenth century with coastal surveys by Spanish and British sailors. The Lewis and Clark Expedition reached the mouth of the Columbia River in 1805, paving the way for the fur trade and subsequent American settlement. During the 1840s, thousands of settlers migrated to the region via the Oregon Trail. Oregon was admitted to the Union as the 33rd state on February 14, 1859. The culture of the state is characterized by a strong emphasis on environmental conservation and outdoor recreation. The state was the first to enact a bottle bill to reduce litter and maintains public ownership of its entire coastline.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Salem\n* Approximate area: 98,381 square miles\n* Approximate population: 4.2 million\n* Largest city: Portland\n* Signature features: Crater Lake, Mount Hood, the Oregon Trail, extensive temperate rainforests",
    "summary": "Oregon is a Pacific Northwest state known for its diverse geography, which includes a rugged coastline, the volcanic Cascade Range, and the arid High Desert. Its economy relies on agriculture in the Willamette Valley, timber production, and a growing technology sector centered around Portland. Salem serves as the administrative center of the state, which is also recognized for its strong environmental conservation policies.",
