    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nPennsylvania is located in the Mid-Atlantic and Northeastern regions of the United States. It is bordered by New York to the north, New Jersey to the east across the Delaware River, Delaware to the southeast, Maryland to the south, West Virginia to the southwest, and Ohio to the west. The southern border with Maryland is defined by the historical Mason-Dixon line. Pennsylvania also shares a water border with the Canadian province of Ontario across Lake Erie to the northwest. Although it is landlocked from the Atlantic Ocean, the state has direct access to the ocean via the navigable Delaware River.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state is bisected diagonally by the Appalachian Mountains, which run from the southwest to the northeast. The Ridge and Valley Appalachians dominate the central part of the state, featuring long, even ridges and continuous valleys. To the west lies the Allegheny Plateau, a heavily forested region that includes the Allegheny National Forest. The eastern part of the state features the Piedmont plateau and the Atlantic Coastal Plain near Philadelphia, while the Pocono Mountains provide a prominent upland region in the northeast. The highest point is Mount Davis in the southwest. Major rivers include the Delaware River forming the eastern border, the Susquehanna River flowing through the central region, and the Ohio River, which forms at the confluence of the Allegheny and Monongahela rivers in Pittsburgh. The state also features a small shoreline along Lake Erie in the northwest.\n\n## Climate\nPennsylvania experiences a diverse climate. It is generally classified as humid continental in the northern and western regions, and humid subtropical in the extreme southeastern corner near Philadelphia. Summers are typically warm to hot and humid, while winters are cold and snowy. The mountainous central and northern areas receive significantly more snowfall, often influenced by lake-effect snow from Lake Erie in the northwestern corner. Precipitation is generally distributed evenly throughout the year. The state occasionally experiences severe weather, including nor'easters in the eastern counties during winter and occasional tornadoes during the summer months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Pennsylvania is highly diversified, with major sectors including manufacturing, agriculture, healthcare, and finance. Historically known for heavy industry and steel production, particularly in Pittsburgh, the state has transitioned toward technology, robotics, and healthcare services. Agriculture remains significant. Pennsylvania is a leading producer of mushrooms, apples, poultry, and dairy products, alongside a prominent chocolate and snack food industry centered in towns like Hershey. The state is also a major energy producer, utilizing extensive natural gas reserves in the Marcellus Shale, alongside traditional coal mining. Philadelphia is the largest city, serving as a major financial, educational, and cultural hub with a major port on the Delaware River. Pittsburgh is the second-largest city, anchoring the western part of the state. Other notable cities include Allentown, Erie, Reading, and the administrative center, Harrisburg.\n\n## History & culture\nPennsylvania was founded in 1681 by William Penn as a refuge for Quakers, establishing an early legacy of religious tolerance. It played a central role in the American Revolution. Philadelphia served as the meeting place for the Founding Fathers who drafted both the Declaration of Independence and the United States Constitution. The state was also a crucial battleground during the American Civil War, most notably at the Battle of Gettysburg in 1863, and hosted the winter encampment of the Continental Army at Valley Forge. Culturally, Pennsylvania is known for its Pennsylvania Dutch population, primarily in the south-central region, who maintain traditional agricultural lifestyles. The state has a strong sports culture and is home to numerous prestigious universities, including the University of Pennsylvania, Pennsylvania State University, and Carnegie Mellon University.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Harrisburg\n* Approximate area: Roughly 46,055 square miles (119,283 square kilometers)\n* Approximate population: About 13 million\n* Largest city: Philadelphia\n* Signature features: Independence Hall, Appalachian Mountains, historical steel industry, Pennsylvania Dutch Country",
    "summary": "Pennsylvania is a Mid-Atlantic state bisected by the Appalachian Mountains, known for its historical significance in the founding of the United States. Its diversified economy includes major sectors in energy, agriculture, and technology, anchored by the major cities of Philadelphia and Pittsburgh. The state features a varied geography ranging from the Atlantic Coastal Plain to the Allegheny Plateau and a shoreline along Lake Erie.",
