    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nRhode Island is located in the New England region of the northeastern United States. It is bordered by Massachusetts to the north and east, and Connecticut to the west. To the south, the state shares a maritime border with New York in the waters of Block Island Sound and the Atlantic Ocean. It is the smallest state in the country by total area, measuring roughly forty-eight miles long and thirty-seven miles wide.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Rhode Island is dominated by the Narragansett Bay, which extends southward into the Atlantic Ocean and contains over thirty islands. The largest of these is Aquidneck Island, officially named Rhode Island, which gives the state its name. Other notable islands include Conanicut Island, Prudence Island, and Block Island, which is located about nine miles south of the mainland. The state is generally flat with no significant mountain ranges. The highest natural point is Jerimoth Hill, standing at roughly 812 feet above sea level in the northwestern part of the state near the Connecticut border. Major waterways include the Blackstone River, which flows south from Massachusetts into the Seekonk and Providence rivers, and the Pawcatuck River, which forms part of the southwestern border with Connecticut. The coastline is characterized by sandy beaches, rocky shores, and numerous inlets, providing extensive saltwater access despite the small land area.\n\n## Climate\nRhode Island experiences a humid continental climate, though its southern coastal areas transition into a humid subtropical climate. Summers are typically warm and humid, while winters are cold and snowy. The Atlantic Ocean heavily influences the weather, moderating temperatures along the coast compared to the inland areas. Precipitation is distributed fairly evenly throughout the year. The state is occasionally affected by severe weather events, including winter storms known as nor'easters, and tropical storms or hurricanes in the late summer and autumn months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Rhode Island is based on healthcare, education, manufacturing, and financial services. Historically recognized for textiles and jewelry making, the modern manufacturing sector focuses heavily on submarine construction, shipbuilding, and ocean technology. Tourism is also a significant industry, driven by the coastal beaches and historic sites. Providence is the administrative center and most populous city, serving as a regional hub for higher education and healthcare. Other major cities include Warwick, known for hosting the primary commercial airport of the state, and Cranston. Newport, located on Aquidneck Island, is recognized for its maritime history, naval base, and large historic mansions. Pawtucket, situated on the Blackstone River, played a central role in the early American Industrial Revolution.\n\n## History & culture\nRhode Island was founded in 1636 by Roger Williams, a religious exile from the Massachusetts Bay Colony who sought to establish a settlement based on religious freedom and the separation of church and state. It was the first of the original Thirteen Colonies to declare independence from Great Britain in 1776, and the last to ratify the United States Constitution in 1790. The state has a significant maritime history, reflected in its long tradition of sailing, fishing, and naval operations. The culture is heavily influenced by early English colonists, as well as later waves of Irish, Italian, and Portuguese immigrants. The state is also home to Brown University and the Rhode Island School of Design, which contribute significantly to the academic landscape of Providence.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Providence\n* Approximate area: 1,214 square miles\n* Approximate population: 1.1 million\n* Signature features: Narragansett Bay, historic Newport mansions, Block Island, smallest US state by area",
    "summary": "Rhode Island is the smallest state in the United States, located in the New England region and heavily defined by the waters of Narragansett Bay. Its economy relies on healthcare, education, and maritime industries, with Providence serving as the administrative center. Founded on principles of religious freedom, the state features a rich history tied to the early American Industrial Revolution and naval operations.",
