    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\n\nTexas is located in the South Central region of the United States. It shares international borders with the Mexican states of Chihuahua, Coahuila, Nuevo Leon, and Tamaulipas to the southwest. Within the United States, it is bordered by New Mexico to the west, Oklahoma to the north, Arkansas to the northeast, and Louisiana to the east. The southeastern boundary of the state is formed by the coastline of the Gulf of Mexico.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe state encompasses a diverse range of landscapes, divided into several major geographic regions. The Gulf Coastal Plains stretch from the Gulf of Mexico inland, featuring low-lying terrain, marshes, and pine forests in the east, known as the Piney Woods. The Interior Lowlands cover much of the northern and central parts of the state, characterized by rolling hills and agricultural land. The Great Plains extend into the Texas Panhandle and central-west areas, including the Llano Estacado and the Edwards Plateau. The Basin and Range Province in the extreme west contains the highest terrain in the state, including the Guadalupe Mountains. Guadalupe Peak is the highest point at 8,751 feet. Major rivers include the Rio Grande, which forms the international border with Mexico, as well as the Pecos, Brazos, Colorado, and Trinity rivers. Notable protected areas include Big Bend National Park and Guadalupe Mountains National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nTexas experiences a wide variety of climate types due to its vast size. The eastern half of the state generally has a humid subtropical climate, characterized by hot summers and mild winters, with significant annual rainfall. The western half transitions into a semi-arid and arid climate, receiving much less precipitation and experiencing greater temperature extremes. The Panhandle region experiences colder winters with occasional snowfall. The Gulf Coast is susceptible to extreme weather events, including hurricanes and tropical storms, particularly during the late summer and autumn months. Tornadoes are common in the northern and central regions, which lie at the southern end of Tornado Alley.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Texas is one of the largest in the United States and includes multiple major industries. Historically rooted in cattle ranching, cotton farming, and oil production, the modern economy includes sectors such as technology, manufacturing, aerospace, and energy. The state is a leading producer of crude oil and natural gas, while also generating renewable energy through wind power. Major urban centers drive regional economies. Houston is the largest city and a center for the energy and biomedical industries. The Dallas-Fort Worth metroplex is a node for telecommunications, finance, and transportation. Austin, the administrative center, contains a large technology sector. San Antonio features a strong military presence and a tourism industry.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHuman habitation in the region dates back thousands of years, with Indigenous groups such as the Comanche, Apache, and Caddo living in the area before European arrival. The Spanish established the first European settlements in the seventeenth century. Texas became part of independent Mexico in 1821. Following the Texas Revolution in 1836, the region became the independent Republic of Texas before being annexed by the United States in 1845. The state seceded during the American Civil War and was readmitted in 1870. The culture of Texas reflects a blend of Southern, Western, and Mexican influences. This is evident in the state cuisine, such as Tex-Mex and barbecue, and its musical traditions, which include country, blues, and Tejano music.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Austin\n* Approximate area: 268,596 square miles\n* Approximate population: 30 million\n* Largest city: Houston\n* Signature features: The Alamo, space exploration facilities in Houston, extensive cattle ranches, and the Rio Grande border",
    "summary": "Texas is a large state located in the South Central region of the United States, known for its diverse geography that ranges from coastal plains to arid western mountains. Its economy is one of the largest in the country, driven by energy, technology, and agriculture across major cities like Houston, Dallas, and Austin. The state possesses a unique cultural heritage shaped by its history as a Spanish colony, a Mexican province, and an independent republic before joining the United States.",
