    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nWashington is located in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States. It is bordered by the Canadian province of British Columbia to the north, Idaho to the east, Oregon to the south, and the Pacific Ocean to the west. The Columbia River forms much of its southern boundary with Oregon, while the Strait of Juan de Fuca separates the state from Canada's Vancouver Island to the northwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state has diverse geography divided into several distinct regions. The Olympic Peninsula in the west features the Olympic Mountains and a dense temperate rainforest. The Puget Sound lowlands run north to south, containing deep-water harbors and numerous islands. The Cascade Range bisects the state from north to south, featuring prominent stratovolcanoes such as Mount Rainier, Mount St. Helens, Mount Baker, Mount Adams, and Glacier Peak. Eastern Washington is characterized by the Columbia Plateau, a semi-arid region shaped by ancient basalt flows and massive glacial floods that created the Channeled Scablands. Major rivers include the Columbia River, the Snake River, and the Yakima River. The state contains three national parks: Olympic, Mount Rainier, and North Cascades.\n\n## Climate\nThe Cascade Range creates a significant climatic divide across the state. Western Washington experiences an oceanic climate with mild, wet winters and relatively dry, cool summers. The western slopes of the Olympic Peninsula receive some of the highest precipitation in the continental United States, often exceeding 150 inches annually. Eastern Washington lies in the rain shadow of the Cascades, resulting in a semi-arid climate. This eastern region experiences much greater temperature extremes, with hot, dry summers and cold, snowy winters. Precipitation in the east is significantly lower, often falling below 20 inches per year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nWashington has a robust economy driven by aerospace, technology, agriculture, forestry, and international trade. The Seattle metropolitan area is a major global hub for software development, e-commerce, and cloud computing, hosting the headquarters of Microsoft and Amazon. The region is also historically significant for commercial aircraft manufacturing, led by Boeing. The ports of Seattle and Tacoma handle a massive volume of trans-Pacific maritime trade. In eastern Washington, agriculture is a primary economic driver. The state is the leading producer of apples, sweet cherries, and hops in the United States, and it has a prominent wine industry. Major cities include Seattle, which is the largest city, Spokane in the east, Tacoma, Vancouver, Bellevue, and the administrative center, Olympia. The state relies heavily on hydroelectric power generated by large dams on the Columbia River, such as the Grand Coulee Dam.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples have inhabited the region for thousands of years. Prominent groups include the Coast Salish, Chinook, Yakama, and Nez Perce tribes, who relied heavily on salmon fishing and cedar forests. European exploration began in the late eighteenth century with Spanish and British expeditions mapping the coastline. The Lewis and Clark Expedition reached the area in 1805. The region was part of the Oregon Country, jointly occupied by the United States and Britain until the Oregon Treaty of 1846 established the 49th parallel as the international border. Washington Territory was created in 1853, and Washington was admitted as the 42nd state in 1889. Early economic growth was fueled by logging, fishing, and mining. Today, the culture of the state is heavily influenced by its natural environment, fostering strong traditions in outdoor recreation, environmental conservation, and a globally recognized coffee culture.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Olympia\n* Approximate area: 71,300 square miles (184,660 square kilometers)\n* Approximate population: 7.8 million\n* Largest city: Seattle\n* Signature features: Mount Rainier, Puget Sound, leading producer of apples and hops",
    "summary": "Washington is a Pacific Northwest state known for its diverse geography, which ranges from the temperate rainforests of the Olympic Peninsula to the semi-arid Columbia Plateau. The state has a robust economy driven by the technology and aerospace industries in the Seattle area, alongside significant agricultural production in the east. Bisected by the Cascade Range, Washington is defined by its prominent stratovolcanoes, deep-water ports, and extensive hydroelectric infrastructure.",
