    "mainNotes": "## Location within United States\nWest Virginia is a landlocked state located in the Appalachian region of the Southern United States, though it is often considered part of the Mid-Atlantic region. It shares borders with five states. Pennsylvania lies to the north, Maryland to the northeast, and Virginia to the southeast and south. Kentucky borders it to the southwest, and Ohio is located to the northwest across the Ohio River. The state is known for its irregular shape, featuring two distinct panhandles. The Northern Panhandle extends between Pennsylvania and Ohio, while the Eastern Panhandle stretches between Maryland and Virginia.\n\n## Physical features\nWest Virginia is entirely located within the Appalachian Mountain system, earning it the nickname the Mountain State. It is the only state in the nation with its entire area falling within this mountain range. The state features rugged terrain, deep river valleys, and rolling hills. The Allegheny Mountains dominate the eastern portion of the state, containing Spruce Knob, which is the highest point in West Virginia at about 4,863 feet. To the west, the Allegheny Plateau gradually slopes toward the Ohio River. Major rivers include the Ohio River, which forms the western boundary, and the Kanawha River, which flows through the capital. The New River, despite its name, is one of the oldest rivers on the continent and flows through the New River Gorge, a prominent national park and preserve. The state is heavily forested, with broadleaf deciduous trees covering roughly three-quarters of its land area.\n\n## Climate\nThe state experiences a humid subtropical climate at lower elevations, particularly in the southwestern valleys, and a humid continental climate in the higher elevations of the mountains. Summers are generally warm to hot and humid, while winters are cold. The mountainous regions receive significantly more snowfall than the lower valleys. Precipitation is relatively well distributed throughout the year. The eastern panhandle and the Ohio River valley tend to have milder winters compared to the central Appalachian ridges. Fog is a common occurrence in the river valleys, especially during the morning hours.\n\n## Economy & cities\nHistorically, the economy of West Virginia was heavily dependent on coal mining and logging. While coal remains a significant export and energy source, the state has diversified its economy to include chemical manufacturing, biotechnology, aerospace, and tourism. The chemical industry is particularly concentrated in the Kanawha River valley. Agriculture plays a smaller role, with poultry, cattle, and apples being primary products. Charleston, located at the confluence of the Elk and Kanawha rivers, is the administrative center and the most populous city. Huntington, situated along the Ohio River, is the second-largest city and serves as a major port and industrial center. Morgantown, located in the north, is a prominent educational and research hub.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European settlement, the area was used as hunting grounds by various Native American groups, including the Iroquois and Shawnee. European exploration began in the late seventeenth century, followed by settlement by people of English, Scotch-Irish, and German descent. West Virginia has a unique political origin. It separated from Virginia during the American Civil War because the western counties opposed secession from the Union. The state was officially admitted to the Union in 1863. The culture of West Virginia is deeply rooted in Appalachian traditions. This heritage is evident in its regional music, particularly bluegrass and old-time string bands, as well as traditional crafts and folklore. The state also has a strong labor history associated with the unionization of coal miners in the early twentieth century.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: United States\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Charleston\n* Approximate area: 24,230 square miles\n* Approximate population: 1.77 million\n* Largest city: Charleston\n* Signature features: Entirely within the Appalachian Mountains, New River Gorge National Park, coal mining heritage",
    "summary": "West Virginia is a landlocked state in the Appalachian region of the United States, known for being the only state entirely within the Appalachian Mountain range. Its economy was historically dominated by coal mining and logging, though it has since diversified into chemical manufacturing and tourism. The state was formed during the American Civil War when its western counties refused to secede from the Union with the rest of Virginia.",
