    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\n\nHainan is an island province located in the southernmost part of the People's Republic of China. It is separated from the Leizhou Peninsula of Guangdong province to the north by the shallow Qiongzhou Strait. To the west lies the Gulf of Tonkin, and to the east and south is the South China Sea. The province officially administers several disputed archipelagos in the South China Sea, including the Paracel Islands, Spratly Islands, and Macclesfield Bank, though sovereignty over these maritime features is contested by multiple neighboring countries.\n\n## Physical features\n\nHainan Island is the largest island under the undisputed control of the People's Republic of China. The terrain is characterized by a central mountainous region that gradually slopes down to flat coastal plains. Wuzhi Mountain, or Five Finger Mountain, is the highest peak, reaching an elevation of 1,867 meters. The island features a dense network of rivers radiating outward from the central highlands. The Nandu River is the longest, flowing north into the Qiongzhou Strait, while the Changhua River flows west and the Wanquan River flows east. The coastline is marked by numerous bays, such as Yalong Bay and Sanya Bay, and the province includes protected areas like the Hainan Tropical Rainforest National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe province experiences a tropical monsoon climate. Temperatures remain warm to hot throughout the year, with minimal variation between seasons. The region has a distinct wet season from May to October, driven by the summer monsoon, and a drier season from November to April. Hainan is frequently affected by typhoons during the late summer and autumn months, bringing heavy rainfall and strong winds to the coastal areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nHainan has an economy heavily reliant on agriculture, tourism, and free trade initiatives. The agricultural sector produces tropical crops, including rubber, coconuts, pepper, and tropical fruits. Tourism is a major industry, particularly in the southern city of Sanya, which is a major destination for domestic travelers. The provincial government has been developing the entire island into a free trade port to attract foreign investment and international business. Haikou, located on the northern coast, is the administrative center, the largest city, and the primary industrial and commercial hub. Other notable cities include Danzhou in the northwest and Qionghai on the eastern coast. The Wenchang Spacecraft Launch Site, a major national facility, is located on the northeastern coast.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, Hainan was considered a remote frontier region of the Chinese empire, often used as a place of exile for disgraced officials, including the Song dynasty poet Su Shi. It was administratively part of Guangdong province for centuries before becoming a separate province in 1988. The island is home to a diverse population. The Han Chinese constitute the majority, but the province has a significant population of the indigenous Li people, who primarily reside in the central and southern mountainous areas. The Miao and Hui peoples also form notable minority communities. The local culture features distinct culinary traditions, such as Wenchang chicken, and traditional Li textile weaving.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Haikou\n* Approximate area: 35,354 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 10 million\n* Largest city: Haikou\n* Signature features: Tropical beach resorts, Wuzhi Mountain, Wenchang Spacecraft Launch Site",
    "summary": "Hainan is a tropical island province in southern China known for its agricultural production, free trade port development, and tourism industry. Its geography features central highlands, such as Wuzhi Mountain, surrounded by coastal plains and major cities like Haikou and Sanya. The province also officially administers several disputed archipelagos in the South China Sea.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
