    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nGuizhou is a landlocked province located in the southwestern region of the People's Republic of China. It shares borders with several other provincial-level administrative divisions. To the north, it is bounded by Sichuan province and the direct-administered municipality of Chongqing. Hunan province lies to the east, while the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region is situated to the south. Yunnan province borders Guizhou to the west. The province sits on the eastern end of the Yunnan-Guizhou Plateau, serving as a transitional zone between the high-altitude Tibetan Plateau to the west and the lower hills and plains to the east.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Guizhou is highly mountainous and rugged, with mountains and hills making up roughly 92 percent of its total land area. The province is famous for its extensive karst landscapes, which feature limestone formations, deep gorges, natural bridges, sinkholes, and extensive cave systems. Major mountain ranges include the Wumeng Mountains in the west, the Dalou Mountains in the north, and the Miaoling Mountains in the south-central region. The highest peak is Jiucaiping, reaching an elevation of about 2,900 meters. Guizhou is divided by two major river basins. The northern and central areas drain into the Yangtze River basin, primarily through the Wu River. The southern areas drain into the Pearl River basin via the Beipan River and Nanpan River. The province is also home to Huangguoshu Waterfall, which is one of the largest waterfalls in East Asia.\n\n## Climate\nGuizhou experiences a humid subtropical monsoon climate. The province is known for its relatively mild temperatures year-round, avoiding severe cold in the winter and extreme heat in the summer. Average January temperatures range from 1 to 10 degrees Celsius, while July temperatures typically range from 17 to 28 degrees Celsius. The region receives abundant precipitation, mostly concentrated in the summer months. Guizhou is noted for its high humidity and frequent cloud cover. A traditional Chinese saying describes the province as rarely having three consecutive days of clear weather.\n\n## Economy & cities\nHistorically considered one of China's least economically developed provinces, Guizhou has experienced rapid economic growth in the twenty-first century. The province has leveraged its cool climate and abundant hydroelectric power to become a major hub for the big data and cloud computing industries. Tech companies have established large data centers in the Gui'an New Area. Traditional industries include coal mining, electricity generation, tobacco production, and the manufacturing of Moutai, a highly prized brand of baijiu liquor. Guiyang is the administrative center and the largest city, acting as the political and commercial hub. Other major cities include Zunyi, known for its historical significance, Liupanshui, an industrial center focused on coal, and Anshun, a gateway to regional tourism.\n\n## History & culture\nHuman habitation in Guizhou dates back to prehistoric times, but it was formally established as a province during the Ming dynasty in 1413. For centuries, the region was governed through the tusi system, where local tribal leaders ruled on behalf of the imperial court. The Qing dynasty later replaced these local leaders with imperial officials to integrate the region more closely with the central government. During the twentieth century, Guizhou played a critical role in the Chinese Communist Party's Long March. The 1935 Zunyi Conference was a pivotal event that solidified Mao Zedong's leadership. Culturally, Guizhou is highly diverse. Ethnic minorities make up roughly 36 percent of the population. The largest minority groups include the Miao, Bouyei, Dong, Tujia, and Yi peoples, who maintain distinct architectural styles, festivals, and textile traditions.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Guiyang\n* Approximate area: 176,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 38.5 million\n* Largest city: Guiyang\n* Signature features: Extensive karst topography, big data industry hubs, Huangguoshu Waterfall, and diverse ethnic minority cultures.",
    "summary": "Guizhou is a mountainous, landlocked province in southwestern China known for its extensive karst landscapes and diverse ethnic minority populations. Historically one of the country's less developed regions, it has recently experienced rapid economic growth by becoming a major hub for the big data and cloud computing industries. The province is administered from Guiyang and features significant natural landmarks like the Huangguoshu Waterfall.",
