    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nHebei is a province located in the North China region. It is notable for completely surrounding the national capital municipality of Beijing, as well as bordering the municipality of Tianjin. The province shares borders with Liaoning to the northeast, Inner Mongolia to the north, Shanxi to the west, Henan to the south, and Shandong to the southeast. To the east, Hebei has a coastline along the Bohai Sea, which is the innermost gulf of the Yellow Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Hebei transitions from mountainous regions in the north and west to a broad plain in the southeast. The Yan Mountains, or Yanshan, run east to west across the northern part of the province. The Taihang Mountains form a natural boundary along the western border with Shanxi. The central and southern areas are part of the North China Plain, which is relatively flat and highly suitable for agriculture. The province is primarily drained by the Hai River system, which flows into the Bohai Sea. The Luan River is another major waterway in the northeast. Baiyangdian, located in the central part of the province, is the largest freshwater lake in northern China.\n\n## Climate\nHebei experiences a temperate continental monsoon climate. Winters are cold and dry, heavily influenced by the Siberian high pressure system. Summers are hot and humid, with the majority of the annual precipitation falling during July and August due to the East Asian monsoon. Spring is typically dry and can bring sandstorms originating from the Mongolian plateau. The climate varies significantly with elevation. The mountainous regions in the north and west have cooler average temperatures and shorter growing seasons compared to the southeastern plains.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Hebei is heavily industrialized. The province is the leading producer of steel and iron in China, supporting significant manufacturing and construction sectors. Coal mining and textiles are also major industries. On the North China Plain, agriculture is a vital economic component, with farmers cultivating wheat, maize, cotton, and peanuts. Shijiazhuang is the administrative center and the most populous city, functioning as a crucial railway hub for the region. Tangshan is a major industrial center known for its steel production and its recovery from a devastating earthquake in 1976. Qinhuangdao serves as a major port on the Bohai Sea. The national government is currently developing the Xiong'an New Area in central Hebei to serve as a new metropolis and relieve Beijing of non-essential capital functions.\n\n## History & culture\nThe name Hebei translates to north of the river, referring to its location entirely north of the Yellow River. During the Qing dynasty, the region was known as Zhili, meaning directly ruled, because it was administered directly by the imperial court in Beijing. The province contains significant historical landmarks. The Great Wall of China crosses northern Hebei and meets the Bohai Sea at Shanhai Pass in Qinhuangdao. Chengde, located in the northeast, features the Mountain Resort, a vast summer palace complex built by Qing emperors that is now a UNESCO World Heritage site. The province is also known for traditional arts, including Wuqiang New Year pictures and various local forms of Chinese opera.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Shijiazhuang\n* Approximate area: 188,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 74 million\n* Largest city: Shijiazhuang\n* Signature features: Surrounds Beijing and Tianjin, Shanhai Pass of the Great Wall, leading center of Chinese steel production",
    "summary": "Hebei is a northern Chinese province that geographically surrounds the national capital of Beijing and the municipality of Tianjin. Its landscape transitions from the Taihang and Yan mountains in the north and west to the agricultural North China Plain in the south. The province is a major industrial hub, leading the country in steel production, and features historical sites like the Shanhai Pass of the Great Wall.",
