    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nAnhui is a landlocked province located in the eastern region of the People's Republic of China. It shares borders with several other major provinces. To the northeast lies Jiangsu, while Zhejiang is located to the southeast. Jiangxi borders Anhui to the south, and Hubei is situated to the southwest. Henan forms the northwestern border, and a very short border with Shandong exists to the extreme north. The province sits across the basins of two major Chinese rivers, acting as a transitional zone between northern and southern China.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Anhui is highly diverse, generally divided into three main regions by the Huai River in the north and the Yangtze River in the south. The area north of the Huai River is part of the flat North China Plain. The central region, located between the Huai and Yangtze rivers, consists of rolling hills and the Jianghuai Plain. The southern third of the province is dominated by rugged mountain ranges. The Dabie Mountains lie along the southwestern border with Hubei. Southern Anhui is famous for the Huangshan mountain range, also known as the Yellow Mountains, which features steep granite peaks and ancient pine trees. Mount Jiuhua, one of the four sacred mountains of Chinese Buddhism, is also located in this southern region. Lake Chao, or Chaohu, is one of the largest freshwater lakes in China and sits in the central part of the province near Hefei.\n\n## Climate\nAnhui experiences a transitional climate that varies significantly from north to south. The region north of the Huai River has a temperate monsoon climate, characterized by colder, drier winters and hot summers. The area south of the Huai River features a subtropical monsoon climate, which brings milder winters and higher annual precipitation. The province has four distinct seasons. During early summer, southern and central Anhui experience the East Asian rainy season, commonly referred to as the plum rain season, which brings heavy and prolonged rainfall.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Anhui relies on a mix of agriculture, heavy industry, and manufacturing. The northern plains are major producers of wheat and sorghum, while the southern regions cultivate rice and tea. Anhui is a prominent center for the automotive industry, hosting the headquarters of companies like Chery in Wuhu and serving as a major manufacturing hub for electric vehicles in Hefei. Other significant industries include coal mining in Huainan, steel production in Ma'anshan, and the manufacturing of home appliances. Hefei is the administrative center and largest city, recognized as a growing national hub for science and technology. Other major urban centers include Wuhu, a major port on the Yangtze River, as well as Bengbu and Anqing.\n\n## History & culture\nThe province was formally established in the seventeenth century during the Qing dynasty. The name Anhui is a portmanteau derived from two historical cities, Anqing and Huizhou. The southern region is the birthplace of Hui culture, which is noted for its distinctive Huizhou architecture featuring white walls and dark tiles. Traditional Hui merchants were historically among the most powerful trading groups in China. The region is also the origin of Hui opera, which heavily influenced the development of modern Peking opera. The ancient villages of Xidi and Hongcun preserve traditional Huizhou layouts and are recognized as UNESCO World Heritage sites. Anhui is also renowned for its tea production, including Keemun black tea and Huangshan Maofeng green tea.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Hefei\n* Approximate area: 139,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 61 million\n* Largest city: Hefei\n* Signature features: The granite peaks of Huangshan (Yellow Mountains), traditional Huizhou architecture, and the transitional Huai River boundary.",
    "summary": "Anhui is a landlocked province in eastern China that serves as a geographical and cultural transition zone between the northern plains and the southern mountains. The province is divided by the Huai and Yangtze rivers and is known for its heavy industries, agricultural output, and technological development in its capital, Hefei. It is also celebrated for its historical Hui culture and the striking granite peaks of the Yellow Mountains.",
