    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nHeilongjiang is the northernmost and easternmost province of the People's Republic of China, located in the northeast. The province shares domestic borders with Jilin province to the south and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region to the west. Internationally, Heilongjiang shares a long border with the Russian Federation to the north and east. This international boundary is primarily defined by the Amur River and the Ussuri River. The northernmost point of China is in Heilongjiang near Mohe, and the easternmost point is at the confluence of the Amur and Ussuri rivers.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is named after the Heilong River, the Chinese name for the Amur. The topography of Heilongjiang is characterized by mountain ranges, vast plains, and extensive river systems. The Greater Khingan Range runs along the western border with Inner Mongolia. The Lesser Khingan Range dominates the northern part of the province. In the southeast, the Zhangguangcai, Laoyeling, and Wanda mountain ranges form a rugged landscape. Between these mountain systems lie two major plains. The Songnen Plain is located in the southwest, and the Sanjiang Plain is situated in the northeast. Major rivers include the Amur, the Songhua, the Ussuri, and the Mudan. Lake Khanka is a large freshwater lake located on the southeastern border with Russia.\n\n## Climate\nHeilongjiang experiences a humid continental climate in its southern and central regions, while the northernmost areas have a subarctic climate. The province is known for its long, severely cold winters and short, warm summers. The Siberian high pressure system dominates the winter weather, bringing dry and freezing conditions. January temperatures average roughly minus 31 degrees Celsius in the north to minus 15 degrees Celsius in the south. Summers are influenced by the East Asian monsoon, which brings the majority of the annual precipitation. Average July temperatures range from 18 to 23 degrees Celsius. The frost-free period is relatively short, lasting between three and five months depending on the latitude.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Heilongjiang has historically been driven by heavy industry and agriculture. It is a key part of Northeast China, a region formerly known as the industrial heartland of the country. The province is rich in natural resources, including coal, timber, and petroleum. The Daqing oil field is one of the largest and most productive in China. Agriculture is highly developed due to the presence of fertile black soil. Major crops include soybeans, maize, wheat, and rice. Harbin is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a major hub for transportation, education, and commerce. Other significant cities include Qiqihar, known for its heavy machinery manufacturing, Daqing, centered around the petrochemical industry, and Mudanjiang, a regional transport hub near the Russian border.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was historically inhabited by various Tungusic peoples, including the ancestors of the Jurchen and the Manchu. During the Qing dynasty, the area was initially restricted from Han Chinese settlement, but this policy was reversed in the late nineteenth century to counter Russian expansion. This led to a massive migration of Han Chinese farmers into the region. In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the construction of the Chinese Eastern Railway brought significant Russian influence to the area. This influence is still visible in the architecture and culture of Harbin. In the 1930s and 1940s, Heilongjiang was occupied by the Japanese Empire as part of Manchukuo. Today, the culture is predominantly Han Chinese, but it retains elements of Manchu heritage and Russian cultural remnants.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Harbin\n* Approximate area: 454,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 31 million\n* Largest city: Harbin\n* Signature features: The Harbin International Ice and Snow Sculpture Festival, the Daqing oil field, and the northernmost point of China at Mohe.",
    "summary": "Heilongjiang is China's northernmost and easternmost province, known for its severely cold winters, fertile agricultural plains, and historical heavy industry. Bordering Russia along the Amur and Ussuri rivers, the province features a unique blend of Han Chinese, indigenous Tungusic, and Russian cultural influences. Its administrative center, Harbin, serves as a major economic hub and is famous for its annual ice sculpture festival.",
