    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nHenan is a landlocked province located in the central part of the People's Republic of China. It is often referred to as the Central Plains region. The province shares borders with six other provincial-level administrative divisions. To the north, it is bounded by Hebei and Shanxi. Shaanxi lies to the west, while Hubei is located to the south. Anhui borders Henan to the east and southeast, and Shandong is situated to the northeast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Henan is characterized by a transition from mountainous terrain in the west to expansive plains in the east. The eastern and central portions of the province are part of the North China Plain, which is flat and highly suitable for agriculture. In the west, the landscape is dominated by the Funiu Mountains, an eastern extension of the Qinling mountain range. The Taihang Mountains form part of the northwestern border, and the Dabie Mountains lie along the southern border with Hubei.\n\nTwo major river systems flow through the province. The Yellow River, or Huang He, flows west to east through the northern part of Henan. It enters the North China Plain near the city of Luoyang and passes through the capital, Zhengzhou. The Huai River originates in the Tongbai Mountains in southern Henan and flows eastward, serving as a traditional geographic dividing line between northern and southern China.\n\n## Climate\nHenan experiences a continental monsoon climate that transitions between humid subtropical in the south and humid continental in the north. The province has four distinct seasons. Winters are generally cold and dry, particularly in the northern areas influenced by Siberian anticyclones. Summers are hot and humid, driven by the East Asian monsoon, which brings the majority of the region's annual precipitation between June and August. Spring and autumn are relatively short and transitional. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 12 to 16 degrees Celsius, with precipitation decreasing from the southeast to the northwest.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Henan relies heavily on agriculture, industry, and manufacturing. The province is one of China's leading producers of wheat, sesame, and cotton, making it a critical region for national food security. Industrial sectors include coal mining, aluminum processing, and food production. In recent decades, manufacturing and technology have expanded significantly. The capital city, Zhengzhou, is a major national transportation hub and a center for electronics manufacturing, notably hosting large facilities that produce smartphones.\n\nOther major cities include Luoyang, Kaifeng, Anyang, and Nanyang. Luoyang and Kaifeng are historically significant cities that have modernized their economies with heavy industry and tourism. Nanyang, located in the southwest, is the province's most populous municipality by administrative area and focuses on agriculture and manufacturing.\n\n## History & culture\nHenan is widely recognized as a primary cradle of Chinese civilization. The region was the political and cultural center of China for roughly three thousand years. It contains four of the Eight Great Ancient Capitals of China, which are Luoyang, Kaifeng, Anyang, and Zhengzhou. The ruins of Yin, located near Anyang, served as the capital of the late Shang dynasty and yielded the earliest known examples of Chinese writing on oracle bones.\n\nThe province is also home to significant religious and cultural sites. Mount Song, located near the city of Dengfeng, is one of the Five Great Mountains of China. It is the site of the Shaolin Temple, famous for its association with Chan Buddhism and martial arts. Near Luoyang, the Longmen Grottoes contain tens of thousands of Buddhist statues carved into limestone cliffs, representing a peak of Chinese stone carving art.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Zhengzhou\n* Approximate area: 167,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 98 million\n* Largest city: Zhengzhou\n* Signature features: Yellow River valley, Shaolin Temple, Four Great Ancient Capitals of China",
    "summary": "Henan is a populous, landlocked province in central China that serves as a major agricultural and transportation hub. Geographically divided by the Yellow and Huai rivers, it transitions from western mountains to the expansive North China Plain in the east. As a primary cradle of Chinese civilization, the province is home to numerous historical sites, including four ancient capitals and the Shaolin Temple.",
