    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nGansu is a province located in the northwest region of the People's Republic of China. It is identifiable on a map by its elongated shape, which stretches from the northwest to the southeast. The province shares a brief international border with Mongolia to the north. Domestically, it is bordered by the autonomous regions of Inner Mongolia to the north and northeast, Ningxia to the east, and Xinjiang to the west. It also shares borders with the provinces of Shaanxi to the east, Sichuan to the south, and Qinghai to the south and southwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Gansu is diverse and elevated, situated at the intersection of the Loess Plateau, the Tibetan Plateau, and the Mongolian Plateau. A defining geographical feature is the Hexi Corridor, a narrow, elongated passage of arable land situated between the high Qilian Mountains to the south and the Gobi Desert to the north. The Qilian Mountains form a natural boundary with Qinghai province, featuring peaks that exceed 5,000 meters in elevation.\n\nThe Yellow River flows through the southern portion of the province, passing directly through the administrative center of Lanzhou. In the arid northwestern region, inland river systems such as the Shule River and the Ruo Shui provide water to local oases before terminating in desert basins. The landscape in the north and west transitions into arid desert, merging with the Gobi Desert and the Badain Jaran Desert.\n\n## Climate\nGansu experiences a transition of climate zones, ranging from a semi-arid continental climate in the southeast to a strictly arid climate in the northwest. The southeastern region, near the Loess Plateau, receives the most precipitation and experiences relatively mild temperatures. As one moves northwest along the Hexi Corridor, the climate becomes increasingly dry.\n\nWinters across the province are generally long and cold, while summers can be hot in the desert regions and milder in the higher elevations. The northwestern areas receive minimal rainfall and are subject to large temperature fluctuations between day and night. Spring often brings strong winds and sandstorms, particularly in the areas bordering the Gobi Desert.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Gansu is supported by mining, heavy industry, and agriculture. The province holds large reserves of non-ferrous metals. The city of Jinchang is a center for nickel production, while Yumen has a long history of oil extraction. Lanzhou serves as an industrial hub, particularly for petrochemicals, metallurgy, and machinery manufacturing. The province has also developed large-scale wind and solar power projects in its western desert regions.\n\nAgriculture is concentrated in the southeastern river valleys and the oases of the Hexi Corridor. Farmers cultivate wheat, maize, cotton, and various melons. Major cities include Lanzhou, the largest city and administrative center, as well as Tianshui in the southeast. Jiuquan is a prominent city in the northwest, located near a national aerospace launch center, while Jiayuguan is a center for steel production.\n\n## History & culture\nGansu holds historical importance as the primary route of the ancient Silk Road. The Hexi Corridor served as the main artery connecting the Chinese heartland with Central Asia, facilitating trade and cultural exchange. The province contains the western terminus of the Ming Dynasty Great Wall, located at the Jiayuguan pass.\n\nThe region contains notable Buddhist heritage sites. The Mogao Caves near the city of Dunhuang hold an extensive collection of Buddhist art and manuscripts dating back over a millennium. The province is ethnically diverse, home to populations of Hui, Tibetan, Dongxiang, and Yugur minorities alongside the Han Chinese majority. The Labrang Monastery in Xiahe is a major center of the Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Lanzhou\n* Approximate area: 425,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 25 million\n* Largest city: Lanzhou\n* Signature features: The Hexi Corridor, Mogao Caves, Jiayuguan pass of the Great Wall",
    "summary": "Gansu is an elongated province in northwestern China that historically served as a vital segment of the ancient Silk Road through the Hexi Corridor. Its diverse geography ranges from the elevated Qilian Mountains in the south to the arid Gobi Desert in the north, with the Yellow River flowing through its capital, Lanzhou. The province relies on agriculture, heavy industry, and mining, and is noted for cultural landmarks like the Mogao Caves and the western end of the Great Wall.",
