    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nJiangxi is a landlocked province located in the southeastern part of the People's Republic of China. It spans from the banks of the Yangtze River in the north to the hillier regions of the south. The province shares borders with six other Chinese provinces. To the north, it is bounded by Anhui and Hubei. Zhejiang lies to the northeast, and Fujian is located to the east. Guangdong borders Jiangxi to the south, and Hunan is situated to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Jiangxi is defined by a basin surrounded by mountains on three sides, with the northern edge opening up to the Yangtze River valley. The most prominent hydrological feature is Poyang Lake, which is the largest freshwater lake in China. It is located in the northern part of the province and drains into the Yangtze River. The Gan River is the principal waterway of Jiangxi. It flows from south to north through the center of the province and empties into Poyang Lake. The province is highly mountainous along its borders. The Wuyi Mountains form a natural boundary with Fujian in the east. The Luoxiao Mountains run along the western border with Hunan. The Nanling Mountains are located in the south. Mount Lu, also known as Lushan, is a prominent massif in the north near Jiujiang and is recognized for its steep peaks and deep valleys.\n\n## Climate\nJiangxi experiences a humid subtropical climate. Summers are long, hot, and highly humid. Winters are short, cool, and damp. The province receives abundant precipitation throughout the year. The heaviest rainfall typically occurs during the spring and early summer months, a period often associated with the East Asian monsoon and the regional plum rains. Late summer and autumn are generally drier, though the province can occasionally be affected by typhoons moving inland from the southeastern coast. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 16 to 20 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Jiangxi relies on agriculture, mining, and manufacturing. The province is a major producer of rice, tea, and citrus fruits, particularly navel oranges in the southern Ganzhou region. Jiangxi is exceptionally rich in mineral resources. It is a leading global source of tungsten, copper, and rare earth elements. The city of Guixi hosts one of the largest copper smelting facilities in the country. Nanchang is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the primary industrial and commercial hub. Jiujiang is a major port city on the Yangtze River. Jingdezhen, located in the northeast, is historically and economically tied to ceramic and porcelain production.\n\n## History & culture\nJiangxi has a long history as a center of Chinese culture and agriculture due to its position along the Gan River trade route. During the Ming and Qing dynasties, Jingdezhen became the preeminent center for porcelain manufacturing, supplying ceramics to the imperial court and for global export. In modern history, Jiangxi played a central role in the Chinese Communist Revolution. The Nanchang Uprising of 1927 is recognized as the founding event of the People's Liberation Army. Subsequently, the Jinggang Mountains in western Jiangxi served as an early base for communist forces. The southern part of the province, particularly around Ganzhou, is a major population center for the Hakka people, a Han Chinese subgroup with distinct linguistic and architectural traditions.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Nanchang\n* Approximate area: 166,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 45 million\n* Largest city: Nanchang\n* Signature features: Poyang Lake (China's largest freshwater lake), Jingdezhen porcelain production, and the Gan River valley.",
    "summary": "Jiangxi is a landlocked province in southeastern China known for its mountainous borders, the Gan River valley, and Poyang Lake, the country's largest freshwater lake. Its economy is driven by agriculture, extensive mineral mining, and a historic porcelain industry centered in Jingdezhen. The province also holds significant modern historical importance as an early base for the Chinese Communist Revolution.",
