    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nHunan is a landlocked province located in the south-central part of the People's Republic of China. It is situated south of the middle reaches of the Yangtze River. The province shares borders with six other provincial-level administrative divisions. It is bounded by Hubei to the north, Jiangxi to the east, Guangdong to the south, Guangxi to the southwest, Guizhou to the west, and the municipality of Chongqing to the northwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe name of the province translates to \"south of the lake\", referring to Dongting Lake. This large, shallow lake is located in the northeastern part of the province and serves as a major flood basin for the Yangtze River. Hunan is enclosed by mountains on three sides. The Wuling Mountains and Xuefeng Mountains lie to the west and northwest. The Nanling Mountains form the southern border, and the Luoxiao Mountains run along the eastern border. The central and northern areas consist mostly of low hills, basins, and river valleys. The Xiang River is the largest river in the province. It flows northward through the eastern and central regions before emptying into Dongting Lake. Other major rivers include the Zi, Yuan, and Lishui, all of which also drain into Dongting Lake. In the northwest, the Wulingyuan scenic area in Zhangjiajie features thousands of distinct quartzite sandstone pillars.\n\n## Climate\nHunan experiences a humid subtropical monsoon climate. The region has four distinct seasons, characterized by abundant precipitation and high humidity throughout the year. Summers are typically long, hot, and humid, with heavy rainfall occurring between April and July. Winters are short, cool, and damp, with temperatures occasionally dropping below freezing. Spring and autumn serve as transitional periods with highly variable weather. The mountainous regions in the west and south generally experience cooler temperatures and higher precipitation compared to the central plains and river valleys.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Hunan relies on agriculture, mining, and heavy industry. The province is a major producer of rice, tea, and citrus fruits. It is also one of the leading regions in China for the extraction and processing of non-ferrous metals, holding significant reserves of antimony and tungsten. Manufacturing is a primary economic driver, particularly the production of construction machinery, rail transit equipment, and new materials. Changsha is the administrative center and the largest city, known for its heavy machinery manufacturing and media industries. Zhuzhou is a major railway hub and metallurgical center. Xiangtan is an industrial base focused on electromechanical products. Together, these three cities form the Chang-Zhu-Tan city cluster, which functions as the economic core of the province. Other notable cities include Yueyang, a major port on Dongting Lake, and Hengyang, a transportation and industrial center in the south.\n\n## History & culture\nDuring the Zhou dynasty, the area of present-day Hunan was part of the State of Chu. The region has a long history of agricultural development due to its fertile river valleys. In modern history, Hunan is notable as the birthplace of several prominent Chinese Communist Party leaders, including Mao Zedong, who was born in the village of Shaoshan. The province is also recognized for its distinct regional culture. Xiang cuisine, one of the Eight Great Traditions of Chinese cuisine, originates from Hunan and is characterized by its heavy use of fresh chili peppers, garlic, and shallots. The Yuelu Academy in Changsha, founded during the Song dynasty, is one of the oldest and most prestigious academies in Chinese history.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Changsha\n* Approximate area: 211,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: Roughly 66 million\n* Largest city: Changsha\n* Signature features: Dongting Lake, Zhangjiajie sandstone pillars, spicy Xiang cuisine, and the Chang-Zhu-Tan heavy industry cluster.",
