    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nQinghai is a landlocked province situated in the northwest of the People's Republic of China. It is located on the northeastern part of the Tibetan Plateau. The province shares borders with Gansu to the north and east, Xinjiang to the northwest, Tibet to the south and southwest, and Sichuan to the southeast. It is the fourth largest province-level administrative region in China by area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Qinghai is dominated by high altitude terrain, with an average elevation of over 3,000 meters above sea level. The province is named after Qinghai Lake, which is the largest inland saltwater lake in China. Major mountain ranges include the Kunlun Mountains in the north, the Tanggula Mountains in the south, and the Qilian Mountains along the border with Gansu. The province is often referred to as the water tower of China because it contains the headwaters of three major Asian rivers. The Yellow River originates in the Bayan Har Mountains in central Qinghai. The Yangtze River begins in the Tanggula Mountains in the southwest. The Mekong River, known in China as the Lancang River, also has its source in the southern part of the province. The Qaidam Basin, located in the northwest, is a massive hyperarid basin containing salt lakes and extensive mineral deposits. Sanjiangyuan National Nature Reserve protects the headwaters of these three major rivers.\n\n## Climate\nQinghai experiences a harsh, high-altitude continental climate. Winters are long, severely cold, and dry, while summers are short and relatively mild. The high elevation results in significant diurnal temperature variations, meaning temperatures can fluctuate drastically between day and night. Precipitation is generally low and unevenly distributed, with the majority falling during the summer months. The Qaidam Basin is particularly arid, receiving very little rainfall throughout the year. The eastern agricultural areas around Xining have a slightly milder climate compared to the high plateau regions.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Qinghai is relatively small compared to eastern Chinese provinces, heavily relying on agriculture, animal husbandry, and resource extraction. The Qaidam Basin is rich in natural resources, including natural gas, petroleum, lithium, and various salts, which drive the local mining and chemical industries. Pastoralism is a traditional economic activity, with yaks and Tibetan sheep being the primary livestock raised on the vast plateau grasslands. Xining is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the economic and transportation hub of the province. Golmud is the second largest city and a crucial transit point on the Qinghai-Tibet Railway, connecting the region to Tibet and facilitating resource transport from the Qaidam Basin.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the region that is now Qinghai was a frontier zone where various nomadic and agrarian societies interacted. It was inhabited by the Qiang people in ancient times and later became a zone of contact between the Tibetan Empire and various Chinese dynasties, including the Tang and Qing. The area was incorporated into the Qing dynasty in the eighteenth century and officially became a province of the Republic of China in 1928. The population is ethnically diverse. While Han Chinese make up the majority, there are significant populations of Tibetans, Hui, Tu, Salar, and Mongols. Tibetan Buddhism and Islam are prominent religions in the province. Kumbum Monastery, located near Xining, is a major pilgrimage site and an important center of the Gelug school of Tibetan Buddhism.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Xining\n* Approximate area: 720,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.9 million\n* Largest city: Xining\n* Signature features: Qinghai Lake, Sanjiangyuan (source of the Yangtze, Yellow, and Mekong rivers), Qaidam Basin",
