    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nJilin is a province located in the northeastern region of China. It is bordered by Heilongjiang province to the north, Liaoning province to the south, and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region to the west. Jilin also shares international borders with Russia to the east and North Korea to the southeast. The border with North Korea is defined by the Yalu and Tumen rivers. Although Jilin is completely landlocked, its easternmost point is located roughly 15 kilometers from the Sea of Japan along the Tumen River delta.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Jilin generally slopes downward from the southeast to the northwest. The southeastern part of the province is dominated by the Changbai Mountains. This range includes Mount Paektu, a dormant volcano that features Heaven Lake, a large crater lake situated on the border with North Korea. The central region of Jilin consists of the Songliao Plain, which is characterized by flat, fertile land. The western section of the province transitions into grasslands, wetlands, and sandy areas that border the eastern edge of the Eurasian Steppe. The Songhua River is the most prominent waterway flowing through the interior of the province. The Yalu and Tumen rivers form the southeastern boundary.\n\n## Climate\nJilin experiences a humid continental climate, characterized by distinct seasonal changes. Winters are long, extremely cold, and snowy, with temperatures frequently dropping below minus 20 degrees Celsius. The mountainous eastern regions experience the most severe winter conditions. Summers are short, warm, and humid. The East Asian monsoon brings the majority of the province's annual precipitation during the summer months, particularly in July and August. Spring and autumn are brief transitional seasons with high winds and rapid temperature fluctuations.\n\n## Economy & cities\nChangchun is the administrative center and the most populous city in Jilin. It is a major industrial hub, widely recognized as the birthplace of the Chinese automotive industry. The city remains a primary manufacturing center for vehicles and railway carriages. Jilin City, the second-largest urban center, is located along the Songhua River and is noted for its chemical and metallurgical industries. Agriculture is a vital component of the provincial economy. The fertile central plains make Jilin one of China's leading producers of corn, soybeans, and rice. The eastern mountainous areas support a significant forestry sector and are famous for producing traditional medicinal products, including ginseng and deer antlers.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, Jilin was part of the broader region known as Manchuria. It was inhabited by various Tungusic and Mongolic peoples, including the Mohe and the Jurchen, who were the ancestors of the Manchu people. The ancient kingdom of Goguryeo established its early capitals in the southern part of modern Jilin. The archaeological sites around the city of Ji'an, including royal tombs and stele, are preserved as UNESCO World Heritage sites. In the 1930s, the region was incorporated into the Japanese puppet state of Manchukuo, and Changchun served as its capital under the name Hsinking. After the establishment of the People's Republic of China, Jilin developed into a heavy industry base. The province is also home to a large ethnic Korean population, primarily concentrated in the Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture in the east.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Changchun\n* Approximate area: 187,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 24 million\n* Largest city: Changchun\n* Signature features: Changbai Mountains, Heaven Lake, automotive manufacturing industry, Yanbian Korean Autonomous Prefecture",
