    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nLiaoning is located in the northeastern region of the People's Republic of China. It is the southernmost of the three provinces that make up Northeast China, historically known as Manchuria. It borders the Yellow Sea and the Bohai Sea to the south. To the southeast, the Yalu River forms the international border with North Korea. Domestically, it shares borders with Jilin province to the northeast, Inner Mongolia to the northwest, and Hebei province to the southwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Liaoning is characterized by a central plain flanked by mountainous regions to the east and west. The Liaodong Peninsula extends southward into the sea, dividing the Bohai Sea from the Korea Bay. The eastern part of the province is dominated by the Changbai Mountains and the Qianshan range, which are heavily forested. The western region contains the Nulu'erhu Mountains, which transition into the Mongolian Plateau. The central area is the Liao River Plain, formed by the Liao River, the principal waterway of the province. Other significant rivers include the Yalu, the Daliao, and the Hun River. The coastline features numerous bays and islands, such as the Changshan Archipelago.\n\n## Climate\nLiaoning experiences a temperate monsoon climate. Winters are long, cold, and dry, influenced by the Siberian anticyclone. Summers are short, hot, and humid, driven by the East Asian monsoon, which brings the majority of the annual precipitation. Average temperatures range from roughly minus 10 degrees Celsius in January to about 24 degrees Celsius in July. Coastal areas like Dalian have a milder maritime climate compared to the inland cities, experiencing less extreme temperature variations. Spring and autumn are brief transitional seasons.\n\n## Economy & cities\nLiaoning has historically been one of China's most important industrial bases. The province is rich in mineral resources, including iron ore, coal, and magnesite, which supported the early development of heavy industries such as steel production, machinery, and petrochemicals. Shenyang, the administrative center, is a major hub for manufacturing and aerospace. Dalian, located at the tip of the Liaodong Peninsula, is a major seaport, financial center, and hub for information technology and shipbuilding. Anshan is known for its large-scale iron and steel industry. Fushun and Benxi are also notable industrial centers. Agriculture remains significant in the central plains, producing corn, rice, soybeans, and apples.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a complex history, serving as a frontier between Han Chinese agriculturalists and various nomadic or semi-nomadic peoples. It was the homeland of the Manchu people, who established the Qing dynasty in the seventeenth century. Shenyang, then known as Mukden, served as the early Qing capital, and the Mukden Palace remains a prominent historical site. During the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Liaoning was a focal point of geopolitical struggles involving the Russian Empire, the Empire of Japan, and China, leading to significant railway and industrial development under foreign influence. After the establishment of the People's Republic of China, it became a model province for Soviet-style industrialization.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Shenyang\n* Approximate area: 145,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 42.5 million\n* Largest city: Shenyang\n* Signature features: Mukden Palace, heavy industrial base of Northeast China, Liaodong Peninsula",
