    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nShaanxi is a landlocked province located in the northwestern region of the People's Republic of China. It shares borders with eight other provincial-level divisions, which is the highest number of neighboring subdivisions for any province in China alongside Inner Mongolia. To the north, it borders Inner Mongolia. To the east, it is bounded by Shanxi and Henan. Hubei lies to the southeast, Chongqing to the south, and Sichuan to the southwest. To the west and northwest, Shaanxi borders Gansu and Ningxia.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Shaanxi is diverse and is traditionally divided into three distinct natural regions. The northern part of the province is dominated by the Loess Plateau, a vast highland characterized by thick deposits of wind-blown, yellowish soil called loess. This region is heavily eroded, featuring deep gullies and ravines. The central region consists of the Wei River Valley, also known as the Guanzhong Plain. This fertile graben basin runs east to west and is watered by the Wei River, the largest tributary of the Yellow River. The southern region is separated from the central plain by the rugged Qinling Mountains, which serve as a major geographical and ecological dividing line between northern and southern China. South of the Qinling range lies the Han River valley, which features a more subtropical environment. Mount Hua, one of the Five Great Mountains of China, is located in eastern Shaanxi.\n\n## Climate\nBecause of its elongated shape from north to south, Shaanxi experiences a variety of climate zones. The northern Loess Plateau has a cold, arid to semi-arid continental monsoon climate with long, dry winters and hot summers. The central Wei River Valley has a temperate semi-humid climate, experiencing distinct seasons with hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters. South of the Qinling Mountains, the climate transitions to a humid subtropical zone. This southern region receives significantly more rainfall than the central and northern areas and experiences milder winters.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Shaanxi relies heavily on fossil fuels, high technology, aerospace, and manufacturing. The northern region, particularly around the city of Yulin, is a major center for coal, petroleum, and natural gas extraction. The central Guanzhong Plain is the economic and industrial core of the province. Xi'an, the administrative center and largest city, is a major hub for the aerospace industry, software development, and higher education. Other significant cities in the central industrial corridor include Xianyang, Baoji, and Weinan. Agriculture remains important, with the northern and central regions producing wheat, corn, and apples, while the southern region around Hanzhong cultivates rice.\n\n## History & culture\nShaanxi is widely considered one of the primary cradles of Chinese civilization. The central Wei River Valley served as the political center of China for over a millennium. Thirteen feudal dynasties established their capitals in the area of present-day Xi'an, historically known as Chang'an, including the Zhou, Qin, Han, and Tang dynasties. The province is the site of the Terracotta Army, a large collection of funerary sculptures depicting the armies of Qin Shi Huang, the first Emperor of China. In more recent history, the northern city of Yan'an served as the endpoint of the Long March and the primary base for the Chinese Communist Party from 1935 to 1948. The traditional culture of the Loess Plateau includes unique folk music and distinctive cave dwellings known as yaodong, which are carved directly into the loess soil.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Xi'an\n* Approximate area: 205,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 39.5 million\n* Largest city: Xi'an\n* Signature features: The Terracotta Army, the Loess Plateau, and the Qinling Mountains",
    "summary": "Shaanxi is a landlocked province in northwest China that is geographically divided into the northern Loess Plateau, the central Wei River Valley, and the southern Qinling Mountains. It is historically significant as a cradle of Chinese civilization and the site of ancient capitals like Chang'an, as well as the Terracotta Army. Today, the province has a diverse economy driven by energy extraction in the north and aerospace and technology industries in its administrative center, Xi'an.",
