    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nShanxi is a landlocked province located in the North China region. It shares borders with Inner Mongolia to the north, Hebei to the east, Henan to the south, and Shaanxi to the west. The name of the province translates to \"West of the Mountains\", which refers to its geographic position west of the Taihang Mountains.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is dominated by a plateau bounded by mountain ranges and is situated on the eastern edge of the Loess Plateau. The Loess Plateau is characterized by thick layers of wind-blown, yellowish soil. The Taihang Mountains form the eastern boundary, while the Lüliang Mountains run along the western side. The Wutai Mountains are located in the northeast, and the Heng Mountains are in the north. Mount Wutai contains the highest peak in the province, reaching an elevation of over 3,000 meters. The Yellow River forms the western and southern borders with Shaanxi and Henan. The Fen River, a major tributary of the Yellow River, flows north to south through the center of the province, creating the fertile Fen River Valley. The Sanggan River drains the northern part of the province. Shanxi has no coastline.\n\n## Climate\nShanxi experiences a continental monsoon climate. Winters are long, dry, and cold, heavily influenced by the Siberian high pressure system. Summers are warm and humid, bringing the majority of the annual precipitation to the region. Spring and autumn are relatively short transitional seasons. The province frequently experiences dust storms in the spring due to its proximity to the Gobi Desert and the dry soils of the Loess Plateau. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 3 to 14 degrees Celsius, depending on latitude and elevation. Annual precipitation generally ranges from about 400 to 650 millimeters, with the southern regions receiving more rainfall than the north.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Shanxi has historically been heavily reliant on coal mining and heavy industry. The province holds some of the largest coal reserves in China, which has driven its industrial development for decades. Other major industries include metallurgy, power generation, and chemical production. Agriculture is concentrated primarily in the Fen River Valley and the southern plains, producing crops such as wheat, maize, millet, and sorghum, along with cash crops like apples and walnuts. Taiyuan is the administrative center and the largest city, functioning as a major hub for heavy industry and manufacturing. Datong, located in the north, is a significant coal mining center. Other notable cities include Changzhi and Linfen. In recent years, the province has been transitioning towards renewable energy and tourism to diversify its economy and address environmental degradation caused by coal extraction.\n\n## History & culture\nShanxi is considered one of the cradles of ancient Chinese civilization. During the Spring and Autumn period, it was the core territory of the state of Jin. This history is the source of the province's common single-character abbreviation, \"Jin\". During the Ming and Qing dynasties, merchants from the region, known as the Jin merchants, dominated trade and banking across China. Pingyao is a well-preserved ancient walled city and a UNESCO World Heritage site, recognized for its traditional architecture and its historical role as a national financial center in the 19th century. The Yungang Grottoes near Datong feature ancient Chinese Buddhist temple grottoes dating back to the 5th and 6th centuries. Mount Wutai is recognized as one of the Four Sacred Buddhist Mountains of China. Local culture includes Jin opera and a distinct variety of Chinese spoken in the region, known as Jin Chinese.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Taiyuan\n* Approximate area: 156,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 34.9 million\n* Largest city: Taiyuan\n* Signature features: Extensive coal reserves, Loess Plateau landscape, ancient walled city of Pingyao, Yungang Grottoes",
