    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nJiangsu is located on the eastern coast of the People's Republic of China. It borders the Yellow Sea to the east. Neighboring provinces include Shandong to the north, Anhui to the west, and Zhejiang and the municipality of Shanghai to the south. It is situated in the Yangtze River Delta region, which is a highly developed area in eastern China.\n\n## Physical features\nJiangsu is notably flat, with plains covering roughly 68 percent of its total area. It has the lowest average elevation of any Chinese province. The province is dominated by extensive water systems, earning it the historical nickname of the land of fish and rice. The Yangtze River flows through the southern part of the province, emptying into the East China Sea near Shanghai. The Huai River historically flowed through northern Jiangsu before its course was altered. The Grand Canal runs north to south through the province, connecting the Yangtze and Yellow river basins. Major lakes include Lake Tai in the south, which it shares with Zhejiang, and Lake Hongze in the west. The coastline along the Yellow Sea features extensive tidal flats and wetlands, such as the Yancheng Nature Reserve, which provides critical habitat for the red-crowned crane.\n\n## Climate\nThe province experiences a transition between a humid subtropical climate in the south and a humid continental climate in the north. The Huai River serves as the traditional dividing line between these two climate zones. Summers are generally hot and humid, with abundant rainfall brought by the East Asian monsoon. Winters are cool to cold, with the northern regions experiencing occasional snowfall and freezing temperatures. The coastal areas are susceptible to typhoons during the late summer and early autumn months. Average annual precipitation ranges from roughly 800 to 1,200 millimeters, decreasing from south to north.\n\n## Economy & cities\nJiangsu has one of the largest and most developed provincial economies in China. It is a major hub for manufacturing, electronics, textiles, chemicals, and automotive production. The southern region, known as Sunan, is particularly wealthy and heavily integrated with neighboring Shanghai. Agriculture remains significant, with major crops including rice, wheat, cotton, and tea, alongside extensive aquaculture. Nanjing, the administrative center, is a major inland port and educational hub on the Yangtze River. Suzhou, located near Shanghai, is renowned for its high-tech industrial parks and is the largest city in the province by economic output and urban population. Other major cities include Wuxi, known for manufacturing and solar technology, Xuzhou, a transportation and coal mining center in the north, and Nantong, a major port city.\n\n## History & culture\nJiangsu has been a center of Chinese culture and commerce for centuries. Nanjing served as the capital of various Chinese dynasties, including the early Ming dynasty and the Republic of China. The region is famous for its classical gardens, particularly the Classical Gardens of Suzhou, which are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. The province is also known for Kunqu opera, one of the oldest extant forms of Chinese opera, and traditional crafts such as Suzhou silk embroidery and Yixing clay teapots. The Grand Canal facilitated trade and cultural exchange, contributing to the historical prosperity of cities like Yangzhou and Suzhou.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Nanjing\n* Approximate area: 102,600 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 85 million\n* Largest city: Suzhou\n* Signature features: Classical Gardens of Suzhou, Lake Tai, the Grand Canal, extensive plains and waterways",
