    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nSichuan is a landlocked province located in the southwestern region of the People's Republic of China. It shares borders with several other provincial-level administrative divisions. To the northwest lies Qinghai province, while Gansu and Shaanxi provinces border it to the north and northeast. The Chongqing municipality, which was administratively part of Sichuan until 1997, forms the eastern border. Guizhou province is located to the southeast, Yunnan province to the south, and the Tibet Autonomous Region borders Sichuan to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is divided into two distinct topographic regions. The eastern portion consists of the Sichuan Basin, a fertile lowland surrounded by mountains. The western portion is highly mountainous, forming part of the Hengduan Mountains and the eastern edge of the Tibetan Plateau. The highest elevation in the province is Mount Gongga, which reaches roughly 7,556 meters above sea level. Sichuan is drained by the Yangtze River and its major tributaries, including the Min, Tuo, Jialing, and Dadu rivers. The Jinsha River, the upper course of the Yangtze, forms the western boundary with Tibet. The province is highly seismically active due to tectonic fault lines, leading to significant events like the 2008 Wenchuan earthquake. Notable protected areas include Jiuzhaigou Valley National Park in the north, recognized for its multi-tiered waterfalls and colorful karst lakes.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Sichuan varies significantly depending on the local topography. The eastern Sichuan Basin experiences a humid subtropical climate. This area is characterized by long, mild, and highly humid winters, alongside hot and very humid summers. The basin is noted for its frequent fog and low annual sunshine totals. In contrast, the western mountainous regions feature a subtropical highland climate that transitions into an alpine climate at higher elevations. These western areas experience much colder temperatures, longer winters, and significantly more sunshine than the eastern basin.\n\n## Economy & cities\nSichuan has a diverse economy rooted in agriculture, natural resources, and manufacturing. The fertile Sichuan Basin supports extensive agricultural production, yielding large quantities of rice, wheat, rapeseed, pork, and silk. The province holds substantial mineral reserves, particularly natural gas, titanium, and vanadium. Industrial sectors include metallurgy, aerospace, electronics, and machinery manufacturing. The steep gradients of the western rivers make Sichuan a major producer of hydroelectric power. Chengdu is the administrative center and the primary economic hub, serving as a center for finance, technology, and transportation in western China. Other significant cities include Mianyang, a center for the electronics industry, as well as Nanchong, Yibin, and Luzhou.\n\n## History & culture\nSichuan has a long history of human settlement, historically shielded from external influence by its rugged borders. The region was home to the ancient Shu civilization, which is documented by bronze artifacts found at the Sanxingdui archaeological site. In the third century BCE, the Dujiangyan Irrigation System was constructed on the Min River. This system still functions today and is responsible for the agricultural productivity of the Chengdu Plain. The province is strongly associated with Sichuan cuisine, a culinary tradition characterized by bold, pungent flavors and the distinct numbing effect of the Sichuan peppercorn. Sichuan is also the primary natural habitat for the giant panda, with extensive breeding centers and protected sanctuaries located throughout the western mountains.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Chengdu\n* Approximate area: 485,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 83 million\n* Largest city: Chengdu\n* Signature features: Giant panda sanctuaries, spicy regional cuisine, the Sichuan Basin, and the ancient Sanxingdui ruins",
    "summary": "Sichuan is a populous, landlocked province in southwestern China known for its fertile eastern basin and mountainous western plateau. Its administrative center, Chengdu, serves as a major economic and cultural hub for the region. The province is globally recognized for its spicy cuisine, ancient historical sites, and status as the primary habitat of the giant panda.",
