    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nTaiwan is an island province located in southeastern China, separated from the mainland by the Taiwan Strait. The Taiwan Strait is roughly 180 kilometers wide. To the north of the island lies the East China Sea, to the east is the Philippine Sea, to the south is the Luzon Strait, and to the southwest is the South China Sea. Neighboring mainland provinces across the strait include Fujian and Guangdong. The political status of Taiwan is disputed, as it is claimed by the People's Republic of China as a province but is governed independently by the Republic of China.\n\n## Physical features\nThe main island of Taiwan is characterized by a stark contrast between its eastern and western regions. The eastern two-thirds of the island consist mostly of rugged mountain ranges. The Central Mountain Range runs from north to south, featuring Yushan, which is the highest peak at roughly 3,952 meters. Other significant ranges include the Xueshan Range and the Alishan Range. The western third of the island is composed of flat to gently rolling plains, where the majority of the population resides. The province also includes several smaller island groups, such as the Penghu archipelago in the Taiwan Strait, as well as Kinmen and Matsu located near the mainland coast. Major rivers include the Zhuoshui River, which is the longest, and the Gaoping River, which has the largest drainage basin. Notable natural landmarks include Taroko Gorge, a marble canyon carved by the Liwu River, and Sun Moon Lake, the largest body of water on the island.\n\n## Climate\nTaiwan experiences a marine tropical and subtropical climate. The northern and central regions have a humid subtropical climate, while the southern part of the island is tropical. Summers are long, hot, and highly humid, lasting from May to September. Winters are short and mild, though the northern areas receive more rainfall during this time due to the northeastern monsoon. Average temperatures in the summer hover around 30 degrees Celsius, while winter temperatures in the lowlands generally remain above 15 degrees Celsius. The island is subject to frequent typhoons between July and October. These storms bring heavy rainfall and strong winds, contributing significantly to the annual water supply but also causing occasional landslides.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTaiwan has a highly developed, export-oriented economy. It is a global leader in information and communication technology, particularly in the manufacturing of semiconductor microchips. Other major industries include electronics, petrochemicals, machinery, and textiles. Agriculture plays a smaller role in the modern economy, though the fertile western plains produce rice, sugarcane, and a wide variety of tropical fruits. Taipei is the administrative center and a major financial hub, located in the northern part of the island. New Taipei City surrounds Taipei and is the most populous city. Other major urban centers include Kaohsiung in the south, known for its massive seaport, Taichung in the central region, and Tainan, which is noted for its historical architecture. The western coastal plain is heavily urbanized and connected by a high-speed rail network.\n\n## History & culture\nTaiwan has a diverse cultural heritage shaped by indigenous Austronesian peoples, Han Chinese migration, and periods of foreign administration. The island was governed by the Qing dynasty for over two centuries before being ceded to Japan in 1895. Following the end of World War II in 1945, administration was transferred to the Republic of China. The culture is a blend of traditional Chinese customs, indigenous traditions, and Japanese influences. Mandarin is the primary language, while Taiwanese Hokkien and Hakka are also widely spoken. Religious practices are highly syncretic, combining elements of Buddhism, Taoism, and Confucianism, with thousands of temples scattered across the island. The island is famous for its culinary scene, particularly its night markets offering street food such as beef noodle soup and bubble tea.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Taipei\n* Approximate area: 36,193 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 23.5 million\n* Largest city: New Taipei City\n* Signature features: Global semiconductor manufacturing hub, Yushan (Jade Mountain), Taroko Gorge",
