    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nShandong is a coastal province located in the East China region. It is situated on the eastern edge of the North China Plain and extends into the Bohai Sea and Yellow Sea as the Shandong Peninsula. The province shares land borders with Hebei to the northwest, Henan to the west, Anhui to the southwest, and Jiangsu to the south. Across the Bohai Strait to the north lies the Liaodong Peninsula in Liaoning province, and across the Yellow Sea to the east is the Korean Peninsula.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is divided into two main topographical areas, which are the inland plain and the mountainous peninsula. The central and south-central areas are mountainous and hilly. Mount Tai is the most prominent peak, reaching an elevation of 1,532 meters. It is one of the Five Great Mountains of China. The Yellow River flows through the western and northern parts of the province, emptying into the Bohai Sea in the city of Dongying. The coastline is long and rugged, featuring numerous bays, islands, and natural harbors along the Shandong Peninsula. The Grand Canal also passes through the western part of the province.\n\n## Climate\nShandong has a temperate monsoon climate. Summers are hot and rainy, while winters are cold and dry. The coastal areas experience a milder maritime influence, resulting in cooler summers and warmer winters compared to the inland regions. Precipitation is concentrated in the summer months, often brought by the East Asian monsoon. Average annual temperatures range from 11 to 14 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation varies from 500 to 900 millimeters, generally decreasing from the southeast to the northwest.\n\n## Economy & cities\nShandong has one of the largest provincial economies in China. It is a major agricultural producer, known for wheat, cotton, peanuts, garlic, and various fruits like apples and cherries. The province is heavily industrialized. Key industries include petroleum extraction at the Shengli Oil Field, chemical processing, metallurgy, machinery, and textiles. Jinan is the administrative center, serving as a major political, cultural, and transportation hub. Qingdao is the largest city and a major seaport, known for its brewing industry and electronics manufacturing. Other significant cities include Yantai, Weifang, Zibo, and Linyi. Weifang is a center for kite manufacturing.\n\n## History & culture\nShandong is a historical center of Chinese civilization. It is the birthplace of Confucius, who was born in Qufu, and Mencius, making it the historical center of Confucianism. The Temple and Cemetery of Confucius and the Kong Family Mansion in Qufu are major historical sites. During the Spring and Autumn period and the Warring States period, the region was dominated by the states of Qi and Lu. Shandong is still commonly referred to as Lu in Chinese abbreviations. The province has a distinct culinary tradition. Lu cuisine is one of the Eight Culinary Traditions of China, known for its seafood, soups, and use of garlic and onions. Mount Tai has been a site of imperial worship for millennia, drawing emperors to perform the Fengshan sacrifices.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Jinan\n* Approximate area: 157,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 101 million\n* Largest city: Qingdao\n* Signature features: Mount Tai, birthplace of Confucius, Tsingtao Brewery",
    "summary": "Shandong is an eastern coastal province of China located on the lower reaches of the Yellow River. It is a major economic and agricultural hub recognized for its prominent peninsula, Mount Tai, and the coastal city of Qingdao. As the birthplace of Confucius, the province holds significant historical and cultural importance in Chinese civilization.",
