    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nHubei is a landlocked province located in the central region of the People's Republic of China. The name Hubei translates to north of the lake, referring to its geographic position north of Dongting Lake. The province shares borders with six other provincial-level administrative divisions. It is bounded by Henan to the north, Anhui to the east, Jiangxi to the southeast, Hunan to the south, Chongqing municipality to the west, and Shaanxi to the northwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Hubei is defined by its extensive river systems and varied topography. The Yangtze River enters the province from the west through the prominent Three Gorges, flowing eastward across the province. The Han River, the largest tributary of the Yangtze, flows from the northwest and merges with the Yangtze at Wuhan. The central and eastern parts of Hubei are dominated by the Jianghan Plain, a fertile, low-lying area characterized by numerous lakes and wetlands. Historically, Hubei was known as the province of a thousand lakes, though many have been drained for agriculture over the past century. The western portion of the province is highly mountainous. The Daba Mountains and the Wudang Mountains dominate the northwest, while the Shennongjia Forestry District features some of the highest peaks in central China, including Shennong Peak.\n\n## Climate\nHubei experiences a humid subtropical monsoon climate, characterized by four distinct seasons. Summers are typically long, hot, and highly humid. Wuhan is historically recognized as one of the furnace cities of China due to its oppressive summer heat. Winters are relatively short, cold, and damp, with occasional snowfall occurring in the mountainous western regions. Spring and autumn are generally mild and serve as transitional seasons. The province receives abundant precipitation, most of which falls during the summer monsoon months between June and August.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Hubei is diverse, relying on heavy industry, manufacturing, agriculture, and energy production. Wuhan, the administrative center and largest city, is a major transportation hub located at the confluence of the Yangtze and Han rivers. It is a center for metallurgy, automobile manufacturing, and high-technology industries. Yichang, located in western Hubei, is a critical hub for hydroelectric power. It is the site of the Gezhouba Dam and the large Three Gorges Dam, which is one of the highest-capacity power stations in the world. Xiangyang and Shiyan are also significant industrial cities, particularly known for automobile production. Agriculture remains important in the Jianghan Plain, where farmers cultivate rice, wheat, cotton, and tea. The province is also a major producer of freshwater fish and lotus roots.\n\n## History & culture\nHubei has a long history, serving as the center of the influential State of Chu during the Eastern Zhou dynasty. The Chu culture left a lasting legacy in the region, distinct from the cultures of the Yellow River valley to the north. In modern history, Hubei played a pivotal role in the Chinese Revolution. The Wuchang Uprising, which took place in Wuhan on October 10, 1911, triggered the Xinhai Revolution that ultimately overthrew the Qing dynasty and established the Republic of China. The province is also culturally significant for the Wudang Mountains, a major center for Daoism and traditional Chinese martial arts. The Yellow Crane Tower in Wuhan is a prominent historical landmark that has been celebrated in Chinese poetry for centuries.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Wuhan\n* Approximate area: 185,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 58 million\n* Largest city: Wuhan\n* Signature features: The Three Gorges Dam, the confluence of the Yangtze and Han rivers, and the Wudang Mountains",
    "summary": "Hubei is a landlocked province in central China known for its extensive river systems, including the Yangtze and Han rivers. Its administrative center, Wuhan, is a major industrial and transportation hub, while the western city of Yichang hosts the Three Gorges Dam. Historically significant as the center of the ancient State of Chu and the starting point of the 1911 Xinhai Revolution, Hubei features a diverse landscape ranging from the fertile Jianghan Plain to the mountainous west.",
