    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nGuangxi is an autonomous region located in southern China. It shares an international border with Vietnam to the southwest. Domestically, it is bordered by Yunnan to the west, Guizhou to the north, Hunan to the northeast, and Guangdong to the southeast. To the south, Guangxi has a coastline along the Gulf of Tonkin, which is part of the South China Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe region is known for its distinctive karst topography. This landscape features limestone peaks, caves, and sinkholes, most notably around the city of Guilin and the Li River. The terrain is generally mountainous and hilly, with the Nanling Mountains forming the northeastern border and the Yuecheng Mountains located in the north. The highest peak is Mount Mao'er, which reaches an elevation of roughly 2,141 meters. The Pearl River system dominates the hydrology of Guangxi. Its major tributaries, including the Xi River, the Yu River, and the Liu River, flow from west to east across the region. The coastal area in the south features natural harbors and mangrove forests.\n\n## Climate\nGuangxi experiences a subtropical monsoon climate. The region has long, hot, and humid summers, followed by short, mild winters. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 17 to 23 degrees Celsius. Rainfall is abundant, particularly during the summer monsoon season from May to October, which brings heavy precipitation and occasional typhoons to the coastal areas. The mountainous regions in the north are generally cooler and receive slightly less rainfall than the southern coastal plains.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Guangxi relies on agriculture, mining, and manufacturing. The region is China's leading producer of sugarcane and also grows significant quantities of rice, citrus fruits, and tropical crops. Guangxi has rich mineral deposits, particularly bauxite, manganese, and tin, which support a large metallurgical industry. Manufacturing sectors include automobile production, machinery, and food processing. Nanning, the administrative center, is the political, economic, and cultural hub, known as the Green City due to its abundant tropical foliage. Liuzhou is a major industrial center, particularly for automotive manufacturing. Guilin is a primary tourist destination, driving the local service economy through its scenic landscapes. Beihai serves as a crucial seaport on the Gulf of Tonkin.\n\n## History & culture\nGuangxi was incorporated into the Chinese empire during the Qin dynasty in the third century BCE. The region has historically been a frontier area with a diverse ethnic makeup. In 1958, Guangxi was designated as an autonomous region for the Zhuang people, who are the largest ethnic minority group in China. The Zhuang constitute roughly one-third of the region's population and have distinct linguistic and cultural traditions, including the San Yue San festival and traditional bronze drum casting. Other significant ethnic groups include the Han, Yao, Miao, and Dong. The region was also the site of the Jintian Uprising in 1851, which marked the beginning of the Taiping Rebellion.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous region\n* Administrative center: Nanning\n* Approximate area: 237,600 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 50 million\n* Largest city: Nanning\n* Signature features: Karst topography along the Li River, large Zhuang ethnic minority population",
