    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nNingxia is a landlocked autonomous region located in the northwest of the People's Republic of China. It is one of the smallest provincial-level divisions in the country. The region shares borders with three other provincial-level subdivisions. Inner Mongolia surrounds it to the north and east, Shaanxi borders a small section to the east, and Gansu lies to the south and west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Ningxia is highly diverse despite its small size. The region is largely defined by the Yellow River, which flows through the northern section and creates a fertile agricultural plain. The Helan Mountains form a natural boundary in the northwest, separating the region from the Tengger Desert. In the south, the landscape transitions into the Loess Plateau, characterized by deep ravines and hills. The Liupan Mountains are located in the southernmost part of the region, providing a greener and more forested environment compared to the arid north. To the east, Ningxia borders the Mu Us Desert. The Shapotou area in Zhongwei is notable for its sand dunes meeting the Yellow River.\n\n## Climate\nNingxia experiences a continental climate that ranges from arid to semi-arid. Winters are long, cold, and dry, while summers are hot and brief. The region receives very little precipitation, with most rainfall occurring during the summer months from July to September. The southern mountainous areas receive slightly more rainfall than the northern plains. Because of the dry climate and high elevation, Ningxia has abundant sunshine and a high diurnal temperature variation. These conditions are highly favorable for specific types of agriculture, particularly the cultivation of grapes and goji berries.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Ningxia relies heavily on agriculture, mining, and energy production. The Yellow River has provided irrigation for centuries, allowing the northern plains to produce abundant wheat, rice, and fruits. Ningxia is China's leading producer of goji berries and has developed a prominent wine industry along the eastern foothills of the Helan Mountains. The region also possesses significant coal reserves, which support industries such as power generation, metallurgy, and chemical manufacturing. Yinchuan is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the economic and cultural hub. Other major cities include Shizuishan in the north, known for coal mining, Wuzhong in the central agricultural belt, Zhongwei in the west, and Guyuan in the southern Loess Plateau.\n\n## History & culture\nNingxia has a long history as a frontier region and a vital corridor along the ancient Silk Road. During the eleventh to thirteenth centuries, it was the center of the Western Xia dynasty, established by the Tangut people. The Western Xia tombs, located near Yinchuan, remain a major historical site from this era. Sections of the Great Wall of China also run through the region, built during the Ming dynasty to defend against northern nomadic groups. Today, Ningxia is designated as an autonomous region for the Hui people, a predominantly Muslim ethnic minority in China. The Hui make up roughly one-third of the population, and Islamic architectural influences are visible in mosques and public buildings throughout the region.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous Region\n* Administrative center: Yinchuan\n* Approximate area: 66,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.2 million\n* Largest city: Yinchuan\n* Signature features: Hui Muslim culture, Western Xia tombs, extensive goji berry and wine production, Yellow River irrigation plains.",
    "summary": "Ningxia is a small autonomous region in northwest China known for its arid climate, Yellow River irrigation plains, and significant Hui Muslim population. Historically the center of the Western Xia dynasty, its modern economy relies on coal mining, agriculture, and a growing wine and goji berry industry.",
