    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nInner Mongolia is located in the northern part of the People's Republic of China. It is a large, elongated autonomous region that stretches across the northern border of the country. It shares an extensive international border with Mongolia to the north and a shorter border with the Russian Federation to the northeast. Domestically, it borders eight provincial-level divisions: Heilongjiang, Jilin, Liaoning, Hebei, Shanxi, Shaanxi, Ningxia, and Gansu.\n\n## Physical features\nThe region is characterized by a high plateau known as the Inner Mongolian Plateau, which sits at an average elevation of about 1,000 meters above sea level. The landscape is dominated by extensive grasslands, including the Hulunbuir, Xilingol, and Ordos steppes. The Greater Khingan Mountains run through the northeastern part of the region, providing dense forested areas. In the west and south, the terrain transitions into arid deserts, most notably the Badain Jaran Desert, the Tengger Desert, and the Gobi Desert. The Yellow River flows through the southwestern part of the region, creating the fertile Hetao Plain before turning sharply south.\n\n## Climate\nInner Mongolia experiences a temperate continental monsoon climate. The region has long, cold, and dry winters, largely influenced by the Siberian anticyclone. Summers are short and warm, bringing the majority of the region's annual precipitation. Rainfall decreases significantly from east to west. The eastern forested and grassland areas receive moderate rainfall, while the western desert regions are highly arid, receiving very little precipitation throughout the year. High winds are common, particularly in the spring, which can lead to dust storms that affect much of northern China.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Inner Mongolia relies heavily on agriculture, animal husbandry, and mining. The large grasslands support a significant livestock industry, making the region a leading producer of sheep, wool, dairy, and beef in China. The region also has abundant natural resources, possessing some of the largest coal and rare earth mineral reserves in the world. The city of Baotou is a major industrial hub and the largest city in the region, known specifically for its rare earth mining and steel production. Hohhot, the administrative center, is a center for the dairy industry and regional administration. Ordos is another significant economic center, driven by coal, natural gas, and textiles.\n\n## History & culture\nInner Mongolia has historically been a transitional zone between the agrarian civilizations of central China and the nomadic pastoralists of the Eurasian Steppe. The region was incorporated into various Chinese dynasties, including the Qin, Han, and Ming, often serving as a frontier defense area marked by sections of the Great Wall. It was a core territory of the Mongol Empire established by Genghis Khan in the thirteenth century. Today, it is an autonomous region designated for the Mongol ethnic minority, though Han Chinese make up the demographic majority. Traditional Mongolian culture remains visible in the region through the Naadam festival, which features wrestling, horse racing, and archery, as well as the use of the traditional Mongolian script alongside Chinese characters.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous region\n* Administrative center: Hohhot\n* Approximate area: 1,183,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 24,000,000\n* Largest city: Baotou\n* Signature features: Extensive grasslands like the Hulunbuir Steppe, significant rare earth mineral deposits, and traditional Mongolian nomadic culture.",
    "summary": "Inner Mongolia is a large autonomous region in northern China known for its extensive grasslands, arid deserts, and rich deposits of coal and rare earth minerals. Historically a transitional zone between agrarian China and nomadic steppe cultures, the region maintains its traditional Mongolian heritage while serving as a major center for animal husbandry and mining. Its administrative center is Hohhot, though Baotou stands as its largest city and primary industrial hub.",
