    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nZhejiang is a coastal province located in the eastern part of the People's Republic of China. It is situated south of the Yangtze River delta. The province borders the East China Sea to the east, Fujian province to the south, Jiangxi province to the southwest, Anhui province to the northwest, and Jiangsu province and the municipality of Shanghai to the north.\n\n## Physical features\nZhejiang is characterized by a complex topography dominated by hills and mountains, which cover roughly seventy percent of its total land area. The terrain generally slopes from southwest to northeast. The Yandang Mountains are located in the southern part of the province, noted for their steep peaks and waterfalls. The Tianmu Mountains lie in the northwest. The Qiantang River is the principal waterway, flowing through the province and emptying into Hangzhou Bay. This bay is noted for the Qiantang River tidal bore, one of the largest tidal bores globally. The coastal area is highly indented, featuring thousands of islands. The Zhoushan Archipelago is the largest island group in China, located just off the northeastern coast. The northern part of the province consists of a fertile plain that forms part of the Yangtze River Delta, characterized by a dense network of waterways and lakes, including West Lake in Hangzhou.\n\n## Climate\nZhejiang experiences a humid subtropical climate. The province has four distinct seasons, with long, hot, and humid summers and short, chilly, and relatively dry winters. Spring is generally rainy, while autumn is mild and sunny. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 15 to 19 degrees Celsius. The region receives abundant precipitation, averaging between 1,000 and 1,900 millimeters annually. Late summer and early autumn frequently bring typhoons from the East China Sea, which can cause heavy rainfall and strong winds along the coastal areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\nZhejiang has one of the most developed and wealthiest economies in China. The province is noted for its strong private sector, entrepreneurial culture, and light manufacturing industries. Major economic sectors include textiles, electronics, machinery, and chemical production. E-commerce and information technology are prominent, largely because Hangzhou is the headquarters of major technology companies. The Port of Ningbo-Zhoushan is one of the busiest cargo ports in the world by tonnage, facilitating extensive international trade. Agriculture remains important in the northern plains, where rice, tea, and silk are traditional products. Longjing tea, grown near Hangzhou, is a widely recognized regional product. Major cities include Hangzhou, the administrative center and largest city, Ningbo, a major port and industrial hub, and Wenzhou, noted for its active private enterprise. Other significant urban centers are Shaoxing, Jinhua, and Jiaxing.\n\n## History & culture\nThe area of modern Zhejiang was the center of the ancient Yue state during the Spring and Autumn period. It later became an economic and cultural heartland of China following the southward migration of the Song dynasty, which established its capital at Lin'an, present-day Hangzhou. The province has a rich literary and scholarly tradition. Zhejiang is the birthplace of Yue opera, one of the most popular forms of Chinese theater. The region is also noted for celadon ceramics, historically produced in kilns around Longquan. The Grand Canal, an ancient engineering project, terminates in Hangzhou, linking the region to northern China and facilitating centuries of cultural and economic exchange.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Hangzhou\n* Approximate area: 101,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 65 million\n* Largest city: Hangzhou\n* Signature features: West Lake, Zhoushan Archipelago, Qiantang River tidal bore, Longjing tea",
