    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nXinjiang is located in the northwest of the People's Republic of China. It is the largest province-level administrative division in the country, covering about one-sixth of China's total land area. The region shares international borders with eight countries. These are Mongolia, Russia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, Afghanistan, Pakistan, and India. Domestically, it borders the Tibet Autonomous Region to the south, and Qinghai and Gansu provinces to the southeast. Xinjiang is a designated autonomous region that has been the subject of international scrutiny and human rights controversies regarding the treatment of its Uyghur population, alongside historical separatist movements seeking an independent state.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Xinjiang is defined by rugged mountain ranges and vast desert basins. The Tian Shan mountain range divides the region into two main sections. The northern section is the Junggar Basin, and the southern section is the Tarim Basin. The Tarim Basin contains the Taklamakan Desert, which is the largest desert in China and one of the largest shifting sand deserts in the world. Other major mountain ranges include the Kunlun Mountains in the south, the Pamir Mountains in the west, and the Altai Mountains in the northeast. The Turpan Depression, located in eastern Xinjiang, is the lowest point in China at roughly 154 meters below sea level. Important waterways include the Tarim River, which is the longest inland river in China, and the Irtysh River, which flows north out of the region toward the Arctic Ocean.\n\n## Climate\nXinjiang experiences an arid and semi-arid continental climate. The region is located far from any ocean and is surrounded by high mountains, which blocks moisture from reaching the interior. This results in very low annual precipitation. The climate is characterized by extreme temperature variations between summer and winter, as well as significant temperature shifts between day and night. The Turpan Depression is known for recording some of the highest summer temperatures in China. Because rainfall is scarce, the region relies heavily on snowmelt and glaciers from the Tian Shan and Kunlun mountains to sustain its rivers and agricultural oases.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Xinjiang is heavily based on agriculture, energy extraction, and trade. The region is a major global producer of cotton. Other significant agricultural products include tomatoes, melons, and grapes, with the Turpan area being particularly famous for its viticulture. Xinjiang holds vast reserves of natural resources, including oil, natural gas, and coal. The Tarim Basin is a primary site for petroleum extraction. Urumqi is the administrative center and the largest economic hub in the region. Other notable cities include Kashgar, which is a historic trading center, Karamay, which was built around the oil industry, and Yining. Xinjiang also serves as a central land route for international trade initiatives connecting China to Central Asia and Europe.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically referred to as the Western Regions in Chinese texts, the area was a vital segment of the ancient Silk Road. This network of trade routes facilitated the exchange of goods, religions, and technologies between East Asia, Central Asia, and Europe for centuries. The region came under the direct control of the Qing dynasty in the late eighteenth century and was subsequently named Xinjiang. The population is ethnically diverse. The two largest ethnic groups are the Uyghurs, a Turkic ethnic group predominantly practicing Islam, and the Han Chinese. Other significant populations include Kazakhs, Hui, Kyrgyz, and Mongols. The local culture features distinct culinary traditions, such as roasted mutton, flatbreads, and pilaf, alongside traditional arts like the Uyghur Muqam musical suites.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous region\n* Administrative center: Urumqi\n* Approximate area: 1,660,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 25.8 million\n* Largest city: Urumqi\n* Signature features: The Taklamakan Desert, the Tian Shan mountain range, and ancient Silk Road oasis cities",
