    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\n\nXizang, commonly known as Tibet, is located in the southwest of the People's Republic of China. It is bordered by the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region to the north, Qinghai province to the northeast, Sichuan province to the east, and Yunnan province to the southeast. To the south and west, it shares international borders with Myanmar, India, Bhutan, and Nepal. The political status of the region has been a subject of international debate, with the Central Tibetan Administration in exile contesting the Chinese government's incorporation and governance of the territory.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe region is situated on the Tibetan Plateau, which is widely recognized as the highest and largest plateau in the world. The average elevation exceeds 4,000 meters. The landscape is defined by massive mountain ranges. The Himalayas form the southern boundary, the Kunlun Mountains lie to the north, and the Karakoram range is located to the west. Mount Everest, known locally as Qomolangma, sits on the border between Xizang and Nepal. The region is the source of several major Asian rivers. The Yarlung Tsangpo River flows eastward before becoming the Brahmaputra River in India. Other major rivers originating here include the Mekong, the Salween, and the Yangtze. The region also features numerous high-altitude saltwater and freshwater lakes, including Lake Namtso, Lake Yamdrok, and Lake Manasarovar.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a severe high-altitude alpine climate. The extreme elevation results in thin air, high solar radiation, and generally low temperatures throughout the year. There is a significant diurnal temperature variation, meaning days can be relatively warm while nights frequently drop below freezing. Precipitation is generally low and highly concentrated during the summer monsoon months from June to September. The climate varies geographically. The southeastern area around Nyingchi is lower in elevation and receives more rainfall, supporting dense forests. In contrast, the northwestern Changtang region is a high-altitude desert characterized by extreme cold, strong winds, and arid conditions.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe traditional economy relies heavily on subsistence agriculture and nomadic pastoralism. Highland barley is the primary crop, and yaks, sheep, and goats are the main livestock. In recent decades, the economy has diversified through significant state investment in infrastructure, such as the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. Mining is a major industry, with extraction focusing on copper, lithium, and other minerals. Tourism is also a central economic driver, drawing visitors to the region's natural landscapes and religious sites. Lhasa is the administrative center, the economic hub, and the largest city. Other significant urban centers include Shigatse, Chamdo, and Nyingchi.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe region was the center of the Tibetan Empire, which reached its peak between the seventh and ninth centuries. Tibetan Buddhism developed over subsequent centuries and became the foundational element of local culture, art, and daily life. The Potala Palace and Jokhang Temple in Lhasa are central religious and historical landmarks. The region was incorporated into the People's Republic of China in 1951. Following a regional uprising in 1959, the 14th Dalai Lama fled to India. The area was officially established as an autonomous region in 1965. The population is predominantly ethnic Tibetan, and the Tibetan language is widely spoken alongside Mandarin Chinese.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous Region\n* Administrative center: Lhasa\n* Approximate area: 1,228,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.6 million\n* Largest city: Lhasa\n* Signature features: Mount Everest, the Tibetan Plateau, the Potala Palace, and the Yarlung Tsangpo River",
