    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nChongqing is a direct-administered municipality located in southwestern China. It is situated in the transitional area between the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau and the middle and lower reaches of the Yangtze River. It borders Sichuan province to the west, Shaanxi province to the north, Hubei province to the east, Hunan province to the southeast, and Guizhou province to the south. It is the only municipality in China located deep inland, far from the eastern coast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Chongqing is highly uneven, characterized by mountains and hills that cover roughly ninety percent of its total land area. It is often referred to as the Mountain City. The Daba Mountains lie to the north, the Wu Mountains to the east, the Wuling Mountains to the southeast, and the Dalou Mountains to the south. The Yangtze River flows through the municipality from west to east, cutting through the Wu Mountains to form the Three Gorges. The Jialing River, a major tributary, joins the Yangtze at the center of Chongqing city. The region also features extensive karst landscapes, including the Wulong Karst, which is a UNESCO World Heritage site recognized for its natural bridges and limestone caves.\n\n## Climate\nChongqing experiences a humid subtropical climate. Summers are notoriously long, hot, and highly humid. The city is historically recognized as one of the Three Furnaces of the Yangtze River valley, alongside Wuhan and Nanjing, due to its oppressive summer heat. Winters are short, mild, and damp, with very little snowfall. The region is also known for its heavy fog, particularly in the winter and spring months, earning it the nickname Fog City. Annual precipitation is abundant, falling mostly during the summer monsoon season.\n\n## Economy & cities\nChongqing serves as a major economic center for the upstream Yangtze basin. Its economy is heavily industrialized, with major sectors including automotive manufacturing, electronics, iron and steel, and chemicals. The municipality is one of the largest automobile producing regions in China. Agriculture also plays a significant role in the rural counties, producing rice, oranges, and pork. As a municipality, Chongqing operates essentially as a province, containing numerous districts and counties. The central urban area, situated at the confluence of the Yangtze and Jialing rivers, is the political and commercial core. Other significant districts include Wanzhou and Fuling, which serve as regional hubs along the Yangtze River. The city is connected by a complex network of bridges, tunnels, and a monorail system adapted to the steep terrain.\n\n## History & culture\nChongqing has a long history serving as a political and cultural center in the Ba region. During the Second Sino-Japanese War, it served as the provisional capital of the Republic of China from 1938 to 1946. This period brought rapid industrialization and a massive influx of refugees and institutions from eastern China. In 1997, Chongqing was separated from Sichuan province and elevated to a direct-administered municipality to spearhead the development of China's western regions and to coordinate the resettlement of residents displaced by the Three Gorges Dam project. Culturally, the region is known for its spicy Sichuan-style cuisine, most notably Chongqing hot pot, which utilizes heavy amounts of Sichuan peppercorns and chili peppers.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Direct-administered municipality\n* Administrative center: Chongqing\n* Approximate area: 82,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 32 million\n* Largest city: Chongqing\n* Signature features: The Three Gorges, mountainous terrain, spicy hot pot cuisine, confluence of the Yangtze and Jialing rivers",
