    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nBeijing is a direct-administered municipality located in northern China. It is situated at the northern tip of the North China Plain. The municipality is almost completely surrounded by Hebei Province, except for a short border with the Tianjin municipality to the southeast. It lies approximately 150 kilometers inland from the Bohai Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe municipality features a diverse topography divided between mountains and plains. The northern, northwestern, and western parts are mountainous, while the southeastern part is a flat plain that gradually descends toward the coast. The Taihang Mountains run along the western edge, and the Yan Mountains dominate the northern area. Mount Dongling, located in the western Xishan range, is the highest point in the municipality at roughly 2,303 meters. Major rivers flowing through Beijing include the Yongding River and the Chaobai River, both of which eventually flow into the Hai River system. The Miyun Reservoir, built on the upper reaches of the Chaobai River, is a crucial water source for the region. Beijing also serves as the northern terminus of the Grand Canal.\n\n## Climate\nBeijing experiences a monsoon-influenced humid continental climate. Summers are hot and humid due to the East Asian monsoon, which brings the majority of the annual precipitation between June and August. Winters are cold, dry, and windy, heavily influenced by the vast Siberian anticyclone. Spring can bring sandstorms blowing in from the Gobi Desert, although extensive afforestation efforts have reduced their frequency in recent decades. Autumn is generally considered to have mild and pleasant weather. Average temperatures range from below freezing in January to high temperatures exceeding 30 degrees Celsius in July.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAs a direct-administered municipality, Beijing functions as both a single city and a provincial-level subdivision. The urban core is divided into districts such as Dongcheng, Xicheng, Chaoyang, and Haidian. Chaoyang is the primary central business district and hosts numerous foreign embassies. Haidian is known for its concentration of universities and technology companies, particularly the Zhongguancun technology hub. The economy is heavily service-oriented, dominated by finance, information technology, scientific research, and real estate. Beijing is home to the headquarters of most of China's largest state-owned enterprises and houses a high concentration of Fortune Global 500 companies. The municipality is served by two major aviation hubs, Beijing Capital International Airport and Beijing Daxing International Airport.\n\n## History & culture\nBeijing has served as the political center of China for most of the past eight centuries. It was the capital during the Yuan, Ming, and Qing dynasties. The city is renowned for its imperial architecture, most notably the Forbidden City, which served as the imperial palace. Other significant historical sites include the Temple of Heaven, the Summer Palace, and various sections of the Great Wall of China, such as Badaling and Mutianyu, which run through the northern mountains of the municipality. The city is also the center of Peking opera, a traditional form of Chinese theater. Traditional courtyard houses, known as siheyuan, and narrow alleys called hutongs are characteristic of the historical urban layout. Beijing is also notable for being the first city to host both the Summer and Winter Olympic Games, in 2008 and 2022 respectively.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Direct-administered municipality\n* Administrative center: Beijing\n* Approximate area: 16,410 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 21.8 million\n* Largest city: Beijing\n* Signature features: The Forbidden City, sections of the Great Wall of China, and status as the national capital",
