    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nTianjin is a direct-administered municipality located in northern China. It is situated along the western coast of the Bohai Gulf, which is an inner gulf of the Yellow Sea. The municipality is bordered by Hebei province to the north, south, and west. To the northwest, Tianjin shares a border with the municipality of Beijing. Together with Beijing and Hebei, Tianjin forms the Jing-Jin-Ji economic region, a major metropolitan and industrial corridor in northern China.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Tianjin is predominantly flat, as it lies on the northeastern edge of the North China Plain. The elevation generally decreases from the north to the south and from the west to the east toward the sea. The northernmost section of the municipality, specifically Jizhou District, contains the only significant elevations, featuring the Yanshan Mountains. Mount Panshan is a prominent peak in this northern area. The central and southern parts of the municipality are characterized by alluvial plains and coastal mudflats. The Hai River, often called the mother river of Tianjin, flows through the center of the municipality and empties into the Bohai Gulf. The river system is formed by the confluence of several major tributaries, including the Yongding, Ziya, and Daqing rivers.\n\n## Climate\nTianjin experiences a monsoon-influenced climate that transitions between a humid continental climate and a semi-arid climate. The municipality has four distinct seasons. Winters are cold, windy, and very dry, largely due to the Siberian anticyclone. Summers are hot and humid, with the majority of the annual precipitation occurring during July and August because of the East Asian monsoon. Spring is generally dry and windy, occasionally bringing sandstorms blowing in from the Gobi Desert. Autumn is typically mild and dry. The average annual precipitation is roughly 500 to 600 millimeters.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTianjin is a major industrial and commercial hub in northern China. The Port of Tianjin is the largest artificial deep-water port in northern China and ranks among the busiest ports in the world by cargo tonnage. The local economy relies heavily on manufacturing, including aerospace, petrochemicals, automotive production, and electronics. The Binhai New Area, located along the coast, serves as a massive special economic zone that drives much of the municipality's foreign investment and industrial output. The urban core of Tianjin is divided into several districts, such as Heping, Nankai, and Hexi. Heping District serves as the traditional commercial and financial center.\n\n## History & culture\nThe development of Tianjin is closely tied to its location as a transport hub. It gained prominence during the Sui and Tang dynasties with the construction of the Grand Canal, which facilitated the transport of grain to the capital. In 1860, following the Second Opium War, Tianjin was opened as a treaty port. This led to the establishment of nine foreign concessions, which heavily influenced the architectural landscape of the city. Areas like the Five Great Avenues feature hundreds of preserved European-style buildings. Culturally, Tianjin is recognized as a center for traditional Chinese performing arts, particularly Xiangsheng, a comedic dialogue performance. The local cuisine is known for street food items such as Jianbing guozi, a savory crepe, and Goubuli steamed stuffed buns.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Direct-administered municipality\n* Administrative center: Tianjin\n* Approximate area: 11,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 13.8 million\n* Largest city: Tianjin\n* Signature features: Port of Tianjin, historic European concession architecture, and the Hai River",
