    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nShanghai is located on the eastern coast of China, situated at the estuary of the Yangtze River. As a direct-administered municipality, it sits at the eastern edge of the Yangtze River Delta. It shares land borders with Jiangsu province to the north and west, and Zhejiang province to the south. To the east, the municipality faces the East China Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe municipality occupies a flat, low-lying alluvial plain created by the deposition of sediment from the Yangtze River. The average elevation is roughly four meters above sea level. The Yangtze River flows along the northern edge of the municipality before emptying into the sea. The Huangpu River, a major tributary of the Yangtze, flows north through the center of the municipality, dividing the urban core into the historic Puxi area on the west bank and the modern Pudong area on the east bank. Suzhou Creek is another significant waterway that flows east to join the Huangpu River. The municipality includes several islands, the largest being Chongming Island, which is an alluvial island located in the Yangtze estuary. Natural lakes include Dianshan Lake in the western Qingpu District. The terrain is overwhelmingly flat, though a few small hills, such as Sheshan, are located in the southwestern suburbs.\n\n## Climate\nShanghai experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by four distinct seasons. Winters are chilly and damp, with average temperatures in January hovering around four degrees Celsius. Summers are hot and humid, with July and August temperatures frequently exceeding 35 degrees Celsius. Spring and autumn offer mild and moderate weather. The municipality receives significant rainfall throughout the year. The East Asian monsoon brings a specific rainy period known as the plum rain season in June and early July, which results in frequent and heavy precipitation. In late summer and early autumn, typhoons originating in the Pacific Ocean occasionally bring high winds and intense rainfall to the coastal areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\nShanghai is a major global financial center, a transport hub, and a manufacturing base. The Port of Shanghai consistently ranks as the busiest container port in the world. The local economy relies heavily on financial services, retail, real estate, and manufacturing. Key manufacturing sectors include automotive production, electronic information technology, petrochemicals, and steel production. The Lujiazui area in Pudong serves as the primary financial district, hosting the Shanghai Stock Exchange and multinational corporate headquarters. As a municipality, Shanghai does not contain separate cities but is divided into sixteen districts. Prominent districts include Huangpu, Jing'an, and Xuhui in the historic core, as well as the expansive Pudong New Area. The Zhangjiang Hi-Tech Park is a major center for technology and pharmaceutical research.\n\n## History & culture\nOriginally a small fishing village and market town, Shanghai grew in economic importance during the Qing dynasty due to its favorable port location. Following the First Opium War, the 1842 Treaty of Nanjing opened the city to foreign trade. This led to the establishment of the Shanghai International Settlement and the French Concession. This period of foreign influence left a distinct architectural legacy, most visibly along the Bund, a waterfront promenade featuring neoclassical and art deco buildings. In 1921, the Chinese Communist Party was founded in the French Concession. The local culture, known as Haipai, developed as a blend of traditional Wu Chinese customs and Western influences. The local language is Shanghainese, a dialect of Wu Chinese, though Mandarin is the official language.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Direct-administered municipality\n* Administrative center: Shanghai\n* Approximate area: 6,340 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 24.8 million\n* Largest city: Shanghai (the municipality is coterminous with the city)\n* Signature features: The Bund historic waterfront, the Lujiazui financial skyline, and the Port of Shanghai",
