    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\nMacao is a special administrative region of the People's Republic of China, located on the southern coast of the country. It sits on the western side of the Pearl River Delta, directly across from Hong Kong, which is located to the east. Macao shares its northern border with the city of Zhuhai in Guangdong Province. To the south and east, it faces the South China Sea. As a special administrative region, Macao maintains a separate political and economic system from mainland China under the principle of one country, two systems.\n\n## Physical features\nThe territory of Macao originally consisted of the Macao Peninsula and the two islands of Taipa and Coloane. Over time, extensive land reclamation projects have significantly altered the physical geography of the region. The Cotai Strip, a large area of reclaimed land, now connects Taipa and Coloane into a single landmass. The terrain is generally flat along the coastal and reclaimed areas, while the original islands and peninsula feature steep, rolling hills. The highest point in Macao is Alto de Coloane, which reaches an elevation of about 170 meters. The region lacks major rivers or natural lakes, relying heavily on the Pearl River estuary for its hydrological environment. Seac Pai Van Park on Coloane provides a preserved natural green space amidst the dense urban development.\n\n## Climate\nMacao experiences a humid subtropical climate, heavily influenced by the East Asian monsoon. Summers are long, hot, and highly humid, with frequent heavy rainfall and occasional typhoons that originate in the South China Sea. The typhoon season generally lasts from July to September, bringing strong winds and significant precipitation. Winters are short, mild, and mostly dry, as cold winds from Siberia are moderated before reaching the southern coast. Spring and autumn are transitional seasons, with spring often bringing cloudy and drizzly conditions, while autumn is generally sunny and comfortable.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Macao is heavily dependent on casino gaming and tourism, making it one of the major gambling centers in the world. The gaming industry is concentrated on the Macao Peninsula and the reclaimed Cotai Strip, which houses large integrated resorts. Aside from gaming, the economy relies on retail, hospitality, and financial services. Manufacturing, which historically included textiles and fireworks, has declined significantly in recent decades. Macao is highly urbanized and functions as a single city, with no separate municipalities. The administrative center is Macao, which encompasses the entire territory. The region is densely populated, with commercial and residential zones tightly packed into the available land.\n\n## History & culture\nMacao was leased to Portugal by the Ming dynasty in 1557 as a trading post, making it the first European settlement in the Far East. It remained under Portuguese administration until December 1999, when sovereignty was transferred to the People's Republic of China. This long period of Portuguese administration left a lasting impact on the culture, architecture, and legal system of the territory. The Historic Centre of Macao, a UNESCO World Heritage site, features a blend of Chinese and Portuguese architectural styles, exemplified by the Ruins of Saint Paul's and A-Ma Temple. The local culture is a distinct fusion of Cantonese and Portuguese traditions, which is evident in the local Macanese cuisine. Cantonese is the most widely spoken language, while Portuguese remains an official language.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: People's Republic of China\n* Subdivision type: Special Administrative Region\n* Administrative center: Macao\n* Approximate area: 33 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 680,000\n* Largest city: Macao\n* Signature features: Historic Centre of Macao, Cotai Strip casino resorts, Ruins of Saint Paul's",
    "summary": "Macao is a special administrative region of China located on the western side of the Pearl River Delta, bordering Guangdong Province. Formerly administered by Portugal until 1999, the densely populated territory features a distinct blend of Chinese and Portuguese cultural and architectural influences. Today, its economy is heavily driven by tourism and the casino gaming industry centered on the Cotai Strip and the Macao Peninsula.",
