    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nAcre is a state located in the westernmost part of the North Region of Brazil. It is entirely landlocked and shares domestic borders with the Brazilian states of Amazonas to the north and northeast, and Rondônia to the east. Internationally, Acre shares a long border with Peru to the south and west, and a border with Bolivia to the southeast. Because of its extreme western position, Acre is in a different time zone than the capital city of Brasília, generally operating two hours behind Brasília Standard Time.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Acre is predominantly covered by the Amazon rainforest and consists mostly of low plateaus and sedimentary plains. The elevation is generally low, with most of the state sitting below 300 meters above sea level. The highest elevations are found in the extreme west along the Peruvian border, specifically in the Serra do Divisor mountain range. This area is protected by the Serra do Divisor National Park, which is known for its high biodiversity.\n\nAcre is heavily dissected by rivers that form part of the greater Amazon basin. The major rivers flow generally from the southwest to the northeast. Prominent waterways include the Juruá River, the Purus River, the Acre River, the Tarauacá River, and the Envira River. These rivers are highly meandering and serve as vital transportation routes for local communities.\n\n## Climate\nAcre experiences a hot and humid equatorial climate. Temperatures remain consistently high throughout the year, averaging roughly 26 degrees Celsius. The state receives abundant precipitation, typically exceeding 2,000 millimeters annually. There is a distinct wet season from October to April and a dry season from June to August. During the dry season, the region occasionally experiences a weather phenomenon known as a friagem. A friagem occurs when polar air masses travel northward from the southern cone of South America, causing temperatures in Acre to drop suddenly and unusually low for a few days.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Acre relies heavily on the service sector, agriculture, and extraction industries. Historically, the state was famous for the extraction of natural rubber. Today, the extraction of forest products remains important, including timber, Brazil nuts, and açaí. Agriculture has expanded significantly, with cattle ranching, soybeans, cassava, and corn being major contributors to the state economy.\n\nRio Branco is the administrative center and the largest city in the state, housing roughly half of the state population. It serves as the primary commercial and political hub. Cruzeiro do Sul is the second-largest city, located in the western part of the state along the Juruá River. Other notable municipalities include Sena Madureira and Tarauacá.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore the late nineteenth century, the territory of Acre belonged to Bolivia. During the Amazon rubber boom, thousands of Brazilian rubber tappers migrated into the region to exploit the rubber trees. This demographic shift led to tensions and the Acre War between Bolivia and the Brazilian settlers, who temporarily declared the independent Republic of Acre. The conflict was resolved in 1903 with the Treaty of Petrópolis, in which Brazil purchased the territory from Bolivia. Acre officially became a Brazilian state in 1962.\n\nThe culture of Acre is heavily influenced by its indigenous populations, such as the Ashaninka and Huni Kuin peoples, as well as the descendants of northeastern Brazilian migrants. The state is also recognized globally for its environmental conservation movement. Chico Mendes, a local rubber tapper and environmentalist, gained international prominence in the 1980s for his efforts to protect the Amazon rainforest from logging and ranching before his assassination in 1988.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Rio Branco\n* Approximate area: 164,123 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 830,000\n* Largest city: Rio Branco\n* Signature features: Amazon rainforest coverage, historical rubber boom, Serra do Divisor National Park, legacy of Chico Mendes",
    "summary": "Acre is a state in the westernmost part of Brazil's North Region, covered largely by the Amazon rainforest and bordered by Peru and Bolivia. Originally part of Bolivia, the territory was acquired by Brazil in 1903 following a rubber boom that brought thousands of Brazilian migrants to the area. Today, its economy relies on agriculture, forestry, and services, with Rio Branco serving as the administrative center and largest city.",
