    "mainNotes": "## Location within China\n\nHong Kong is located on the southern coast of China at the eastern side of the Pearl River Estuary. It is bordered by the Guangdong Province to the north, specifically sharing a land border with the city of Shenzhen. The South China Sea surrounds the territory to the east, south, and west. Across the Pearl River Delta to the west lies Macau, another special administrative region of China. As a special administrative region, Hong Kong operates under the principle of one country, two systems, maintaining separate governing and economic systems from mainland China.\n\n## Physical features\n\nHong Kong consists of three main territories: Hong Kong Island, the Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories. The region also includes over two hundred offshore islands, with Lantau Island being the largest. The terrain is highly hilly and mountainous, with steep slopes dominating the landscape. Tai Mo Shan is the highest peak, reaching an elevation of 957 meters. Due to the rugged topography, less than twenty-five percent of the land is developed. The remaining area is largely preserved as country parks and nature reserves, such as Sai Kung East Country Park and Lantau South Country Park. The coastline is deeply indented, creating numerous natural harbors and bays, most notably Victoria Harbour, which separates Hong Kong Island from the Kowloon Peninsula. The Sham Chun River forms the natural border with Shenzhen to the north.\n\n## Climate\n\nHong Kong experiences a humid subtropical climate with distinct seasons influenced by the Asian monsoon. Summers are hot, humid, and rainy, with frequent showers and thunderstorms. This season also brings the risk of typhoons, which can cause flooding and landslides. Winters are mild and relatively dry, with occasional cold fronts bringing cooler temperatures from the north. Spring is highly variable and often cloudy, while autumn is generally sunny and warm. The average annual rainfall is high, but the steep terrain means that water catchment and storage require extensive reservoir systems, such as the High Island Reservoir and Plover Cove Reservoir.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Hong Kong is highly developed and characterized by free trade, low taxation, and minimal government intervention. It is one of the world's leading financial centers, hosting a major stock exchange and numerous international banking institutions. The service sector dominates the economy, accounting for over ninety percent of the gross domestic product. Key industries include financial services, trading, logistics, and tourism. The Port of Hong Kong is among the busiest container ports globally. The territory is densely populated, with major urban centers concentrated along the shores of Victoria Harbour. Key districts include Central, which serves as the primary business and financial hub, as well as Mong Kok, Tsim Sha Tsui, and Causeway Bay. The New Territories contain several planned new towns, such as Sha Tin, Tuen Mun, and Tsuen Wan, which were developed to accommodate the growing population.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe region was sparsely populated by farming and fishing communities before the nineteenth century. Following the First Opium War, Hong Kong Island was ceded to the British Empire in 1842. The Kowloon Peninsula and the New Territories were subsequently added to the colony through later treaties. Hong Kong remained under British administration until sovereignty was transferred to the People's Republic of China in 1997. The population is predominantly ethnic Chinese, with a significant presence of international expatriates. Cantonese is the most widely spoken language, while English and Mandarin are also official and commonly used. The culture is a blend of traditional Chinese roots and Western influences, visible in its architecture, cinema, and culinary scene.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: China\n* Subdivision type: Special Administrative Region\n* Administrative center: Hong Kong\n* Approximate area: 1,110 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.4 million\n* Largest city: Hong Kong\n* Signature features: Victoria Harbour skyline, dense urban environment, global financial hub",
