    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nAlagoas is a state located in the eastern part of the Northeast Region of Brazil. It is one of the smallest Brazilian states by land area. Alagoas is bordered by the state of Pernambuco to the north and northwest, the state of Sergipe to the south, and the state of Bahia to the southwest. The eastern boundary of the state is formed by the Atlantic Ocean. The São Francisco River serves as the natural southern border separating Alagoas from Sergipe.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Alagoas transitions from a flat coastal plain in the east to a semi-arid plateau in the west. The coastal region features sandy beaches, restingas, mangroves, and extensive coral reefs. This area is also known for its large coastal lagoons, specifically the Mundaú and Manguaba lagoons, which gave the state its name. Moving inland, the landscape rises into the Borborema Plateau. The western interior is characterized by the Sertão, a dry region with scrubby vegetation known as the Caatinga. The most significant waterway is the São Francisco River, which flows along the southern border and empties into the Atlantic Ocean. Other notable rivers include the Mundaú and the Paraíba do Meio.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Alagoas varies significantly depending on the distance from the Atlantic Ocean. The coastal zone experiences a tropical humid climate with distinct wet and dry seasons. Rainfall in this eastern region is concentrated between the months of April and August. Temperatures along the coast remain consistently warm throughout the year. As the elevation increases toward the Borborema Plateau and extends into the western interior, the climate becomes semi-arid. This inland region, the Sertão, receives highly irregular rainfall and is prone to prolonged droughts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Alagoas has historically relied heavily on agriculture, with sugarcane being the dominant crop cultivated in the fertile coastal and forest zones. The state also produces coconuts, cassava, and tobacco. In recent decades, tourism has become a major economic driver due to the extensive coastal reefs and beaches in municipalities like Maragogi. The industrial sector includes chemical manufacturing, plastics, and food processing. There is also petroleum and natural gas extraction. Maceió is the capital and largest city, serving as the primary commercial and administrative hub. Arapiraca is the second-largest city and functions as an agricultural center in the interior. Penedo is an important historic port city located on the banks of the São Francisco River.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the area was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Caeté people. During the colonial period, Alagoas was initially part of the Captaincy of Pernambuco. It gained its independence as a separate captaincy in 1817 as a consequence of the Pernambucan Revolt. The state is historically significant as the location of the Quilombo dos Palmares. This was a large community of escaped enslaved Africans that resisted Portuguese and Dutch colonial forces for nearly a century under leaders like Zumbi dos Palmares. The culture of Alagoas is heavily influenced by African, Indigenous, and Portuguese traditions. It is known for its traditional folk dances and music, collectively called folguedos, as well as its intricate lacework and ceramics.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Maceió\n* Approximate area: 27,848 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.1 million\n* Largest city: Maceió\n* Signature features: The historic Quilombo dos Palmares, the Mundaú and Manguaba coastal lagoons, and the São Francisco River delta.",
    "summary": "Alagoas is a small coastal state in northeastern Brazil known for its tropical beaches, coastal lagoons, and the semi-arid interior of the Borborema Plateau. Its economy relies on sugarcane agriculture, tourism, and chemical manufacturing, with Maceió serving as the capital and largest city. The state holds significant historical importance as the former site of the Quilombo dos Palmares, a major center of resistance by escaped enslaved Africans.",
