    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nBahia is located in the northeastern region of Brazil. It has a long coastline along the Atlantic Ocean to the east. The state shares borders with eight other Brazilian states. To the north, it borders Sergipe, Alagoas, Pernambuco, and Piauí. Tocantins lies to the west, and Goiás is located to the southwest. To the south, Bahia shares boundaries with Minas Gerais and Espírito Santo.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state features a diverse topography that transitions from coastal plains to interior highlands. The Atlantic coastline is indented by several bays, most notably the Bay of All Saints (Baía de Todos os Santos), which is the largest bay in Brazil. Inland, the terrain rises into the Chapada Diamantina, a mountainous plateau region characterized by flat-topped peaks, deep valleys, and extensive cave systems. The São Francisco River is the most significant waterway in the state. It flows northward through the western part of Bahia before turning east toward the Atlantic Ocean. Other notable rivers include the Paraguaçu and the Contas. The coastal plain gradually gives way to a semi-arid interior region known as the sertão.\n\n## Climate\nBahia experiences varied climate zones depending on the geographic region. The coastal area has a tropical rainforest climate, characterized by high temperatures and significant rainfall throughout the year. Moving inland, the climate transitions to a tropical savanna zone with distinct wet and dry seasons. The deep interior sertão region features a semi-arid climate. This semi-arid zone receives irregular and sparse rainfall, making it prone to prolonged droughts. The Chapada Diamantina region experiences milder temperatures compared to the rest of the state due to its higher elevation.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Bahia is the largest in northeastern Brazil and relies on agriculture, industry, and services. The Recôncavo region around the Bay of All Saints is an industrial center, focusing on petrochemicals, automobile manufacturing, and oil refining. The western part of the state, particularly around the city of Barreiras, is a major agricultural producer that cultivates soybeans, cotton, and corn. Cacao is historically significant and is still grown in the southern coastal region near the city of Ilhéus. Salvador is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a major port and commercial hub. Other important cities include Feira de Santana, a major transportation and trade center, and Vitória da Conquista in the southwest. Tourism is also a major economic sector, driven by historical sites and coastal areas.\n\n## History & culture\nBahia holds a central place in Brazilian history as the site of the first Portuguese arrival in 1500, when Pedro Álvares Cabral landed near present-day Porto Seguro. Salvador was established in 1549 as the first capital of the Portuguese colony of Brazil, a status it maintained until 1763. The state was a major center for the transatlantic slave trade, which brought millions of enslaved Africans to work on sugar and tobacco plantations. Consequently, Bahia has a significant African influence that permeates its culture. This heritage is evident in the local cuisine, which features ingredients like palm oil and black-eyed peas, and in religious practices such as Candomblé. The state is also the birthplace of capoeira, an Afro-Brazilian martial art, and samba de roda, a traditional music and dance style.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Salvador\n* Approximate area: 564,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 14.1 million\n* Largest city: Salvador\n* Signature features: Bay of All Saints, Chapada Diamantina National Park, strong Afro-Brazilian cultural heritage",
    "summary": "Bahia is a state in northeastern Brazil known for its diverse geography, ranging from the tropical Atlantic coast and the Bay of All Saints to the semi-arid interior sertão. Its administrative center, Salvador, served as Brazil's first capital and remains a major cultural and economic hub. The state has a strong Afro-Brazilian heritage that heavily influences its music, cuisine, and traditions.",
