    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\n\nGoiás is a landlocked state located in the Center-West region of Brazil. It shares borders with the states of Tocantins to the north, Bahia to the east, Minas Gerais to the east and southeast, Mato Grosso do Sul to the southwest, and Mato Grosso to the west. Notably, Goiás completely surrounds the Federal District, which houses the national capital, Brasília.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe state is situated on the Brazilian Highlands, known locally as the Planalto Central. The terrain consists mostly of extensive plateaus and flat-topped hills called chapadas. Goiás is dominated by the Cerrado biome, a vast tropical savanna characterized by scattered trees, shrubs, and extensive grasslands. The state contains significant national parks protecting this biome, including Chapada dos Veadeiros National Park, famous for its ancient rock formations and quartz crystals, and Emas National Park. Major river systems drain the state. The Araguaia River forms the western border with Mato Grosso, while the Paranaíba River forms the southern border with Minas Gerais. The Tocantins River flows northward through the state. The highest elevation is Pouso Alto, reaching roughly 1,676 meters above sea level.\n\n## Climate\n\nGoiás experiences a tropical savanna climate, classified as Aw under the Köppen system. This climate features two distinct seasons. The wet season occurs from October to April, bringing heavy rainfall that sustains the region's agriculture and river systems. The dry season lasts from May to September, characterized by very low humidity and scarce precipitation. Average annual temperatures range from 22 to 26 degrees Celsius. During the dry season, daytime temperatures remain high, but nighttime temperatures can drop significantly due to the lack of cloud cover.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Goiás is heavily reliant on agriculture and livestock. It is one of Brazil's leading producers of soybeans, corn, sugarcane, and tomatoes. Cattle ranching is a major industry, alongside significant poultry and pork production. The state also has a robust mining sector, extracting minerals such as nickel, copper, gold, and niobium. Industrial activities are concentrated in food processing, ethanol production, and pharmaceuticals. Goiânia is the administrative center and the largest city, originally designed as a planned capital in the 1930s. Other major urban centers include Aparecida de Goiânia, which forms part of the capital's metropolitan area, Anápolis, a major logistics and industrial hub, and Rio Verde, a center for agribusiness in the southwest.\n\n## History & culture\n\nBefore European colonization, the region was inhabited by various Indigenous groups, including the Karajá and Avá-Canoeiro peoples. In the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, explorers from São Paulo known as bandeirantes arrived in search of gold and enslaved Indigenous labor. The ensuing gold rush led to the establishment of early settlements, including Vila Boa de Goiás. This town served as the state capital until the 1930s, when the government built the planned city of Goiânia to encourage development. Today, the historic center of the former capital, now called Cidade de Goiás, is a UNESCO World Heritage site. The culture of Goiás is deeply tied to its rural roots. The state is the national heartland of sertanejo music, a popular genre similar to country music. The local cuisine frequently features pequi, a native savanna fruit with a distinct flavor, and pamonha, a traditional dish made from fresh sweet corn.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Goiânia\n* Approximate area: 340,246 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.0 million\n* Largest city: Goiânia\n* Signature features: Completely surrounds the Brazilian Federal District, dominated by the Cerrado savanna biome, national hub for sertanejo music",
    "summary": "Goiás is a landlocked state in the Center-West region of Brazil, known for completely surrounding the nation's Federal District. Its geography is dominated by the Cerrado savanna biome, which supports a massive agricultural and livestock economy. The state is also recognized for its planned capital, Goiânia, and its strong cultural ties to sertanejo music.",
