    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nAmapá is a state located in the extreme northern region of Brazil. It is bordered to the north by French Guiana, an overseas department of France. To the west and south, it shares a domestic border with the Brazilian state of Pará. The eastern boundary of Amapá is formed by the Atlantic Ocean. The state is situated at the mouth of the Amazon River, which flows along its southern edge. The border with French Guiana is defined by the Oiapoque River.\n\n## Physical features\nThe landscape of Amapá is dominated by the Amazon rainforest, which covers the vast majority of its territory. The coastal plain features extensive mangrove swamps and tidal floodplains. Inland, the terrain transitions into a dense tropical forest and slightly elevated plateaus. The Tumucumaque Mountains are located in the northwestern part of the state. This range is home to Tumucumaque Mountains National Park, one of the largest tropical forest national parks in the world. Major rivers include the Araguari River, which flows entirely within the state, and the Jari River, which forms part of the southwestern border with Pará. The coastline includes geographical landmarks such as Cape Orange, located near the northern border.\n\n## Climate\nAmapá experiences an equatorial climate, characterized by high temperatures and significant humidity throughout the year. Average annual temperatures typically range from 25 to 28 degrees Celsius. The state receives abundant precipitation, with annual rainfall often exceeding 2,500 millimeters. The climate features a distinct wet season that generally lasts from December to August, bringing heavy and frequent rain showers. A relatively dry season occurs from September to November, although rain still falls during these months. This consistent equatorial climate supports the dense rainforest ecosystems found across the state.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Amapá relies heavily on the extraction of natural resources, agriculture, and public services. Mining is a significant industry, with historical and ongoing extraction of manganese, gold, and iron ore. The Serra do Navio region was particularly known for its large manganese deposits. Forestry and the harvesting of non-timber forest products, such as Brazil nuts and açaí berries, also contribute to the local economy. Macapá is the administrative center and the largest city, housing the majority of the state population. Santana, located just south of Macapá, is the second largest city and serves as the primary port for the state, handling the export of minerals and timber. Oiapoque is a notable municipality in the north, functioning as a key border crossing into French Guiana.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the region was inhabited by various indigenous groups, including the Arawak and Carib peoples. During the colonial era, the territory was heavily contested by the Portuguese, French, English, and Dutch due to its strategic location at the mouth of the Amazon River. The Treaty of Utrecht in 1713 established the Oiapoque River as the boundary between Portuguese Brazil and French Guiana, although border disputes with France continued until a Swiss arbitration settled the matter in 1900. Amapá was part of the state of Pará until 1943, when it was separated to become a federal territory. It officially achieved statehood in 1988 with the adoption of the new Brazilian constitution. The local culture is a blend of indigenous, African, and Portuguese influences. A prominent cultural expression is the Marabaixo, a traditional folk dance and music style with deep African roots. Macapá is also known for the Marco Zero monument, which marks the exact line of the Equator.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Macapá\n* Approximate area: 142,828 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 733,000\n* Largest city: Macapá\n* Signature features: The Equator passes directly through Macapá, and the state contains Tumucumaque Mountains National Park.",
