    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nMaranhão is a state located in the Northeast Region of Brazil. It is situated on the northern coast of the country, bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north. To the east, it shares a border with the state of Piauí, separated largely by the Parnaíba River. To the south and southwest, it borders the state of Tocantins. To the west, it shares a boundary with the state of Pará. Maranhão occupies a transitional geographic zone between the Amazon basin to the west and the semi-arid regions of the Brazilian Northeast.\n\n## Physical features\nMaranhão features coastal plains, low plateaus, and significant river basins. The indented coastline features the Baía de São Marcos and Baía de São José, surrounding the island of Upaon-Açu where the capital sits. Lençóis Maranhenses National Park is a distinctive coastal landform consisting of vast white sand dunes interspersed with seasonal rainwater lagoons. The Itapecuru and Mearim rivers flow entirely within the state, emptying into the northern bays. The Parnaíba River forms the eastern border, while the Tocantins River forms part of the southwestern border. The vegetation is highly diverse due to the state's transitional location, known as the Meio-Norte. It includes patches of Amazon rainforest in the west, Cerrado savanna in the south and center, and Babassu palm forests in the central valleys.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Maranhão is predominantly tropical. Temperatures remain high throughout the year, averaging roughly 27 degrees Celsius. The state experiences a distinct wet season and a dry season. The western portion of the state receives higher annual rainfall due to the proximity of the Amazon rainforest, often exceeding 2,000 millimeters per year. The eastern and southern regions are comparatively drier, influenced by the semi-arid climate of the broader Northeast Region. The rainy season generally occurs from January to June, which is responsible for filling the lagoons in the coastal dune systems.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Maranhão relies heavily on agriculture, industry, and port logistics. The southern and eastern parts produce soybeans, corn, and cotton, forming part of the MATOPIBA agricultural frontier. The industrial sector is anchored by aluminum production and metallurgy, particularly in the capital. The Port of Itaqui, located near São Luís, is one of the deepest and busiest ports in Brazil. It serves as a crucial export hub for iron ore mined in the neighboring state of Pará, transported via the Carajás Railway, as well as for regional agricultural products. São Luís is the administrative center and largest city. Imperatriz, located on the Tocantins River in the southwest, is the second largest city and a major commercial hub for the agricultural and timber industries. Other notable cities include São José de Ribamar, Timon, and Caxias.\n\n## History & culture\nVarious indigenous groups, including the Tupinambá, originally inhabited the area. São Luís holds the distinction of being the only Brazilian state capital founded by the French. French colonists established a settlement in 1612, naming it for King Louis XIII. The region was briefly occupied by the Dutch before coming under permanent Portuguese control in the mid-seventeenth century. The historic center of São Luís is a UNESCO World Heritage site, noted for its colonial architecture and Portuguese painted ceramic tiles called azulejos. The state has a distinct culture influenced by indigenous, African, and European traditions. It is known for the Bumba Meu Boi festival, a traditional folkloric performance that combines music, dance, and theater. Additionally, São Luís has a strong contemporary association with reggae music.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: São Luís\n* Approximate area: 331,983 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 6.7 million\n* Largest city: São Luís\n* Signature features: Lençóis Maranhenses National Park, French colonial history, Port of Itaqui, transition zone between Amazon and Cerrado biomes",
