    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nAmazonas is located in the North Region of Brazil. It is the largest state in the country by land area, occupying a significant portion of the western Amazon basin. The state shares domestic borders with Roraima to the north, Pará to the east, Mato Grosso to the southeast, Rondônia to the south, and Acre to the southwest. Additionally, Amazonas has international borders with three countries. It borders Venezuela to the north, Colombia to the northwest, and Peru to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Amazonas is dominated by the Amazon Rainforest and the extensive Amazon River basin. The state is characterized by a dense network of waterways. The primary river is the Amazon, which is known as the Solimões River from the Peruvian border until it reaches the city of Manaus. At Manaus, the sandy-colored Solimões converges with the dark waters of the Rio Negro in a phenomenon known as the Meeting of the Waters. Other major rivers flowing through the state include the Purus, Madeira, Juruá, and Içá.\n\nThe terrain consists mostly of flat, low-lying plains and flooded forests. However, the northern border with Venezuela features the Guiana Shield highlands. This area is home to Pico da Neblina, which stands at roughly 2,995 meters and is the highest mountain in Brazil. Significant protected areas include Pico da Neblina National Park, Jaú National Park, and the Anavilhanas National Park, which protects one of the largest river archipelagos in the world.\n\n## Climate\nAmazonas experiences a tropical equatorial climate, classified as Af under the Köppen climate classification system. The region is characterized by high temperatures and high humidity throughout the year. Average annual temperatures consistently range between 26 and 28 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is abundant, with most areas receiving between 2,000 and 3,000 millimeters of rain annually. While rain occurs year-round, there is a distinct wet season that typically lasts from December to May, causing river levels to rise significantly and flood the surrounding forests.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Amazonas underwent a major transformation in the twentieth century. Historically dependent on the extraction of wild rubber, the modern economy is heavily driven by the industrial sector. This is largely due to the Free Economic Zone of Manaus, a tax-free industrial pole established by the federal government to promote regional development. The zone manufactures electronics, motorcycles, and various consumer goods. Extractive activities, agriculture, and ecotourism also contribute to the economy.\n\nManaus is the administrative center, the largest city, and the primary economic hub of the state. It functions as a major inland port accessible to ocean-going vessels. Other important municipalities include Parintins, Itacoatiara, Manacapuru, and Coari. Due to the dense rainforest environment, the state has a limited road network, and transportation relies heavily on river navigation and air travel.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous populations inhabited the Amazon basin for thousands of years prior to European contact. In the sixteenth century, Spanish explorer Francisco de Orellana became the first European to navigate the length of the Amazon River. Portuguese colonization followed, focusing on establishing military forts and religious missions to secure the territory.\n\nDuring the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the region experienced the Amazon rubber boom. The global demand for rubber brought significant wealth to the state, funding the construction of European-style architecture in Manaus, such as the Amazon Theatre. Today, the culture of Amazonas reflects a strong Indigenous heritage blended with Portuguese influences. A major cultural event is the Parintins Folklore Festival, an annual celebration held in the city of Parintins that features a traditional theatrical competition.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Manaus\n* Approximate area: 1,559,159 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.9 million\n* Largest city: Manaus\n* Signature features: Amazon Rainforest, Amazon River, Meeting of the Waters, Pico da Neblina, Free Economic Zone of Manaus",
