    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nParaíba is a state located in the Northeast Region of Brazil. It is bordered by the state of Rio Grande do Norte to the north, Ceará to the west, and Pernambuco to the south. To the east, Paraíba has a coastline along the Atlantic Ocean. A notable geographic marker within the state is Ponta do Seixas, located in the capital city of João Pessoa. Ponta do Seixas is recognized as the easternmost point of the continental Americas.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Paraíba is divided into distinct geographic zones from the coast to the interior. The coastal plain, known as the Zona da Mata, features sandy beaches, estuaries, and remnants of the Atlantic Forest. Moving inland, the terrain transitions into the Agreste, a slightly elevated region. Further west lies the Borborema Plateau, a highland area that acts as a barrier to moisture from the ocean. Beyond the plateau is the Sertão, a vast semi-arid depression. Major rivers include the Paraíba River, which flows eastward to the Atlantic Ocean, and the Piranhas River, which flows northward into Rio Grande do Norte. The state also contains the Valley of the Dinosaurs in the municipality of Sousa, which preserves fossilized dinosaur footprints.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Paraíba varies significantly depending on the region. The coastal area experiences a tropical humid climate with distinct wet and dry seasons. Most of the rainfall along the coast occurs between the autumn and winter months. The interior Sertão region has a semi-arid climate characterized by high temperatures and low, irregular precipitation. This interior area is prone to severe and prolonged droughts. The Borborema Plateau experiences slightly cooler temperatures due to its higher elevation, and it receives more rainfall than the Sertão but less than the coastal plain.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Paraíba relies on a mix of agriculture, industry, and services. The coastal region historically depended on sugarcane cultivation, which remains an important agricultural product alongside pineapple and cassava. In the interior, cattle ranching and the cultivation of cotton and sisal are common. The industrial sector includes textile manufacturing, footwear production, and food processing. Tourism is a growing industry, driven by the coastal beaches and historical sites. João Pessoa is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the primary economic and political hub. Campina Grande is the second-largest city and is recognized as a center for technology, higher education, and software development. Other significant municipalities include Santa Rita, Patos, and Sousa.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the region was inhabited by Indigenous groups such as the Potiguara and Tabajara. Portuguese colonists established the first permanent settlement in 1585, initially naming it Filipéia de Nossa Senhora das Neves, which eventually became João Pessoa. The area experienced a period of Dutch occupation during the seventeenth century before returning to Portuguese control. The early economy was heavily based on sugar plantations worked by enslaved Africans. Culturally, Paraíba is known for its traditional music and festivals. The state is a center for forró music and cordel literature, a type of popular folk poetry. Campina Grande hosts a massive Festa Junina celebration, attracting visitors from across the country every June.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: João Pessoa\n* Approximate area: 56,440 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4,000,000\n* Largest city: João Pessoa\n* Signature features: Ponta do Seixas (easternmost point of the Americas), Valley of the Dinosaurs, Borborema Plateau",
    "summary": "Paraíba is a state in northeastern Brazil known for containing the easternmost point of the continental Americas at Ponta do Seixas. Its geography transitions from a humid coastal plain on the Atlantic Ocean to the semi-arid interior known as the Sertão, separated by the Borborema Plateau. The state's economy is driven by agriculture, textiles, and a growing technology sector centered in the city of Campina Grande.",
