    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nMato Grosso is a landlocked state located in the Center-West region of Brazil. It shares an international border with Bolivia to the southwest. Domestically, it is bordered by the states of Amazonas and Pará to the north, Tocantins and Goiás to the east, Mato Grosso do Sul to the south, and Rondônia to the west. It is the third largest state in Brazil by total land area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe landscape of Mato Grosso is defined by three major biomes. The northern region is covered by the Amazon Rainforest. The central and eastern areas consist of the Cerrado, a vast tropical savanna. The southwestern portion contains part of the Pantanal, one of the largest continuous tropical wetlands in the world. The state lacks a coastline. Prominent landforms include the Chapada dos Guimarães, a sandstone plateau featuring steep cliffs and waterfalls. The state is drained by several major river systems. The Paraguay River and the Cuiabá River flow southward through the Pantanal. The northern part of the state is drained by tributaries of the Amazon River, including the Xingu, Juruena, and Teles Pires rivers.\n\n## Climate\nMato Grosso experiences a tropical climate. The state has two distinct seasons, which include a rainy season from October to April and a dry season from May to September. Temperatures remain high throughout the year, often exceeding 30 degrees Celsius. The northern Amazonian region receives higher annual precipitation and maintains higher humidity than the central Cerrado. During the dry season, the Pantanal water levels drop significantly, and the Cerrado region becomes susceptible to wildfires.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mato Grosso is heavily dependent on agriculture and livestock. It is the largest producer of soybeans, corn, and cotton in Brazil. The state also maintains one of the largest cattle herds in the country. This agricultural expansion has led to significant economic growth but has also caused severe deforestation in the Amazon and Cerrado biomes. Cuiabá is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the primary commercial and cultural hub. Várzea Grande is located adjacent to Cuiabá and forms a major metropolitan area. Other important cities include Rondonópolis in the south, which is a major agricultural processing center, and Sinop and Sorriso in the north, both of which grew rapidly due to the expansion of soybean farming.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European arrival, the region was inhabited by numerous indigenous groups, including the Bororo, Xavante, and Kayapó peoples. In the early eighteenth century, Portuguese explorers known as Bandeirantes arrived in search of gold and indigenous slaves. The discovery of gold along the Coxipó River led to the founding of Cuiabá in 1719. The region was originally claimed by Spain under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but Portuguese settlement secured it for Brazil. In 1979, the federal government divided the original state into two, creating the new state of Mato Grosso do Sul in the southern half. The culture of Mato Grosso blends indigenous traditions with Portuguese colonial influences. In recent decades, migration from southern Brazil has introduced gaucho cultural elements, particularly in the agricultural towns of the north.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Cuiabá\n* Approximate area: 903,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.6 million\n* Largest city: Cuiabá\n* Signature features: The Pantanal wetlands, extensive soybean and cattle production",
    "summary": "Mato Grosso is a large, landlocked state in the Center-West region of Brazil known for its diverse biomes, including the Amazon Rainforest, Cerrado savanna, and Pantanal wetlands. Its capital and largest city is Cuiabá. The state's economy is heavily driven by agriculture, particularly the extensive production of soybeans, corn, and cattle.",
