    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nPará is a state located in the North Region of Brazil. It is the second largest state in the country by area. It shares domestic borders with six other Brazilian states. To the north, it borders Amapá and Roraima. To the east, it borders Maranhão and Tocantins. To the south, it borders Mato Grosso, and to the west, it borders Amazonas. Pará also has international borders with Guyana and Suriname to the far northwest. The state features a coastline along the Atlantic Ocean to the northeast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Pará is dominated by the Amazon River and its large basin. The Amazon River flows eastward through the state and empties into the Atlantic Ocean. At the mouth of the Amazon lies Marajó Island, which is the largest fluvial-maritime island in the world. Several major tributaries intersect the state, including the Tapajós, Xingu, and Tocantins rivers. The terrain primarily consists of low-lying Amazonian plains covered by dense tropical rainforest. In the northernmost areas, the land rises into the Guiana Shield, which includes parts of the Tumucumaque Mountains National Park. The southern portion of the state transitions into the northern edges of the Brazilian Highlands.\n\n## Climate\nPará experiences a predominantly equatorial climate. Temperatures remain consistently warm throughout the year, typically averaging around 26 to 28 degrees Celsius. Humidity levels are notably high. Precipitation is abundant, though the distribution of rainfall varies by region. The northern and coastal areas receive heavy rainfall almost year-round. The southern and eastern parts of the state experience a more pronounced dry season, usually lasting from June to November, followed by a distinct wet season.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Pará relies heavily on mining, agriculture, and energy production. The state is a major global producer of iron ore, primarily sourced from the extensive Carajás Mine in the southeast. Other significant mineral exports include bauxite, manganese, and gold. Agriculture is another major economic driver, with extensive cattle ranching and soybean cultivation in the southern and eastern regions. Pará is also the largest producer of açaí, black pepper, and cocoa in Brazil. The state generates substantial hydroelectric power, notably from the Tucuruí Dam on the Tocantins River. Belém is the administrative center and largest city, serving as a major port and commercial hub. Other important cities include Ananindeua, Santarém in the lower Amazon, and the mining centers of Marabá and Parauapebas.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European arrival, the region was inhabited by numerous indigenous groups, including the Marajoara culture known for its complex pottery. Portuguese colonization began in 1616 with the founding of Belém to secure the mouth of the Amazon River. During the 1830s, the state was the site of the Cabanagem, a major regional revolt by the poor and indigenous populations against the political elite. In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Pará experienced significant economic expansion during the Amazon rubber boom, which funded extensive urban development in Belém. The culture of Pará is heavily influenced by indigenous, African, and Portuguese traditions. The state is known for the Círio de Nazaré, an annual Catholic festival in Belém that attracts millions of pilgrims. Regional cuisine prominently features local ingredients like açaí, manioc, tucupi broth, and the jambu leaf. Traditional music and dance styles, such as carimbó, are central to the local cultural identity.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Belém\n* Approximate area: 1,248,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 8.1 million\n* Largest city: Belém\n* Signature features: Marajó Island, the Carajás iron ore mine, and the Amazon River delta.",
    "summary": "Pará is a large state in northern Brazil dominated by the Amazon River basin and dense tropical rainforests. Its economy is heavily driven by iron ore mining at the Carajás Mine, agriculture, and hydroelectric power. The state is culturally significant for its indigenous heritage, the historic rubber boom architecture of its capital Belém, and unique regional traditions like the Círio de Nazaré festival.",
