    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nPernambuco is a state located in the Northeast Region of Brazil. It features a long, narrow shape that stretches from the Atlantic Ocean in the east deep into the Brazilian interior to the west. The state shares borders with Paraíba and Ceará to the north, Piauí to the west, and Alagoas and Bahia to the south. In addition to its mainland territory, Pernambuco administers the Fernando de Noronha archipelago, which is situated roughly 350 kilometers off the northeastern coast of Brazil in the Atlantic Ocean.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Pernambuco is traditionally divided into three distinct longitudinal zones. The easternmost zone is the Zona da Mata, a coastal plain that originally supported dense Atlantic Forest and is characterized by fertile soils. Moving inland, the Agreste serves as a transitional zone situated on the Borborema Plateau, an elevated region that blocks moisture from reaching the interior. The westernmost and largest zone is the Sertão, a semi-arid region characterized by the Caatinga biome, which consists of thorny scrub vegetation. Major rivers include the Capibaribe River, which flows eastward and empties into the Atlantic Ocean at Recife. The São Francisco River forms a significant portion of the southwestern border with Bahia and provides critical water resources for irrigation in the dry interior.\n\n## Climate\nPernambuco experiences two primary climate types based on its geographic zones. The coastal Zona da Mata has a tropical humid climate with high temperatures year-round and distinct wet and dry seasons. The majority of the rainfall in this coastal region occurs between April and July. The interior Sertão features a semi-arid climate characterized by high temperatures, low humidity, and irregular rainfall. This inland region is highly susceptible to prolonged droughts. The transitional Agreste zone experiences a sub-humid climate, with temperatures and rainfall levels falling between those of the coast and the deep interior.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Pernambuco is diverse, encompassing agriculture, industry, and services. The coastal region remains a major producer of sugarcane, continuing a centuries-old agricultural tradition. In the interior, the city of Petrolina utilizes irrigation from the São Francisco River to produce export-quality fruits, particularly grapes and mangoes. The state has a significant industrial sector centered around the Suape Port and Industrial Complex, which houses petrochemical refineries, shipyards, and automotive manufacturing plants. Recife, the administrative center and largest city, is a major hub for healthcare, education, and technology, hosting the Porto Digital technology park. Other major cities include Jaboatão dos Guararapes, the historic city of Olinda, and Caruaru, which serves as a commercial center in the Agreste region.\n\n## History & culture\nDuring the colonial era, the Captaincy of Pernambuco was one of the most prosperous regions in Portuguese America due to its lucrative sugar plantations. The wealth generated by sugar attracted the Dutch West India Company, which occupied Recife and Olinda from 1630 to 1654. Following the expulsion of the Dutch, the region experienced several political uprisings, including the Pernambucan Revolt of 1817, which briefly established an independent republic. The cultural landscape of Pernambuco is deeply influenced by Indigenous, African, and Portuguese traditions. The state is the birthplace of musical and dance styles such as frevo and maracatu, which are prominently featured during the annual Carnival celebrations in Recife and Olinda. Caruaru is noted for its large-scale Festa Junina celebrations and its traditional clay figurine crafts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Recife\n* Approximate area: 98,311 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 9.0 million\n* Largest city: Recife\n* Signature features: The Fernando de Noronha archipelago, the historic colonial architecture of Olinda, and traditional cultural expressions like frevo and maracatu.",
