    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nPiauí is a state located in the Northeast Region of Brazil. It shares borders with several other Brazilian states. To the west, the Parnaíba River forms a natural boundary with Maranhão. To the southwest, Piauí borders Tocantins. Bahia lies to the south and east, while Pernambuco and Ceará border the state to the east. In the north, Piauí has a very brief coastline along the Atlantic Ocean. Measuring approximately 66 kilometers, this is the shortest coastline of any coastal state in Brazil.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Piauí is largely defined by the Parnaíba River basin. The Parnaíba River flows northward and empties into the Atlantic Ocean, creating the Parnaíba Delta. This delta is a massive archipelago of islands, mangroves, and dunes. The terrain of the state consists mostly of gently rolling plains and low plateaus that form part of the broader Brazilian Highlands. In the southeastern part of the state, the landscape features sandstone massifs and deep valleys. This area is home to the Serra da Capivara National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its dense concentration of prehistoric rock art. Another significant protected area is the Serra das Confusões National Park, which preserves a large expanse of the Caatinga biome and features dramatic rocky outcrops.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Piauí varies from tropical in the north to semi-arid in the interior. The northern region, particularly near the coast and the Parnaíba River valley, experiences a tropical wet and dry climate with higher humidity and more consistent rainfall. The interior of the state, known as the sertão, falls within the semi-arid climate zone. This region experiences prolonged dry seasons and irregular rainfall, making it susceptible to drought. Temperatures across the state are generally high throughout the year, often exceeding 30 degrees Celsius. The rainy season typically occurs between December and May, while the rest of the year remains very dry.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTeresina is the administrative center and the largest city in Piauí. It is notable for being the only capital city in the Northeast Region that is not located on the coast. Other major cities include Parnaíba near the northern coast, Picos in the central-south region, and Floriano along the Parnaíba River. The economy of Piauí relies heavily on the service sector, agriculture, and livestock. Cattle and goat ranching are traditional economic activities in the interior. In recent decades, the southern part of the state has seen significant growth in mechanized agriculture, particularly the cultivation of soybeans and cotton. The state also produces cashew nuts, sugarcane, and carnauba wax. Mining plays a smaller role, though the town of Pedro II is known for its opal mines. Tourism is a growing industry, driven by the archaeological sites of Serra da Capivara and the ecological attractions of the Parnaíba Delta.\n\n## History & culture\nHuman presence in Piauí dates back tens of thousands of years, as evidenced by the extensive rock paintings found in the Serra da Capivara region. During the colonial era, European settlement in Piauí differed from the rest of northeastern Brazil. While other coastal states were colonized primarily for sugarcane plantations, Piauí was settled by cattle ranchers moving inland from Bahia and Pernambuco. This pastoral history deeply influenced the local culture and economy. Piauí also played a role in the Brazilian War of Independence. The Battle of Jenipapo, fought in 1823 near the town of Campo Maior, was a decisive engagement between local forces and Portuguese troops. The culture of Piauí features traditional festivals such as Bumba Meu Boi, alongside regional cuisines that heavily incorporate sun-dried meats, local beans, and cashew products.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Teresina\n* Approximate area: 251,531 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.3 million\n* Largest city: Teresina\n* Signature features: The shortest coastline of any Brazilian coastal state, the prehistoric rock art of Serra da Capivara National Park, and the Parnaíba Delta.",
