    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nThe state of Rio de Janeiro is located in the Southeast region of Brazil. It shares borders with three other Brazilian states. Espírito Santo lies to the northeast, Minas Gerais is situated to the north and northwest, and São Paulo borders the state to the southwest. The eastern and southern boundaries of the state are formed by the Atlantic Ocean, providing an extensive coastline.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of the state is characterized by coastal plains, bays, and steep mountain ranges. The Baixada Fluminense is a large lowland area surrounding Guanabara Bay. The coastline features several prominent indentations, including Guanabara Bay, Sepetiba Bay, and Ilha Grande Bay. Inland, the terrain rises sharply into the Serra do Mar and the Serra da Mantiqueira mountain ranges. The highest point in the state is Pico das Agulhas Negras, which reaches approximately 2,791 meters and sits on the border with Minas Gerais. The Paraíba do Sul is the most significant river in the state, flowing from São Paulo through the Paraíba Valley before emptying into the Atlantic Ocean. The state contains several protected areas, such as Itatiaia National Park, Tijuca National Park, and Serra dos Órgãos National Park, which is known for the Dedo de Deus peak.\n\n## Climate\nThe state experiences a predominantly tropical climate along the coast and in the lowland areas. These regions have hot, humid summers and mild, relatively dry winters. Summer rainfall is frequent between December and March. In the higher elevations of the Serra do Mar and Serra da Mantiqueira, the climate is classified as tropical altitude or subtropical. Cities in these mountainous areas, such as Petrópolis and Teresópolis, record significantly lower average temperatures than the coastal plains and occasionally experience frost during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nRio de Janeiro holds the second largest economy among Brazilian states. The service sector is the largest component of the economy, driven by commerce, finance, and tourism. The state is the leading producer of petroleum and natural gas in Brazil, with extensive offshore drilling operations located in the Campos Basin and the Santos Basin. The city of Macaé serves as a major operational hub for the offshore oil industry. Manufacturing is another crucial sector, highlighted by the steel production facilities in Volta Redonda. The administrative center and largest city is Rio de Janeiro. Other highly populated cities include São Gonçalo, Duque de Caxias, Nova Iguaçu, and Niterói, all of which are part of the greater metropolitan area.\n\n## History & culture\nPortuguese explorers first encountered Guanabara Bay in 1502. The city of Rio de Janeiro was founded in 1565 and eventually became the colonial capital of Brazil in 1763. It later served as the capital of the Portuguese Empire from 1808 to 1821. The city remained the national capital of Brazil until 1960, when the government relocated to Brasília. Following this move, the city of Rio de Janeiro became the state of Guanabara. In 1975, Guanabara merged with the surrounding state of Rio de Janeiro to form the current political boundaries. The state has a strong cultural influence within Brazil, recognized as a focal point for the development of samba and bossa nova music. It is also known for its large annual Carnival festivals and its historical association with Brazilian football, centered around the Maracanã Stadium.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Rio de Janeiro\n* Approximate area: 43,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 16 million\n* Largest city: Rio de Janeiro\n* Signature features: Guanabara Bay, offshore petroleum extraction in the Campos Basin, Christ the Redeemer statue on Corcovado mountain",
