    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nRio Grande do Sul is the southernmost state of Brazil. It is bordered by the Brazilian state of Santa Catarina to the north. To the west, the Uruguay River forms the international border with Argentina. To the south, the state shares an international border with Uruguay. The eastern boundary of the state is formed by the Atlantic Ocean.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Rio Grande do Sul transitions between two major biomes. The northern half of the state features the Atlantic Forest and the elevated plateau of the Serra Geral mountain range. The southern half is dominated by the Pampas, which are vast, rolling grasslands. The state has a long coastal plain that contains large lagoon systems. Lagoa dos Patos is the largest lagoon in Brazil, and it connects to the Atlantic Ocean near the city of Rio Grande. Further south lies Lagoa Mirim, which is shared with Uruguay. Major rivers include the Uruguay River, the Jacuí River, and the Ibicuí River. The Jacuí River flows into the Guaíba Lake, which borders the capital city. Aparados da Serra National Park, located on the border with Santa Catarina, is noted for its deep canyons such as Itaimbezinho.\n\n## Climate\nRio Grande do Sul has a humid subtropical climate. It is one of the few Brazilian states with four distinct seasons. Summers are generally hot, while winters can be quite cold by Brazilian standards. Frost is common during the winter months. In the higher elevations of the Serra Gaúcha, occasional snowfall occurs. Precipitation is relatively abundant and distributed evenly throughout the year, supporting the state's extensive agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe state has a diverse economy based on agriculture, livestock, and manufacturing. Rio Grande do Sul is a leading national producer of soybeans, wheat, rice, and tobacco. The southern grasslands support a massive cattle ranching industry, producing beef and leather. The Serra Gaúcha region is the center of the Brazilian wine industry. Industrial sectors include automotive manufacturing, petrochemicals, footwear, and machinery. Porto Alegre is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a major economic and cultural hub. Other significant cities include Caxias do Sul, an industrial center in the mountains, and Pelotas, located in the southern coastal plain. The city of Rio Grande operates as one of the most important maritime ports in Brazil.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European colonization, the region was inhabited by Indigenous groups such as the Guarani and Kaingang. During the colonial era, the territory was heavily contested between the Portuguese and Spanish empires. This borderland status led to a militarized society and the development of the Gaúcho culture, centered around cattle ranching on the Pampas. Between 1835 and 1845, the state fought a separatist rebellion against the Brazilian Empire known as the Ragamuffin War. In the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, the state received significant waves of European immigrants. German and Italian immigrants settled heavily in the northern and mountainous regions, influencing local architecture, agriculture, and cuisine. The local culture is strongly associated with the consumption of yerba mate tea, known locally as chimarrão, and traditional Brazilian barbecue, or churrasco.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Porto Alegre\n* Approximate area: 281,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 11.3 million\n* Largest city: Porto Alegre\n* Signature features: Gaúcho culture, Lagoa dos Patos, and the Serra Gaúcha wine region",
