    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nRio Grande do Norte is a state located in the Northeast Region of Brazil. It occupies the northeasternmost tip of the South American continent. The state is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north and east, the state of Paraíba to the south, and the state of Ceará to the west. Because of its geographic position at the corner of the continent, the coastline makes a sharp turn from an east-west orientation to a north-south orientation near Cape São Roque. The state also holds jurisdiction over the Rocas Atoll, a biological reserve located in the Atlantic Ocean roughly 260 kilometers off the mainland coast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Rio Grande do Norte transitions from coastal plains to inland plateaus. The eastern and northern coastlines feature large beaches, lagoons, and sand dunes, such as those found at Genipabu. Moving inland, the terrain rises into the Borborema Plateau, which dominates the southern portion of the state. The central and western areas consist of lower, flatter terrain that forms part of the semi-arid interior known as the sertão. Major rivers include the Potengi River, which empties into the Atlantic Ocean at Natal, and the Piranhas-Açu River system, which provides irrigation for the dry western regions.\n\n## Climate\nThe state experiences two primary climate zones. The eastern coastal region has a tropical wet and dry climate, characterized by high humidity, warm temperatures year-round, and a distinct rainy season that typically lasts from April to August. The interior region, covering the majority of the state's land area, features a hot semi-arid climate. This inland area receives highly irregular rainfall and is prone to prolonged droughts. The vegetation in the semi-arid zone consists mostly of caatinga, a biome characterized by thorny shrubs, cacti, and drought-resistant trees.\n\n## Economy & cities\nNatal is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the primary hub for services, commerce, and tourism. Mossoró, the second-largest city, is located in the western part of the state and is a major center for onshore petroleum extraction and agriculture. Rio Grande do Norte is the largest producer of sea salt in Brazil, generating the vast majority of the country's supply from evaporation ponds along the northern coast near Macau and Areia Branca. The state is also a leading producer of wind energy and cultivates export crops such as melons, mangoes, and cashews. Tourism is a significant economic driver along the coast.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European arrival, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Potiguara. Portuguese colonization began in the late sixteenth century with the construction of the Forte dos Reis Magos at the mouth of the Potengi River. During the seventeenth century, the area experienced a period of Dutch occupation before returning to Portuguese control. In the twentieth century, Rio Grande do Norte played a strategic role during World War II. The United States military established an airbase in Parnamirim, near Natal, which served as an important refueling point for Allied aircraft flying to Africa and Europe. The local culture is heavily influenced by Portuguese and indigenous traditions, featuring regional foods like sun-dried meat and cultural festivals centered around forró music.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Natal\n* Approximate area: 52,811 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.3 million\n* Largest city: Natal\n* Signature features: Produces the majority of Brazil's sea salt, features large coastal sand dunes, and includes the Rocas Atoll biological reserve.",
    "summary": "Rio Grande do Norte is a state in northeastern Brazil known for its strategic location at the corner of the South American continent. Its geography transitions from a tropical coastline famous for large sand dunes to a semi-arid interior dominated by the caatinga biome. The state has a diverse economy driven by sea salt production, wind energy, agriculture, and tourism centered around its capital city, Natal.",
