    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\n\nRoraima is the northernmost state of Brazil. It is situated in the North Region of the country. The state shares international borders with Venezuela to the north and northwest and with Guyana to the east. Domestically, Roraima is bordered by the Brazilian states of Pará to the southeast and Amazonas to the south and west. The equator crosses the southern portion of the state, placing the majority of Roraima in the Northern Hemisphere.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Roraima is defined by the Guiana Shield and the Amazon basin. The terrain transitions from dense Amazon rainforest in the south and west to open savannas, known locally as the lavrado, in the northeast. The state is named after Mount Roraima, a large tabletop mountain or tepui located at the tripoint border of Brazil, Venezuela, and Guyana. The Branco River is the primary waterway in the state. It is formed by the confluence of the Uraricoera and Tacutu rivers and flows southward to join the Rio Negro. Large portions of the state are protected areas or indigenous territories, including the Yanomami Indigenous Territory.\n\n## Climate\n\nRoraima experiences a tropical climate. The southern and western areas feature a tropical rainforest climate with high humidity and significant rainfall throughout the year. The eastern and northern savanna regions have a tropical monsoon or tropical savanna climate. These areas experience a distinct dry season from December to March and a wet season from May to October. Temperatures remain consistently high year-round, averaging roughly 26 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Roraima is the smallest of any Brazilian state. It relies heavily on the service sector, public administration, agriculture, and mining. Agricultural outputs include soybeans, rice, and corn, while cattle ranching is prominent in the savanna regions. Mining for gold and diamonds occurs in the state, though illegal mining operations have caused significant environmental and social conflicts, particularly within indigenous reserves. Boa Vista is the administrative center and the largest city. It is the only Brazilian state capital located entirely north of the equator. Other notable municipalities include Rorainópolis in the south, Caracaraí on the Branco River, and Pacaraima on the Venezuelan border.\n\n## History & culture\n\nIndigenous peoples, including the Yanomami, Macuxi, and Wapishana, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. European exploration began in the eighteenth century when the Portuguese built Fort São Joaquim to secure the area against Spanish and Dutch incursions. The region was long administered as part of Amazonas. In 1943, the federal government separated the area to create the Federal Territory of Rio Branco. The territory was renamed Roraima in 1962 and was elevated to full statehood in 1988. The culture of Roraima is heavily influenced by its indigenous populations, as well as migrants from the Northeast Region of Brazil. In recent years, the state has experienced significant demographic changes due to the arrival of migrants and refugees crossing the northern border from Venezuela.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Boa Vista\n* Approximate area: 224,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 636,000\n* Largest city: Boa Vista\n* Signature features: Mount Roraima, the Branco River, and the Yanomami Indigenous Territory",
