    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nCatamarca is a province located in the northwestern region of Argentina. It shares an international border with the Republic of Chile to the west. Within Argentina, it is bordered by the province of Salta to the north, Tucumán and Santiago del Estero to the east, Córdoba to the southeast, and La Rioja to the south. The province is entirely landlocked and sits at a position connecting the high Andean plateau with the lower plains of the Argentine interior.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Catamarca is highly mountainous and is generally divided into three distinct topographical zones. The westernmost zone is the Puna, a high-altitude desert plateau that features some of the highest peaks in the Andes. This area includes Ojos del Salado, which sits on the Chilean border and is the highest active volcano in the world, as well as Monte Pissis and the Galán caldera. The central region consists of the Sierras Pampeanas, a series of ancient mountain ranges separated by deep valleys and dry basins known as bolsones. The eastern part of the province transitions into lower sierras and the edges of the Gran Chaco plain. Major watercourses are scarce due to the arid environment, but the Santa María River and the Valle River provide essential water resources for the populated valleys.\n\n## Climate\nCatamarca experiences a predominantly arid and semi-arid climate, though conditions vary significantly with altitude. The eastern valleys have a subtropical climate with very hot summers and mild winters. Most of the province's limited rainfall, which averages roughly 400 to 500 millimeters annually in the east, occurs during the summer months. The central sierras are drier, while the western Puna region features a harsh, cold desert climate with extreme diurnal temperature variations and almost no precipitation. The province is also affected by the Zonda, a dry and warm wind that descends from the Andes and frequently raises temperatures while lowering humidity.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Catamarca is heavily reliant on mining and agriculture. The province is a major producer of minerals, historically anchored by the Bajo de la Alumbrera mine, which yielded large quantities of copper and gold. In recent years, the extraction of lithium from the salt flats in the Puna region has become a central economic driver. Agricultural activity is concentrated in the irrigated valleys, where farmers cultivate olives, grapes for wine production, walnuts, and cotton. Livestock rearing, particularly goats and llamas, is common in the drier and higher altitude areas. San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as the commercial and political hub. Other notable cities include Andalgalá, Tinogasta, Belén, and Santa María, which function as regional agricultural and mining centers.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Diaguita and the Calchaquí, who were later incorporated into the expanding Inca Empire. Spanish explorers arrived in the mid-sixteenth century, and the city of San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca was officially founded in 1683 after earlier settlements were destroyed by indigenous resistance. The province has a strong cultural heritage rooted in this blend of indigenous and Spanish colonial traditions. Catamarca is known for its textile production, especially the weaving of garments from vicuña and llama wool. This tradition is celebrated annually at the National Poncho Festival, which is a major cultural event in the region.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca\n* Approximate area: 102,600 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 429,000\n* Largest city: San Fernando del Valle de Catamarca\n* Signature features: Ojos del Salado volcano, extensive lithium and copper mining operations, and the annual National Poncho Festival",
    "summary": "Catamarca is a mountainous province in northwestern Argentina known for its arid climate, high Andean peaks, and rich mineral resources. Its economy relies heavily on copper and lithium mining, as well as agriculture in its irrigated valleys. The province features a blend of indigenous and Spanish colonial culture, famously celebrated through its traditional textile weaving.",
