    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nSanta Catarina is a state located in the South Region of Brazil. It is bordered by the state of Paraná to the north and the state of Rio Grande do Sul to the south. To the west, it shares an international border with the Misiones province of Argentina. The eastern boundary of the state is formed by the Atlantic Ocean. It is one of the smaller Brazilian states by land area but occupies a strategic position connecting the major economies of the Southern Cone.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Santa Catarina is characterized by a narrow coastal plain, steep mountain ranges, and an expansive western plateau. The Atlantic coastline is highly indented, featuring numerous bays, inlets, and islands. The most prominent island is Santa Catarina Island, which hosts a significant portion of the state capital. Moving inland, the terrain rises abruptly at the Serra do Mar and the Serra Geral mountain ranges. These highlands separate the coastal lowlands from the interior plateau. The highest peak in the state is Morro da Boa Vista, reaching approximately 1,827 meters above sea level. The state is drained by several major river systems. The Uruguay River and its tributary, the Pelotas River, form the southern border with Rio Grande do Sul. The Itajaí-Açu River is the most important waterway in the eastern part of the state, flowing through a heavily populated valley into the Atlantic Ocean.\n\n## Climate\nSanta Catarina experiences a humid subtropical climate. The coastal plain and the western valleys generally have warmer temperatures and lack a dry season. The interior plateau and the mountain ranges have a temperate climate with milder summers and cold winters. Because of its southern latitude and varying elevations, Santa Catarina is one of the few places in Brazil that regularly records freezing temperatures and occasional snowfall during the winter months. Cities in the high-altitude serras, such as São Joaquim and Urupema, are known for these winter conditions. Precipitation is relatively well distributed throughout the year across the entire state.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe state possesses a highly diversified and industrialized economy, consistently ranking among the highest in Brazil for standard of living and human development. The agricultural sector is a major producer of poultry, pork, and apples, with the western city of Chapecó serving as a hub for agribusiness. The manufacturing sector is robust, featuring textile production in the Itajaí Valley, ceramics in the south, and metal mechanics and electrical equipment in the north. The technology sector is heavily concentrated in Florianópolis. Tourism is also a major economic driver, centered on coastal destinations like Balneário Camboriú and the Beto Carrero World theme park. Joinville is the largest city and a major industrial center. Florianópolis serves as the administrative center. Other significant cities include Blumenau, São José, Criciúma, and the port city of Itajaí.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European settlement, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups, primarily the Guarani and Kaingang peoples. Portuguese colonization began in the seventeenth century, with a significant influx of settlers from the Azores islands arriving on the coast in the eighteenth century. During the nineteenth century, Santa Catarina became a major destination for European immigrants. German immigrants settled heavily in the Itajaí Valley and the northern regions, founding cities like Blumenau and Joinville. Italian immigrants largely settled in the southern part of the state. This immigration history has left a profound mark on the culture of Santa Catarina. The European influence is visible in the local architecture, agricultural practices, and annual festivals, the most famous being the Oktoberfest held in Blumenau.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Florianópolis\n* Approximate area: 95,736 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.6 million\n* Largest city: Joinville\n* Signature features: Strong German and Italian cultural heritage, rare occurrences of snowfall in the high-altitude mountain ranges.",
    "summary": "Santa Catarina is a state in southern Brazil known for its high standard of living, diverse industrial and agricultural economy, and distinct European cultural heritage. Its geography ranges from an indented Atlantic coastline to high mountain ranges where rare Brazilian snowfall occurs. The state is governed from the island city of Florianópolis, while Joinville serves as its largest urban and industrial center.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
