    "mainNotes": "## Location within Brazil\nTocantins is a landlocked state located in the North region of Brazil. It is situated in the central part of the country and serves as a transition zone between the Amazon Basin and the central plateau. The state shares borders with six other Brazilian states. To the northwest lies Pará, while Maranhão is located to the northeast. Piauí borders it to the east, Bahia to the southeast, Goiás to the south, and Mato Grosso to the west.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Tocantins is defined largely by the Araguaia and Tocantins rivers, which flow northward and form the primary drainage basin of the state. The Araguaia River forms the western border with Mato Grosso and Pará. Within this river lies Bananal Island, recognized as the largest fluvial island in the world. The Tocantins River runs through the central part of the state. The landscape is dominated by the Cerrado biome, a vast tropical savanna characterized by scattered trees and extensive grasslands. In the northernmost areas, the vegetation transitions into the Amazon rainforest. The eastern part of the state features the Jalapão region, an arid landscape known for its orange sand dunes, clear water springs, and tabletop mountains.\n\n## Climate\nTocantins experiences a tropical savanna climate, classified as Aw under the Köppen system. The weather is consistently hot throughout the year, with average annual temperatures typically ranging between 26 and 29 degrees Celsius. The state has two highly distinct seasons. The wet season occurs from November to April, bringing heavy rainfall that replenishes the rivers and sustains the agricultural sector. The dry season lasts from May to October. During these months, rainfall is extremely rare, humidity drops significantly, and the risk of natural savanna fires increases.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Tocantins relies heavily on agriculture and livestock. The flat topography of the Cerrado is highly suitable for large-scale mechanized farming. Soybeans and corn are the primary cash crops, while beef cattle ranching occupies large tracts of land. The state also generates significant hydroelectric power through dams on the Tocantins River, such as the Luís Eduardo Magalhães Dam. Palmas is the administrative center and the largest city. It is a planned city that was constructed specifically to serve as the state capital. Other major urban centers include Araguaína, which acts as a commercial and agricultural hub in the northern region, and Gurupi in the south. Porto Nacional is an important historical and cultural city located on the banks of the Tocantins River.\n\n## History & culture\nTocantins is the newest state in Brazil. It was officially created on October 5, 1988, following the promulgation of the new Brazilian Constitution. The territory was formed by separating the northern half of Goiás state, a division driven by a long-standing desire for political and economic autonomy among the residents of the northern region. Construction of the new capital, Palmas, began in 1989. The culture of the state reflects a blend of influences from the Northeast, North, and Central-West regions of Brazil. The state is also home to several Indigenous groups, including the Karajá and Javaé peoples, who primarily inhabit the Bananal Island region and maintain traditional practices such as ceramics and river fishing.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Brazil\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Palmas\n* Approximate area: 277,466 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.5 million\n* Largest city: Palmas\n* Signature features: Bananal Island is the largest river island in the world, and the state is the newest in Brazil, created in 1988.",
    "summary": "Tocantins is the newest state in Brazil, established in 1988 from the northern half of Goiás, and is located in the country's North region. Its geography is defined by the Cerrado savanna and the Araguaia-Tocantins river basin, which contains Bananal Island, the largest river island in the world. The state has a rapidly growing agricultural economy centered on soybean cultivation and cattle ranching, administered from the planned capital city of Palmas.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
