    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nEntre Ríos is a province located in the northeastern part of Argentina. It forms the southern portion of the Argentine Mesopotamia region. The province shares domestic borders with Corrientes to the north, Santa Fe to the west, and Buenos Aires to the south. To the east, the Uruguay River forms an international border with the country of Uruguay.\n\n## Physical features\nThe name Entre Ríos translates to \"Between Rivers\", which accurately describes its geography. The province is completely surrounded by water. The Paraná River forms its western and southern boundaries, while the Uruguay River forms its eastern boundary. The Guayquiraró River and the Mocoretá River mark the northern border with Corrientes. The terrain consists mostly of flat plains that transition into gently rolling hills, known locally as lomadas. The region lacks mountainous terrain. The province features a vast network of wetlands, streams, and gallery forests. Two notable protected areas are El Palmar National Park, which preserves a large concentration of native Yatay palms, and Pre-Delta National Park, which protects the islands and wetlands at the beginning of the Paraná River delta.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Entre Ríos transitions from humid subtropical in the northern areas to a temperate pampean climate in the south. The province receives abundant and relatively evenly distributed rainfall throughout the year, averaging between 900 and 1,200 millimeters annually. Summers are typically hot and humid, with average high temperatures often exceeding 30 degrees Celsius. Winters are mild, though southern winds known as the Pampero can bring brief periods of cold weather and frost. The consistent moisture and moderate temperatures support dense vegetation and extensive agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAgriculture and agro-industry form the backbone of the provincial economy. Entre Ríos is a major national producer of citrus fruits, particularly oranges and mandarins, as well as rice, soybeans, wheat, and corn. The province is also the leading producer of poultry in Argentina. Forestry and timber processing are significant industries along the Uruguay River. Tourism is a growing sector, driven by natural hot springs, river beaches, and sport fishing. Paraná is the administrative center and largest city, located on the eastern bank of the Paraná River. Other major cities include Concordia, an agricultural and commercial hub in the northeast, Gualeguaychú in the southeast, and Concepción del Uruguay, an important port city on the Uruguay River.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European arrival, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Guaraní and the Charrúa. Spanish explorers first navigated the local rivers in the sixteenth century, but permanent settlements developed slowly. In the nineteenth century, Entre Ríos played a central role in the formation of the Argentine state. Local leader Justo José de Urquiza led the province to prominence, and the city of Paraná served as the capital of the Argentine Confederation from 1854 to 1861. During the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the province received a large influx of European immigrants. Volga Germans, Italians, and Jewish agricultural colonists established numerous settlements, significantly shaping the local culture and agricultural practices. Today, the province is known for its gaucho traditions and annual festivals. The Carnival of Gualeguaychú is the largest and most widely attended carnival celebration in Argentina.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Paraná\n* Approximate area: 78,781 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.4 million\n* Largest city: Paraná\n* Signature features: Bounded by the Paraná and Uruguay rivers, El Palmar National Park, and the Carnival of Gualeguaychú.",
    "summary": "Entre Ríos is a province in the Argentine Mesopotamia region, defined by its borders along the Paraná and Uruguay rivers. Its economy relies heavily on agriculture, particularly citrus and poultry, as well as tourism centered around river activities and hot springs. The province is culturally significant for its history as the nineteenth-century capital of the Argentine Confederation and its large European immigrant agricultural colonies.",
