    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nJujuy is located in the extreme northwest of Argentina. It is bordered by the Argentine province of Salta to the south and east. Internationally, it shares borders with Chile to the west and Bolivia to the north. It is one of the smallest provinces in Argentina by area but occupies a strategic position connecting the Argentine Northwest with the Andean highlands of neighboring countries.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Jujuy is defined by the Andes mountain range and its associated high-altitude plateaus. The province is divided into three main topographical regions. The Puna is a high, arid plateau in the west, sitting at elevations mostly above 3,500 meters. The Quebrada de Humahuaca is a prominent, narrow mountain valley running south to north, carved by the Rio Grande. This valley is flanked by mineral-rich mountains with distinct color banding, such as the Cerro de los Siete Colores near the town of Purmamarca. To the east, the terrain descends into the Sierras Subandinas and the Yungas, a region of dense, subtropical mountain forests. Major rivers include the Rio Grande, which flows through the Quebrada de Humahuaca, and the San Francisco River, which drains the eastern forests. The province also contains several salt flats, most notably the Salinas Grandes on the Puna plateau.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Jujuy varies significantly depending on elevation and topography. The western Puna region experiences an arid, cold climate with extreme daily temperature fluctuations and very little rainfall. The Quebrada de Humahuaca has a temperate, semi-arid climate, characterized by dry winters and mild, moderately wet summers. The eastern Yungas region features a subtropical climate with high humidity and abundant rainfall, mostly concentrated in the summer months between November and March. This sharp climatic gradient allows for diverse ecosystems within a relatively small geographic area.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Jujuy relies heavily on agriculture, mining, and tourism. In the fertile valleys and the eastern subtropical zones, agricultural production includes sugarcane, tobacco, citrus fruits, and beans. Mining is a major industry in the Puna region, where extraction focuses on lithium, zinc, lead, and silver. The Cauchari solar plant, a large solar power facility, operates in the high-altitude Puna. Tourism is centered around the Quebrada de Humahuaca, drawing visitors to its indigenous villages and geological formations. San Salvador de Jujuy is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the commercial and political hub. Other notable settlements include San Pedro de Jujuy, Libertador General San Martin, La Quiaca on the Bolivian border, and Humahuaca.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by various indigenous groups, including the Omaguaca and Atacama peoples, who later came under the influence of the Inca Empire. The Spanish established San Salvador de Jujuy in 1593 after several failed attempts due to indigenous resistance. During the Argentine War of Independence, Jujuy was a significant northern frontier. General Manuel Belgrano led the Jujuy Exodus in 1812, a strategic scorched-earth retreat by the local population to deny resources to advancing royalist forces. Today, Jujuy retains a strong indigenous cultural influence, visible in its festivals, music, and traditional textiles. The Pachamama celebrations in August and the Carnival of Humahuaca are central to the local cultural calendar. The Quebrada de Humahuaca was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site in 2003 for its historical role as a major trade route and its preserved cultural landscape.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: San Salvador de Jujuy\n* Approximate area: 53,219 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 811,000\n* Largest city: San Salvador de Jujuy\n* Signature features: Quebrada de Humahuaca, Cerro de los Siete Colores, Salinas Grandes, Yungas forests",
    "summary": "Jujuy is a province in the extreme northwest of Argentina, known for its dramatic Andean topography, including the arid Puna plateau and the subtropical Yungas forests. Its economy relies on mining, agriculture, and tourism, with visitors often drawn to the culturally and historically significant Quebrada de Humahuaca. The province shares international borders with Chile and Bolivia and retains a strong indigenous cultural heritage.",
