    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nLa Pampa is a landlocked province located in the center of Argentina. It serves as a geographical transition zone between the fertile Pampas region to the east and the arid Patagonian region to the south. The province shares borders with several other Argentine provinces. To the north, it is bounded by San Luis and Córdoba. The province of Buenos Aires lies to the east. The Colorado River forms its southern border with the province of Río Negro. To the west, La Pampa borders the province of Mendoza.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of La Pampa is largely characterized by expansive plains, though the landscape changes significantly from east to west. The eastern portion of the province consists of flat, fertile grasslands suitable for agriculture. Moving westward, the terrain becomes increasingly arid and transitions into a plateau with undulating hills and salt pans. The Colorado River is the most significant permanent watercourse, flowing along the southern boundary. The Salado River, known locally as the Chadileuvú or Curacó, crosses the western part of the province, but its flow is highly irregular and often dries up completely due to upstream water usage in neighboring provinces. A notable geological feature is the Lihué Calel National Park in the south-central area, which protects a system of low mountain ranges and preserves regional flora and fauna.\n\n## Climate\nLa Pampa experiences a temperate climate that exhibits a distinct east-to-west precipitation gradient. The eastern sector has a temperate pampean climate with moderate rainfall, averaging roughly 700 millimeters annually. This allows for dryland farming and sustains natural grasslands. The western and southern regions feature a semi-arid climate. In these areas, rainfall drops to about 300 millimeters per year, and temperature extremes are more pronounced. Summers in the west are hot, while winters can bring freezing temperatures and occasional frost. Strong winds are common throughout the province, particularly during the transition between seasons.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of La Pampa is heavily dependent on agriculture and livestock. The fertile eastern plains support the cultivation of wheat, corn, sunflowers, and soybeans. Cattle ranching is a major industry across the province, with the drier western regions relying on extensive grazing methods. In addition to agriculture, the western sector has a growing energy sector, including oil and natural gas extraction, as well as salt mining operations. Santa Rosa is the administrative center and the largest city, functioning as the primary commercial and political hub. General Pico is the second-largest city and an important agro-industrial center in the northeast. Other notable towns include Victorica, which is the oldest town in the province, and Macachín.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European settlement, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups, primarily the Tehuelche and later the Mapuche peoples. The area remained largely outside the control of the Spanish Empire and the early Argentine republic. In the late nineteenth century, the Argentine government launched military campaigns known as the Conquest of the Desert to assert control over the territory and displace the indigenous populations. Following these campaigns, the area was organized as a national territory in 1884. European immigrants, particularly from Spain, Italy, and Volga German communities, arrived to establish agricultural colonies. La Pampa was officially elevated to provincial status in 1951. Between 1952 and 1955, it was temporarily renamed Eva Perón Province. Today, the culture of La Pampa is deeply rooted in rural traditions, with the figure of the gaucho playing a central role in local identity, festivals, and folklore.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Santa Rosa\n* Approximate area: 143,440 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 366,000\n* Largest city: Santa Rosa\n* Signature features: Transition zone between the Pampas and Patagonia, Lihué Calel National Park, prominent gaucho culture",
    "summary": "La Pampa is a central Argentine province that serves as a geographical and climatic transition zone between the fertile eastern plains and the arid Patagonian south. Its economy is heavily driven by agriculture and cattle ranching, with Santa Rosa acting as the administrative and commercial center. The region is deeply influenced by its rural history, European agricultural immigration, and traditional gaucho culture.",
