    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nLa Rioja is a province located in the western part of Argentina. It is traditionally considered part of the Cuyo region, although it is also associated with the Argentine Northwest. The province shares an international border with Chile to the west. Domestically, it is bordered by the province of Catamarca to the north, Córdoba to the east, San Luis to the south, and San Juan to the south.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of La Rioja is highly mountainous and arid. The western edge of the province is dominated by the Andes mountain range, which features high elevations. Cerro Bonete and Monte Pissis, the latter shared with Catamarca, are among the highest peaks in the Americas, reaching roughly 6,700 meters above sea level. Moving eastward, the landscape transitions into the Precordillera and the Sierras Pampeanas, which are characterized by block mountains and deep valleys. The province lacks a coastline and has very few permanent rivers. The most significant watercourses are the Vinchina River and the Desaguadero River system, though most rivers in the region are seasonal and form endorheic basins. A prominent natural feature is Talampaya National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its large red sandstone cliffs and significant Triassic dinosaur fossils.\n\n## Climate\nLa Rioja experiences a predominantly arid and semi-arid climate. Precipitation is very low, averaging roughly 200 millimeters per year in most areas, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Summers are typically very hot, while winters are mild with cold nights. The western mountainous regions experience much colder temperatures and snow at high altitudes. The province is frequently affected by the Zonda, a dry and hot wind that descends from the Andes, which can cause rapid temperature increases and dust storms.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of La Rioja is heavily dependent on agriculture, which relies entirely on oasis irrigation systems due to the arid climate. The province is a major producer of grapes, olives, and walnuts. It is particularly noted for its wine industry, specializing in the Torrontés grape variety. Mining is another component of the economy, with deposits of gold, copper, and uranium, though large scale mining has faced local opposition over water concerns. Tourism is a growing sector, driven primarily by visitors to Talampaya National Park. The administrative center and largest city is La Rioja, which serves as the political and economic hub. Chilecito is the second largest city, located in a major wine producing valley and known for the historic cable car that once served the La Mejicana gold mine. Other notable towns include Villa Unión and Chamical.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Diaguita and Capayán peoples, who practiced agriculture with advanced irrigation techniques. The city of La Rioja was founded in 1591 by Spanish conquistador Juan Ramírez de Velasco. During the nineteenth century, the province played a central role in the Argentine civil wars. It was a stronghold for the Federalist party, led by prominent local caudillos like Juan Facundo Quiroga and Ángel Vicente Peñaloza, who fought against the centralist Unitarian government in Buenos Aires. The cultural heritage of the province is heavily influenced by this history, as well as its indigenous roots and traditional agricultural practices.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: La Rioja\n* Approximate area: 89,680 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 384,000\n* Largest city: La Rioja\n* Signature features: Talampaya National Park, Torrontés wine production, historical association with nineteenth-century federalist caudillos",
    "summary": "La Rioja is an arid, mountainous province in western Argentina known for its agricultural oases that produce olives and Torrontés wine. The region features the high peaks of the Andes mountains in the west and the red rock formations of Talampaya National Park. Historically, it served as a major stronghold for Federalist leaders during the nineteenth-century Argentine civil wars.",
