    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nMendoza is a province located in the central-western part of Argentina. It is a central component of the historical Cuyo region. The province shares its entire western international border with the Republic of Chile, separated by the Andes mountain range. Domestically, Mendoza is bordered by the province of San Juan to the north, San Luis to the east, La Pampa to the southeast, and Neuquén to the south.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Mendoza is defined by the transition from the Andes in the west to flat plains in the east. The western border features the Principal Cordillera, which includes Mount Aconcagua. At roughly 6,960 meters, Aconcagua is the highest peak in the Western Hemisphere and is protected within Aconcagua Provincial Park. East of the main range lies the Precordillera, a lower series of mountains. The eastern half of the province consists of semi-arid plains. Several rivers flow eastward from the Andean snowmelt, including the Mendoza, Tunuyán, Diamante, and Atuel rivers. The Colorado River forms the southern boundary with Neuquén. These rivers carve deep canyons and are essential for irrigation.\n\n## Climate\nMendoza experiences an arid to semi-arid climate. Precipitation is low, averaging roughly 200 to 250 millimeters annually in the plains. The region has distinct seasons with hot summers and relatively cold winters. Because of the dry air, there is a high diurnal temperature variation, meaning temperatures drop significantly at night. The province is frequently affected by the Zonda, a dry and warm foehn wind that descends from the Andes between May and November. The high mountain areas experience a cold alpine climate with permanent snow and glaciers.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mendoza relies heavily on agriculture, agro-industry, and services. It is the leading wine-producing province in Argentina, responsible for roughly 70 percent of the country's total wine output. The region is particularly noted for its Malbec varietal. Because of the arid climate, agriculture depends on an extensive system of irrigation canals known as acequias, which distribute river water to vineyards, olive groves, and fruit orchards. Beyond agriculture, the province has significant petroleum extraction industries in the southern Cuyo basin. Tourism is another major economic driver, centered around wine tours, mountaineering, and winter sports at resorts like Las Leñas. The administrative center is the city of Mendoza, which forms a large urban agglomeration with surrounding departments such as Guaymallén, Godoy Cruz, Maipú, and Luján de Cuyo. San Rafael, located in the south, is the second most important city and a hub for agriculture and tourism.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish arrival, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups, most notably the Huarpe people, who established the first irrigation systems in the area. Spanish explorers arrived from Chile, and Pedro del Castillo founded the city of Mendoza in 1561. The region remained under the Captaincy General of Chile until it was transferred to the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata in 1776. In the early nineteenth century, General José de San Martín used Mendoza as his base to organize the Army of the Andes, which crossed the mountains in 1817 to liberate Chile from Spanish rule. A devastating earthquake in 1861 destroyed the original provincial capital. The city was subsequently rebuilt with wide tree-lined avenues and large plazas designed to provide safe gathering spaces during seismic events. Today, the province celebrates its viticultural heritage annually with the National Grape Harvest Festival.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Mendoza\n* Approximate area: 148,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,000,000\n* Largest city: Mendoza\n* Signature features: Mount Aconcagua, extensive Malbec wine production, historic acequia irrigation system",
    "summary": "Mendoza is a province in central-western Argentina known for its arid climate, extensive viticulture, and the towering peaks of the Andes. It produces the majority of Argentina's wine, utilizing historic irrigation canals to cultivate crops in the dry environment. The province is also home to Mount Aconcagua, the highest mountain in the Americas, making it a major destination for mountaineering and outdoor tourism.",
