    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nMisiones is a province located in the northeastern corner of Argentina. It is part of the Argentine Mesopotamia region. The province forms a narrow peninsula of land that juts out from the rest of the country. It shares international borders with Paraguay to the west and Brazil to the north, east, and south. Misiones connects to the rest of Argentina only through a short domestic border with Corrientes province to the southwest. The international borders are defined almost entirely by major rivers. The Paraná River separates Misiones from Paraguay, while the Iguazu River and the Uruguay River separate it from Brazil.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Misiones is situated on the Paraná Plateau. The landscape consists mostly of rugged, rolling hills and low mountains. The highest elevations are found in the Sierra de Misiones and the Sierra de la Victoria, reaching roughly 800 meters above sea level. The province is known for its extensive river systems and waterfalls. The most prominent physical feature is Iguazu Falls, located on the northern border with Brazil within Iguazú National Park. The falls consist of a system of 275 individual drops, including the prominent Garganta del Diablo. The region is covered by the Paranaense forest, a dense subtropical rainforest ecosystem that supports high biodiversity, including jaguars, toucans, and broad-snouted caimans. The soil in Misiones is notably rich in iron, giving it a distinct red color.\n\n## Climate\nMisiones experiences a humid subtropical climate. It is one of the wettest provinces in Argentina, receiving abundant rainfall throughout the year with no distinct dry season. Annual precipitation generally ranges from 1,600 to 2,200 millimeters. Summers are hot and highly humid, while winters are mild. Frost can occur occasionally in the higher elevations and southern valleys during the winter months, but snow is extremely rare. The constant moisture and warm temperatures create ideal conditions for the dense rainforest vegetation that covers much of the province.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Misiones relies heavily on agriculture, forestry, and tourism. The province is the primary producer of yerba mate in Argentina, a plant used to make a traditional caffeinated beverage. Other significant agricultural products include tea, tobacco, citrus fruits, and cassava. Forestry and timber processing are also major industries, supported by both native forests and pine plantations. Tourism is a critical economic driver, centered primarily around Iguazú National Park and the Jesuit ruins. Posadas is the administrative center and largest city, located in the southwest on the banks of the Paraná River. Other important cities include Puerto Iguazú in the far north, which serves as the gateway to the falls, as well as Oberá and Eldorado in the central and western parts of the province.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by the Guaraní people. In the seventeenth century, Jesuit missionaries arrived and established a series of settlements known as reductions. These missions were designed to convert the Guaraní to Christianity and organize them into self-sustaining agricultural communities. The province takes its name from these missions. The Jesuits were expelled from the Spanish Empire in 1767, and the ruins of several reductions, such as San Ignacio Miní, remain today as UNESCO World Heritage sites. In the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Misiones received a significant influx of European immigrants. Settlers from Germany, Poland, Ukraine, and Scandinavia established agricultural colonies, heavily influencing the local architecture, cuisine, and cultural festivals.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Posadas\n* Approximate area: 29,801 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.28 million\n* Largest city: Posadas\n* Signature features: Iguazu Falls, Jesuit mission ruins, red iron-rich soil, yerba mate production",
    "summary": "Misiones is a northeastern Argentine province situated in the Mesopotamia region, bordered almost entirely by Brazil and Paraguay along major rivers. The province is characterized by its red iron-rich soil, subtropical rainforests, and significant landmarks like Iguazu Falls and historic Jesuit ruins. Its economy is largely driven by forestry, tourism, and the cultivation of yerba mate.",
