    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nCorrientes is a province located in the northeastern region of Argentina. It forms part of the Argentine Mesopotamia, a geographic region defined by its position between major rivers. The province shares international borders with three countries. Paraguay lies to the north and west, Brazil is situated to the east, and Uruguay is located to the southeast. Within Argentina, Corrientes borders the province of Misiones to the northeast, Entre Ríos to the south, Santa Fe to the west, and Chaco to the northwest.\n\n## Physical features\nThe physical geography of Corrientes is dominated by water. The province is entirely surrounded by major rivers. The Paraná River forms the western and northern borders, while the Uruguay River forms the eastern border. The interior landscape is mostly flat and low-lying, characterized by savannas, grasslands, and extensive aquatic ecosystems. The most prominent physical feature is the Iberá Wetlands, known locally as the Esteros del Iberá. This vast network of swamps, bogs, stagnant lakes, and lagoons covers a significant portion of the central and north-central province. It is one of the largest freshwater wetlands in the world and serves as a major habitat for diverse wildlife, including capybaras, caimans, and hundreds of bird species. The Iberá National Park protects a large section of this ecosystem.\n\n## Climate\nCorrientes experiences a humid subtropical climate. The region receives abundant precipitation throughout the year, though rainfall is generally heavier in the eastern part of the province. The western section experiences a slight decrease in rainfall during the winter months. Summers are typically hot and humid, with average high temperatures often exceeding thirty degrees Celsius. Winters are mild and relatively short, with frost being a rare occurrence, especially in the northern areas. This warm, moist climate supports the abundant vegetation found across the province and facilitates extensive agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Corrientes relies heavily on agriculture, livestock, and energy production. The province is a major national producer of rice, citrus fruits, tobacco, and yerba mate. Cattle and sheep ranching are widespread on the central and southern grasslands. Forestry is also a significant industry, particularly in the eastern regions where pine and eucalyptus plantations are common. Corrientes contributes significantly to the national energy grid through the Yacyretá Dam, a large hydroelectric facility on the Paraná River shared with Paraguay. The city of Corrientes serves as the provincial capital and the primary economic hub. Other important cities include Goya, known for its tobacco production and annual fishing festival, as well as Paso de los Libres, Curuzú Cuatiá, and Mercedes.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore European arrival, the region was inhabited primarily by the Guaraní people. The city of Corrientes was founded by the Spanish in 1588, serving as a strategic port between Asunción and Buenos Aires. The province played a prominent role in the Argentine civil wars of the nineteenth century. Today, Corrientes retains a strong Guaraní cultural influence. It is one of the few Argentine provinces to recognize an indigenous language as co-official, with Guaraní sharing that status with Spanish. The province is also the birthplace of Chamamé, a traditional folk music and dance style that blends indigenous, Spanish, and Eastern European immigrant influences.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Corrientes\n* Approximate area: 88,199 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,120,000\n* Largest city: Corrientes\n* Signature features: The Iberá Wetlands, Chamamé folk music, and co-official status of the Guaraní language.",
    "summary": "Corrientes is a province in northeastern Argentina situated within the Mesopotamia region between the Paraná and Uruguay rivers. It is best known for the expansive Iberá Wetlands and its strong agricultural economy based on rice, citrus, and livestock. The province also features a unique cultural heritage, highlighted by the traditional Chamamé music and the co-official status of the Guaraní language.",
