    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nSanta Fe is a province located in the center-east of Argentina. It shares borders with several other Argentine provinces. To the north lies Chaco, while the eastern border is defined by the Paraná River, which separates Santa Fe from Corrientes and Entre Ríos. To the south is the province of Buenos Aires. The western border is shared with Córdoba and Santiago del Estero.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is characterized by an expansive, flat landscape with very little variation in elevation. It spans two major geographical regions of Argentina. The northern part of the province lies within the Gran Chaco, a lowland alluvial plain known for its scrub forests and wetlands. The central and southern portions belong to the Pampas, a vast and highly fertile grassland. The most prominent hydrological feature is the Paraná River, which forms the entire eastern boundary and serves as a crucial waterway. The Salado River is another major watercourse, flowing southeast across the province to join the Paraná River near the capital city. Other smaller rivers and wetlands, such as the Jaaukanigás, are scattered throughout the northern and eastern areas.\n\n## Climate\nSanta Fe experiences a transition in climate from north to south. The northern region has a subtropical climate with distinct wet and dry seasons, characterized by hot summers and mild winters. The central and southern areas feature a temperate, humid Pampas climate. In these southern zones, rainfall is more evenly distributed throughout the year, though summers remain the wettest season. Average annual temperatures range from roughly 21 degrees Celsius in the north to 17 degrees Celsius in the south.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Santa Fe is heavily driven by agriculture and agro-industry. The fertile soils of the Pampas support large-scale production of soybeans, wheat, corn, and sunflowers. Cattle ranching and dairy farming are also major economic activities, particularly in the central and western regions. The province is a global leader in the production and export of soybean oil and biodiesel. A large industrial and port complex stretches along the Paraná River from San Lorenzo to Rosario, handling a significant portion of Argentina's agricultural exports. Rosario is the largest city and the primary economic hub of the province. The administrative center is the city of Santa Fe. Other important urban centers include Rafaela, known for its dairy industry, and Venado Tuerto, a major agricultural center in the south.\n\n## History & culture\nThe city of Santa Fe was founded in 1573 by the Spanish explorer Juan de Garay. The province played a central role in the formation of the modern Argentine state. The city of Santa Fe is noted as the site where the Argentine Constitution of 1853 was drafted and signed. Rosario holds historical significance as the location where the Argentine flag was first raised by Manuel Belgrano in 1812. During the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the province received a large influx of European immigrants. Italians, Spaniards, Swiss, and Germans established numerous agricultural colonies, such as Esperanza, which significantly shaped the demographic and cultural landscape of the region.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Santa Fe\n* Approximate area: 133,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.5 million\n* Largest city: Rosario\n* Signature features: The Paraná River agricultural port complex, birthplace of the Argentine flag in Rosario",
    "summary": "Santa Fe is a central-eastern Argentine province known for its highly fertile Pampas grasslands and its strategic location along the Paraná River. The province is a major powerhouse for Argentina's agricultural and agro-industrial sectors, particularly in soybean and dairy production. While the city of Santa Fe serves as the administrative capital and historical site of the 1853 Constitution, Rosario is the largest city and primary economic hub.",
