    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\n\nTucumán is a province located in the northwest region of Argentina. It is bordered by the province of Salta to the north, Santiago del Estero to the east, and Catamarca to the south and west. Covering roughly 22,524 square kilometers, it is the smallest province in Argentina by land area. Despite its small size, it is the most densely populated province in the country.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Tucumán is divided into two distinct regions. The eastern portion of the province consists of flat plains that form part of the Gran Chaco region. The western half is dominated by mountain ranges belonging to the Sierras Pampeanas and the Subandean systems. The most prominent mountain range is the Sierra de Aconquija, which forms a natural border with Catamarca. The highest peak in the province is Cerro del Bolsón, reaching an elevation of roughly 5,550 meters above sea level. The primary watercourse is the Salí River, which originates in the north and flows southward through the central valley. The Salí River collects water from numerous mountain tributaries before exiting the province and eventually emptying into the Dulce River system. The province also contains the Campo de los Alisos National Park, which protects the high-altitude biodiversity of the Aconquija mountains.\n\n## Climate\n\nTucumán experiences a subtropical climate with distinct wet and dry seasons. The eastern plains are generally warm and receive moderate rainfall. The western mountain slopes intercept moisture-laden winds from the Atlantic Ocean, resulting in heavy orographic precipitation during the summer months. This abundant rainfall supports a dense, humid subtropical forest ecosystem known as the Southern Andean Yungas. The heavy vegetation in this region led to the province being historically referred to as the Garden of the Republic. At higher elevations in the western mountains, the climate becomes significantly colder and more arid, eventually transitioning into alpine conditions with snow-capped peaks.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Tucumán is heavily reliant on agriculture and agro-industry. The province is a major global producer of lemons, as well as lemon juice and essential oils. Sugarcane is another foundational crop, and the region is dotted with numerous sugar mills that process the harvest. Other significant agricultural products include strawberries, blueberries, and soybeans. The industrial sector includes automotive parts manufacturing, textiles, and food processing. San Miguel de Tucumán is the provincial capital and the largest city, serving as the commercial and administrative hub of the northwest region. Other important cities include Banda del Río Salí, Yerba Buena, Tafí Viejo, and Concepción. Tafí del Valle is a prominent mountain town that serves as a center for regional tourism.\n\n## History & culture\n\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Diaguita and the Lule. San Miguel de Tucumán was originally founded in 1565 at a site known as Ibatín, but the settlement was relocated to its present position in 1685 to avoid flooding and disease. The province holds a central place in national history because the Argentine Declaration of Independence was signed in San Miguel de Tucumán on July 9, 1816. The historic building where this occurred, known as the Casa Histórica de la Independencia, remains a national monument. The province is also an educational center, hosting the National University of Tucumán, which attracts students from across the region and contributes to the local academic culture.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: San Miguel de Tucumán\n* Approximate area: 22,524 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.7 million\n* Largest city: San Miguel de Tucumán\n* Signature features: Smallest Argentine province by area, site of the 1816 Argentine Declaration of Independence, major global producer of lemons",
    "summary": "Tucumán is the smallest province in Argentina by land area, located in the country's northwest region. It is geographically divided between eastern plains and western mountains, supporting a major agricultural economy focused on lemons and sugarcane. The province is historically significant as the site where the Argentine Declaration of Independence was signed in 1816.",
