    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nAguascalientes is a landlocked state located in the central part of Mexico. It is one of the smallest states in the country by land area. Aguascalientes shares borders with only two other Mexican states. Zacatecas surrounds it to the north, east, and west, while Jalisco borders it to the south. The state is strategically positioned along the historical route connecting Mexico City to the northern mining regions.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Aguascalientes is defined by its transition between the Mexican Plateau and the Sierra Madre Occidental mountain range. The terrain consists of rolling plains in the central and eastern areas, while the western and northern regions are characterized by rugged mountains. Notable mountain ranges include the Sierra Fría, which contains some of the highest elevations in the state, and the Sierra del Laurel. A notable geological formation is the Cerro del Muerto, a mountain ridge whose silhouette resembles a sleeping person. The state belongs to the Lerma-Santiago river basin. Its primary waterway is the San Pedro River, also known as the Aguascalientes River, which flows southward through the state to eventually join the Río Grande de Santiago in Jalisco.\n\n## Climate\nAguascalientes experiences a predominantly semiarid climate, particularly in the central plains and lower elevations. The western mountainous regions, such as the Sierra Fría, have a temperate climate due to their higher altitude. Average annual temperatures range from 17 to 18 degrees Celsius. The state receives moderate precipitation, averaging about 500 millimeters annually. Most of the rainfall occurs during the summer months from June to September. Winters are generally mild, though freezing temperatures can occur in the higher elevations of the Sierra Madre Occidental.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Aguascalientes is industrialized and relies significantly on manufacturing. The state is a major hub for the automotive industry, hosting large assembly plants for international companies like Nissan, along with a vast network of automotive parts suppliers. Other important industrial sectors include electronics, textiles, and food processing. Agriculture remains relevant, with the municipality of Calvillo being a major national producer of guavas. The state also has a growing wine industry. The capital and largest city is Aguascalientes, which dominates the state economically and demographically. Other significant municipalities include Jesús María, which forms part of the capital's metropolitan area, Calvillo, and Rincón de Romos.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by various nomadic indigenous groups collectively known as the Chichimecas. The city of Aguascalientes was founded in 1575 as a fortified outpost to protect travelers and silver shipments along the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro, the royal road linking Mexico City to Zacatecas. The state is known for hosting the Feria Nacional de San Marcos, one of the oldest and largest fairs in Mexico, which attracts millions of visitors each spring. Aguascalientes is also the birthplace of José Guadalupe Posada, a printmaker and engraver who created the Calavera Catrina image associated with the Day of the Dead.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: Free and Sovereign State\n* Administrative center: Aguascalientes\n* Approximate area: 5,618 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.4 million\n* Largest city: Aguascalientes\n* Signature features: Feria Nacional de San Marcos, major automotive manufacturing hub, Cerro del Muerto mountain formation",
    "summary": "Aguascalientes is a small, landlocked state in central Mexico situated between the Mexican Plateau and the Sierra Madre Occidental. Its economy is heavily driven by automotive manufacturing, though it also maintains agricultural production such as guava farming in Calvillo. The state is culturally significant for hosting the annual San Marcos Fair and as a historic stop along the silver mining routes of the Camino Real de Tierra Adentro.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
