    "mainNotes": "## Location within Australia\nQueensland is located in the northeastern portion of Australia. It is bordered by the Northern Territory to the west, South Australia to the southwest, and New South Wales to the south. To the east, Queensland is bounded by the Coral Sea and the Pacific Ocean. To the north, the Torres Strait separates the state from Papua New Guinea. The Gulf of Carpentaria forms a large coastal indentation in the northwest. The Tropic of Capricorn crosses the state, placing the northern half in the tropics and the southern half in the temperate zone.\n\n## Physical features\nQueensland has a diverse geography that includes tropical rainforests, mountain ranges, and arid inland areas. The Great Dividing Range runs roughly parallel to the eastern coast, creating a barrier between the coastal plains and the drier interior. The highest peak in the state is Mount Bartle Frere, located in the northern tropical region. The state is home to the Great Barrier Reef, the largest coral reef system in the world, which stretches along the eastern coast in the Coral Sea. Off the southern coast lies K'gari, formerly known as Fraser Island, which is the largest sand island in the world. Important river systems include the Flinders River, the longest river entirely within the state, and the Fitzroy River. The Daintree Rainforest in the north is one of the oldest continuously surviving tropical rainforests in the world. The western inland region, known as the Outback, features flat, arid landscapes and the Channel Country, where intermittent rivers create wide floodplains after heavy rains.\n\n## Climate\nDue to its vast size, Queensland experiences multiple climate zones. The northern coastal areas have a tropical climate with a distinct wet season and dry season, often experiencing monsoons and tropical cyclones between November and April. The southern coastal regions, including Brisbane, have a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm summers and mild winters. The inland and western regions are predominantly semi-arid to arid, experiencing high summer temperatures and very low annual rainfall. Inland towns like Birdsville can experience extreme heat waves, while the elevated areas of the Granite Belt in the south can occasionally see winter frost.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Queensland is driven by agriculture, mining, and tourism. The state is a major producer of coal, natural gas, bauxite, and copper. Agricultural output includes beef, sugarcane, cotton, and tropical fruits. Tourism is heavily focused on the Great Barrier Reef, the Gold Coast, and the tropical north. Brisbane, located in the southeast, is the administrative center and the most populous city. Other major urban centers include the Gold Coast and Sunshine Coast in the southeast, as well as regional coastal cities like Townsville, Cairns, Mackay, and Rockhampton. The port city of Gladstone is a major hub for industrial exports.\n\n## History & culture\nAboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders have inhabited the region for tens of thousands of years. Dutch explorer Willem Janszoon was the first recorded European to land in Queensland, arriving at the Cape York Peninsula in 1606. British settlement began in 1824 with a penal colony at Moreton Bay. Queensland was originally part of New South Wales before separating to become a distinct colony in 1859. The state was named in honor of Queen Victoria, who signed the letters patent establishing the colony. The state joined the Commonwealth of Australia as a founding member in 1901. Today, Queensland has a diverse population and maintains a strong cultural identity tied to its outdoor lifestyle, sports, and agricultural heritage.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Australia\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Brisbane\n* Approximate area: 1,853,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.4 million\n* Largest city: Brisbane\n* Signature features: Great Barrier Reef, Daintree Rainforest, Cape York Peninsula",
    "summary": "Queensland is a large state in northeastern Australia known for its diverse geography, which includes the Great Barrier Reef, tropical rainforests, and the arid Outback. Its economy relies heavily on mining, agriculture, and tourism, with the majority of its population concentrated along the eastern coast. Brisbane serves as the administrative center and largest city of the state.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
