    "mainNotes": "## Location within Argentina\nSantiago del Estero is a province located in the northern region of Argentina. It is entirely landlocked and sits at the heart of the Gran Chaco plain. The province shares borders with six other Argentine provinces. To the northwest lies Salta, while Chaco borders it to the northeast. Santa Fe is located to the east, and Córdoba is situated to the south. To the west, Santiago del Estero shares boundaries with Catamarca and Tucumán.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Santiago del Estero is predominantly flat, forming a major part of the Gran Chaco region. The landscape slopes gently from the northwest to the southeast. Two major rivers dominate the hydrology of the province, which are the Dulce River and the Salado River. Both rivers flow diagonally across the province from the northwest to the southeast. The Dulce River eventually empties into the Mar Chiquita, a large saline lake located just south of the provincial border in Córdoba. While the province is mostly a vast plain, there are low mountain ranges in the west and south, including the Sierras de Guasayán and the Sierras de Ambargasta. The natural vegetation consists largely of dry forests and savannas. Copo National Park, located in the extreme northeast, protects a significant area of native quebracho trees and endangered wildlife such as the jaguar and the giant armadillo.\n\n## Climate\nSantiago del Estero experiences a subtropical climate characterized by a distinct dry season. The region is known for having some of the highest summer temperatures in Argentina. During the summer months, temperatures frequently exceed 40 degrees Celsius. Winters are generally mild and dry, though occasional frosts can occur. Precipitation is highly concentrated in the summer, while the winter months receive very little rainfall. The eastern part of the province receives more annual rainfall than the western part, leading to a transition from semi-arid conditions in the west to a more humid environment in the east.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Santiago del Estero relies heavily on agriculture, livestock, and forestry. The province is a major producer of cotton, soybeans, maize, wheat, and sorghum. Livestock ranching is also significant, with a focus on cattle and goats. Historically, the extraction of quebracho wood for timber and tannin was a primary economic driver, and forestry remains an active industry. Tourism provides additional revenue, particularly in the city of Termas de Río Hondo, which is famous for its natural hot springs. The administrative center and largest city is Santiago del Estero. Other important urban centers include La Banda, which forms a metropolitan area with the capital, as well as Añatuya and Frías.\n\n## History & culture\nThe capital city of Santiago del Estero was founded in 1553 by Spanish colonizers. It is the oldest continuously inhabited city founded by Europeans in Argentina. Because many subsequent expeditions to found other Argentine cities departed from here, it is traditionally called the Mother of Cities. Before Spanish arrival, the region was inhabited by various indigenous groups, including the Tonocoté and Lule people. The province retains a strong indigenous cultural influence. It is the only province in Argentina where a local dialect of the Quichua language is still spoken by a notable portion of the rural population. The region is also a major center for traditional Argentine folklore, particularly the chacarera, a popular folk music and dance style.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Argentina\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Santiago del Estero\n* Approximate area: 136,351 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,054,000\n* Largest city: Santiago del Estero\n* Signature features: Oldest continuously inhabited Spanish settlement in Argentina, Termas de Río Hondo hot springs, strong Quichua linguistic heritage",
    "summary": "Santiago del Estero is a province in northern Argentina located within the flat, subtropical Gran Chaco region. Its economy is largely driven by agriculture, livestock, and forestry, while its capital is historically significant as the oldest continuously inhabited Spanish settlement in the country. The province is also noted for its strong folkloric traditions and the enduring presence of the Quichua language.",
