    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nChihuahua is located in northwestern Mexico. It is the largest state in the country by land area. To the north, it shares an extensive international border with the United States, specifically with the states of New Mexico and Texas. Within Mexico, Chihuahua is bordered by Sonora to the west, Sinaloa to the southwest, Durango to the south, and Coahuila to the east.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Chihuahua is defined by two primary landscapes. The western half of the state is dominated by the Sierra Madre Occidental, a rugged mountain range characterized by deep ravines and high plateaus. This region contains the Copper Canyon system, known in Spanish as Barrancas del Cobre. This network of six distinct canyons is larger and deeper than the Grand Canyon in the United States. The eastern and northern portions of the state lie within the Chihuahuan Desert, a vast expanse of arid plains and isolated mountain ridges. The most significant river is the Rio Grande, known in Mexico as the Río Bravo del Norte, which forms the international border with Texas. The Conchos River is the largest river entirely within the state and serves as a major tributary to the Rio Grande.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Chihuahua varies significantly depending on elevation and topography. The Chihuahuan Desert experiences an arid and semi-arid climate. This region is characterized by extreme temperature fluctuations, with very hot summers and cold winters, alongside minimal annual rainfall. Conversely, the Sierra Madre Occidental features a temperate climate. The higher elevations receive considerably more precipitation, which supports extensive pine and oak forests. During the winter months, these mountainous areas frequently experience freezing temperatures and snowfall.\n\n## Economy & cities\nChihuahua possesses a highly industrialized economy. A significant portion of its economic output is generated by maquiladoras, which are manufacturing and assembly plants that produce goods primarily for export to the United States. The largest city in the state is Ciudad Juárez, located on the international border directly across from El Paso, Texas. Ciudad Juárez is a major hub for the automotive and electronics manufacturing sectors. The administrative center is the city of Chihuahua, situated in the center of the state. Chihuahua City also maintains a strong industrial base, particularly in aerospace and automotive parts production. Beyond manufacturing, the state has a robust agricultural sector, leading the country in the production of apples and pecans. Cattle ranching and forestry are also prominent. Mining remains an important industry, with the state producing significant quantities of silver, gold, zinc, and lead.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has been inhabited for thousands of years by various indigenous groups. The most prominent indigenous population today is the Tarahumara, who refer to themselves as the Rarámuri. They primarily reside in the rugged terrain of the Sierra Madre Occidental and are globally recognized for their endurance running abilities. Spanish exploration and colonization began in the sixteenth century, largely motivated by the discovery of rich silver deposits. During the early twentieth century, Chihuahua was a central battleground in the Mexican Revolution. The state served as the primary base of operations for revolutionary general Pancho Villa. The modern culture of Chihuahua is heavily influenced by its northern frontier history, featuring a strong vaquero, or cowboy, tradition that is reflected in local music, cuisine, and rodeo events.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Chihuahua\n* Approximate area: 247,455 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.7 million\n* Largest city: Ciudad Juárez\n* Signature features: Copper Canyon system, Chihuahuan Desert, Tarahumara culture",
    "summary": "Chihuahua is the largest state in Mexico, located in the northwestern part of the country bordering Texas and New Mexico. Its geography is defined by the arid Chihuahuan Desert in the east and the rugged Sierra Madre Occidental in the west, which houses the massive Copper Canyon system. The state has a highly industrialized economy driven by cross-border manufacturing, particularly in its largest city, Ciudad Juárez, and its administrative center, Chihuahua City.",
    "model": "gemini-3.1-pro-preview"
