    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nCoahuila is a state located in the northern region of Mexico. It shares a long international border with the United States to the north and northeast, specifically with the state of Texas. The Rio Grande, known in Mexico as the Río Bravo del Norte, forms this natural international boundary. Within Mexico, Coahuila is bordered by the state of Nuevo León to the east, San Luis Potosí and Zacatecas to the south, and Durango and Chihuahua to the west. It is the third-largest state in Mexico by land area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Coahuila consists primarily of arid plains, rolling hills, and rugged mountain ranges. The Sierra Madre Oriental traverses the eastern and central parts of the state, creating significant elevation changes and deep canyons. The western portion of the state lies within the Chihuahuan Desert, which is characterized by dry basins and isolated mountain ridges. Major rivers include the Río Bravo del Norte on the border, as well as the Río Sabinas in the coal region and the Río Nazas, which flows into the southwestern part of the state from Durango. A notable ecological site is the Cuatro Ciénegas Biosphere Reserve. This desert oasis features hundreds of freshwater springs, pools, and marshes that support numerous endemic species of fish, reptiles, and plants.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Coahuila is predominantly arid and semi-arid. The vast desert regions experience high temperatures during the summer months and mild to cool temperatures during the winter. Precipitation is generally scarce across the plains and desert basins, falling mostly during brief summer storms. In the higher elevations of the Sierra Madre Oriental, the climate becomes more temperate. These mountainous areas receive more consistent rainfall and can experience freezing temperatures and occasional snowfall during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nCoahuila possesses a highly industrialized economy that is closely tied to the United States market. The state is a major center for automotive manufacturing. The administrative center, Saltillo, hosts numerous assembly plants and parts suppliers. Monclova is a significant hub for steel production, while the northern border cities of Piedras Negras and Ciudad Acuña rely heavily on the maquiladora industry and cross-border trade. In the southwest, Torreón is the economic center of the Comarca Lagunera region, an area known for dairy production, agriculture, and heavy industry. Mining is also a historical and current economic driver, with Coahuila producing nearly all of Mexico's coal, along with significant amounts of silver, zinc, and copper. The town of Parras de la Fuente is recognized for its historic vineyards and wine production.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by various nomadic and semi-nomadic indigenous groups. During the colonial era, the area was part of the Spanish province of Nueva Extremadura. Following Mexican independence, it was combined with Texas to form the state of Coahuila y Tejas until the Texas Revolution in the 1830s. Coahuila played a central role in the Mexican Revolution of 1910. It was the birthplace of key revolutionary figures, including Francisco I. Madero and Venustiano Carranza. The culture of Coahuila features northern Mexican traditions, including a diet that relies heavily on flour tortillas, beef, and cabrito, which is roast kid goat. The state also hosts a small population of the Kickapoo indigenous people, who migrated to the area from the United States in the nineteenth century.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Saltillo\n* Approximate area: 151,563 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.1 million\n* Largest city: Saltillo\n* Signature features: Cuatro Ciénegas biosphere reserve, major automotive and steel manufacturing industries, extensive Chihuahuan Desert landscapes.",
    "summary": "Coahuila is a large, heavily industrialized state in northern Mexico that shares a border with Texas along the Rio Grande. Its landscape is defined by the arid Chihuahuan Desert and the rugged Sierra Madre Oriental mountains. The state is a major economic hub for automotive manufacturing, steel production, and coal mining, with key cities including Saltillo, Torreón, and Monclova.",
