    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nMexico City is located in the south-central region of Mexico. It is situated in the Valley of Mexico, a large basin within the high plateaus of the center of the country. The entity is almost entirely surrounded by the State of Mexico to the north, east, and west. To the south, it shares a border with the state of Morelos. Mexico City is landlocked. It serves as the national capital and is a distinct first-level federal entity, meaning it is not part of any of the 31 regular states.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Mexico City is defined by its high elevation and its location within the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt. The city sits at an average elevation of roughly 2,240 meters above sea level. The northern and central areas are relatively flat, having been built on the dry bed of Lake Texcoco. The southern portion is highly mountainous. The Ajusco volcano is the highest point, reaching about 3,930 meters. The region is prone to earthquakes due to its location on soft lake sediments and proximity to active fault lines. While the original lake system was largely drained over the centuries to prevent flooding, remnants of the ancient waterways survive in the southern borough of Xochimilco. This area features a network of canals and artificial islands known as chinampas. The Magdalena River is the only remaining free-flowing river within the city limits.\n\n## Climate\nMexico City experiences a subtropical highland climate. The high altitude moderates temperatures, resulting in mild weather throughout the year. Average annual temperatures range from 12 to 16 degrees Celsius. The climate features two distinct seasons. The dry season runs from November to May, while the wet season occurs from June to October. During the wet season, heavy afternoon rain showers are common. The surrounding mountains can trap air within the valley. This sometimes leads to temperature inversions and the accumulation of air pollution during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nMexico City is the primary economic hub of Mexico and a major financial center in Latin America. The economy is heavily driven by the service sector, including finance, telecommunications, retail, and tourism. While heavy manufacturing was historically prominent, much of it has relocated to the surrounding State of Mexico. The city now focuses on light industry, pharmaceuticals, and consumer goods. The entity is divided into 16 administrative boroughs, known as alcaldías. Iztapalapa is the most populous borough, located in the east. Cuauhtémoc serves as the historical and financial core, housing the national government. Miguel Hidalgo is known for its commercial districts, while Coyoacán is recognized for its educational institutions.\n\n## History & culture\nThe area was originally settled by various indigenous groups. In 1325, the Mexica people founded Tenochtitlan on an island in Lake Texcoco. This city grew into the capital of the Aztec Empire. Spanish forces conquered the city in 1521, destroying much of the original structures and building the capital of the Viceroyalty of New Spain over the ruins. Following Mexican independence, the city was designated as the Federal District in 1824. In 2016, political reforms officially changed its status to an autonomous federal entity named Ciudad de México. The city is a cultural center, home to the National Autonomous University of Mexico and Chapultepec Park. The historic center is anchored by the Zócalo, a massive public square bordered by the Metropolitan Cathedral and the National Palace.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: First-level federal entity\n* Administrative center: Mexico City\n* Approximate area: 1,485 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 9.2 million\n* Largest city: Mexico City (Iztapalapa is the most populous borough)\n* Signature features: The Zócalo, Xochimilco canals, Chapultepec Park",
    "summary": "Mexico City is a high-altitude federal entity located in the Valley of Mexico, serving as the nation's capital and primary economic hub. Originally built on the drained bed of Lake Texcoco by the Aztecs, the city is now divided into 16 boroughs and is known for its rich history, significant cultural landmarks, and massive population.",
