    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nDurango is a landlocked state located in the northwestern and central regions of Mexico. It is the fourth largest state in the country by land area. Durango shares borders with five other Mexican states. Chihuahua lies to the north, Coahuila to the northeast, and Zacatecas to the southeast. To the southwest, Durango borders Nayarit, and to the west, it shares a boundary with Sinaloa. The state is situated inland and does not have a coastline.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Durango is defined by two major topographical zones. The western half of the state is dominated by the Sierra Madre Occidental, a massive mountain range characterized by deep canyons, high plateaus, and extensive pine and oak forests. The eastern half transitions into the vast, arid plains of the Chihuahuan Desert. A prominent geographic feature in the northeast is the Bolsón de Mapimí, a large endorheic basin that extends into neighboring states. Major rivers include the Nazas River and the Aguanaval River, both of which flow eastward into the Bolsón de Mapimí and do not reach the ocean. The Baluarte River flows westward through the mountains toward the Pacific Ocean. The state also contains the Mapimí Biosphere Reserve, which protects desert ecosystems and the Zone of Silence, an area known for magnetic anomalies.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Durango varies significantly depending on the elevation and region. The eastern and central plains experience an arid and semi-arid climate, with low annual precipitation and high summer temperatures. The western mountainous region features a temperate climate. In the highest elevations of the Sierra Madre Occidental, temperatures can drop below freezing during the winter months, and snow is relatively common. Most of the state receives the majority of its rainfall during the summer months, typically between June and September.\n\n## Economy & cities\nDurango has a diverse economy based on mining, forestry, agriculture, and manufacturing. The state is a major producer of precious and industrial metals, including silver, gold, and iron. The western forests support a significant timber and wood processing industry. Agricultural outputs include cattle, beans, apples, and alfalfa. In recent years, the manufacturing sector has grown, particularly in the production of automotive parts and textiles. Victoria de Durango is the administrative center and the largest city, located in the central part of the state. Other major urban centers include Gómez Palacio and Lerdo. These two cities are situated in the northeast and form part of the Comarca Lagunera, a large metropolitan and agricultural area shared with the city of Torreón in the neighboring state of Coahuila.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish arrival, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups such as the Tepehuan, Tarahumara, and Huichol. Spanish explorers reached the area in the sixteenth century. Francisco de Ibarra founded the city of Victoria de Durango in 1563, and the region became the center of the province of Nueva Vizcaya during the colonial period. The state played a notable role in the Mexican Revolution, as the revolutionary general Pancho Villa was born in the municipality of San Juan del Río. Culturally, Durango is strongly associated with the film industry. During the mid-twentieth century, the state served as a primary filming location for dozens of American and Mexican Western movies due to its rugged landscapes and clear skies. The state is also widely associated with scorpions, which are common in the region and frequently featured in local crafts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: Free and Sovereign State\n* Administrative center: Victoria de Durango\n* Approximate area: 123,451 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.83 million\n* Largest city: Victoria de Durango\n* Signature features: Sierra Madre Occidental, Bolsón de Mapimí, Western film history, birthplace of Pancho Villa",
    "summary": "Durango is a landlocked state in northwestern and central Mexico known for its diverse geography, which ranges from the rugged Sierra Madre Occidental to the arid plains of the Chihuahuan Desert. Its economy relies on mining, forestry, and agriculture, with major populations centered in Victoria de Durango and the Comarca Lagunera region. Historically significant as the birthplace of Pancho Villa, the state is also recognized for its legacy as a prominent filming location for Western movies.",
