    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nGuanajuato is a landlocked state located in the central region of Mexico. It is part of the macroregion known as the Bajío. The state shares borders with Zacatecas to the north, San Luis Potosí to the northeast, Querétaro to the east, Michoacán to the south, and Jalisco to the west. Its central position has historically made it a vital crossroads for trade and transportation between the northern mining regions and the capital of Mexico City.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Guanajuato is defined by three main physiographic regions. The northern part of the state lies on the Mexican Plateau, characterized by arid plains and rolling hills. The central and eastern areas feature the Sierra Gorda and the Sierra de Guanajuato, which contain rugged terrain and deep ravines. The southern portion of the state intersects with the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt, creating fertile valleys and volcanic soils. The Lerma River is the most significant waterway, flowing through the southern part of the state and supporting regional agriculture. Another major river is the Laja River, which feeds into the Lerma. Lake Yuriria, an artificial body of water created by Augustinian monks in the sixteenth century, serves as an important wetland habitat.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Guanajuato varies significantly depending on elevation and regional topography. The northern and central plateau regions generally experience a semi-arid climate with limited precipitation. In contrast, the southern and mountainous areas feature a temperate climate with more moderate temperatures. Average annual temperatures across the state range from roughly 16 to 20 degrees Celsius. The state has a distinct rainy season that occurs primarily between June and September, while the rest of the year remains relatively dry.\n\n## Economy & cities\nGuanajuato possesses a diverse economy driven by manufacturing, agriculture, and tourism. The state is a major hub for the automotive industry, with large assembly plants located in municipalities like Silao and Celaya. León, the largest city in the state, is internationally recognized for its leather and footwear manufacturing. Agriculture remains central to the Bajío region, producing crops such as corn, sorghum, wheat, and beans. Irapuato is particularly noted for its strawberry production, while Salamanca hosts a major petroleum refinery. Tourism is heavily concentrated in the administrative center of Guanajuato and the city of San Miguel de Allende, both recognized for their colonial architecture.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by various indigenous groups, primarily the Chichimecas and the Purépecha. The Spanish arrived in the 1520s and soon discovered massive silver deposits, turning the area into one of the most productive mining centers in the world. Guanajuato is widely known as the cradle of Mexican Independence. In 1810, the priest Miguel Hidalgo y Costilla issued the Cry of Dolores in the town of Dolores Hidalgo, initiating the armed rebellion against Spanish rule. The state is also recognized for its cultural contributions, hosting the annual Festival Internacional Cervantino, one of the largest arts festivals in Latin America.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: Free and Sovereign State\n* Administrative center: Guanajuato\n* Approximate area: 30,608 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 6.1 million\n* Largest city: León\n* Signature features: Cradle of Mexican Independence, historic silver mining industry, colonial architecture of the Bajío region",
    "summary": "Guanajuato is a centrally located Mexican state in the fertile Bajío region, known for its historical significance as the cradle of Mexican Independence. Its economy relies on a mix of automotive manufacturing, agriculture, and tourism centered around its colonial cities. While the city of Guanajuato serves as the administrative center, León is the state's largest city and a major industrial hub.",
