    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nShizuoka Prefecture is located in the Chubu region on the Pacific coast of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is bordered by Kanagawa Prefecture to the east, Yamanashi Prefecture and Nagano Prefecture to the north, and Aichi Prefecture to the west. The prefecture faces the Pacific Ocean to the south, featuring a long coastline that curves around Suruga Bay and Enshu Nada.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Shizuoka is defined by its extensive coastline, deep bays, and high mountains. The most prominent physical feature is Mount Fuji, the highest peak in Japan, which Shizuoka shares with neighboring Yamanashi Prefecture. The northern border is dominated by the Akaishi Mountains, also known as the Southern Alps, which include peaks exceeding 3,000 meters in elevation. The eastern portion of the prefecture consists of the Izu Peninsula, a rugged, volcanic landform known for its geothermal activity and coastal cliffs. Suruga Bay, located between the Izu Peninsula and the central coastline, is the deepest bay in Japan. Several major rivers flow south from the mountains into the Pacific Ocean, including the Fuji River, the Abe River, the Oi River, and the Tenryu River. In the western part of the prefecture lies Lake Hamana, a large brackish lake connected to the Pacific Ocean. Much of the natural landscape is protected within the Fuji-Hakone-Izu National Park and the Minami Alps National Park.\n\n## Climate\nShizuoka experiences a humid subtropical climate. The coastal plains generally have mild winters with little to no snowfall and hot, humid summers. The region receives abundant precipitation throughout the year, with the heaviest rainfall occurring during the summer monsoon and the autumn typhoon season. The warm Kuroshio Current offshore helps moderate coastal temperatures. In contrast, the mountainous northern areas and the slopes of Mount Fuji experience a much cooler climate, with heavy snowfall and freezing temperatures during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Shizuoka is highly diversified, featuring strong agricultural, manufacturing, and fishing sectors. The prefecture is the largest producer of green tea in Japan, with extensive tea plantations covering its hillsides. It is also a major producer of mandarin oranges, known locally as mikan. The manufacturing sector is heavily concentrated in the western city of Hamamatsu, which is famous for producing musical instruments, motorcycles, and automobiles. Companies such as Yamaha, Suzuki, and Honda have deep historical ties to this area. The city of Fuji is a major center for the paper and pulp industry. Yaizu is one of Japan's most productive fishing ports, specializing in tuna and bonito. Shizuoka is the administrative center, while Hamamatsu is the largest city by population. Other significant cities include Numazu, Fuji, and the hot spring resort city of Atami on the Izu Peninsula.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore the Meiji Restoration, the area comprising modern Shizuoka Prefecture was divided into three distinct provinces: Izu, Suruga, and Totomi. The region holds significant historical importance due to its association with Tokugawa Ieyasu, the founder of the Tokugawa shogunate. Ieyasu spent much of his early life and his retirement in Sunpu, which is now modern-day Shizuoka city. His remains were initially interred at Kunozan Toshogu shrine in Shizuoka before being moved to Nikko. During the Edo period, the Tokaido, the primary coastal route connecting Kyoto and Edo, ran directly through the region. The prefecture hosted twenty-two of the fifty-three post stations on this historic highway.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Shizuoka\n* Approximate area: 7,777 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.5 million\n* Largest city: Hamamatsu\n* Signature features: Mount Fuji, green tea production, Izu Peninsula hot springs, musical instrument manufacturing",
    "summary": "Shizuoka is a coastal prefecture in central Honshu known for its diverse geography, which includes the Izu Peninsula, Suruga Bay, and the southern half of Mount Fuji. Its economy is driven by green tea agriculture, a massive fishing industry, and manufacturing hubs like Hamamatsu that produce musical instruments and vehicles. Historically significant as a major segment of the Tokaido road, the region is also closely associated with the life of shogun Tokugawa Ieyasu.",
