    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nNuevo León is located in the northeastern region of Mexico. It is bordered by the Mexican states of Tamaulipas to the north and east, San Luis Potosí to the south, and Coahuila to the west. To the extreme north, Nuevo León shares a narrow, 14-kilometer international border with the United States along the state of Texas, centered around the Colombia Solidarity International Bridge. The state is entirely landlocked, though it lies relatively close to the Gulf of Mexico. There are no active territorial disputes regarding its borders.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Nuevo León is characterized by a dramatic transition from flat plains to rugged mountains. The Sierra Madre Oriental mountain range runs through the state from the northwest to the southeast, dividing the territory. This range features prominent peaks such as Cerro de la Silla, which serves as an iconic symbol of the region, as well as Cerro de las Mitras and Cerro de la Maza. Much of this mountainous terrain is protected within the Cumbres de Monterrey National Park, which contains deep canyons, waterfalls like Horsetail Falls, and pine-oak forests. North of the mountains, the landscape flattens into the Gulf Coastal Plain, featuring arid shrublands. The state's primary hydrological systems include the San Juan River, which flows into the Rio Grande, and the Santa Catarina River, which passes through the capital city. The El Cuchillo reservoir, built on the San Juan River, is one of the largest reservoirs in northeastern Mexico and provides a critical water supply.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Nuevo León is predominantly arid and semi-arid, particularly in the northern plains. The mountainous regions of the Sierra Madre Oriental experience a more temperate highland climate with higher levels of humidity. Average annual precipitation is low and highly irregular, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the late summer and autumn months. This rainfall is often associated with tropical depressions and hurricanes originating in the Gulf of Mexico. Temperatures in the state can be extreme. Summer temperatures regularly exceed 40 degrees Celsius in the lowlands, while winter temperatures can drop below freezing, particularly in high-altitude mountain areas where snowfall occasionally occurs.\n\n## Economy & cities\nNuevo León is one of the most economically prosperous and industrialized states in Mexico. It has a highly developed manufacturing sector, with major industries including steel production, cement manufacturing, glassmaking, automotive parts, and beer brewing. The state capital, Monterrey, is the anchor of the third-largest metropolitan area in the country and serves as a major financial and industrial hub. Other prominent municipalities within this metropolitan area include San Pedro Garza García, which is known as a major financial center, Apodaca, which hosts numerous industrial parks and the international airport, and San Nicolás de los Garza. The state's proximity to the United States has made it a prime destination for foreign direct investment and maquiladora operations.\n\n## History & culture\nPrior to Spanish colonization, the region was inhabited by various nomadic indigenous groups collectively referred to as Coahuiltecans. In the late 16th century, the Spanish Crown established the New Kingdom of León, a province governed by Luis de Carvajal y de la Cueva. Monterrey was permanently founded in 1596 by Diego de Montemayor. Due to its isolation from central Mexico and frequent conflicts with indigenous populations, the region developed a distinct, self-reliant culture. During the 19th and 20th centuries, Nuevo León transitioned rapidly from an agricultural economy to an industrial powerhouse. Cultural traditions in the state include norteño music, which heavily features the accordion, and a culinary heritage centered on grilled meats, particularly cabrito and machacado.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Monterrey\n* Approximate area: 64,156 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.8 million\n* Largest city: Monterrey\n* Signature features: Cerro de la Silla mountain and the industrial hub of Monterrey",
    "summary": "Nuevo León is a highly industrialized, landlocked state in northeastern Mexico centered around its capital, Monterrey. Characterized by the rugged Sierra Madre Oriental mountains and arid northern plains, the state shares a short international border with Texas. It is a major economic powerhouse known for manufacturing, financial services, and distinctive cultural traditions like norteño music.",
