    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\nQuerétaro is located in the north-central region of Mexico, in a geographic area known as El Bajío. It is a landlocked state and one of the smaller federal entities in the country. It shares borders with five other Mexican states. To the north and northeast lies San Luis Potosí, to the west is Guanajuato, to the southwest is Michoacán, to the southeast is the State of Mexico, and to the east is Hidalgo.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state features a highly diverse topography divided into two main physiographic provinces. The southern portion belongs to the Mesa del Centro, characterized by rolling plains, fertile valleys, and scattered volcanic hills. The northern portion is dominated by the Sierra Madre Oriental, specifically the rugged Sierra Gorda region. This northern zone contains steep mountains, deep canyons, and high peaks, with elevations exceeding 3,000 meters above sea level. Querétaro lies within two major hydrological basins. The southern and western areas drain into the Lerma-Santiago river system, while the northern and eastern regions drain into the Pánuco River basin. Important rivers flowing through the state include the Santa María, the Extoraz, and the San Juan.\n\n## Climate\nQuerétaro experiences a wide range of climates due to its varied topography and elevation. The southern valleys and plains, including the metropolitan area of the capital, have a predominantly semi-arid to temperate climate. This region experiences warm summers and mild winters, with most precipitation falling during the summer months. In contrast, the Sierra Gorda in the north contains multiple microclimates. These range from dry, arid scrublands in the rain shadows of the mountains to humid subtropical climates and temperate pine-oak forests on the windward slopes. Average annual precipitation varies from under 500 millimeters in the drier southern plains to over 1,000 millimeters in the wettest mountainous zones.\n\n## Economy & cities\nQuerétaro has one of the most dynamic and fastest-growing economies in Mexico. The state is a major hub for high-tech industries, particularly aerospace manufacturing, automotive parts production, and information technology. It hosts a significant aerospace cluster with international manufacturing facilities and research centers. Agriculture and food processing also play vital roles, particularly in the southern valleys, which are known for dairy, poultry, and wine production. Santiago de Querétaro is the capital, largest city, and primary economic center. Other significant cities include San Juan del Río, an important industrial and agricultural hub, and Tequisquiapan, which is a center for tourism and viticulture.\n\n## History & culture\nBefore the Spanish conquest, the region was inhabited by indigenous groups, including the Otomí, Chichimeca, and Pame. The Spanish founded Santiago de Querétaro in 1531, and it became an important colonial outpost. The state played a pivotal role in Mexican history. In 1810, the Conspiracy of Querétaro served as the catalyst for the Mexican War of Independence. In 1848, the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo, which ended the Mexican-American War, was signed in the capital. Emperor Maximilian I of Mexico was captured and executed at the Cerro de las Campanas in Querétaro in 1867. Additionally, the current Constitution of Mexico was drafted and signed in the city in 1917. The historic center of Santiago de Querétaro is a UNESCO World Heritage site, famous for its colonial layout and its iconic 18th-century stone aqueduct. The five Franciscan Missions of the Sierra Gorda are also designated as UNESCO World Heritage sites.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Santiago de Querétaro\n* Approximate area: 11,684 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,368,000\n* Largest city: Santiago de Querétaro\n* Signature features: The historic 74-arch stone aqueduct of Santiago de Querétaro and the rugged biosphere reserve of the Sierra Gorda.",
    "summary": "Querétaro is a small, landlocked state in north-central Mexico known for its diverse geography, which transitions from southern plains to the rugged Sierra Gorda mountains. The state is an economic powerhouse driven by advanced manufacturing, particularly in the aerospace and automotive sectors. Rich in history, its capital city of Santiago de Querétaro features a UNESCO-listed colonial center and served as the site for pivotal events like the drafting of the 1917 Mexican Constitution.",
