    "mainNotes": "## Location within Mexico\n\nVeracruz is a long, narrow state located in eastern Mexico along the Gulf of Mexico. It shares borders with seven other Mexican states. To the north lies Tamaulipas. To the west, it borders San Luis Potosí, Hidalgo, and Puebla. To the south and southwest, it is bordered by Oaxaca and Chiapas, while Tabasco lies to the southeast. Its eastern boundary is defined by a coastline stretching over 700 kilometers along the Gulf of Mexico.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Veracruz is highly diverse, transitioning rapidly from sea level to some of the highest peaks in Mexico. The state is dominated by the Sierra Madre Oriental mountain range in the west and the Trans-Mexican Volcanic Belt. Pico de Orizaba, also known as Citlaltépetl, is Mexico's highest peak at 5,636 meters, sitting on the border with Puebla. Another notable peak is the Cofre de Perote. The coastal plain is wide in the north and south but narrows significantly in the center. Veracruz is drained by several major rivers, including the Pánuco River on the northern border, the Tuxpan River, the Cazones River, the Tecolutla River, and the Papaloapan and Coatzacoalcos rivers in the south. The state also contains the Laguna de Catemaco, a large lake located in the volcanic Tuxtlas region.\n\n## Climate\n\nDue to its varied topography, Veracruz experiences a wide range of climates. The coastal plains generally have a tropical wet and dry climate or a tropical monsoon climate, characterized by high temperatures and high humidity year-round. The rainy season typically lasts from June to October, often influenced by tropical storms and hurricanes originating in the Gulf of Mexico. In the foothills of the Sierra Madre Oriental, the climate transitions to a humid subtropical climate, often referred to as a cloud forest zone, where fog and drizzle are common. The high-altitude mountain peaks experience cold highland climates, with temperatures frequently dropping below freezing and snow occurring on the highest summits like Pico de Orizaba.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nVeracruz has a diverse economy rooted in agriculture, petroleum, and maritime trade. The state is a major producer of crops such as sugarcane, coffee, vanilla, citrus fruits, and corn. Livestock ranching is also highly developed on the coastal plains. Veracruz possesses significant oil and natural gas reserves, particularly in the northern and southern regions, supporting a large petrochemical industry. The port of Veracruz is one of the oldest, largest, and most historically significant commercial ports in Mexico, handling vast quantities of import and export goods.\n\nThe administrative center is Xalapa, a major educational and cultural hub. The largest city in the state is the port city of Veracruz, located on the coast. Other major urban centers include Coatzacoalcos, a key petrochemical port in the south, Poza Rica, an oil-producing city in the north, and Orizaba and Córdoba, which are important industrial and agricultural centers in the mountainous interior.\n\n## History & culture\n\nVeracruz has a rich pre-Columbian history. It was home to major Mesoamerican civilizations, including the Olmecs, who are considered the mother culture of Mesoamerica, as well as the Totonacs and Huastecs. The archaeological site of El Tajín, famous for its Pyramid of the Niches, is a UNESCO World Heritage site located in the northern part of the state. In 1519, Hernán Cortés founded Villa Rica de la Vera Cruz, establishing the first Spanish settlement on the North American mainland.\n\nThe culture of Veracruz is a unique blend of Indigenous, Spanish, and African influences. This fusion is evident in its traditional music, particularly Son Jarocho, which features instruments like the jarana and is famously represented by the song 'La Bamba.' The state is also famous for its culinary traditions, which heavily feature seafood, plantains, and the use of indigenous herbs like acuyo.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Mexico\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Xalapa\n* Approximate area: 71,820 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 8.06 million residents\n* Largest city: Veracruz\n* Signature features: Pico de Orizaba (the highest peak in Mexico) and the ancient ruins of El Tajín.",
    "summary": "Veracruz is a long, narrow Mexican state stretching along the Gulf of Mexico, characterized by a diverse geography that ranges from tropical coastal plains to Pico de Orizaba, the nation's highest peak. Its economy relies heavily on agriculture, petroleum extraction, and maritime trade through its major port city, while its capital, Xalapa, serves as an educational hub. The state boasts a rich cultural heritage shaped by Olmec, Totonac, Spanish, and African influences, famously represented by the El Tajin archaeological site and Son Jarocho music.",
