    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Chechnya is located in the North Caucasus region of southwestern Russia. It is situated within the North Caucasian Federal District. Chechnya shares international borders with the nation of Georgia to the south. Domestically, it is bordered by the Russian federal subjects of Dagestan to the east and northeast, Ingushetia to the west, North Ossetia, Alania to the northwest, and Stavropol Krai to the northwest. Although Chechnya experienced severe separatist conflicts and a self-declared bid for independence during the 1990s, it is internationally recognized as an integral federal subject of the Russian Federation.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Chechnya is highly diverse, transitioning from flat plains in the north to high alpine peaks in the south. The northern third of the republic lies within the Terek-Kuma Lowland, characterized by dry steppe and semi-desert terrain. Moving southward, the land rises into the Caucasus foothills and eventually the high peaks of the Greater Caucasus range. The highest point in Chechnya is Mount Tebulosmta, which reaches an elevation of 4,493 meters along the border with Georgia. The primary waterways are the Terek River, which flows through the northern plains, and its major tributaries, the Sunzha and Argun rivers, which drain the southern highlands and cut deep gorges through the mountains.\n\n## Climate\nChechnya experiences a continental climate that varies significantly based on elevation. The northern plains have a semi-arid climate with hot summers, where temperatures often exceed 35 degrees Celsius, and cold winters with light snowfall. The central valleys and foothills have a more moderate, temperate climate. In the southern mountainous regions, the climate is alpine. Winters in the mountains are long, cold, and snowy, while summers remain cool. Average January temperatures range from minus 3 degrees Celsius in the lowlands to minus 12 degrees Celsius in the high mountains.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Chechnya is historically rooted in the petroleum industry. Grozny was once one of Russia's primary oil-refining centers, though much of this infrastructure was destroyed during the conflicts of the late 20th century and has since undergone gradual reconstruction. Today, agriculture plays a vital role, particularly in the fertile central lowlands. Major agricultural products include wheat, barley, sugar beets, and vegetables, alongside sheep and cattle farming. Grozny is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the economic hub. Other significant urban centers include Gudermes, which is a major regional railway junction, Shali, and Urus-Martan.\n\n## History & culture\nThe indigenous people of Chechnya are the Chechens, a Nakh-speaking ethnic group who call themselves Nokhchiy. The majority of the population practices Sunni Islam, which has historically influenced local laws and social structures. Chechnya was annexed by the Russian Empire in the 19th century after decades of resistance during the Caucasian War. In 1944, the entire Chechen population was forcibly deported to Central Asia by Soviet authorities, returning only in 1957. Following the collapse of the Soviet Union, Chechnya suffered two devastating wars between Russian forces and separatist fighters. The region has since stabilized under a highly centralized pro-Moscow government. Traditional Chechen culture is characterized by a strict code of conduct called Nokhkchalla, traditional dance, and medieval stone defensive towers preserved in the southern highlands.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Grozny\n* Approximate area: 17,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,510,000\n* Largest city: Grozny\n* Signature features: The high peak of Mount Tebulosmta and the Akhmad Kadyrov Mosque in Grozny, which is one of the largest mosques in Europe.",
