    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKabardino-Balkaria is located in the northern Caucasus region of southwestern Russia. It is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, classified as a republic. The republic shares international borders to the south with Georgia. Within Russia, it is bordered by the Republic of North Ossetia-Alania to the east and southeast, the Stavropol Krai to the north and northeast, and the Karachay-Cherkess Republic to the west and northwest. Its position on the northern slopes of the Caucasus Mountains places it at a critical geographic and cultural crossroads between Europe and Asia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Kabardino-Balkaria is highly mountainous, characterized by dramatic elevation changes from north to south. The southern part of the republic is dominated by the Great Caucasus range. This area contains Mount Elbrus, which is the highest peak in Russia and Europe, reaching an elevation of 5,642 meters above sea level. Other major peaks include Mount Dykh-Tau and Mount Koshtan-Tau, both of which exceed 5,000 meters. The northern part of the republic transitions into the fertile Kabardian Plain, which is part of the larger Forecaucasus region. The republic is drained by several major rivers belonging to the Terek River basin. The Baksan, Malka, Cherek, and Urukh rivers flow through deep gorges in the mountains before entering the plains, providing significant hydroelectric potential and water for irrigation.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Kabardino-Balkaria varies significantly based on elevation. The northern plains experience a continental climate characterized by warm summers and moderately cold winters. Average January temperatures in the plains range from minus 4 degrees Celsius to minus 12 degrees Celsius, while July temperatures average around 23 degrees Celsius. In the mountainous southern regions, the climate becomes alpine, with much lower temperatures and higher precipitation. Annual precipitation ranges from about 500 millimeters in the plains to over 2,000 millimeters in the high-altitude zones. Snow cover in the high Caucasus persists year-round, feeding numerous glaciers that act as the source for the region's rivers.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kabardino-Balkaria is diverse, with agriculture, manufacturing, and tourism serving as the primary sectors. The fertile northern plains support intensive agriculture, including the cultivation of grains, sunflower seeds, vegetables, and fruits, alongside livestock breeding. Industrial activities are concentrated in the urban areas and include food processing, non-ferrous metallurgy, machine building, and the production of building materials. Tourism and outdoor recreation are highly developed, centered around Mount Elbrus, the Baksan Valley, and various mineral spring resorts. Nalchik is the administrative center and the largest city, acting as the economic and cultural hub. Other notable cities include Prokhladny, which is a major railway junction, Baksan, and Nartkala.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe republic is named after its two primary indigenous ethnic groups, the Kabardians, who speak a Northwest Caucasian language, and the Balkars, who speak a Turkic language. Historically, the Kabardians inhabited the lowland plains while the Balkars resided in the mountainous highlands. The region came under Russian influence in the sixteenth century, culminating in formal incorporation into the Russian Empire during the nineteenth century. Following the Russian Revolution, the territory was established as an autonomous oblast in 1921 and later upgraded to an autonomous republic. During World War II, the region suffered under German occupation, and the Balkar population was forcibly deported to Central Asia in 1944, though they were permitted to return in 1957. Today, the republic maintains a rich cultural heritage, with Islam being the predominant religion among both Kabardians and Balkars, alongside a significant Russian Orthodox minority.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Nalchik\n* Approximate area: 12,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 900,000\n* Largest city: Nalchik\n* Signature features: Mount Elbrus, the highest peak in Europe, and the scenic Baksan Valley.",
    "summary": "Kabardino-Balkaria is a mountainous republic of Russia located on the northern slopes of the Caucasus Mountains, bordering Georgia to the south. It is home to Mount Elbrus, Europe's highest peak, and features a diverse economy driven by agriculture, light industry, and alpine tourism. The republic is named for its two main indigenous ethnic groups, the Kabardians and the Balkars, and is administered from the city of Nalchik.",
