    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Dagestan is located in the southernmost part of the Russian Federation, situated in the North Caucasus region. It shares international land borders with Azerbaijan to the south and Georgia to the southwest. Within the Russian Federation, Dagestan is bordered by the Republic of Chechnya to the west, Stavropol Krai to the northwest, and the Republic of Kalmykia to the north. The eastern boundary of the republic is formed by a long coastline along the Caspian Sea. Dagestan is an established federal subject of Russia, and its territorial boundaries are internationally recognized.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Dagestan is highly diverse, divided between northern lowlands and southern mountains. The southern half of the republic is dominated by the Greater Caucasus Mountains. The highest point in Dagestan is Mount Bazardüdü, which reaches an elevation of 4,466 meters on the border with Azerbaijan. In contrast, the northern portion of the republic lies within the Caspian Lowland, much of which is situated below global sea level. The primary river systems draining the region are the Terek, the Sulak, and the Samur. The Sulak River has carved the Sulak Canyon, which is one of the deepest canyons in the world, reaching depths of up to 1,920 meters. The republic features approximately 400 kilometers of coastline along the Caspian Sea, characterized by sandy beaches and shallow waters.\n\n## Climate\nDagestan experiences a varied climate due to its dramatic topographical relief. The northern lowlands have a dry, semi-arid continental climate, characterized by hot summers and cold, relatively snowless winters. The coastal strip along the Caspian Sea enjoys a more moderate maritime climate. In the southern mountainous regions, the climate transitions to a highland type, where temperatures decrease with altitude. Winters in the mountains are long and cold, with significant snow cover, while summers are brief and cool. Makhachkala, the capital, experiences average January temperatures of about 0 degrees Celsius and average July temperatures of about 25 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Dagestan is driven by agriculture, industrial manufacturing, and energy production. Agricultural activities include sheep herding, grain farming, and viticulture, particularly in the fertile lowlands and foothills. The region is known for its brandy and wine production. Industrial sectors include oil and gas extraction, food processing, and machinery manufacturing. Hydroelectric power is highly developed, with several major stations operating on the Sulak River. Makhachkala is the administrative center, largest city, and primary seaport. Other significant urban centers include Khasavyurt, Kaspiysk, and Derbent. Derbent is historically significant as a key trading post and defensive gateway.\n\n## History & culture\nDagestan is notable for its extreme ethnic and linguistic diversity, with more than 30 distinct indigenous ethnic groups. The largest groups include the Avars, Dargins, Kumyks, Lezgins, and Laks, with no single group constituting an absolute majority. Russian serves as the primary administrative language, alongside several recognized local languages. Islam is the predominant religion, introduced to the region during the Arab conquests in the 7th century. The ancient city of Derbent contains the Naryn-Kala fortress, a UNESCO World Heritage site dating to the Sasanian Empire. Dagestan was formally incorporated into the Russian Empire in 1813 under the Treaty of Gulistan, following centuries of Persian and Ottoman influence.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Makhachkala\n* Approximate area: 50,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3,200,000\n* Largest city: Makhachkala\n* Signature features: The Sulak Canyon, which is one of the deepest canyons in the world, and the ancient fortress city of Derbent.",
