    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Kalmykia is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, situated in the southwestern part of the country within the Southern Federal District. It occupies a strategic position in the Caspian Depression, bordering several other Russian administrative divisions. To the south lies the Republic of Dagestan, while the Stavropol Krai borders it to the southwest. The Rostov Oblast lies to the west, the Volgograd Oblast to the northwest and north, and the Astrakhan Oblast to the east and northeast. Kalmykia also possesses a coastline along the Caspian Sea to the southeast. The republic's political status as an integral part of the Russian Federation is internationally recognized and undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\nKalmykia is characterized by its predominantly flat, low-lying topography, as much of its territory lies within the Caspian Depression, which is situated below sea level. The western portion of the republic features the Yergeni Hills, a low upland chain that rises gently above the surrounding plains. The landscape consists primarily of dry steppe, semi-desert, and desert biomes. Water resources are scarce in this arid region. The most significant water bodies include Lake Manych-Gudilo, a large, shallow saltwater lake located in the Kuma-Manych Depression along the southwestern border, and the Chogray Reservoir. The Sarpinsky Lakes form a chain of shallow basins in the north. The Volga River touches the far northeastern corner of the republic, but most of the territory lacks permanent flowing rivers.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Kalmykia is sharply continental and highly arid. Summers are long, dry, and hot, with temperatures frequently exceeding 35 degrees Celsius. Winters are cold and characterized by minimal snowfall, with temperatures often dropping below minus 10 degrees Celsius. The region is subject to strong, dry winds known as sukhovey, which accelerate soil erosion and contribute to desertification. Annual precipitation is exceptionally low, ranging from approximately 170 millimeters in the eastern desert areas to about 400 millimeters in the western uplands.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Kalmykia is heavily dependent on agriculture, particularly livestock breeding. The vast steppe pastures support extensive herds of sheep, beef cattle, and horses. Kalmykia is a major producer of fine wool and meat within Russia. The industrial sector is relatively small and focuses primarily on food processing, building materials, and the extraction of oil and natural gas, which are found in modest reserves. Elista is the administrative, cultural, and economic center of the republic, housing the majority of its population. Other notable urban settlements include Lagan, a port town located near the Caspian Sea coast, and Gorodovikovsk, situated in the agricultural west.\n\n## History & culture\nKalmykia is unique as the only region in Europe where Buddhism is the dominant religion. The Kalmyks are descendants of Oirat Mongols who migrated from Central Asia to the Volga steppe region in the early seventeenth century, establishing the Kalmyk Khanate. In 1943, the Soviet government dissolved the republic and deported the entire Kalmyk population to Siberia, an event that resulted in massive loss of life. The survivors were permitted to return in 1957, and the republic was subsequently restored. Modern Kalmyk culture is a blend of nomadic Mongol traditions and Tibetan Buddhism. Elista is famous for its grand Buddhist temples, such as the Golden Temple of Shakyamuni Buddha, and its association with international chess, highlighted by the Chess City complex built for the 1998 Chess Olympiad.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Elista\n* Approximate area: 76,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 267,000\n* Largest city: Elista\n* Signature features: The only Buddhist-majority region in Europe, and Elista's Chess City complex.",
    "summary": "The Republic of Kalmykia is a federal subject of Russia located in the arid Caspian Depression of southwestern Russia. It is unique as the only Buddhist-majority region in Europe, with its culture deeply rooted in Oirat Mongol traditions. The economy relies heavily on livestock breeding, and its capital, Elista, is renowned as a major center for international chess.",
