    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nBuryatia is located in the south-central region of Siberia, along the eastern shore of Lake Baikal. It is part of the Far Eastern Federal District. It shares an international border with Mongolia to the south. Within Russia, it borders the Irkutsk Oblast to the west and north, the Zabaykalsky Krai to the east, and the Republic of Tuva to the southwest.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Buryatia is dominated by mountainous terrain and the massive water body of Lake Baikal. Over 60 percent of the lake's shoreline lies within the republic. Major mountain ranges include the Sayan Mountains in the west and the Khamar-Daban Range near the lake. The highest point is Mount Munku-Sardyk, reaching 3,491 meters on the Mongolian border. Significant rivers flowing through the region include the Selenga River, which is the main tributary of Lake Baikal, the Barguzin River, and the Upper Angara River. The Vitim River, a major tributary of the Lena, originates in the eastern highlands. Forested taiga covers a vast portion of the territory, transitioning into mountain tundra at higher elevations and steppe in the southern basins.\n\n## Climate\n\nBuryatia experiences a sharply continental climate characterized by extreme temperature variations between seasons. Winters are long, dry, and very cold, with average January temperatures dropping to minus 25 degrees Celsius or lower. Summers are short but relatively warm, with July averages around 20 degrees Celsius. The region receives low to moderate annual precipitation, mostly falling as rain during the summer months. The presence of Lake Baikal exerts a moderating influence on the immediate coastal areas, making winters slightly milder and summers cooler compared to the interior valleys.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Buryatia relies heavily on mining, forestry, agriculture, and manufacturing. The republic is rich in mineral resources, including significant deposits of gold, tungsten, uranium, zinc, and coal. Industrial manufacturing is concentrated in the capital, Ulan-Ude, which features major locomotive repair facilities and aviation plants. Agriculture is primarily focused on livestock breeding, including cattle, sheep, and horses, particularly in the southern steppe regions. Tourism is an emerging sector, centered on Lake Baikal and nature reserves such as the Barguzin Nature Reserve. Ulan-Ude is the largest city and administrative center, situated at the junction of the Uda and Selenga rivers. Other notable urban centers include Severobaykalsk on the northern shore of Lake Baikal and Gusinoozyorsk.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous people of the region are the Buryats, a Mongolic ethnic group who have historically practiced pastoral nomadism. Buddhism and shamanism are deeply rooted in Buryat culture. The region became the center of Russian Buddhism, with the Ivolginsky Datsan serving as the spiritual headquarters. Russian contact began in the seventeenth century with the arrival of Cossack explorers and fur traders. The region was officially integrated into the Russian Empire through treaties with the Qing Dynasty in the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries. The construction of the Trans-Siberian Railway in the late nineteenth century accelerated Russian settlement and economic integration. Today, the population is ethnically diverse, with ethnic Russians forming the majority, followed by Buryats.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Ulan-Ude\n* Approximate area: 351,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 975,000\n* Largest city: Ulan-Ude\n* Signature features: Lake Baikal shoreline and the Ivolginsky Datsan Buddhist monastery",
    "summary": "Buryatia is a Russian republic located in eastern Siberia along the shores of Lake Baikal, sharing a southern border with Mongolia. Its geography is defined by mountainous terrain, extensive taiga forests, and a sharply continental climate. The region features a rich cultural heritage shaped by indigenous Buryat traditions, Tibetan Buddhism, and Russian history, with its economy centered on mining, manufacturing, and forestry.",
