    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKarachay-Cherkessia, officially known as the Karachay-Cherkess Republic, is a federal subject of the Russian Federation located in the North Caucasus region of southwestern Russia. It is part of the North Caucasian Federal District. The republic shares internal borders with Krasnodar Krai to the west and northwest, Stavropol Krai to the north and northeast, and the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic to the east. To the south and southwest, it shares an international border with Georgia, specifically along the Caucasus crest bordering the breakaway region of Abkhazia and the region of Samegrelo-Zemo Svaneti. The political status of Abkhazia is a subject of international dispute, with Russia recognizing it as independent while Georgia and most of the international community consider it Georgian territory.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Karachay-Cherkessia is highly mountainous, with about eighty percent of the republic situated in the highlands of the Greater Caucasus. The southern border runs along the Main Caucasian Range. Mount Elbrus sits on the eastern border shared with Kabardino-Balkaria, with its western slopes extending into the republic. The region is rich in water resources. The Kuban River, one of the major rivers of the Caucasus, originates from the glaciers of Mount Elbrus and flows northward. Other significant rivers include the Teberda, Bolshoy Zelenchuk, Maly Zelenchuk, Urup, and Laba. The Teberda Nature Reserve protects the pristine mountain ecosystems, subalpine meadows, and coniferous forests.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Karachay-Cherkessia is characterized by vertical zonation, varying from moderate continental in the northern plains to alpine in the high mountains. In the northern lowlands, winters are mild with average January temperatures around minus four degrees Celsius, while summers are warm with July averages reaching twenty-two degrees Celsius. In the mountainous south, temperatures decrease with altitude, and high peaks experience permanent snow. Precipitation ranges from approximately five hundred millimeters annually in the northern plains to over two thousand millimeters in the high mountains.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Karachay-Cherkessia relies on agriculture, industry, and tourism. Agriculture focuses on grain cultivation and sugar beets in the north, and livestock breeding in the south. Industrial activities include chemical production, food processing, and mining coal, lead, and zinc. Tourism is centered on mountain resorts like Dombay and Arkhyz, which attract skiers and mountaineers. Arkhyz also hosts the Special Astrophysical Observatory of the Russian Academy of Sciences, operating the RATAN-600 radio telescope. Cherkessk is the administrative, economic, and cultural center. Other notable urban areas include Ust-Dzheguta, Karachayevsk, and Teberda.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe territory has a rich history shaped by its diverse ethnic groups, primarily the Turkic-speaking Karachays and the Circassian Cherkess. The area came under Russian control in the nineteenth century. The Karachay-Cherkess Autonomous Oblast was established in 1922. It underwent several administrative reorganizations, including the forced deportation of the Karachay population to Central Asia during World War II. The population returned in 1957, restoring the joint oblast. In 1991, the region became a republic within the Russian Federation. Today, the republic is multiethnic, with Karachays, Russians, Cherkess, Abaza, and Nogais forming the primary groups. Islam and Orthodox Christianity are the main religions.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Cherkessk\n* Approximate area: 14,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 460,000\n* Largest city: Cherkessk\n* Signature features: Mount Elbrus western slopes, Dombay ski resort, and the Special Astrophysical Observatory near Arkhyz.",
