    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nThe Republic of Khakassia is a federal subject of Russia, located in southwestern Eastern Siberia in the upper basin of the Yenisey River. Khakassia borders Krasnoyarsk Krai to the north and east, the Tuva Republic to the south, the Altai Republic to the southwest, and Kemerovo Oblast to the west. This landlocked republic occupies a transition zone between the Siberian taiga and the Central Asian steppes. The political status of Khakassia as an undisputed constituent republic of the Russian Federation is globally recognized.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Khakassia transitions from high mountain ranges to flat basin plains. The western portion is dominated by the Kuznetsk Alatau range, while the southern border is defined by the Western Sayan Mountains. These ranges slope into the Minusinsk Basin, a fertile depression in the eastern and central parts of the territory. The primary river is the Yenisey, which flows along the eastern border. The Abakan River, a major tributary, bisects the republic before joining the Yenisey at the capital. Khakassia is also known for its lakes, including both freshwater and mineralized saltwater bodies like Lake Shira and Lake Itkul.\n\n## Climate\n\nKhakassia experiences a dry continental climate, influenced by its inland position and surrounding mountains. Winters are long, cold, and dry, with average January temperatures between minus fifteen and minus twenty degrees Celsius. Summers are warm and short, with average July temperatures around nineteen degrees Celsius. The basin area receives around three hundred millimeters of precipitation annually, while the mountain slopes receive significantly more, often exceeding eight hundred millimeters.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Khakassia is driven by metallurgy, mining, and energy production. The republic hosts the Sayano-Shushenskaya Hydroelectric Power Station on the Yenisey River, one of the largest hydroelectric plants in the world. This facility powers the massive aluminum smelting industry in Sayanogorsk. Mining is also critical, with significant extraction of coal, iron ore, and non-ferrous metals. Chernogorsk is the primary center for coal mining. Agriculture in the fertile basin focuses on wheat, barley, and livestock farming. Abakan, the administrative center and largest city, serves as the primary transport and cultural hub.\n\n## History & culture\n\nKhakassia has a rich archaeological heritage, featuring ancient nomadic sites from the Tagar and Tashtyk cultures. Thousands of burial mounds, or kurgans, and stone stelae are scattered across the steppe, with the Great Salbyk Kurgan being the most famous. The indigenous Khakas people are a Turkic ethnic group who traditionally practiced pastoral nomadism. Russian settlement began in the seventeenth century, driven by mineral discoveries. Khakassia became an autonomous oblast in 1930 and was elevated to a republic in 1991.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Abakan\n* Approximate area: 61,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 530,000\n* Largest city: Abakan\n* Signature features: The Great Salbyk Kurgan and the nearby Sayano-Shushenskaya Hydroelectric Power Station.",
    "summary": "The Republic of Khakassia is a mountainous federal subject of Russia located in south-central Siberia along the Yenisey River basin. Its economy relies heavily on coal mining, aluminum smelting powered by the massive Sayano-Shushenskaya Dam, and agricultural activities in the fertile Minusinsk Basin. The region is also famous for its rich archaeological heritage, including thousands of ancient burial mounds and stelae left by early nomadic cultures.",
