    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Karelia is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, located in the northwestern part of the country. It shares a long international border with Finland to the west. Within Russia, Karelia is bordered by Murmansk Oblast to the north, Arkhangelsk Oblast to the east, Vologda Oblast to the southeast, and Leningrad Oblast to the south. The northeastern coast of the republic is washed by the White Sea, which is an inlet of the Barents Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nKarelia is characterized by a glaciated landscape shaped by the Fennoscandian ice sheet. It lies on the Baltic Shield, resulting in rocky terrain with thin soils and exposed bedrock. The republic contains more than 60,000 lakes. Europe's two largest lakes, Lake Ladoga and Lake Onega, lie partially within Karelia. Major rivers include the Kem, the Vyg, the Shuya, and the Suna, which features the Kivach Waterfall. The terrain is generally flat to hilly, with the highest elevation at Mount Nuorunen reaching about 576 meters. Dense taiga forests, dominated by pine, spruce, and Karelian birch, cover roughly 85 percent of the territory. Protected areas include Paanajärvi and Vodlozero national parks.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Karelia transitions from maritime to continental, moderated by proximity to the Baltic, White, and Barents seas. Winters are long and cold but lack the extreme severity of eastern Siberia. Average January temperatures range from minus 8 degrees Celsius in the south to minus 14 degrees Celsius in the north. Summers are short and cool, with average July temperatures ranging from 12 degrees Celsius in the north to 17 degrees Celsius in the south. Annual precipitation averages between 500 and 700 millimeters, falling mostly as rain in summer and snow in winter.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy relies heavily on natural resources. Forestry, logging, and wood processing are primary industries, with major pulp and paper mills in Segezha and Kondopoga. Mining focuses on iron ore extraction at Kostomuksha, alongside the quarrying of granite, marble, and shungite, a unique carbonaceous mineral. Petrozavodsk, the administrative center and largest city, serves as the industrial hub, hosting machine-building enterprises. Other notable towns include Sortavala, near the Finnish border, and Belomorsk, situated on the White Sea coast at the terminus of the White Sea-Baltic Canal.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, Karelia was inhabited by Finno-Ugric peoples, including Karelians and Veps, alongside Slavic settlers. The region was contested between the Swedish Empire and the Novgorod Republic, and later the Russian Empire, before being integrated into Russia by the Treaty of Nystad in 1721. During the mid-twentieth century, Karelia's borders shifted significantly. Following the Winter War and World War II, the Soviet Union annexed parts of Finnish Karelia, and the region existed as the Karelo-Finnish Soviet Socialist Republic from 1940 to 1956. Culturally, Karelia is renowned as the source of the oral folklore compiled into the *Kalevala*, the national epic of Finland.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Petrozavodsk\n* Approximate area: 172,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 530,000\n* Largest city if different from the administrative center: Petrozavodsk is the largest city\n* Signature features: Lake Ladoga and Lake Onega, Kizhi Island wooden architecture, and the Karelian birch",
    "summary": "The Republic of Karelia is a northwestern Russian federal subject bordering Finland, characterized by a glaciated landscape containing Europe's two largest lakes, Ladoga and Onega. Its economy is driven by forestry, paper production, and mining, with its administrative center located at Petrozavodsk. Culturally, the region is famous as the historical source of the folklore compiled into the Finnish national epic, the Kalevala.",
