    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nThe Komi Republic is a federal subject of Russia located in the northeastern part of European Russia, west of the Ural Mountains. It shares borders with the Nenets Autonomous Okrug to the north, the Yamalo-Nenets and Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrugs to the east, Sverdlovsk Oblast to the southeast, Perm Krai to the south, Kirov Oblast to the southwest, and Arkhangelsk Oblast to the west. Its territory lies largely within the Pechora and Vychegda river basins.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain is mostly flat plains, rising to the Ural Mountains along the eastern border. Mount Narodnaya, the highest peak in the Urals at 1,895 meters, sits on the eastern boundary. The Pechora River flows north into the Barents Sea, while the Vychegda River drains the south toward the Northern Dvina. The Virgin Komi Forests cover over 32,000 square kilometers, forming the largest intact subarctic forest in Europe and a UNESCO World Heritage Site. This area includes Yugyd Va National Park and the Pechora-Ilych Nature Reserve. The republic also features the Manpupuner rock formations, seven massive stone pillars on the western slopes of the Urals.\n\n## Climate\n\nKomi has a harsh subarctic climate with long, cold winters and short, cool summers. Permafrost is common in the north, where tundra vegetation prevails, while the south features taiga. Average January temperatures range from minus 15 degrees Celsius in the south to minus 22 degrees Celsius in the north. Summers are brief, with July averages between 11 and 17 degrees Celsius. Precipitation averages 400 to 700 millimeters annually, mostly falling as snow, which covers the ground for up to two hundred days.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy relies on natural resource extraction. The Pechora Coal Basin, centered on Vorkuta, has historically been a major coal source. Oil and gas extraction are concentrated around Ukhta and Usinsk, with pipelines transporting resources westward. Forestry and wood processing are also major industries. Syktyvkar, the administrative center and largest city, is a hub for pulp and paper production. Ukhta is known as the birthplace of the Russian oil industry, while Vorkuta is a major northern coal-mining center.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous Komi are a Finno-Ugric people speaking a Permic language. Christianized in the fourteenth century by Saint Stephen of Perm, who created the Old Permic script, the region was annexed by Moscow in the late fifteenth century. During the Soviet era, the Komi Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic was established, and industrialization was accelerated by forced labor in the Vorkuta Gulag system. Today, ethnic Russians form the majority, but the Komi minority maintains its cultural heritage.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Syktyvkar\n* Approximate area: 416,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 720,000\n* Largest city: Syktyvkar\n* Signature features: Virgin Komi Forests and the Manpupuner rock formations",
    "summary": "The Komi Republic is a federal subject of Russia located west of the Ural Mountains, known for its vast subarctic forests and rich reserves of coal, oil, and natural gas. Its administrative center is Syktyvkar, and the region is home to the UNESCO-listed Virgin Komi Forests and the unique Manpupuner rock formations. Historically inhabited by the Finno-Ugric Komi people, the republic transitioned into a heavily industrialized region during the Soviet era.",
