    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nTuva (officially the Tyva Republic) is located in the southern part of Siberia. It lies in the geographical center of Asia. It shares an international border with Mongolia to the south and east. Within the Russian Federation, it borders the Altai Republic to the west, the Republic of Khakassia to the northwest, Krasnoyarsk Krai to the north, Irkutsk Oblast to the northeast, and the Republic of Buryatia to the east. The political status of Tuva as a constituent republic of the Russian Federation is internationally recognized and undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Tuva is characterized by a mountain basin structure. Over eighty percent of the republic is covered by mountains, primarily the Sayan Mountains to the north and the Tannu-Ola Mountains to the south. The highest point in Tuva is Mongun-Tayga, which reaches an elevation of 3,970 meters above sea level. The region is highly significant hydrologically as the birthplace of the Yenisey River, one of the longest river systems in Asia. The Great Yenisey (Biy-Khem) and the Little Yenisey (Kaa-Khem) rivers meet at Kyzyl to form the Upper Yenisey (Ulug-Khem). Tuva also contains numerous lakes, including the saltwater Lake Uvs Nuur, which is shared with Mongolia and is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.\n\n## Climate\n\nTuva experiences a harsh, sharply continental climate. Due to its inland position and mountainous terrain, the region has long, cold winters and short, warm summers. In the basins, winter temperatures regularly drop below minus thirty degrees Celsius, with extreme lows reaching minus fifty degrees Celsius. Summers are warm, with average July temperatures in the basins ranging from eighteen to twenty degrees Celsius, though temperatures can occasionally exceed thirty-five degrees Celsius. Precipitation is relatively low and unevenly distributed. The basins receive only about two hundred millimeters of annual precipitation, while the mountain slopes can receive up to one thousand millimeters, mostly falling as rain during the summer months.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Tuva is primarily based on agriculture, mining, and forestry. Nomadic pastoralism, particularly the herding of sheep, goats, cattle, yaks, and reindeer, remains a vital economic activity for the rural population. The mining sector exploits rich deposits of coal, non-ferrous metals, gold, and asbestos. The administrative and economic center of the republic is Kyzyl, which is situated at the confluence of the Great and Little Yenisey rivers. Kyzyl is home to the majority of the republic's industrial enterprises and cultural institutions. Other notable urban settlements include Ak-Dovurak, which developed around a major asbestos mining operation, and Shagonar and Chadan, which serve as regional agricultural and coal mining hubs. Transport infrastructure is limited, as Tuva lacks a direct connection to the main Russian railway network, relying instead on highways such as the Yenisey highway for trade and transit.\n\n## History & culture\n\nTuva has a rich history influenced by various nomadic empires, including the Xiongnu, Goekturks, and Mongols. In the eighteenth century, the region came under the rule of the Qing Dynasty of China, known then as Tannu Uriankhai. Following the collapse of the Qing Dynasty, Tuva declared independence and became the Tannu Tuva People's Republic in 1921, a nominal sovereign state under Soviet influence. In 1944, the republic was integrated into the Soviet Union as an autonomous oblast, later becoming an autonomous republic. The indigenous Tuvan people are a Turkic ethnic group who traditionally practice Tibetan Buddhism and shamanism. Tuva is globally renowned for its unique cultural heritage, particularly the art of Khoomei, or Tuvan throat singing, which involves producing multiple pitches simultaneously.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Kyzyl\n* Approximate area: 170,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 337,000 people\n* Largest city: Kyzyl\n* Signature features: The geographical center of Asia monument and the traditional practice of throat singing (Khoomei)",
    "summary": "The Tuva Republic is a mountainous federal subject of Russia located in southern Siberia along the Mongolian border. It is characterized by a harsh continental climate, a basin-and-range topography that forms the headwaters of the Yenisey River, and an economy centered on pastoralism and mining. The region is culturally distinct for its indigenous Turkic population, Tibetan Buddhist traditions, and world-famous throat-singing heritage.",
