    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Mari El Republic is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, located in the eastern portion of the East European Plain. It lies within the middle Volga River basin, which is part of the Volga Federal District. Mari El shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. It is bounded by Nizhny Novgorod Oblast to the west and northwest, Kirov Oblast to the north and east, the Republic of Tatarstan to the southeast, and the Chuvash Republic to the south. The southern border of the republic is largely defined by the course of the Volga River.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Mari El is predominantly flat, characterized by the swampy Mari Depression in the west and center. The eastern part of the republic is more elevated, featuring the southern spurs of the Vyatka Uval, a hilly ridge that rises to heights of about 275 meters. Forests cover over 50 percent of the republic's territory, consisting of mixed coniferous and deciduous trees. The region is drained by the Volga River and its numerous tributaries. Significant rivers flowing through the republic include the Vetluga, the Rutka, the Bolshaya Kokshaga, the Malaya Kokshaga, and the Ilet. Mari Chodra National Park, located in the southeastern part of the republic, protects large areas of pine forests, wetlands, and clean karst lakes such as Lake Yalchik.\n\n## Climate\nMari El experiences a temperate continental climate. Winters are typically long, cold, and snowy, with average January temperatures hovering around minus 13 degrees Celsius. Summers are relatively warm but short, with average July temperatures of approximately 19 degrees Celsius. The republic receives moderate precipitation, averaging between 450 and 550 millimeters annually, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mari El relies on a mix of manufacturing, forestry, and agriculture. Major industries include machine building, metalworking, electronics, and the processing of wood and paper products. The city of Volzhsk, located on the Volga River, is a major industrial hub known for its pulp and paper mill. The agricultural sector focuses on dairy farming, cattle breeding, and the cultivation of rye, oats, barley, and flax. Yoshkar-Ola serves as the administrative, cultural, and economic center of the republic. Kozmodemyansk, a historic port city on the Volga, is another key urban center.\n\n## History & culture\nThe indigenous inhabitants of the region are the Mari, a Finno-Ugric ethnic group. Historically, the Mari lands were under the influence of Volga Bulgaria and the Golden Horde before being incorporated into the Kazan Khanate. Following the conquest of Kazan by Ivan the Terrible in 1552, the territory was annexed by the Tsardom of Russia. In 1920, the Soviet government established the Mari Autonomous Oblast, which was later upgraded to the Mari Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic in 1936. Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, the region became the Mari El Republic in 1992. The Mari people have preserved their unique culture, including the Mari Traditional Religion, which is one of the few surviving indigenous pagan religions in Europe.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Yoshkar-Ola\n* Approximate area: 23,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 670,000\n* Largest city: Yoshkar-Ola\n* Signature features: Mari Chodra National Park and the preservation of the Mari Traditional Religion, Europe's last active pagan faith.",
    "summary": "The Mari El Republic is a federal subject of Russia located in the middle Volga region, characterized by its flat, heavily forested landscape and numerous rivers. Its administrative center is Yoshkar-Ola, and its economy is driven by forestry, agriculture, and manufacturing. The republic is culturally significant as the homeland of the Finno-Ugric Mari people, who actively preserve their traditional pagan faith alongside Orthodox Christianity.",
