    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Tatarstan is located in the eastern portion of the East European Plain, within the Volga Federal District of the Russian Federation. It shares borders with eight other Russian federal subjects. To the north lie Kirov Oblast, the Udmurt Republic, and the Mari El Republic. To the west is the Chuvash Republic. To the south, Tatarstan borders Ulyanovsk, Samara, and Orenburg Oblasts. The Republic of Bashkortostan lies along its eastern border. There are no active territorial disputes regarding its borders, and it is internationally recognized as an integral federal subject of Russia.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Tatarstan consists mostly of rolling plains and low hills. The Volga Upland characterizes the area west of the Volga River, while the Bugulma-Belebey Upland occupies the southeast, containing the highest elevation in the republic at approximately 381 meters above sea level. The region is defined by its extensive river network. The Volga River and the Kama River, two of the longest rivers in Europe, merge within Tatarstan to form the Kuybyshev Reservoir, which is the largest reservoir in Eurasia by surface area. Other significant rivers include the Vyatka and the Belaya. The landscape transitions from mixed forests in the north to forest-steppe zones in the south.\n\n## Climate\nTatarstan experiences a moderate humid continental climate, characterized by warm summers and cold, snowy winters. Average temperatures in January, the coldest month, range from minus 11 to minus 14 degrees Celsius. July temperatures average around 19 to 21 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges between 450 and 500 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically forms in November and persists until April, lasting approximately 150 days.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTatarstan is one of the most economically developed regions in Russia. Its economy relies heavily on oil production, petrochemical manufacturing, and heavy engineering. The Romashkino field, located in the south, is one of the largest oil fields in the country. Almetyevsk serves as the primary hub for oil extraction and pipeline transport. Naberezhnye Chelny is a major industrial city known for the Kamaz truck manufacturing plant. Nizhnekamsk is a center for the petrochemical industry. Kazan, the administrative center and largest city, is a major financial, educational, and transport hub situated at the confluence of the Volga and Kazanka rivers.\n\n## History & culture\nThe territory of Tatarstan has a rich history, beginning with the medieval state of Volga Bulgaria, which adopted Islam in the tenth century. It later became part of the Golden Horde and subsequently the Khanate of Kazan. In 1552, Tsar Ivan IV, known as Ivan the Terrible, conquered Kazan, annexing the region into the Russian state. In 1920, the Soviet government established the Tatar Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic. Today, the population is split almost equally between ethnic Tatars, who traditionally practice Sunni Islam, and ethnic Russians, who are predominantly Orthodox Christian. The Kazan Kremlin, a UNESCO World Heritage site, features both the Annunciation Cathedral and the Kul Sharif Mosque, symbolizing this cultural synthesis.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Kazan\n* Approximate area: 68,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4,000,000\n* Largest city: Kazan\n* Signature features: Confluence of the Volga and Kama rivers, the historic Kazan Kremlin, and the Kamaz heavy truck industry.",
    "summary": "Tatarstan is a highly developed republic of the Russian Federation located at the confluence of the Volga and Kama rivers. Its administrative center is Kazan, a major cultural and economic hub known for its historic Kremlin that symbolizes the coexistence of Muslim Tatar and Orthodox Russian cultures. The region's economy is driven by robust oil extraction, petrochemical industries, and heavy machinery manufacturing.",
