    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Republic of Ingushetia is located in the North Caucasus region of southwestern Russia. It is situated on the northern slopes of the Greater Caucasus mountain range. Ingushetia shares borders with the Russian Republic of North Ossetia-Alania to the west and north, and the Chechen Republic to the east and northeast. To the south, it shares an international border with the country of Georgia. The boundary between Ingushetia and Chechnya was officially redefined by a bilateral agreement in 2018, which resolved long-standing territorial ambiguities but caused local political demonstrations.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Ingushetia is characterized by a dramatic transition from high mountains in the south to low-lying plains in the north. The southern territory is dominated by the Caucasus Mountains, with Mount Shan reaching an elevation of about 4,451 meters on the Georgian border. Another culturally significant peak is Stolovaya Mountain, which rises to roughly 3,000 meters. The central and northern areas consist of the fertile Sunzha Valley and the southern edge of the Terek Plain. The primary river is the Sunzha, which flows from west to east across the republic. Its major tributaries, the Assa and the Armkhi, carve deep gorges through the southern mountains. The Erzi Nature Reserve preserves these mountainous ecosystems, including alpine meadows, pine forests, and rare wildlife.\n\n## Climate\nIngushetia experiences a climate that varies greatly with elevation. The northern plains have a humid continental climate, characterized by warm summers with average temperatures around 21 degrees Celsius and moderately cold winters averaging minus 4 degrees Celsius. In contrast, the southern mountainous regions have an alpine climate. Winters in the mountains are long and cold, with heavy snow cover, while summers are brief and cool. Annual precipitation ranges from approximately 400 millimeters in the northern lowlands to more than 1,000 millimeters in the high-altitude southern zones.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Ingushetia is based primarily on agriculture, oil extraction, and light industry. Agricultural activities in the northern plains focus on growing wheat, barley, corn, and sugar beets, while livestock breeding of sheep and cattle is common in the mountain valleys. The republic possesses oil and natural gas reserves, centered around the town of Malgobek, though production has decreased from its historical peaks. Other industries include food processing, textile manufacturing, and the production of building materials. Magas, established in 1998, is the administrative center and one of the smallest capital cities in Russia. Nazran, the former capital, remains the largest city and the primary commercial and transport hub.\n\n## History & culture\nThe Ingush people are an indigenous ethnic group of the Caucasus, closely related to the neighboring Chechens. They traditionally refer to themselves as Ghalghai, which translates to tower dwellers. This name reflects the unique medieval stone towers that dot the southern mountain valleys, particularly in the Dzheyrakh Gorge. These towers served as both defensive fortifications and family dwellings. Islam is the dominant religion in the republic, and traditional codes of conduct, known as Ezdel, govern social relations. Historically, Ingushetia was annexed by the Russian Empire in 1810. During World War II, the entire Ingush population was deported to Central Asia by the Soviet government, returning only after 1957. Ingushetia became a distinct republic within the Russian Federation in 1992 following the dissolution of the Chechen-Ingush Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Magas\n* Approximate area: 3,600 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 510,000\n* Largest city: Nazran\n* Signature features: The medieval stone towers of the Dzheyrakh Gorge and the modern Concord Tower in Magas",
    "summary": "Ingushetia is the smallest republic of the Russian Federation, located on the northern slopes of the Greater Caucasus Mountains. Its administrative center is the planned city of Magas, while the former capital of Nazran serves as its largest economic hub. The republic is famous for its rich Vainakh culture, characterized by medieval stone defensive towers scattered across its mountainous southern terrain.",
