    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nThe Udmurt Republic, also known as Udmurtia, is a federal subject of Russia located in the eastern portion of the East European Plain. It is situated in the western Ural region, between the Volga River and the Ural Mountains. Udmurtia shares internal borders with Kirov Oblast to the north and west, Perm Krai to the east, the Republic of Bashkortostan to the southeast, and the Republic of Tatarstan to the south. The republic is entirely landlocked and does not share any international borders. Its political status as an integral republic of the Russian Federation is undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Udmurtia is a rolling, hilly plain sloping from north to south. The highest elevations are in the north within the Upper Kama Upland, reaching about 338 meters above sea level. The southern part consists of lower plains and river valleys. Udmurtia lies within the basins of the Kama and Vyatka rivers, major tributaries of the Volga. The Kama flows through the southeastern portion, while the Vyatka touches the western border. Other significant rivers include the Cheptsa and Kilmez. Approximately 40 percent of the territory is covered by mixed and coniferous forests. Nechkinsky National Park, situated along the Kama River, protects valuable forest and wetland ecosystems.\n\n## Climate\n\nUdmurtia experiences a moderate continental climate with distinct seasonal variations. Winters are long and cold, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 14 to minus 16 degrees Celsius. Extreme winter temperatures can drop below minus 40 degrees Celsius. Summers are relatively warm but short, with average July temperatures around 18 to 19 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, averaging between 500 and 600 millimeters annually, with the majority of rainfall occurring during summer. Snow cover typically persists from November through April.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Udmurtia is highly industrialized, focusing on defense manufacturing, mechanical engineering, metallurgy, and oil extraction. The administrative center and largest city is Izhevsk, globally recognized as a major center for firearms production, including Kalashnikov rifles. Izhevsk also produces automobiles and steel. Other key industrial cities include Sarapul, known for radio-electronics, and Votkinsk, notable for manufacturing thermal equipment and military missiles. Glazov, situated in the north, processes uranium and zirconium for the nuclear industry. Agriculture focuses on dairy farming and grain cultivation.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous people are the Udmurts, a Finno-Ugric ethnic group. The territory was integrated into the Russian state during the mid-sixteenth century, after the fall of the Khanate of Kazan. Russian settlement increased due to the establishment of ironworks and arms factories in the eighteenth century. In 1920, the Soviet government established the Udmurt Autonomous Oblast, which became an Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic in 1934. It became the Udmurt Republic in 1990. Both Russian and Udmurt are official languages. Culturally, the republic is famous as the birthplace of composer Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky in Votkinsk.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Izhevsk\n* Approximate area: 42,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,450,000\n* Largest city: Izhevsk\n* Signature features: Birthplace of composer Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky in Votkinsk, and the historic manufacturing center of Kalashnikov firearms in Izhevsk.",
    "summary": "Udmurtia is a landlocked republic of the Russian Federation located in the eastern East European Plain, bordered by Tatarstan, Bashkortostan, Perm Krai, and Kirov Oblast. The republic is highly industrialized, with its capital Izhevsk serving as a major defense manufacturing hub, and it is culturally notable as the homeland of the Finno-Ugric Udmurt people and the birthplace of Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky. Its geography features a rolling, forested landscape drained by the Kama River basin under a moderate continental climate.",
