    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKhabarovsk Krai is located in the Russian Far East, representing a vast territory along the Pacific coast. It shares land borders with Primorsky Krai to the south, the Jewish Autonomous Oblast and Amur Oblast to the west, the Sakha Republic (Yakutia) to the northwest, and Magadan Oblast to the north. To the east, it is bounded by the Sea of Okhotsk and the Sea of Japan. The narrow Strait of Tartary separates the krai from Sakhalin Island. Khabarovsk Krai shares a short international boundary with the Heilongjiang province of China in its southwestern corner. A border dispute with China over Bolshoy Ussuriysky Island near Khabarovsk city was resolved and demarcated in 2008, dividing the island between the two nations.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Khabarovsk Krai is dominated by rugged mountain ranges and vast river basins. Mountain systems cover most of the territory, including the Sikhote-Alin range in the south, which runs parallel to the coast, and the Dzhugdzhur Range along the northwestern coast of the Sea of Okhotsk. The highest point is Mount Berill, reaching 2,933 meters in the Suntar-Khayata Range. The primary hydrological feature is the Amur River, one of the longest rivers in Asia, which flows through the southern part of the krai and empties into the Amur Liman. Other major rivers include the Bureya and the Amgun. The region contains extensive taiga forests and protected areas such as Anyuysky National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Khabarovsk Krai is characterized by a severe subarctic climate in the north, transitioning to a humid continental climate with strong monsoonal influences in the south. Winters are long, cold, and dry, influenced by the Siberian High, with average January temperatures dropping to minus 22 degrees Celsius in Khabarovsk and below minus 40 degrees Celsius in the northern interior. Summers are short, warm, and humid, driven by Pacific monsoonal winds that bring the majority of the annual precipitation. Average July temperatures in the south reach approximately 21 degrees Celsius. Coastal areas experience frequent fog and cooler summer temperatures due to the cold currents of the Sea of Okhotsk.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Khabarovsk Krai relies heavily on natural resource extraction, heavy industry, and transportation. Major economic sectors include forestry, metallurgy, coal mining, and commercial fishing. The region is also a vital manufacturing hub for the Russian Far East, particularly in aerospace and shipbuilding. Komsomolsk-on-Amur is a major industrial center known for producing military and civilian aircraft. Khabarovsk, the administrative center, serves as a major financial, educational, and transportation hub. It is a key station along the Trans-Siberian Railway and the Baikal-Amur Mainline, which facilitate trade between Russia, China, and other East Asian nations.\n\n## History & culture\n\nIndigenous peoples, including the Nanai, Evenks, and Udege, have inhabited the Amur River basin for millennia. Russian exploration began in the mid-seventeenth century with expeditions led by explorers like Yerofey Khabarov, after whom the administrative center is named. The region was formally incorporated into the Russian Empire through the Treaty of Aigun in 1858 and the Treaty of Beijing in 1860. Soviet industrialization in the twentieth century brought rapid population growth, the construction of the Baikal-Amur Mainline, and the establishment of industrial cities like Komsomolsk-on-Amur. Culturally, the krai preserves a mix of indigenous traditions and Russian heritage.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Krai\n* Administrative center: Khabarovsk\n* Approximate area: 787,600 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.29 million residents\n* Largest city: Khabarovsk\n* Signature features: The Amur River basin and the Sikhote-Alin mountain range, which is home to the endangered Amur tiger.",
    "summary": "Khabarovsk Krai is a massive first-level administrative division in the Russian Far East, bordered by the Sea of Okhotsk and China. Its economy is driven by heavy industry, aerospace manufacturing, and natural resources, centered around the major cities of Khabarovsk and Komsomolsk-on-Amur. The region features diverse geography, including the Amur River basin and the rugged Sikhote-Alin mountain range.",
    "model": "gemini-3.5-flash"
