    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nThe Republic of Mordovia is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, located in the eastern portion of the East European Plain. It is situated within the Volga Federal District. Mordovia is landlocked and shares borders with several other Russian subdivisions. To the north, it borders Nizhny Novgorod Oblast. To the northeast lies the Chuvash Republic, while Ulyanovsk Oblast borders Mordovia to the east. Penza Oblast is situated to the south, and Ryazan Oblast borders the republic to the west. The capital city of Saransk is located in the eastern part of the republic, approximately 640 kilometers east of Moscow.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Mordovia is characterized by a transition from the Oka-Don Plain in the west to the Volga Upland in the east. The western region is relatively flat, while the eastern portion features more undulating hills with elevations reaching up to 324 meters above sea level. The republic belongs to the Volga River basin. Its primary rivers include the Moksha, which flows through the western and central areas, and the Sura, which forms a portion of the eastern border. Major tributaries of the Moksha within Mordovia include the Vad and the Sivin. The Insar River flows through the capital city of Saransk. Forests cover approximately 27 percent of the territory, consisting of mixed and deciduous woodlands, particularly in the north and west. Protected areas include the Mordovian State Nature Reserve and the Smolny National Park, which preserve regional biodiversity.\n\n## Climate\n\nMordovia experiences a moderate continental climate. This climate is characterized by cold, snowy winters and warm, relatively humid summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is approximately minus eleven degrees Celsius. In July, the warmest month, the average temperature is around nineteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 450 and 500 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the warmer months of late spring and summer. Snow cover typically persists from late November until April.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Mordovia is diverse, relying on both industrial manufacturing and agriculture. The administrative center, Saransk, is the primary economic and industrial hub. It is historically known as a major center for the electrical engineering and lighting industries, housing large production facilities. Other key industries in the republic include machine building, chemical manufacturing, metalworking, and food processing. Ruzayevka, the second-largest town, serves as a vital regional railway junction connecting central Russia with the Urals and Siberia. Kovylkino is another notable town, functioning as a local agricultural and manufacturing center. Agriculture in Mordovia focuses on the cultivation of grains, sugar beets, and fodder crops, alongside dairy and beef cattle farming.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous population of the region consists of the Mordvins, a Finno-Ugric people divided into two distinct linguistic and cultural subgroups, the Erzya and the Moksha. Russian settlement in the area began around the twelfth century, leading to the gradual integration of Mordovian lands into the Russian state. During the Soviet period, the Mordovian Autonomous Oblast was established in 1930, which was later upgraded to an Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic in 1934. Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, it became the Republic of Mordovia in 1994. Cultural heritage is preserved through traditional crafts, including wood carving and intricate embroidery, as well as the promotion of the Erzya and Moksha languages alongside Russian.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Republic\n* Administrative center: Saransk\n* Approximate area: 26,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 780,000\n* Largest city: Saransk\n* Signature features: Traditional homeland of the Erzya and Moksha Finno-Ugric peoples, and home to the Smolny National Park.",
    "summary": "The Republic of Mordovia is a landlocked federal subject of Russia located in the eastern East European Plain, bordered by regions such as Nizhny Novgorod and Penza. Its capital and largest city is Saransk, which serves as a major industrial hub alongside the key railway junction of Ruzayevka. The republic is culturally significant as the historic homeland of the Finno-Ugric Erzya and Moksha peoples.",
