    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nZabaykalsky Krai is a federal subject of Russia located in the southeastern part of Siberia, classified administratively as part of the Far Eastern Federal District. The krai shares international borders with Mongolia to the south and China to the southeast. Within Russia, it is bordered by the Republic of Buryatia to the west, Irkutsk Oblast to the northwest, the Sakha Republic (Yakutia) to the north, and Amur Oblast to the east. This strategic border position makes the region a critical transit corridor between Russia and East Asian nations. The territory is entirely landlocked and lies east of Lake Baikal, which gives the region its historical name of Transbaikal.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Zabaykalsky Krai is predominantly mountainous, characterized by alternating mountain ranges and deep basins. The Yablonovy Range runs through the territory from southwest to northeast, serving as a major drainage divide between the Arctic and Pacific oceans. Other significant mountain chains include the Chersky Range and the southern edges of the Stanovoy Highlands in the north. The region is drained by an extensive network of rivers. The Shilka and Argun rivers flow through the krai and merge on its eastern border to form the Amur River, one of the longest rivers in Asia. Other major rivers include the Onon, the Ingoda, and the Vitim, which is a tributary of the Lena River. The landscape features extensive taiga forests in the north and mountainous steppe areas in the south.\n\n## Climate\n\nZabaykalsky Krai experiences a harsh, sharply continental climate with subarctic characteristics in the northern mountainous areas. Winters are exceptionally long, dry, and cold, dominated by the influence of the Siberian High. Average January temperatures frequently drop below minus thirty degrees Celsius. Summers are short but can be relatively warm, with July temperatures averaging around twenty degrees Celsius in the valleys. Precipitation is light to moderate, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the brief summer months. The region is also characterized by high levels of annual sunshine, despite the extreme winter cold.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Zabaykalsky Krai relies heavily on mining and heavy industry. The region possesses vast mineral reserves, including significant deposits of copper, uranium, gold, coal, lead, and zinc. The Udokan copper deposit is one of the largest undeveloped copper reserves in the world. Krasnokamensk is a major center for uranium mining, hosting the largest uranium mine in Russia. The administrative center and largest city is Chita, which serves as a major industrial and transportation hub. The Trans-Siberian Railway and the Baikal-Amur Mainline both traverse the krai, facilitating the transport of raw materials and goods. Agriculture is concentrated in the southern steppe regions, focusing on sheep breeding, cattle farming, and grain cultivation.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous population of the region includes the Buryats and the Evenks, who historically practiced nomadic pastoralism and hunting. Russian exploration and settlement began in the mid seventeenth century when Cossack expeditions, led by figures such as Pyotr Beketov, established early forts including Chita in 1653. The region became a prominent place of political exile during the Tsarist era, most notably hosting the Decembrists after their failed uprising in 1825. In the early twentieth century, the territory briefly formed part of the Far Eastern Republic before integration into the Soviet Union. The modern Zabaykalsky Krai was established on March 1, 2008, following a merger of Chita Oblast and the Aginsky Buryat Autonomous Okrug.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Krai\n* Administrative center: Chita\n* Approximate area: 431,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,000,000\n* Largest city: Chita\n* Signature features: The confluence of the Shilka and Argun rivers to form the Amur River, and the massive Udokan copper deposit.",
    "summary": "Zabaykalsky Krai is a mountainous federal subject of Russia located in southeastern Siberia along the borders of Mongolia and China. The region features a harsh continental climate and is defined by major physical features like the Yablonovy Range and the headwaters of the Amur River. Its economy is driven by mining, particularly of copper and uranium, with Chita serving as its administrative and transportation center.",
