    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nStavropol Krai is located in the southwestern part of the Russian Federation, in the northern Caucasus region. It is part of the North Caucasian Federal District. The krai shares borders with Rostov Oblast, the Republic of Kalmykia, the Republic of Dagestan, the Chechen Republic, the Republic of Ingushetia, the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic, the Karachay-Cherkess Republic, and Krasnodar Krai. This central position in Ciscaucasia makes it a vital transport corridor linking European Russia with the Caucasus. The region's administrative status within the Russian Federation is undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Stavropol Krai transitions from flat plains to rolling hills. The central part is dominated by the Stavropol Upland, a plateau rising over 800 meters. To the east, the terrain descends into the semi-desert Caspian Depression, while the southern border rises toward the Greater Caucasus foothills. The region is drained by the Kuban, Kuma, and Manych rivers. While landlocked, it is situated between the Black and Caspian seas. The region is famous for its mineral spring waters in the Caucasus Mineral Waters area, which features unique volcanic hills like Mount Beshtau.\n\n## Climate\n\nStavropol Krai experiences a temperate continental climate. Winters are moderately cold, with average January temperatures around minus five degrees Celsius in the plains. Summers are warm, with average July temperatures exceeding twenty-four degrees Celsius in the eastern lowlands. Precipitation is unevenly distributed. The western and southern areas receive up to 800 millimeters of annual rainfall, supporting agriculture, whereas the eastern plains receive less than 300 millimeters, resulting in semi-desert landscapes. Dry winds are common during summer in the east.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Stavropol Krai is diversified, led by agriculture and food processing. The region is one of Russia's primary grain producers, cultivating winter wheat, barley, and sunflowers. Livestock breeding, particularly sheep farming, is also highly developed. Industrial activities include chemical manufacturing and machine building. The administrative center is Stavropol. Other major cities include Pyatigorsk, Kislovodsk, Yessentuki, and Zheleznovodsk, which form the Caucasus Mineral Waters resort agglomeration. This area is a major center for health tourism and mineral water bottling. Nevinnomyssk is a key industrial city known for chemical production.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe territory of Stavropol Krai was historically inhabited by nomadic tribes, including the Scythians and Alans. Russian settlement accelerated in the late eighteenth century following the construction of the Azov-Mozdok defense line, including the Stavropol fortress in 1777. The region became a crucial imperial outpost during the Caucasus War. In the nineteenth century, the Caucasus Mineral Waters region developed into a fashionable resort area frequented by writers like Mikhail Lermontov. Today, the krai is a multicultural region where Russian traditions coexist with neighboring Caucasian cultures.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Krai\n* Administrative center: Stavropol\n* Approximate area: 66,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,900,000 residents\n* Largest city if different from the administrative center: Stavropol is the largest city.\n* Signature features: The Caucasus Mineral Waters resort region and the Stavropol Upland.",
    "summary": "Stavropol Krai is a federal subject of Russia located in the northern Caucasus region, characterized by a diverse landscape that transitions from the Stavropol Upland to semi-desert plains. The region is a major agricultural hub, famous for grain production, and is internationally renowned for the Caucasus Mineral Waters spa resort area. Its administrative center is the city of Stavropol, which serves as a key cultural and economic hub in southwestern Russia.",
