    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nBelgorod Oblast is located in the southwestern part of the European territory of the Russian Federation. It lies along the southern edge of the Central Russian Upland. The oblast shares an international border with Ukraine to the south and west, specifically bordering the Kharkiv, Luhansk, and Sumy regions of Ukraine. Due to its position on this international boundary, the region has experienced significant military activity and cross-border security tensions since 2022. Domestically, Belgorod Oblast shares borders with Kursk Oblast to the north and northwest, and Voronezh Oblast to the east. The administrative center of the region is the city of Belgorod, which is situated approximately 700 kilometers south of Moscow.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Belgorod Oblast is characterized by a hilly, rolling plain dissected by numerous river valleys, ravines, and gullies. It sits entirely within the Central Russian Upland, with elevations ranging from about 100 to 270 meters above sea level. The region is highly valued for its fertile soils, predominantly deep chernozem, or black earth, which covers over 70 percent of the territory. The river network belongs to the basins of the Don and Dnieper rivers. Major rivers flowing through the oblast include the Seversky Donets, the Oskol, the Vorskla, and the Tikhaya Sosna. Natural vegetation consists of a mix of forest-steppe zones, though much of the original steppe has been converted into agricultural fields. Deciduous forests, featuring oak, ash, and maple, cover about 10 percent of the total area.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a moderate continental climate, characterized by relatively mild winters and warm, long summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is approximately minus eight degrees Celsius, while the average temperature in July, the warmest month, is about twenty degrees Celsius. The frost-free period typically lasts for about 150 to 160 days per year. Annual precipitation averages between 500 and 600 millimeters, with the western parts of the oblast receiving slightly more rainfall than the eastern districts. Most precipitation occurs during the summer months in the form of rain showers, while winter snow cover persists for about three months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Belgorod Oblast is highly developed, driven by both heavy industry and intensive agriculture. The region contains a significant portion of the Kursk Magnetic Anomaly, which is one of the largest iron ore basins in the world. Major mining and metallurgical enterprises operate here, including the Lebedinsky mining and processing plant in Gubkin and the Oskol electrometallurgical plant in Stary Oskol. Agriculture is another major economic pillar, with the oblast ranking among Russia's top producers of meat, poultry, sugar beets, sunflower oil, and grain. The administrative center, Belgorod, serves as the primary educational, cultural, and administrative hub. Other major urban centers include Stary Oskol, an important industrial city, Gubkin, a major mining town, and Shebekino.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the territory of modern Belgorod Oblast was part of the Wild Fields, a sparsely populated region prone to raids by nomadic tribes. In the 17th century, the Russian Tsardom constructed the Belgorod Defensive Line, a massive system of fortifications and fortresses, to secure its southern borders. During World War II, the region was the site of fierce combat between Soviet and German forces. The village of Prokhorovka, located in the northern part of the oblast, was the site of one of the largest tank battles in military history during the Battle of Kursk in July 1943. Today, the Prokhorovka Field State Military-Historical Museum-Reserve serves as a major cultural and historical landmark.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Belgorod\n* Approximate area: 27,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,500,000\n* Largest city: Belgorod\n* Signature features: The Kursk Magnetic Anomaly iron ore deposits and the Prokhorovka World War II battlefield.",
