    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nArkhangelsk Oblast is situated in the northern region of European Russia. It occupies a strategic position along the shores of the White Sea, the Barents Sea, and the Kara Sea, which are marginal seas of the Arctic Ocean. The oblast shares land borders with the Republic of Karelia to the west, Vologda Oblast to the south, Kirov Oblast to the southeast, and the Komi Republic to the east. Additionally, the Nenets Autonomous Okrug is an autonomous entity that is administratively subordinated to Arkhangelsk Oblast, though it is also recognized as a separate federal subject of Russia. The oblast also encompasses several major Arctic archipelagos, including Franz Josef Land and Novaya Zemlya.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Arkhangelsk Oblast is primarily characterized by flat to gently rolling plains, which form part of the larger East European Plain. The landscape is interrupted by low mountain ridges, such as the Timan Ridge in the east and the Vetreny Belt hills in the west. The region is heavily forested, with boreal coniferous forests, or taiga, covering the majority of the territory, while the northernmost coastal areas and Arctic islands feature tundra vegetation. The oblast is drained by an extensive network of rivers. The most prominent of these is the Northern Dvina River, which flows into the White Sea at Arkhangelsk. Other major rivers include the Onega, the Mezen, and the Pechora, the latter of which flows through the Nenets Autonomous Okrug. The territory also contains numerous lakes, such as Lake Lacha and Lake Kozhozero, as well as vast peat bogs. Protected areas include Kenozersky National Park and the Russian Arctic National Park.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Arkhangelsk Oblast is predominantly subarctic, characterized by long, cold winters and short, cool summers. The northern coast and the Arctic islands experience a polar tundra climate. Average January temperatures range from minus twelve degrees Celsius in the southwest to minus eighteen degrees Celsius in the northeast. Summers are brief, with average July temperatures hovering around fifteen degrees Celsius in the south, while the northern islands remain much colder. Annual precipitation is moderate, typically ranging from four hundred to six hundred millimeters, with the majority falling during the summer and autumn months. Snow cover persists for up to two hundred days a year in the northern districts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Arkhangelsk Oblast is heavily reliant on its abundant natural resources. Forestry, timber processing, and the production of pulp and paper are major industrial sectors, with large mills operating in cities like Novodvinsk and Koryazhma. Shipbuilding and marine engineering are also critical, centered primarily in the city of Severodvinsk, which serves as a major base for the construction and repair of nuclear submarines. Mining activities focus on bauxite, diamonds, and gypsum. The Plesetsk Cosmodrome, located near the town of Mirny, is one of the busiest spaceports in the world. Arkhangelsk is the administrative center and largest city, serving as a vital seaport and cultural hub. Other significant urban centers include Kotlas, a major railway junction, and Severodvinsk.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by Finno-Ugric tribes before Slavic settlers, known as Pomors, arrived from the Novgorod region during the twelfth century. The Pomors developed a distinct maritime culture based on fishing, sealing, and Arctic navigation. Arkhangelsk was founded in 1584 and served as Russia's primary international seaport until the establishment of Saint Petersburg in 1703. The region is rich in cultural heritage, exemplified by the wooden architecture of Kenozersky National Park and the historic Solovetsky Monastery on the Solovetsky Islands. This monastery, a UNESCO World Heritage site, was also the site of one of the earliest Soviet Gulag labor camps.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Arkhangelsk\n* Approximate area: 589,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,100,000 residents\n* Largest city: Arkhangelsk\n* Signature features: Solovetsky Monastery, Plesetsk Cosmodrome, and the Franz Josef Land archipelago",
