    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nPerm Krai is located in the eastern portion of European Russia, situated primarily within the Ural region. It is administratively part of the Volga Federal District. The krai shares borders with five other federal subjects of the Russian Federation. It is bordered by the Komi Republic to the north and northwest, Kirov Oblast to the west, the Udmurt Republic to the southwest, the Republic of Bashkortostan to the south, and Sverdlovsk Oblast to the east. The region occupies a strategic position connecting the European and Asian parts of Russia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Perm Krai is characterized by its transition from the East European Plain to the Ural Mountains. The western slopes of the Middle and Northern Ural Mountains define the eastern border of the krai. The highest elevation in the region is Mount Tulymsky Kamen, which reaches 1,496 meters above sea level. Over 70 percent of the krai is covered by dense coniferous taiga forests. The region is drained by an extensive network of rivers belonging to the Volga River basin. The Kama River is the primary waterway, flowing from north to south and hosting major reservoirs such as the Kama and Votkinsk reservoirs. Significant tributaries include the Chusovaya, Sylva, and Vishera rivers. Perm Krai is also famous for its karst topography, exemplified by the Kungur Ice Cave, which features extensive gypsum passages and underground lakes.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a moderate continental climate, characterized by long, snowy winters and relatively short, warm summers. Due to the influence of the Ural Mountains, weather patterns can vary significantly between the western lowlands and the eastern highlands. Average January temperatures range from minus 15 degrees Celsius in the south to minus 18 degrees Celsius in the north. Average July temperatures range from 15 degrees Celsius in the north to 18 degrees Celsius in the south. The eastern mountainous areas receive higher levels of annual precipitation, often exceeding 800 millimeters, compared to the western plains which receive around 600 millimeters.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nPerm Krai is a highly developed industrial region. It possesses abundant natural resources, including petroleum, coal, timber, and mineral salts. The Verkhnekamskoye deposit is one of the largest potash salt deposits in the world, supporting massive chemical and fertilizer industries. Major economic sectors include oil extraction, petrochemical processing, metallurgy, and mechanical engineering. Perm, the administrative center and largest city, is a major industrial, scientific, and cultural hub located on the Trans-Siberian Railway. Other significant industrial cities include Berezniki and Solikamsk, both of which are major centers for potash mining and chemical production.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the area was inhabited by Permic-speaking peoples, including the Komi-Permyaks. Russian expansion into the region accelerated during the 15th and 16th centuries, largely driven by the Stroganov merchant family who established profitable saltworks in Solikamsk. The city of Perm was founded in 1723 as a copper smelting settlement. In 1841, Scottish geologist Roderick Murchison named the Permian geological period after studying the rock strata of this region. Culturally, the krai is renowned for the Permian wooden sculptures preserved in the Perm State Art Gallery, which blend Christian iconography with local pagan traditions.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Krai\n* Administrative center: Perm\n* Approximate area: 160,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.5 million\n* Largest city: Perm\n* Signature features: The Kungur Ice Cave and the world-class Verkhnekamskoye potash deposit.",
