    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nAstrakhan Oblast is located in the southern part of European Russia, within the Southern Federal District. It occupies a strategic position along the lower reaches of the Volga River and its delta at the northern coast of the Caspian Sea. The oblast shares international borders with Kazakhstan to the east. Domestically, it borders Volgograd Oblast to the north and northwest, and the Republic of Kalmykia to the west. Because of its position at the crossroads of Europe and Asia, the region has historically served as an important transit corridor for trade routes connecting Russia with Central Asia and Iran.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Astrakhan Oblast is predominantly flat, as the region lies entirely within the Caspian Depression. A significant portion of the territory, particularly in the south near the Caspian Sea, lies below sea level. The defining geographical feature is the Volga River, which splits into hundreds of branches to form the massive Volga Delta. This delta is one of the largest inland river deltas in the world and is designated as a biosphere reserve to protect its unique wetlands and migratory bird populations. To the east of the Volga lies the Akhtuba River, which runs parallel to the main channel. Notable landforms include Lake Baskunchak, a highly saline lake that supplies a large portion of Russia's salt, and Mount Bolshoye Bogdo, a red sandstone salt dome that represents the highest point in the oblast at roughly 150 meters above sea level.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a dry, temperate continental climate with strong semi-arid characteristics. Summers are hot and dry, with average July temperatures often exceeding 25 degrees Celsius. Winters are cold but relatively dry, with light and inconsistent snow cover. January temperatures average around minus 5 to minus 10 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is sparse throughout the year, averaging between 150 and 300 millimeters annually, with high evaporation rates contributing to the arid conditions of the surrounding steppes.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Astrakhan Oblast is tied to its natural resources and geographic position. The extraction of hydrocarbons, particularly natural gas and sulfur from the Astrakhan gas field, is a primary industrial driver. Salt mining at Lake Baskunchak provides a significant share of national salt production. Historically famous for sturgeon fisheries, the fishing industry remains active under strict regulations to preserve endangered species. Agriculture is highly developed in the fertile Volga-Ahtuba floodplain, famous for Astrakhan watermelons. The administrative center and largest city is Astrakhan, which serves as a major river and seaport. Other notable urban centers include Akhtubinsk, which hosts a military aviation test center, and Znamensk, a closed town associated with the Kapustin Yar rocket range.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe region has a rich history shaped by various nomadic empires. It was once a core territory of the Khazar Khaganate and later the Golden Horde. Following the collapse of the Golden Horde, the independent Astrakhan Khanate emerged in the fifteenth century. Tsar Ivan the Terrible conquered the khanate in 1556, incorporating the territory into the Russian state. The Astrakhan Kremlin, constructed in the late sixteenth century, stands as a symbol of this historical transition. Today, the oblast is characterized by high ethnic diversity, with significant populations of Russians, Kazakhs, and Tatars, reflecting its historical role as a cultural crossroads.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Astrakhan\n* Approximate area: 44,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 950,000\n* Largest city: Astrakhan (same as administrative center)\n* Signature features: The Volga Delta, which is the largest river delta in Europe, and Lake Baskunchak, a major source of industrial salt.",
    "summary": "Astrakhan Oblast is a southern Russian federal subject situated in the Caspian Depression around the massive Volga River Delta. Bordering Kazakhstan and the Caspian Sea, the region features a dry continental climate, flat semi-desert landscapes, and a diverse population. Its economy is driven by natural gas extraction, salt mining at Lake Baskunchak, agriculture, and transport logistics centered in its administrative capital, Astrakhan.",
