    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nChelyabinsk Oblast is located on the border of Europe and Asia, primarily on the eastern slopes of the Southern Ural Mountains and the West Siberian Plain. It is a first-level federal subject of the Russian Federation, situated within the Ural Federal District. The oblast shares an international border with Kazakhstan to the south and southeast. Domestically, it is bordered by the Republic of Bashkortostan to the west, Sverdlovsk Oblast to the north, and Kurgan Oblast to the east. This geographic position makes the region a critical transit corridor connecting European Russia with Siberia.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Chelyabinsk Oblast is divided between the mountainous west and the flat lowlands of the east. The Southern Ural Mountains dominate the western section, with peaks such as Mount Nurgush reaching over 1,400 meters. This mountainous zone contains several protected areas, including Taganay National Park and Zyuratkul National Park. East of the mountains, the terrain transitions into the West Siberian Plain, characterized by forest-steppe landscapes. The region contains thousands of lakes, with Lake Turgoyak and Lake Uvildy being renowned for their water clarity. Major rivers flowing through the oblast include the Miass River, the Uy River, and the upper reaches of the Ural River.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a temperate continental climate, characterized by long, cold winters and warm summers. The Ural Mountains act as a climatic barrier, causing differences in precipitation between the western and eastern parts of the region. January temperatures average between minus 15 and minus 18 degrees Celsius, though extreme winter cold can drop temperatures below minus 40 degrees Celsius. July temperatures average between 18 and 20 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation varies, ranging from up to 800 millimeters in the mountainous western areas to approximately 350 millimeters in the eastern steppes.\n\n## Economy & cities\nChelyabinsk Oblast is one of the most heavily industrialized regions in Russia. Metallurgy is the backbone of the local economy, dominated by massive enterprises such as the Magnitogorsk Iron and Steel Works, which is one of the largest steel producers in the country. The administrative center, Chelyabinsk, is a major industrial hub focusing on metallurgy, tractor manufacturing, and metalworking. Other significant industrial cities include Magnitogorsk, Miass, which produces heavy trucks, and Zlatoust, famous for its historic steel engraving. Beyond heavy industry, the southern steppe regions support agriculture, primarily grain farming.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a rich history dating back to the Bronze Age. It is home to Arkaim, an ancient fortified settlement of the Sintashta culture dating to the second millennium BCE. Russian colonization began in earnest during the 18th century with the establishment of fortresses, including Chelyabinsk in 1736, to secure trade routes and exploit mineral resources. During World War II, the region played a pivotal role as a major industrial center. Numerous factories were evacuated here from the western Soviet Union, earning Chelyabinsk the nickname Tankograd due to its massive tank production. In February 2013, the region gained global attention when a meteor exploded in the atmosphere over Chelyabinsk.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Chelyabinsk\n* Approximate area: 88,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 3.4 million\n* Largest city: Chelyabinsk\n* Signature features: The ancient Arkaim archaeological site and the 2013 Chelyabinsk meteor impact event.",
    "summary": "Chelyabinsk Oblast is a highly industrialized Russian region situated on the border of Europe and Asia along the Southern Ural Mountains. Known for its massive metallurgical industries in cities like Chelyabinsk and Magnitogorsk, the oblast also features diverse landscapes ranging from mountain national parks to steppe lakes. It is historically significant for its ancient Bronze Age sites like Arkaim and its role as a major Soviet manufacturing hub during World War II.",
