    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKemerovo Oblast, also commonly referred to as Kuzbass, is located in the southern part of Western Siberia, Russia. It lies within the Asian portion of the Russian Federation. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. It is bordered by Tomsk Oblast to the north, Krasnoyarsk Krai and the Republic of Khakassia to the east, the Altai Republic to the south, and Altai Krai and Novosibirsk Oblast to the west. Its position places it at the intersection of major Siberian transit routes, making it a critical geographic and economic link in the region.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Kemerovo Oblast is highly diverse, characterized by a central depression surrounded by mountainous terrain. The central region is dominated by the Kuznetsk Basin, a vast low-lying area. This basin is flanked by the Salair Ridge to the west and the Kuznetsk Alatau mountain range to the east. To the south, the region rises into the scenic Gornaya Shoria highlands. The oblast is entirely landlocked and does not possess any coastline. The primary hydrological network is defined by the Tom River, which flows from south to north through the oblast and serves as a major tributary of the Ob River. Other significant rivers include the Inya, the Kiya, and the Yaya. The Kuznetsk Alatau Nature Reserve protects large tracts of pristine coniferous forests and alpine ecosystems in the eastern mountains.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a continental climate, characterized by long, cold winters and short, warm summers. Because of its inland location, temperature variations between seasons are extreme. Average January temperatures range from minus 17 to minus 20 degrees Celsius, while average July temperatures range from 17 to 20 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is unevenly distributed, with the mountainous regions receiving significantly more snowfall and rain than the low-lying Kuznetsk Basin. Snow cover typically persists from late October until April, influencing local agriculture and transportation.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kemerovo Oblast is heavily industrialized and revolves around the extraction of natural resources. The Kuznetsk Coal Basin, or Kuzbass, is one of the largest coal-mining areas in the world, containing vast reserves of high-quality bituminous and coking coal. In addition to coal mining, the region is a major hub for heavy metallurgy, chemical manufacturing, and machine building. Novokuznetsk is the primary center for steel and aluminum production, while the administrative center of Kemerovo hosts large chemical and manufacturing plants. Unlike many Russian oblasts where the administrative center is the undisputed urban giant, Kemerovo and Novokuznetsk are comparable in size, creating a dual-core urban structure.\n\n## History & culture\n\nBefore Russian settlement, the region was inhabited by indigenous Siberian groups, including the Shors and the Teleuts, who still maintain distinct cultural communities in the southern highlands. Russian exploration and colonization began in the early 17th century, leading to the establishment of Kuznetsk in 1618. The discovery of coal deposits by explorer Mikhailo Volkov in 1721 laid the foundation for the region's industrial future. During the Soviet era, the Ural-Kuznetsk Combine project accelerated industrialization, transforming the area into a vital metallurgical base. Kemerovo Oblast was officially established as a separate administrative unit in 1943, during World War II, to optimize coal and steel production for the war effort.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kemerovo\n* Approximate area: 95,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,600,000\n* Largest city: Novokuznetsk\n* Signature features: Kuznetsk Coal Basin (Kuzbass), Kuznetsk Alatau mountains",
    "summary": "Kemerovo Oblast, also known as Kuzbass, is a highly industrialized region in southwestern Siberia, Russia, defined by the Kuznetsk Basin and surrounding mountain ranges. The oblast is a global hub for coal mining and metallurgy, centered around the major urban hubs of Kemerovo and Novokuznetsk. It features a continental climate and a rich history of industrial development dating back to the early eighteenth century.",
