    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nIvanovo Oblast is a first-level federal subject of the Russian Federation, situated in the European part of the country. It is positioned within the Central Federal District. The oblast is one of the smallest administrative territories in Russia by land area. It shares borders with Yaroslavl Oblast to the northwest, Kostroma Oblast to the north, Nizhny Novgorod Oblast to the east, and Vladimir Oblast to the south. The region is highly integrated into the transport and economic networks of Central Russia, lying relatively close to the Moscow metropolitan area, which is located approximately 250 kilometers to the southwest.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Ivanovo Oblast is predominantly flat, characteristic of the East European Plain. The landscape consists of low-lying plains and gently rolling hills, with the highest elevations located in the north and west. The region is well-watered, featuring an extensive network of rivers and lakes. The Volga River is the most significant waterway, traversing the northern section of the oblast. The construction of the Gorky Hydroelectric Station created the Gorky Reservoir on the Volga, which serves as a major geographical feature and transport route. Other prominent rivers include the Klyazma, which flows along the southern border, and its tributaries, the Teza and the Nerl. Forests cover nearly half of the oblast's territory, dominated by mixed coniferous and deciduous species, particularly birch, pine, and spruce. Peat bogs are also common in the low-lying areas.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a temperate continental climate, characterized by cold, snowy winters and warm, relatively short summers. January is the coldest month, with average temperatures hovering around minus twelve degrees Celsius. Snow cover typically persists from late November through April. July is the warmest month, with average temperatures of approximately eighteen degrees Celsius. The average annual precipitation ranges between 550 and 650 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nHistorically, Ivanovo Oblast has been the primary center of the Russian textile industry, earning the administrative center the nickname of the 'Russian Manchester'. The economy remains heavily reliant on light industry, particularly cotton weaving, textile machinery manufacturing, and chemical production related to fabric processing. In recent decades, the region has sought to diversify into food processing, wood processing, and tourism. Ivanovo is the administrative center and largest city, housing more than forty percent of the oblast's population. Kineshma, situated on the banks of the Volga River, is the second-largest city and serves as an important industrial and port center. Other notable urban areas include Shuya, known for its historical manufacturing, and Teykovo, which hosts a major military installation.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe territory of Ivanovo Oblast has a rich cultural heritage tied to the development of the Russian state. During the medieval period, the region was part of the Vladimir-Suzdal Principality. In the nineteenth century, Ivanovo emerged as a rapid industrial hub, leading to significant social changes. The city of Ivanovo played a pivotal role in the Russian Revolution of 1905, where one of the first soviets, or workers' councils, was established. Culturally, the oblast is famous for its folk crafts. The town of Palekh is globally renowned for its traditional lacquer miniatures and icon painting. Additionally, the picturesque town of Plyos on the Volga River is celebrated as an artistic colony that inspired famous Russian landscape painters, including Isaac Levitan. Several towns in the oblast are included in the Golden Ring of Russia tourist route.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Ivanovo\n* Approximate area: 21,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 910,000\n* Largest city: Ivanovo\n* Signature features: Center of the Russian textile industry, home to the historic Golden Ring towns of Plyos and Palekh.",
    "summary": "Ivanovo Oblast is a compact federal subject of Russia located in the Central Federal District, bordered by Yaroslavl, Kostroma, Nizhny Novgorod, and Vladimir oblasts. The region is historically famous as the heart of the Russian textile industry and features a flat, forested landscape drained by the Volga and Klyazma rivers. It holds significant cultural value, containing historic Golden Ring destinations such as Plyos and the traditional lacquer art center of Palekh.",
