    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nKirov Oblast is situated in the northeastern portion of the European part of the Russian Federation. It is officially part of the Volga Federal District. The oblast shares borders with nine other federal subjects, making it one of the most connected regions in Russia. To the north, it borders Arkhangelsk Oblast and the Komi Republic. To the east, it is bounded by Perm Krai. To the south, it shares borders with the Udmurt Republic, the Republic of Tatarstan, and the Republic of Mari El. To the west and southwest, it borders Nizhny Novgorod Oblast, Kostroma Oblast, and Vologda Oblast. The region occupies a strategic position, bridging the central regions of European Russia with the Ural Mountains and Siberia.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Kirov Oblast is characterized by the rolling plains of the East European Plain. The landscape is dominated by wide, flat-topped hills and broad river valleys. In the northern part of the oblast, the Northern Uvals form a hilly watershed that separates the Volga River basin from the Northern Dvina basin. The Vyatka Uval runs through the central and southern parts of the region.\n\nThe river network is extensive, with the Vyatka River serving as the primary hydrological feature. The Vyatka flows for over one thousand kilometers, mostly within the oblast, before draining into the Kama River. Major tributaries of the Vyatka include the Cheptsa, Moloma, Kilmez, and Pizhma rivers. The Luza River flows through the far north, draining into the Sukhona. Forests cover more than sixty percent of the oblast, dominated by coniferous species such as spruce and pine, which transition to mixed forests in the south.\n\n## Climate\nKirov Oblast experiences a temperate continental climate. The region is characterized by long, cold, and snowy winters, followed by short, relatively warm summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from minus thirteen to minus fifteen degrees Celsius. July temperatures average around eighteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation varies between five hundred and seven hundred millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the warmer months. Snow cover typically persists from November through April, influencing local agriculture and forestry operations.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Kirov Oblast is diverse, with strong industrial and agricultural sectors. Forestry and woodworking are highly developed due to the abundant timber resources. The region is a major producer of lumber, plywood, and paper products. Chemical manufacturing is concentrated in Kirovo-Chepetsk, which produces mineral fertilizers and polymers. Mechanical engineering and metallurgy are also significant, with factories producing machine tools, aviation equipment, and agricultural machinery.\n\nKirov, the administrative center, is the largest city and the primary economic hub. Other major urban centers include Kirovo-Chepetsk, Vyatskiye Polyany, Slobodskoy, and Kotelnich. Agriculture focuses on dairy and beef cattle farming, as well as the cultivation of rye, oats, barley, and flax.\n\n## History & culture\nThe territory of Kirov Oblast was originally inhabited by Finno-Ugric peoples, including the Mari, Udmurt, and Komi. Russian settlement began in the late twelfth century, led by colonists from the Novgorod Republic. The settlement of Khlynov was established in 1374 and served as a regional stronghold. In 1489, the region was incorporated into the Grand Duchy of Moscow.\n\nKhlynov was renamed Vyatka in 1780 under Catherine the Great. In 1934, the city and the surrounding region were renamed Kirov in honor of the Soviet leader Sergey Kirov. Culturally, the region is famous for the Dymkovo toy, a traditional painted clay figurine that has been crafted in the area for over four hundred years. Vyatka lace is another traditional handicraft that remains a symbol of local heritage.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kirov\n* Approximate area: 120,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,130,000\n* Largest city: Kirov\n* Signature features: The Vyatka River basin and the traditional Dymkovo clay toy industry.",
    "summary": "Kirov Oblast is a landlocked Russian federal subject located in the northeastern European part of the country within the Volga Federal District. The region is characterized by the Vyatka River basin, extensive coniferous forests, and a temperate continental climate. Its economy relies heavily on forestry, chemical manufacturing, and machine building, while its cultural heritage is highlighted by the traditional Dymkovo clay toys.",
