    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKaliningrad Oblast is a unique federal subject of the Russian Federation because it is an exclave. It is geographically separated from the rest of Russia by other countries. It is situated on the Baltic Sea coast. It shares land borders with Poland to the south, specifically the Warmian-Masurian and Podlaskie Voivodeships, and Lithuania to the north and east, specifically the Klaipėda, Marijampolė, and Tauragė counties. To the west, it faces the Baltic Sea. The transit routes through neighboring countries are geopolitically sensitive, but the territory is internationally recognized as an integral part of the Russian Federation.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe landscape of Kaliningrad Oblast is predominantly low-lying and flat, characterized by rolling hills, marshy lowlands, and extensive coastal features. The highest point in the region is the Lysaya Hill, which reaches an elevation of just over 230 meters above sea level. The coastline features two major lagoon systems separated from the open Baltic Sea by narrow sand spits. The Curonian Spit, shared with Lithuania, separates the Curonian Lagoon from the Baltic Sea, while the Vistula Spit separates the Vistula Lagoon. The Curonian Spit is a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its massive drifting sand dunes and the Dancing Forest. The primary rivers draining the oblast are the Pregolya River, which flows into the Vistula Lagoon, and the Neman River, which forms part of the northern border with Lithuania.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe oblast experiences a transitional climate, shifting from maritime to temperate continental. Because of its proximity to the Baltic Sea, winters are relatively mild compared to mainland Russia, with average January temperatures hovering around minus 1.5 degrees Celsius. Summers are moderately warm and humid, with average July temperatures of approximately 18 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges from 700 to 800 millimeters, distributed relatively evenly throughout the year, though late summer and autumn tend to be the wettest seasons. Fog is a frequent occurrence, particularly in the coastal areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kaliningrad Oblast is highly distinct due to its Special Economic Zone status, which provides customs and tax relief to encourage manufacturing and assembly industries. The region is famous for holding over 90 percent of the world's known amber reserves, making amber mining and processing in the settlement of Yantarny a vital local industry. Other key economic sectors include shipbuilding, automotive assembly, food processing, and fishing. The administrative center and largest city is Kaliningrad, formerly known as Königsberg. Other significant urban centers include Sovetsk, located on the border with Lithuania, Chernyakhovsk, a major railway junction, and Baltiysk, which serves as the primary base of the Russian Navy's Baltic Fleet and is the westernmost town in Russia.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region was inhabited by Baltic tribes before being conquered by the Teutonic Knights in the thirteenth century. It subsequently became the core of the Duchy of Prussia and later East Prussia within the German Empire. Following the defeat of Nazi Germany in World War II, the northern portion of East Prussia was transferred to the Soviet Union under the Potsdam Agreement of 1945. The German population was expelled, and the territory was repopulated with Soviet citizens, primarily Russians and Belarusians. The city of Königsberg was renamed Kaliningrad in 1946 in honor of Soviet leader Mikhail Kalinin. The region contains significant architectural heritage, including the reconstructed fourteenth-century Königsberg Cathedral, which houses the tomb of the philosopher Immanuel Kant, who lived and worked in the city.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kaliningrad\n* Approximate area: 15,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,030,000 residents\n* Largest city: Kaliningrad\n* Signature features: The Curonian Spit UNESCO World Heritage site, the world's largest amber deposits, and its status as Russia's westernmost exclave on the Baltic Sea.",
    "summary": "Kaliningrad Oblast is a Russian exclave situated on the Baltic Sea, bordered by Poland and Lithuania. The region is characterized by flat coastal landscapes, including the UNESCO-listed Curonian Spit, and is home to the world's largest amber reserves. Its administrative center, Kaliningrad, was historically known as the German city of Königsberg before being transferred to the Soviet Union after World War II.",
