    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nKostroma Oblast is located in the northeastern part of European Russia. It is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, classified as an oblast, and is part of the Central Federal District. The oblast shares borders with five other Russian federal subjects. It is bordered by Vologda Oblast to the north, Kirov Oblast to the east, Nizhny Novgorod Oblast to the south, Ivanovo Oblast to the southwest, and Yaroslavl Oblast to the west. The administrative center of the oblast is the historic city of Kostroma, which lies approximately 340 kilometers northeast of Moscow.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Kostroma Oblast is situated within the northeastern portion of the East European Plain. The landscape is predominantly flat or gently rolling, characterized by morainic hills and lowlands. In the northern part of the oblast, the terrain rises slightly to form the Galich-Chukhloma Upland and the western spurs of the Northern Ridge, also known as Severnyye Uvaly. The region is heavily forested, with forests covering more than seventy percent of its territory, making it one of the most wooded areas in central European Russia. Coniferous species like spruce and pine dominate the northern taiga zones, while mixed forests of birch, aspen, and oak appear in the south. The primary hydrological feature is the Volga River, which traverses the southwestern corner of the oblast. Major tributaries flowing through the region include the Kostroma, Unzha, Vetluga, and Neya rivers. The oblast also contains several significant lakes, such as Lake Galichskoye and Lake Chukhlomskoye, as well as the massive Gorky Reservoir on the Volga.\n\n## Climate\nKostroma Oblast experiences a humid continental climate, classified as Dfb under the Köppen climate system. This climate is characterized by long, cold, and snowy winters, and relatively short, warm summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from minus eleven to minus fourteen degrees Celsius. July, the warmest month, has average temperatures ranging from seventeen to nineteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 550 and 650 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November until April, influencing the local hydrology and agricultural cycles.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Kostroma Oblast is heavily reliant on forestry, timber processing, and manufacturing. The abundance of woodland supports large-scale logging, pulp and paper production, and furniture manufacturing. Historically, the region has been a major center for the textile industry, particularly the processing of flax and the production of linen. The energy sector is also prominent, anchored by the Kostroma Power Station in the town of Volgorechensk, which is one of the largest thermal power plants in Europe. Agriculture focuses primarily on dairy farming, animal husbandry, and the cultivation of flax, rye, and fodder crops. The administrative center and largest city is Kostroma. Other significant urban centers include Sharya, a major railway junction and timber hub, Galich, Buy, and Nerekhta.\n\n## History & culture\nEstablished in its modern boundaries in 1944, the region has a deep historical heritage dating back to the medieval period. The city of Kostroma was founded in the twelfth century, traditionally attributed to Yuri Dolgorukiy in 1152. The region played a pivotal role in Russian history during the Time of Troubles. The Ipatiev Monastery in Kostroma is widely recognized as the cradle of the Romanov Dynasty, as it was here in 1613 that Mikhail Romanov was offered the Russian crown. The national hero Ivan Susanin, who sacrificed his life to save the young tsar from Polish forces, is a celebrated figure from this region. Today, Kostroma is an integral part of the Golden Ring of Russia, a famous tourist route showcasing ancient Russian cities and architectural monuments.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kostroma\n* Approximate area: 60,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 580,000\n* Largest city: Kostroma\n* Signature features: The Ipatiev Monastery, which is the historical cradle of the Romanov Dynasty, and a major role in the Russian linen and timber industries.",
    "summary": "Kostroma Oblast is a heavily forested federal subject of Russia located in the northeastern portion of the East European Plain. Traversed by the Volga River, the region is economically driven by forestry, timber processing, and linen production. It holds deep historical significance as a key part of the Golden Ring of Russia and the ancestral home of the Romanov Dynasty.",
