    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nIrkutsk Oblast is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, positioned in the southeastern portion of Siberia. It occupies a vast territory within the Angara and Lena river basins. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian subdivisions. To the west lies Krasnoyarsk Krai, while the Sakha Republic (Yakutia) borders it to the northeast. Zabaykalsky Krai is situated to the east, the Republic of Buryatia lies to the south and east, and the Tuva Republic borders the southwest. The region occupies a highly strategic position in Asian Russia, linking western Siberia with the Russian Far East.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Irkutsk Oblast is defined by diverse landscapes, ranging from flat plateaus to high mountain ranges. The Central Siberian Plateau dominates the northern and central portions of the oblast. In the south and southwest, the terrain rises into the Eastern Sayan Mountains, while the Baikal and Primorsky ranges run along the shores of Lake Baikal. Lake Baikal, the deepest and oldest freshwater lake in the world, forms a significant portion of the southeastern boundary. The Angara River, which is the sole outlet of Lake Baikal, flows northward through the oblast. Other major rivers include the Lena, which originates in the Baikal Mountains and flows north toward the Arctic Ocean, and the Nizhnyaya Tunguska.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a severe continental climate, classified largely as subarctic in the north and humid continental in the south. Winters are long, dark, and extremely cold, with average January temperatures dropping below minus twenty degrees Celsius. Summers are short but can be relatively warm, with July temperatures averaging around eighteen degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, with most rainfall occurring during the summer months. The presence of Lake Baikal exerts a moderating influence on the immediate coastal areas, making winters slightly milder and summers cooler compared to the interior. Permafrost is widespread, particularly in the northern and mountainous regions.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Irkutsk Oblast is heavily reliant on its abundant natural resources. Forestry and timber processing are major industries due to the extensive taiga forests. The region is a major producer of hydroelectricity, generated by a series of massive dams on the Angara River, including the Bratsk, Ust-Ilimsk, and Irkutsk stations. This cheap power supports energy-intensive industries such as aluminum smelting in Bratsk and Shelekhov. Mining is also critical, focusing on gold, coal, iron ore, and rock salt. The administrative center is Irkutsk, located near Lake Baikal. Other major industrial cities include Bratsk, Angarsk, and Ust-Ilimsk. The Trans-Siberian Railway runs through the southern part of the oblast, serving as a vital transport corridor.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by indigenous groups, including the Buryats and Evenks. Russian expansion into the area began in the seventeenth century, with the establishment of the Irkutsk fortress in 1661. Irkutsk quickly grew into a major trading post for furs and Chinese goods. During the nineteenth century, the region became a primary destination for political exiles, notably the Decembrists, who brought education, art, and science to the local community. This influx earned Irkutsk the nickname the Paris of Siberia. The twentieth century brought rapid industrialization and the construction of massive Soviet infrastructure projects.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Irkutsk\n* Approximate area: 767,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,300,000\n* Largest city: Irkutsk\n* Signature features: Lake Baikal shoreline, Angara River hydroelectric cascade, and historic Siberian wooden architecture.",
    "summary": "Irkutsk Oblast is a major administrative region in southeastern Siberia, bordered by Lake Baikal and characterized by vast taiga forests and mountain ranges. The region is an industrial powerhouse driven by massive hydroelectric dams on the Angara River, forestry, and mining. Its capital, Irkutsk, is a historic cultural hub on the Trans-Siberian Railway, famously shaped by nineteenth-century political exiles.",
