    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKurgan Oblast is located in the southern part of the West Siberian Plain, positioned within the Ural Federal District of the Russian Federation. It occupies a strategic geographical position, bordering several Russian oblasts and sharing an international border. To the south, the oblast shares a long international boundary with the Republic of Kazakhstan, specifically the Kostanay and North Kazakhstan regions. Domestically, it is bordered by Chelyabinsk Oblast to the west, Sverdlovsk Oblast to the northwest and north, and Tyumen Oblast to the northeast and east. There are no active territorial disputes regarding its political status.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe territory of Kurgan Oblast is almost entirely flat, characterized by the low-lying relief of the West Siberian Plain. The landscape transitions from forest-steppe in the north to steppe in the south. The region is drained by the Tobol River basin, which flows from south to north toward the Ob River. Major tributaries of the Tobol within the oblast include the Iset, Miass, and Ui rivers. Kurgan Oblast is notable for its high density of lakes, numbering over three thousand. Many of these lakes are saline or bitter-salt, containing therapeutic muds and mineral waters. The most famous of these is Lake Medvezhye, often compared to the Dead Sea due to its high salt concentration and buoyancy.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a classic continental climate, characterized by long, cold winters and warm, relatively short summers. The Ural Mountains to the west block warm Atlantic air masses, while the flat northern plains allow cold Arctic air to sweep southward across the territory. Average January temperatures range from minus sixteen to minus eighteen degrees Celsius. July temperatures average around nineteen to twenty degrees Celsius. Precipitation is relatively low, averaging between three hundred and four hundred millimeters annually, with the majority falling during the summer months. Droughts and late spring frosts are common agricultural hazards.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kurgan Oblast is divided between agriculture and heavy industry. Due to its fertile black soil, the region is a major agricultural producer in the Urals, specializing in spring wheat, rye, barley, and livestock farming. The industrial sector is concentrated in the larger urban centers. The administrative center, Kurgan, is home to Kurganmashzavod, the country's primary manufacturer of infantry fighting vehicles, including the BMP series. Other key industries include metalworking, chemical manufacturing, and pharmaceuticals. Shadrinsk is the second-largest city in the oblast, known for its motor radiator plant and food processing industries.\n\n## History & culture\n\nRussian settlement of the region began in the seventeenth century as pioneers moved eastward into Siberia. The city of Kurgan was founded in 1679 as Tsaryovo Gorodishche, meaning \"tsar's burial mound,\" named after a large ancient kurgan nearby. The region became a place of exile for political dissidents, including several Decembrists in the nineteenth century. Culturally, the oblast is renowned for the Russian Scientific Center for Restorative Traumatology and Orthopaedics, established by Dr. Gavriil Ilizarov. The Ilizarov apparatus, a device used to reshape or limb-lengthen bones, was invented and developed here, making Kurgan a global hub for orthopedic medicine.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kurgan\n* Approximate area: 71,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 760,000\n* Largest city: Kurgan\n* Signature features: The Ilizarov orthopedic center and the highly saline Lake Medvezhye.",
    "summary": "Kurgan Oblast is a first-level Russian administrative division located in the southern West Siberian Plain along the border with Kazakhstan. The region features a flat forest-steppe landscape drained by the Tobol River and is known for its numerous saline lakes, agricultural output, and heavy machinery manufacturing. Its capital, Kurgan, is globally recognized for its pioneering orthopedic medical center and defense industries.",
