    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nLipetsk Oblast is situated in the western part of the Russian Federation, within the Central Federal District. It lies in the European territory of Russia, approximately 370 kilometers south of Moscow. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. It is bordered by Ryazan Oblast to the north, Tambov Oblast to the east, Voronezh Oblast to the south, Kursk Oblast to the southwest, Oryol Oblast to the west, and Tula Oblast to the northwest. The region occupies a strategic position, connecting the central industrial areas of Russia with the southern agricultural regions.\n\n## Physical features\nThe territory of Lipetsk Oblast is located in the forest-steppe zone of the East European Plain. The landscape is divided into two distinct geographic areas. The western part of the oblast lies on the Central Russian Upland, which features a hilly, undulating terrain heavily dissected by ravines and gullies. The eastern part belongs to the Oka-Don Lowland, characterized by flat, low-lying plains. The region is drained by the Don River basin. The Don River flows through the western section of the oblast, while its major tributaries, such as the Voronezh River and the Bystraya Sosna, flow through other parts of the territory. The soils are exceptionally fertile, consisting primarily of rich black earth, or chernozem, which supports intensive agriculture.\n\n## Climate\nLipetsk Oblast experiences a moderate continental climate. Winters are moderately cold, with snow cover lasting from late November to late March. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is about minus 8 degrees Celsius. Summers are warm and relatively short, with an average July temperature of about 20 degrees Celsius. The average annual precipitation ranges between 500 and 550 millimeters, with the maximum rainfall occurring during the summer months in the form of heavy showers.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Lipetsk Oblast is highly developed and exhibits a balanced industrial-agrarian structure. The administrative center, Lipetsk, is a major industrial hub dominated by metallurgy. It is home to the Novolipetsk Steel company, which is one of the largest steel plants in Russia and a major global exporter. Other key industrial sectors include mechanical engineering, food processing, chemical manufacturing, and building materials. The city of Yelets is the second-largest urban center, known for its historic lace-making industry and machinery manufacturing. Agriculture is highly productive due to the fertile chernozem soils. Major agricultural products include wheat, barley, sugar beets, potatoes, and sunflowers, alongside developed dairy and poultry farming.\n\n## History & culture\nThe history of the region dates back to ancient times, with Yelets being first mentioned in historical chronicles in 1146. Lipetsk itself was founded in 1703 when Peter the Great ordered the construction of iron foundries to produce munitions for the Russian army and navy. In 1805, Lipetsk was recognized as a mineral spring resort, becoming one of the oldest spa destinations in Russia. The modern Lipetsk Oblast was officially created in 1954 from portions of neighboring Voronezh, Oryol, Ryazan, and Kursk oblasts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Lipetsk\n* Approximate area: 24,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.1 million people\n* Largest city: Lipetsk\n* Signature features: The massive Novolipetsk Steel plant and the historic mineral spa resort of Lipetsk.",
