    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nMagadan Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the northeastern part of the country. It is positioned within the Far Eastern Federal District. The oblast shares land borders with the Sakha Republic, also known as Yakutia, to the west and northwest, Chukotka Autonomous Okrug to the north, Kamchatka Krai to the east, and Khabarovsk Krai to the southwest. To the south, it is bounded by the Sea of Okhotsk, which connects the region to the Pacific Ocean. This coastal position provides the landlocked interior of northeastern Siberia with access to maritime trade routes, though ice limits navigation during winter.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Magadan Oblast is predominantly mountainous and rugged. The Kolyma Highlands dominate the central and eastern portions of the territory, while the eastern spurs of the Chersky Range extend into the western districts. These mountain systems are separated by deep river valleys and narrow coastal plains. The most significant hydrological feature is the Kolyma River, which originates in the mountains of the oblast and flows northward into the Arctic Ocean. Other notable rivers include the Ayan-Yuryakh and the Buyunda. The coastline along the Sea of Okhotsk is highly indented, featuring major geographic projections such as the Pyagin and Koni Peninsulas, which shelter Nagayev Bay. Vegetation transitions from dense coniferous taiga in the southern river valleys to moss and lichen tundra at higher elevations and northern latitudes.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a severe subarctic climate characterized by long, extremely cold winters and short, cool summers. Coastal areas, including the city of Magadan, benefit from a slight maritime moderation, resulting in milder winters but damper, foggier summers. In contrast, the interior continental zones suffer from extreme temperature drops. Winter temperatures in the interior regularly fall below minus forty degrees Celsius, while summer temperatures occasionally reach twenty-five degrees Celsius. Widespread continuous and discontinuous permafrost underlies almost the entire territory of the oblast, presenting significant challenges for construction and infrastructure development. Precipitation is relatively low, with most falling as snow during the autumn and early winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Magadan Oblast relies heavily on the extraction of natural resources, particularly precious metals. The region is one of the leading producers of gold and silver in Russia, with major mining operations concentrated in the Kolyma basin. Non-ferrous metallurgy, coal mining, and fishing along the Sea of Okhotsk also contribute significantly to the regional economy. The administrative center and largest city is Magadan, which serves as the primary transport hub, port, and cultural center. The port of Magadan in Nagayev Bay remains active year-round with the assistance of icebreakers. Other smaller urban settlements, such as Susuman and Sokol, function primarily as support centers for the gold mining industry or transport infrastructure.\n\n## History & culture\n\nPrior to Russian settlement, the territory was inhabited by indigenous Siberian peoples, including the Evens, Koryaks, and Yakuts, who engaged in reindeer herding and fishing. Russian exploration and integration began in the seventeenth century, but intensive development occurred only in the 1930s following the discovery of vast gold deposits. During the Soviet era, the region became infamous as the center of the Kolyma Gulag system, managed by the state trust Dalstroy. Forced laborers constructed the Kolyma Highway, often referred to as the Road of Bones, which connects Magadan with Yakutsk. Today, this tragic history is memorialized by the Mask of Sorrow, a large concrete monument overlooking Magadan, designed by sculptor Ernst Neizvestny.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Magadan\n* Approximate area: 462,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 134,000\n* Largest city: Magadan\n* Signature features: The Kolyma Highway (Road of Bones) and extensive gold mining operations in the Kolyma Highlands.",
    "summary": "Magadan Oblast is a mountainous federal subject in the Russian Far East known for its severe subarctic climate and rich deposits of gold and silver. The region's administrative center and primary port is Magadan, located on the Sea of Okhotsk. Historically significant as the center of the Soviet-era Kolyma Gulag system, the oblast today relies on mining, fishing, and maritime trade.",
