    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nMurmansk Oblast is located in the extreme northwestern part of Russia, situated almost entirely north of the Arctic Circle. It occupies the Kola Peninsula along with a portion of the mainland to the west and south. The oblast shares international borders with Norway to the northwest and Finland to the west. Domestically, it is bordered by the Republic of Karelia to the south. To the north, the oblast is bounded by the Barents Sea, while the White Sea washes its southern and eastern shores.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Murmansk Oblast is dominated by the Kola Peninsula, which features a diverse landscape of tundra, forest-tundra, and taiga. The central part of the peninsula contains the Khibiny Mountains and the Lovozero Massif. Yudychvumchorr, rising to approximately 1,200 meters, is the highest peak in the Khibiny range. The region is rich in water resources, containing tens of thousands of rivers and lakes. Major rivers include the Ponoy, Varzuga, Umba, Tuloma, and Niva. Lake Imandra is the largest lake in the oblast, followed by Lake Umbozero and Lake Lovozero. Protected natural areas include the Lapland Biosphere Reserve and the Pasvik Nature Reserve, which preserve pristine subarctic ecosystems and diverse wildlife.\n\n## Climate\nDespite its high latitude, the climate of Murmansk Oblast is surprisingly moderate compared to other polar regions. The northern coast is influenced by the warm Murman Current, a branch of the Gulf Stream, which keeps the Barents Sea coast and the port of Murmansk ice-free throughout the winter. The climate transitions from marine-subarctic in the north to moderate-monsoonal in the south. Winters are long and cold, but temperatures are mitigated by maritime air masses. Summers are short, cool, and damp. The region experiences the polar night from late November to mid-January and the polar day, or midnight sun, from late May to mid-July.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe administrative center of the oblast is Murmansk, which is the largest city in the world located north of the Arctic Circle. Other major urban centers include Apatity, Monchegorsk, Severomorsk, and Kandalaksha. The economy is heavily industrial, driven by mining and metallurgy. The region is a major global source of apatite, nepheline, iron ore, nickel, and copper. Severomorsk serves as the primary administrative headquarters for the Russian Northern Fleet, making the region highly strategic for national defense. Fishing is another vital industry, centered around the port of Murmansk. Energy is supplied by the Kola Nuclear Power Plant and several hydroelectric stations.\n\n## History & culture\nThe indigenous inhabitants of the Kola Peninsula are the Saami people, who have traditionally practiced reindeer herding and fishing. Beginning in the twelfth century, Russian settlers known as Pomors began colonizing the White Sea coast. The city of Murmansk was founded in 1916 under the name Romanov-on-Murman, making it the last city established in the Russian Empire. During World War II, Murmansk played a critical role as the primary destination for the Allied Arctic convoys, which delivered essential Lend-Lease supplies. The city withstood intense German bombardment and was later designated a Hero City of the Soviet Union.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Murmansk\n* Approximate area: 144,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 660,000\n* Largest city: Murmansk\n* Signature features: Ice-free Arctic port of Murmansk and the strategic headquarters of the Russian Northern Fleet.",
    "summary": "Murmansk Oblast is a highly strategic Russian region located almost entirely north of the Arctic Circle on the Kola Peninsula. It borders Finland and Norway and features an ice-free northern port on the Barents Sea due to the warming influence of the Gulf Stream. The region is economically vital for its rich mineral mining, fishing industries, and as the home base for the Russian Northern Fleet.",
