    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nKursk Oblast is situated in the western part of the Russian Federation, within the Central Federal District. It shares internal borders with Bryansk Oblast to the northwest, Oryol Oblast to the north, Lipetsk Oblast to the northeast, Voronezh Oblast to the east, and Belgorod Oblast to the south. To the west, the oblast shares an international border with Ukraine, specifically bordering the Sumy Oblast. Because of this international border, the region has been directly affected by the ongoing military conflict between Russia and Ukraine, experiencing cross-border shelling and military incursions.\n\n## Physical features\nThe territory of Kursk Oblast lies on the southern slopes of the Central Russian Upland. The landscape is characterized by a hilly, undulating plain dissected by numerous river valleys, ravines, and gullies. The average elevation ranges from 170 to 250 meters above sea level. The region is highly valued for its exceptionally fertile chernozem, or black earth, soils, which cover a vast majority of the oblast. The primary river system is the Seim River, which flows westward across the oblast before entering Ukraine to join the Desna River. Other notable rivers include the Psyol, the Tuskar, and the upper reaches of the Oskol River. There are no major natural lakes, but numerous artificial reservoirs and ponds exist.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a moderate humid continental climate, characterized by warm summers and relatively cold winters. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is approximately minus 8 degrees Celsius, while the average July temperature is about 20 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges from 500 to 600 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November or early December until late March.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Kursk Oblast is highly developed, relying on a mix of heavy industry, mining, energy production, and agriculture. The region is home to the Kursk Magnetic Anomaly, which is one of the largest iron ore basins in the world. The Mikhailovsky Mining and Processing Integrated Plant, located near the city of Zheleznogorsk, is a major contributor to the Russian steel industry. Energy is supplied by the Kursk Nuclear Power Plant, situated in the town of Kurchatov. Agriculture thrives on the fertile soil, producing wheat, sugar beets, potatoes, and sunflowers. The administrative center and largest city is Kursk. Other major urban centers include Zheleznogorsk, known for mining, and Kurchatov, known for power generation.\n\n## History & culture\nKursk is one of the oldest cities in Russia, first mentioned in historical chronicles in 1032. The region was part of Kievan Rus but suffered significant destruction during the Mongol invasions. In the seventeenth century, it became a key defensive outpost for the Tsardom of Russia. During World War II, the region was the site of the Battle of Kursk in July and August 1943, which remains the largest tank battle in history and a decisive Soviet victory. Culturally, the oblast is known for the Korennaya Pustyn monastery, a major pilgrimage site, and the historic town of Rylsk, which preserves eighteenth-century architecture.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kursk\n* Approximate area: 29,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,080,000 residents\n* Largest city: Kursk\n* Signature features: The Kursk Magnetic Anomaly, which is the largest magnetic anomaly on Earth, and the site of the historic 1943 Battle of Kursk.",
    "summary": "Kursk Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the western part of the country along the border with Ukraine. Situated on the fertile Central Russian Upland, the region is highly prominent for its agricultural output and the massive iron ore deposits of the Kursk Magnetic Anomaly. It is also historically significant as the site of the Battle of Kursk, the largest tank battle in history.",
