    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nKaluga Oblast is a first-level federal subject of the Russian Federation, situated in the central part of the European territory of the country. It is part of the Central Federal District. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. It is bounded by Moscow Oblast to the north and northeast, Tula Oblast to the east, Oryol Oblast to the south, Bryansk Oblast to the southwest, and Smolensk Oblast to the west and northwest. Its strategic location places it in close proximity to the Moscow metropolitan area, which heavily influences its economic and transport connections.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Kaluga Oblast is characterized by a hilly, undulating plain that forms part of the larger East European Plain. The territory is divided between two major upland regions. The southern and eastern portions of the oblast lie within the Central Russian Upland, while the western part is occupied by the Smolensk-Moscow Upland. The average elevation ranges from 150 to 270 meters above sea level.\nThe region has a well-developed river network belonging entirely to the Volga River basin. The Oka River is the primary waterway, flowing through the eastern and southern parts of the oblast. Major tributaries of the Oka within the region include the Ugra, Zhizdra, and Protva rivers. Forests cover approximately 45 percent of the oblast, consisting of mixed and broadleaf species such as birch, aspen, pine, and spruce. Ugra National Park, a UNESCO biosphere reserve, protects significant river valleys and forested landscapes.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a temperate continental climate, characterized by distinct seasonal variations. Winters are moderately cold and snowy, while summers are typically warm and humid. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from minus eight to minus ten degrees Celsius. July, the warmest month, has an average temperature of approximately eighteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges from 600 to 650 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November until early April.\n\n## Economy & cities\nKaluga Oblast possesses a highly developed industrial economy, often cited as one of the most economically successful regions in central Russia. The region has attracted significant foreign and domestic investment, particularly in its automotive manufacturing cluster located in and around the administrative center. Other major industries include machine building, metalworking, pharmaceuticals, food processing, and building materials.\nThe administrative center and largest city is Kaluga, situated on the banks of the Oka River. The second-largest city is Obninsk, which is recognized as Russia's first \"naukograd\" or science city. Obninsk is famous for being the site of the world's first civilian nuclear power plant, which began operations in 1954. Other notable urban centers include Lyudinovo, Kirov, and Maloyaroslavets.\n\n## History & culture\nThe territory of Kaluga Oblast has played a significant role in Russian history. In 1480, the Great Stand on the Ugra River occurred here, marking the end of the Great Horde's dominance over the Grand Duchy of Moscow. During the War of 1812, the Battle of Maloyaroslavets took place in the region, forcing Napoleon's army to retreat along the devastated Smolensk road.\nIn modern history, Kaluga is celebrated as the cradle of space exploration. Konstantin Tsiolkovsky, a pioneer of astronautics theory, lived and worked in Kaluga for several decades. The city houses the Tsiolkovsky State Museum of the History of Cosmonautics, the first museum of its kind in the world. Culturally, the region is also home to the Optina Monastery, an important spiritual center of the Russian Orthodox Church.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Kaluga\n* Approximate area: 29,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,000,000\n* Largest city: Kaluga\n* Signature features: Cradle of space exploration and home to Russia's first science city, Obninsk.",
    "summary": "Kaluga Oblast is a highly industrialized region in western Russia, bordering Moscow Oblast and situated within the East European Plain. It is historically significant as the cradle of Soviet space exploration theory and the site of the world's first civilian nuclear power plant in Obninsk. The oblast features a temperate continental climate and is drained by the Oka River basin.",
