    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nNovosibirsk Oblast is located in the southern part of the West Siberian Plain in Russia. It is situated within the Siberian Federal District. The oblast shares international borders with Kazakhstan to the southwest. Domestically, it is bordered by Omsk Oblast to the west, Tomsk Oblast to the north, Kemerovo Oblast to the east, and Altai Krai to the south. It occupies a strategic position as a transit corridor connecting European Russia with the Russian Far East and East Asia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Novosibirsk Oblast is predominantly flat or gently rolling, characteristic of the West Siberian Plain. The Vasyugan Swamp, one of the largest wetlands in the world, extends into the northern portion of the oblast. The southern region features the Baraba Steppe, a flat grassland interspersed with birch groves and numerous shallow, brackish lakes. The largest lake in the region is Lake Chany, a shallow, fluctuating saltwater lake that is ecologically significant for migratory birds. The primary river system is the Ob River, which flows from south to north through the eastern part of the oblast. The Ob is dammed near Novosibirsk to form the Novosibirsk Reservoir, often referred to locally as the Ob Sea.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a continental climate, characterized by long, cold winters and short, warm summers. Average January temperatures range from minus sixteen to minus twenty degrees Celsius, while average July temperatures range from eighteen to twenty degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, averaging between three hundred and five hundred millimeters annually, with the majority falling during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from November through April. The transitional seasons of spring and autumn are brief and marked by rapid temperature fluctuations.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe administrative center and largest city is Novosibirsk, which is also the third-most populous city in Russia. Other notable cities include Berdsk, Iskitim, and Kuybyshev. The economy is highly diversified. Unlike many Siberian regions, it does not rely solely on resource extraction. Instead, it features a strong industrial base focused on machine building, metalworking, food processing, and chemical production. Agriculture is also significant, particularly grain cultivation, dairy farming, and livestock breeding in the southern steppe areas. Additionally, the region is a major transportation hub, situated along the Trans-Siberian Railway and featuring Tolmachevo Airport, which connects Siberia to major international destinations.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe territory was originally inhabited by various Siberian indigenous groups, including the Siberian Tatars. Russian settlement accelerated in the late seventeenth and eighteenth centuries with the construction of defensive forts. The region experienced rapid development following the construction of the Trans-Siberian Railway in the late nineteenth century, which led to the founding of Novosibirsk in 1893. During the Soviet era, the oblast became a major industrial and scientific center. A key cultural and scientific landmark is Akademgorodok, founded in 1957. Located south of Novosibirsk, it is a world-renowned scientific research hub housing Novosibirsk State University and dozens of research institutes.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Novosibirsk\n* Approximate area: 178,200 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.8 million residents\n* Largest city: Novosibirsk\n* Signature features: The Trans-Siberian Railway junction, the scientific enclave of Akademgorodok, and Lake Chany.",
    "summary": "Novosibirsk Oblast is a key administrative and economic region located in the southern West Siberian Plain of Russia. It features a diverse landscape ranging from the Vasyugan Swamp to the Baraba Steppe, with the Ob River serving as its primary waterway. The region is highly industrialized, serves as a major transportation hub along the Trans-Siberian Railway, and is home to the famous scientific enclave of Akademgorodok.",
