    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nLeningrad Oblast is located in the northwestern part of the Russian Federation, within the Northwestern Federal District. The oblast completely surrounds the federal city of Saint Petersburg, which functions as a separate federal subject. Internationally, Leningrad Oblast shares land borders with Finland to the northwest and Estonia to the west. Domestically, it is bordered by the Republic of Karelia to the north, Vologda Oblast to the east, Novgorod Oblast to the south, and Pskov Oblast to the southwest. The region features a significant coastline along the Gulf of Finland, an arm of the Baltic Sea, providing critical maritime access to Europe.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Leningrad Oblast consists of flat to gently rolling plains, which are part of the East European Plain. Glacial activity shaped the landscape, leaving behind numerous moraines and depressions. A prominent geological feature is the Baltic-Ladoga Klint, an erosional escarpment stretching across the region. The oblast is rich in water resources, containing Lake Ladoga, the largest lake in Europe, and bordering Lake Onega to the northeast. Major rivers include the Neva, which drains Lake Ladoga into the Gulf of Finland, the Svir, which connects Lake Onega to Lake Ladoga, and the Volkhov and Luga rivers. Forests cover over half of the oblast, dominated by coniferous taiga species such as pine and spruce, alongside extensive wetlands and peat bogs.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Leningrad Oblast is classified as humid continental, transitioning toward a subarctic climate in the north. The weather is highly influenced by maritime air masses from the Atlantic Ocean and the Baltic Sea. This results in relatively mild winters and cool, humid summers. The average temperature in January ranges from minus 7 to minus 11 degrees Celsius, while July temperatures average around 17 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges from 600 to 800 millimeters, with the majority falling during the summer and autumn. Overcast days and high humidity levels are characteristic of the region year-round.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Leningrad Oblast is highly industrialized and serves as a major transport hub. Key industries include mechanical engineering, chemical manufacturing, forestry, and paper production. The energy sector is anchored by the Leningrad Nuclear Power Plant in Sosnovy Bor. The oblast also hosts the Port of Ust-Luga, one of the largest ports on the Baltic Sea, handling coal, oil, and container cargo. While Saint Petersburg historically served as the administrative hub, Gatchina was officially designated as the administrative center in 2021. Other major urban centers include Vyborg, Kirishi, and Kingisepp. Agriculture focuses primarily on dairy farming and poultry.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the territory of Leningrad Oblast was known as Ingria, a region contested between Sweden and Russia. In 1703, Peter the Great captured the area during the Great Northern War and founded Saint Petersburg. Vyborg, featuring a medieval castle, was founded by Swedes, later became part of Finland, and was incorporated into the Soviet Union after World War II. During the war, the oblast was a major battleground, and the \"Road of Life\" was established across the frozen ice of Lake Ladoga to supply besieged Leningrad. The oblast contains several UNESCO World Heritage sites, including the Gatchina Palace and the medieval fortress of Oreshek.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Gatchina\n* Approximate area: 83,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,000,000\n* Largest city: Gatchina\n* Signature features: Lake Ladoga, the largest lake in Europe, and the medieval Vyborg Castle.",
    "summary": "Leningrad Oblast is a highly industrialized federal subject in northwestern Russia that surrounds the city of Saint Petersburg and borders Finland and Estonia. The region is characterized by flat glacial plains, extensive wetlands, and Lake Ladoga, which is the largest lake in Europe. Gatchina serves as its administrative center, and its economy relies heavily on maritime trade, forestry, and energy production.",
