    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nKrasnodar Krai is located in the southwestern part of the Russian Federation, within the Southern Federal District. It borders Rostov Oblast to the north, Stavropol Krai to the east, and the Karachay-Cherkess Republic to the southeast. It also completely surrounds the Republic of Adygea, an enclave within the krai. To the south, it shares an international border with Abkhazia, a breakaway region recognized by Russia but internationally regarded as part of Georgia. To the west, the krai is separated from the Crimean Peninsula by the Kerch Strait. The political status of Crimea is disputed, as it was annexed by Russia in 2014 but is internationally recognized as part of Ukraine.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Krasnodar Krai is highly diverse, divided into two distinct zones by the Kuban River. The northern two-thirds of the territory consist of the Kuban-Azov Lowland, a flat steppe region that forms part of the East European Plain. The southern third is dominated by the western peaks of the Greater Caucasus mountain range, which rise progressively higher toward the east. The highest point in the krai is Mount Tsakhvoa, reaching an elevation of 3,256 meters. The region has extensive coastlines, bordered by the Sea of Azov to the northwest and the Black Sea to the southwest. The Kuban River is the primary waterway, flowing westward into the Sea of Azov. Other notable rivers include the Laba and the Belaya. The Western Caucasus, a UNESCO World Heritage site, contains the Caucasus State Nature Biosphere Reserve, protecting pristine mountain ecosystems.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Krasnodar Krai varies significantly by elevation and proximity to the sea. The northern steppe region experiences a humid continental climate with hot summers and relatively cold winters. The Black Sea coast, particularly south of the Caucasus Mountains, features a humid subtropical climate. This coastal strip is protected from cold northern air masses by the mountains, resulting in mild winters and warm, humid summers. Average January temperatures range from minus 4 degrees Celsius in the northern plains to 5 degrees Celsius on the southern coast. Average July temperatures range from 22 to 24 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation varies from 400 millimeters in the dry northern steppes to over 3,200 millimeters in the mountainous areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nKrasnodar Krai is a major economic hub in southern Russia, driven by agriculture, tourism, and transportation. Often referred to as the granary of Russia, the fertile chernozem soils of the northern steppes support intensive cultivation of wheat, barley, sunflowers, sugar beets, and rice. The region is also Russia's primary producer of wine and tea. Tourism is centered on the Black Sea coast, with Sochi serving as Russia's premier resort city and the host of the 2014 Winter Olympics. Krasnodar, the administrative center, is an industrial and educational hub. Other major cities include Novorossiysk, which is Russia's largest commercial port on the Black Sea, and Armavir, an industrial center in the east.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region was inhabited by various nomadic tribes, including the Scythians and Sarmatians, and later hosted Greek colonies along the Black Sea coast. In the late eighteenth century, the Russian Empire secured the region from the Ottoman Empire, and the Kuban Cossacks were settled there to guard the southern borders. The Cossack heritage remains a defining cultural element of the krai today, influencing local music, folklore, and administrative traditions. During the Soviet era, the region was established as Krasnodar Krai in 1937.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Krai\n* Administrative center: Krasnodar\n* Approximate area: 75,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.8 million\n* Largest city: Krasnodar\n* Signature features: The Kuban River basin, the resort city of Sochi, and the vital commercial port of Novorossiysk.",
    "summary": "Krasnodar Krai is a highly diverse region in southwestern Russia, characterized by the fertile Kuban steppe in the north and the Caucasus Mountains in the south. Bordered by both the Black Sea and the Sea of Azov, it serves as a vital agricultural heartland, a major maritime trade gateway, and Russia's premier tourism destination. The region's culture is deeply influenced by its Kuban Cossack heritage and its administrative center is the city of Krasnodar.",
