    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nOrenburg Oblast is situated in the southern part of the Russian Federation, within the Volga Federal District. It occupies a strategic position along the border between Europe and Asia, at the southern tip of the Ural Mountains. The oblast shares a long international border with Kazakhstan to the south and east. Domestically, it is bordered by Samara Oblast to the west, Saratov Oblast to the southwest, the Republic of Tatarstan to the northwest, the Republic of Bashkortostan to the north, and Chelyabinsk Oblast to the northeast. This positioning makes the region a vital transit corridor between European Russia and Central Asia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of the region is defined by its transition from the East European Plain to the southern Ural Mountains. The Ural River, which serves as a symbolic boundary between the European and Asian continents, flows through the oblast from east to west. Other significant watercourses include the Sakmara, Samara, and Ilek rivers. The terrain consists primarily of rolling plains, forest-steppes, and dry steppes. Notable landforms include the Guberlya Mountains in the east and the Obshchy Syrt hills. The Shaitan-Tau State Nature Reserve protects the unique low-mountain oak forest-steppe ecosystems of the region, preserving local biodiversity.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe oblast experiences a temperate continental climate, which becomes increasingly arid toward the south and east. Winters are long and cold, with average January temperatures ranging from minus fifteen to minus eighteen degrees Celsius. Heavy snowstorms, locally called burans, are frequent and can cause significant travel disruptions. Summers are warm and often hot, with average July temperatures between twenty and twenty-two degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation is modest, ranging from approximately four hundred and fifty millimeters in the northwest to under three hundred millimeters in the dry southern steppes, making agriculture susceptible to periodic droughts.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Orenburg Oblast is highly developed, driven by natural resource extraction and heavy industry. The region contains one of the largest gas condensate deposits in Russia, making natural gas processing and oil refining central economic activities. Metallurgy is highly concentrated in the eastern cities of Orsk and Novotroitsk. Agriculture is also vital, with the oblast being a major producer of spring durum wheat, sunflowers, and livestock. Orenburg is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the cultural and educational hub. Orsk, located in the east, is the second-largest city and a major industrial center.\n\n## History & culture\n\nOriginally inhabited by nomadic Bashkir, Kazakh, and Kalmyk populations, the area became integrated into the Russian Empire during the eighteenth century. The Orenburg Cossack Host was established to defend the southern borders and secure trade routes into Central Asia. The administrative center of Orenburg was founded in 1743 after two previous attempts at different sites. Culturally, the region is internationally famous for the Orenburg down shawl. These intricate, hand-knitted lace shawls are made from the exceptionally fine undercoat of local Orenburg goats blended with silk, representing a prized folk handicraft.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Orenburg\n* Approximate area: 124,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.8 million\n* Largest city: Orenburg\n* Signature features: The Ural River continental boundary and the traditional Orenburg down shawls",
    "summary": "Orenburg Oblast is a Russian administrative division situated along the border with Kazakhstan, where the Ural River marks the transition between Europe and Asia. The region features a continental steppe climate and supports an economy driven by agriculture, oil and gas extraction, and heavy metallurgy. It is historically significant as a frontier trade post and is culturally renowned for its traditional hand-knitted down shawls.",
