    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nPskov Oblast is located in the northwestern part of the Russian Federation within the Northwestern Federal District. It shares international borders with three sovereign nations, which are Estonia to the northwest, Latvia to the west, and Belarus to the south. Domestically, it borders Leningrad Oblast to the north, Novgorod Oblast to the east, Tver Oblast to the southeast, and Smolensk Oblast to the south. This strategic position makes it one of the few Russian federal subjects to border three foreign countries, serving historically as a vital gateway and defensive outpost on Russia's western frontier.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Pskov Oblast is characterized by a flat to gently rolling glaciated landscape, which is typical of the East European Plain. The region features the Valday Hills transition in the east and the Bezhanitsy Hills in the south. The highest point in the oblast is Mount Lobno, which reaches an elevation of about 338 meters above sea level. Water bodies are a defining physical feature of the region. Lake Peipus, also known as Lake Chudskoye-Pskovskoye, dominates the northwestern border with Estonia and ranks as one of the largest lakes in Europe. The Velikaya River is the most significant river flowing through the oblast, draining northward into Lake Peipus. Other notable rivers include the Lovat, the Shelon, and the Plyussa. Extensive wetlands, peat bogs, and mixed coniferous-deciduous forests cover more than one-third of the territory.\n\n## Climate\n\nPskov Oblast experiences a humid continental climate, which transitions toward a maritime climate due to its relative proximity to the Baltic Sea. Winters are moderately cold and long, with average January temperatures hovering around minus seven degrees Celsius. Summers are warm but brief, with average July temperatures of approximately eighteen degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, averaging about 600 to 700 millimeters annually, with the majority falling during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from December to late March.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Pskov Oblast is diverse, with agriculture, manufacturing, and transit playing primary roles. Agricultural activities focus on dairy farming, livestock breeding, and the cultivation of flax, grain, and potatoes. Industrial sectors include electrical engineering, mechanical engineering, food processing, and timber production. Pskov is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a major transport hub with rail and road connections linking Saint Petersburg, Riga, and Kyiv. Velikiye Luki is the second-largest city and a major industrial center in the southern part of the oblast, known for its manufacturing and rail infrastructure.\n\n## History & culture\n\nPskov is one of the oldest cities in Russia, first mentioned in historical chronicles in the year 903. During the medieval period, the Pskov Republic existed as an independent state and a powerful trading partner of the Hanseatic League before being annexed by the Grand Duchy of Moscow in 1510. The Pskov Krom, or Kremlin, is a massive medieval fortress located at the confluence of the Velikaya and Pskova rivers. The region is also famous for the Pechory Monastery, which has operated continuously since the fifteenth century. The Pushkin Hills preserve the estate of Mikhailovskoye, where the famous Russian poet Alexander Pushkin wrote some of his most celebrated works.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Pskov\n* Approximate area: 55,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 580,000 residents\n* Largest city: Pskov\n* Signature features: Lake Peipus and the medieval Pskov Krom fortress",
    "summary": "Pskov Oblast is a Russian federal subject situated on the nation's western border with Estonia, Latvia, and Belarus. Its landscape is defined by the massive Lake Peipus, the Velikaya River, and glaciated plains. The region is economically driven by agriculture and transit, and it is culturally renowned for its deep medieval history centered around the ancient city of Pskov.",
