    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nSakhalin Oblast is an island-based federal subject located in the Russian Far East. It is the only Russian oblast situated entirely on islands, comprising Sakhalin Island and the Kuril Islands chain. It is bounded by the Sea of Okhotsk to the north and east, the Sea of Japan to the southwest, and the Pacific Ocean to the southeast. It is separated from the Russian mainland, specifically Khabarovsk Krai, by the Tatar Strait and from the Japanese island of Hokkaido by the La Pérouse Strait. The southern Kuril Islands are claimed by Japan, a territorial dispute that has remained unresolved since the end of World War II.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Sakhalin Oblast is highly mountainous and maritime. Sakhalin Island is divided into the West Sakhalin and East Sakhalin mountain ranges, which run parallel from north to south. Mount Lopatin is the highest peak on Sakhalin Island, reaching an elevation of 1,609 meters. The island features major rivers such as the Tym River and the Poronay River, which flow through fertile central valleys. The Kuril Islands are volcanic in origin, forming part of the Pacific Ring of Fire. This chain contains over one hundred volcanoes, of which roughly forty are active, including Mount Tyatya on Kunashir Island. The region is prone to frequent seismic activity and tsunamis.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe climate of Sakhalin Oblast is subarctic and monsoon-influenced, characterized by cold, snowy winters and cool, humid summers. The surrounding seas moderate temperatures slightly compared to continental Siberia, but they also bring heavy precipitation and frequent fog. Winters are long, with temperatures often dropping below minus fifteen degrees Celsius in the north. Summers are short and mild, with average July temperatures ranging from eleven to sixteen degrees Celsius. The Kuril Islands experience particularly high levels of fog, strong winds, and heavy snowfall due to the interaction of cold arctic air masses and warm ocean currents.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Sakhalin Oblast is heavily driven by natural resource extraction, particularly oil and natural gas. Major offshore energy projects, such as Sakhalin-1 and Sakhalin-2, have attracted significant international investment and transformed the regional economy. Fishing and fish processing are also vital industries, supported by the rich marine life of the Sea of Okhotsk. Forestry and coal mining contribute to the local economy as well. Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk is the administrative center and largest city, serving as the financial and cultural hub. Other notable cities include Kholmsk and Korsakov, which serve as major ice-free seaports facilitating trade with neighboring Asian nations.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous peoples of Sakhalin include the Ainu, Nivkh, and Uilta, who historically relied on fishing and hunting. During the nineteenth and twentieth centuries, the region became a point of geopolitical contention between the Russian Empire and the Empire of Japan. Under the 1875 Treaty of Saint Petersburg, Russia gained full control of Sakhalin in exchange for ceding the Kuril Islands to Japan. Following the Russo-Japanese War, the 1905 Treaty of Portsmouth divided Sakhalin Island along the 50th parallel, giving the southern half to Japan as Karafuto Prefecture. The Soviet Union reclaimed the entire island and the Kuril Islands at the end of World War II, leading to the expulsion of the Japanese population. Today, the local culture reflects a blend of Russian traditions and indigenous heritage, alongside remnants of Japanese architecture and infrastructure.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk\n* Approximate area: 87,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 460,000 residents\n* Largest city: Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk\n* Signature features: The only Russian oblast located entirely on islands, and home to major offshore oil and natural gas extraction projects.",
    "summary": "Sakhalin Oblast is a unique Russian federal subject comprised entirely of Sakhalin Island and the Kuril Islands in the Far East. The region is characterized by mountainous terrain, active volcanism, and a subarctic maritime climate. Its economy relies heavily on offshore oil and gas extraction, fishing, and maritime trade through key ports like Korsakov.",
