    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nRostov Oblast is located in the southern part of the East European Plain, within the Southern Federal District of Russia. It shares domestic borders with Voronezh Oblast to the north, Volgograd Oblast to the northeast and east, the Republic of Kalmykia to the southeast, Stavropol Krai to the south, and Krasnodar Krai to the southwest. To the west, the oblast shares an international border with Ukraine, specifically the Donetsk and Luhansk regions. This western border area has been a focal point of geopolitical tension and military activity, with Russia claiming sovereignty over adjacent Ukrainian territories, a status that remains unrecognized by the international community. The southwestern boundary of the oblast is formed by the Taganrog Gulf of the Sea of Azov.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Rostov Oblast is predominantly flat, characterized by rolling plains and low hills. It occupies a significant portion of the lower Don River basin. The Donets Ridge extends into the western part of the oblast, providing some elevation. The primary hydrological feature is the Don River, which flows from the north to the southwest, emptying into the Taganrog Gulf. Major tributaries within the oblast include the Seversky Donets, the Sal, and the Manych. The Tsimlyansk Reservoir, created by a dam on the Don River, is a major artificial water body used for irrigation, power generation, and navigation. The region is dominated by fertile black soil, known as chernozem, which supports extensive agriculture. Natural vegetation consists mainly of steppe grasslands, though much of this has been converted to farmland.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a moderate continental climate. Winters are cold but relatively mild compared to northern Russia, with average January temperatures ranging from minus five to minus nine degrees Celsius. Summers are hot and long, with average July temperatures hovering between 22 and 24 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation is relatively low, varying from approximately 600 millimeters in the west to under 400 millimeters in the dry eastern districts. The eastern areas are prone to hot, dry winds known as sukhovey during the summer months, which can cause agricultural droughts.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nRostov Oblast possesses a highly developed and diversified economy. Agriculture is a primary sector, leveraging the fertile soil to produce large quantities of winter wheat, sunflowers, barley, and corn. The region is one of Russia's leading agricultural producers and exporters. Industrial activities include heavy machinery manufacturing, transport equipment production, metallurgy, and food processing. The eastern portion of the oblast contains part of the Donets Coal Basin, supporting coal mining industries. Rostov-on-Don, the administrative center, is a major industrial, scientific, and transport hub with a population exceeding one million. Other significant cities include Taganrog, an important seaport and industrial center, Novocherkassk, Shakhty, and Volgodonsk, which hosts the Rostov Nuclear Power Plant.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe history of Rostov Oblast is deeply intertwined with the Don Cossacks, a semi-military community that settled the Don River basin starting in the sixteenth century. Novocherkassk served as the official capital of the Don Cossack Host. During the Russian Civil War, the region was a major stronghold of the anti-Bolshevik White movement. In World War II, the oblast saw intense fighting, particularly during the battles for Rostov-on-Don. Culturally, the region is famous as the birthplace of writer Anton Chekhov, born in Taganrog, and Nobel laureate Mikhail Sholokhov, whose novels depicted Cossack life along the Don River.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Rostov-on-Don\n* Approximate area: 100,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4,200,000\n* Largest city: Rostov-on-Don\n* Signature features: The Don River waterway and the historical homeland of the Don Cossacks",
