    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nOryol Oblast is a federal subject of Russia, situated in the southwestern portion of the Central Federal District. The oblast shares its borders with several Russian administrative divisions. To the north, it borders Kaluga Oblast and Tula Oblast. To the east, it is bounded by Lipetsk Oblast. Kursk Oblast lies directly to the south, while Bryansk Oblast borders it to the west. The region occupies a strategic position, providing transport links between Moscow and the southern regions of Russia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe territory of Oryol Oblast is situated in the central part of the Central Russian Upland. This geography results in a rolling, hilly plain dissected by a network of river valleys and ravines. The average elevation ranges from 200 to 250 meters above sea level. The oblast is significant hydrologically as it contains the headwaters of the Oka River, a major tributary of the Volga. Other significant rivers flowing through the region include the Zusha and the Bystraya Sosna. The soils are highly fertile, consisting predominantly of rich black earth, or chernozem, in the south and east, and gray forest soils in the north and west. Forests cover a relatively small percentage of the oblast, with deciduous and mixed forests scattered in small groves.\n\n## Climate\n\nOryol Oblast experiences a temperate continental climate, typical for the central region of European Russia. This climate is characterized by moderately cold winters and warm, humid summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from approximately minus eight to minus ten degrees Celsius. July is the warmest month, with average temperatures hovering around eighteen to nineteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 500 and 600 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. This level of precipitation, combined with the warm growing season, provides favorable conditions for agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Oryol Oblast is anchored in agriculture and industrial manufacturing. Thanks to its fertile chernozem soils, the agricultural sector is highly productive, focusing on the cultivation of winter wheat, rye, barley, sugar beets, and potatoes. Livestock farming, including dairy and beef cattle raising, is also prominent. The industrial sector is concentrated in the larger urban areas and includes food processing, mechanical engineering, metalworking, and the production of building materials. Oryol is the administrative center and the largest city, acting as the primary economic, educational, and cultural hub. Other notable urban centers include Livny and Mtsensk, both of which support local manufacturing and agricultural processing.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region of Oryol served as a defensive frontier for the Russian state. The city of Oryol was founded in 1566 as a fortress to protect the southern borders. During World War II, the oblast was the site of intense military engagements, particularly during the Battle of Kursk in 1943. The Oryol Offensive, also known as Operation Kutuzov, resulted in the liberation of the region. Culturally, Oryol Oblast is renowned as the home of several prominent Russian writers. The most famous literary site is Spasskoye-Lutovinovo, the family estate of Ivan Turgenev, which is now preserved as a national museum. Other literary figures associated with the region include Nikolai Leskov and Ivan Bunin.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Oryol\n* Approximate area: 24,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 700,000\n* Largest city: Oryol\n* Signature features: Source of the Oka River and the Spasskoye-Lutovinovo estate of Ivan Turgenev",
    "summary": "Oryol Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the Central Russian Upland, known for its highly fertile chernozem soils and agricultural productivity. The region contains the headwaters of the Oka River and is historically significant as a defensive frontier and a major World War II battlefield. It is also celebrated for its rich literary heritage, notably serving as the home of author Ivan Turgenev.",
