    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nOmsk Oblast is situated in the southwestern portion of Siberia, falling within the Siberian Federal District of the Russian Federation. The oblast shares its borders with several other Russian federal subjects, including Tyumen Oblast to the west and north, and Novosibirsk Oblast and Tomsk Oblast to the east. To the south, Omsk Oblast shares an international border with the Republic of Kazakhstan, specifically bordering the North Kazakhstan and Pavlodar regions. There are no active territorial disputes regarding the borders of Omsk Oblast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe territory of Omsk Oblast lies almost entirely within the southern section of the vast West Siberian Plain. The topography is predominantly flat, characterized by low-lying plains, gentle depressions, and steppes. The primary hydrological feature is the Irtysh River, a major tributary of the Ob River, which flows from south to north across the entire length of the oblast. Key tributaries of the Irtysh within the region include the Ishim, Om, Tara, and Osha rivers. The northern part of the oblast is dominated by dense coniferous forests, known as taiga, and extensive marshlands, including portions of the Vasyugan Swamp. Moving southward, the landscape transitions into forest-steppe and eventually open steppe. The region also contains numerous lakes, with Lake Ik and Lake Salym being notable examples of freshwater and saline water bodies.\n\n## Climate\nOmsk Oblast experiences a classic humid continental climate, characterized by a high degree of continentality. Winters are long, dry, and severely cold, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 18 to minus 20 degrees Celsius. Summers are relatively short but warm, with average July temperatures hovering around 18 to 20 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation is moderate, averaging between 300 and 450 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically forms in late October or early November and persists for approximately 150 days.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Omsk Oblast is highly developed and diversified, with a strong industrial base centered in the administrative capital of Omsk. The city of Omsk is home to one of the largest oil refineries in Russia, alongside major chemical, petrochemical, and aerospace manufacturing facilities. Outside of the capital, other urban centers include Tara, Isilkul, and Kalachinsk. Agriculture plays a vital role in the southern steppe regions, where farmers cultivate spring wheat, barley, rye, and sunflowers, alongside livestock farming for dairy and meat production. The Trans-Siberian Railway runs directly through Omsk, making the region a critical logistics and transportation hub connecting European Russia with the Far East.\n\n## History & culture\nPrior to Russian settlement, the region was inhabited by indigenous Siberian Tatars, Khanty, and Mansi peoples. Russian expansion into the area began in earnest in the early 18th century, marked by the founding of the Omsk fortress in 1716 to secure the southern frontier. The construction of the Trans-Siberian Railway in the 1890s triggered rapid economic development and a massive influx of settlers. During the Russian Civil War, Omsk briefly served as the capital of the provisional White Russian government led by Admiral Alexander Kolchak. Today, the oblast preserves a rich cultural heritage, represented by institutions such as the Omsk State Drama Theatre and the Vrubel Museum of Fine Arts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Omsk\n* Approximate area: 141,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.8 million\n* Largest city: Omsk\n* Signature features: The Irtysh River valley and the historic Trans-Siberian Railway junction.",
    "summary": "Omsk Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the southwestern part of the West Siberian Plain, bordering Kazakhstan to the south. The region features a flat landscape dominated by the Irtysh River, transitioning from northern taiga and wetlands to southern steppes. Its economy is anchored by the administrative center of Omsk, a major industrial and transportation hub along the Trans-Siberian Railway.",
