    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nTyumen Oblast is located in the West Siberian region of Russia. It is unique among Russian federal subjects because it administratively encompasses two autonomous okrugs, Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug and Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug. While these okrugs are constitutionally recognized as equal federal subjects in their own right, they remain administratively part of Tyumen Oblast for certain state purposes. This nested political status is a peaceful, established administrative arrangement within the Russian Federation. Including the okrugs, the oblast stretches from the southern border with Kazakhstan to the Kara Sea of the Arctic Ocean. It shares borders with Kazakhstan to the south, Kurgan, Sverdlovsk, and Arkhangelsk Oblasts to the west, and Krasnoyarsk Krai, Tomsk, and Omsk Oblasts to the east.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Tyumen Oblast is dominated by the West Siberian Plain, one of the largest flat lowlands in the world. The terrain is exceptionally flat, characterized by extensive wetlands, peat bogs, and dense forests. The primary river systems are the Ob and its major tributary, the Irtysh. Other significant rivers include the Tobol and the Tura, the latter of which flows through the city of Tyumen. The northern territories feature vast tundra and forest-tundra zones, while the central and southern regions are covered by the dense coniferous forests of the Siberian taiga. The southern margins transition into forest-steppe.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a continental climate, which becomes subarctic and polar in the northern autonomous okrugs. In the southern portion, including the administrative center of Tyumen, winters are long and cold, with average January temperatures ranging from minus fifteen to minus twenty degrees Celsius. Summers are relatively warm but short, with average July temperatures hovering around eighteen to twenty degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, with the majority falling during the summer months. Snow cover persists for five to six months of the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTyumen Oblast is the economic engine of Russia due to its massive reserves of hydrocarbons. The Yamalo-Nenets and Khanty-Mansi regions produce the vast majority of Russia's natural gas and oil. The southern oblast proper focuses on oil refining, petrochemicals, timber processing, and machine building. Tyumen, the administrative center, is a major industrial and educational hub. Tobolsk is another key city, known for its massive petrochemical complex and historical significance. Other major cities within the broader oblast boundaries include Surgut and Nizhnevartovsk, which serve as vital centers for the extraction industries.\n\n## History & culture\nFounded in 1586, Tyumen was the first Russian town established in Siberia, built on the site of the former Siberian Khanate town of Chingi-Tura. It served as a vital transit point for trade and Russian expansion into Asia. Tobolsk, founded shortly after in 1587, became the historical capital of the Siberian Governorate and remains a major spiritual center. The Tobolsk Kremlin, constructed in the late seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, is the only stone kremlin in Siberia. The region preserves a rich blend of Russian pioneer history and indigenous Siberian cultures, including those of the Khanty, Mansi, and Siberian Tatars.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Tyumen\n* Approximate area: Roughly 1,435,200 square kilometers including autonomous okrugs, or about 160,100 square kilometers for the oblast proper\n* Approximate population: Roughly 3.8 million including autonomous okrugs, or about 1.6 million for the oblast proper\n* Largest city: Tyumen\n* Signature features: The historic Tobolsk Kremlin and the gateway to the West Siberian petroleum basin",
    "summary": "Tyumen Oblast is a major administrative region in Western Siberia, stretching from the Kazakh border to the Arctic Ocean when including its nested autonomous okrugs. As the historic gateway to Siberia, it contains the oldest Russian cities in the region, Tyumen and Tobolsk, alongside the country's most critical oil and natural gas reserves. Its geography is defined by the flat West Siberian Plain, extensive river systems, and a harsh continental climate.",
