    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nTver Oblast is located in the western part of the European territory of the Russian Federation. It is situated within the Central Federal District. The oblast shares borders with six other federal subjects of Russia. It is bordered by Novgorod Oblast to the north, Vologda Oblast to the northeast, Yaroslavl Oblast to the east, Moscow Oblast to the southeast, Smolensk Oblast to the south, and Pskov Oblast to the west. This strategic location places it between the two largest Russian metropolitan areas, Moscow and Saint Petersburg, making it a vital transit corridor. There are no disputed international borders or sensitive political territorial claims associated with Tver Oblast.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Tver Oblast is characterized by a mix of plains and low hills. The western portion of the region is dominated by the Valdai Hills, an upland region that serves as a major drainage divide in Europe. This area contains the headwaters of several major rivers, most notably the Volga River, which begins its course near the village of Volgo-Verkhovye. Other significant rivers originating or flowing through the oblast include the Western Dvina, the Dnieper, and the Msta. Tver Oblast is rich in water bodies, containing over 500 lakes. The largest and most famous of these is Lake Seliger, a major tourist and ecological site. Large reservoirs, such as the Rybinsk, Uglich, and Ivankovo reservoirs, also lie partially within the oblast, regulating water flow and providing hydroelectric power. Forests cover more than half of the territory, consisting of a mix of coniferous and deciduous species, which support diverse wildlife.\n\n## Climate\n\nTver Oblast experiences a humid continental climate, classified as Dfb under the Köppen system. This climate is characterized by moderately cold, snowy winters and warm, humid summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from minus 8 to minus 10 degrees Celsius. July, the warmest month, has average temperatures ranging from 17 to 19 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 550 and 750 millimeters, with the western slopes of the Valdai Hills receiving the highest amount of rainfall. Snow cover typically persists from late November through early April, influencing local agriculture and transportation.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Tver Oblast is diverse, with strong industrial, energy, and agricultural sectors. Machine building, metalworking, and chemical production are the primary industrial activities. The region is a major energy producer for central Russia, hosting the Kalinin Nuclear Power Plant near Udomlya and the Konakovo Power Station. The administrative center and largest city is Tver, situated at the confluence of the Volga and Tvertsa rivers. Other major urban centers include Rzhev, known for its historical significance and manufacturing, and Vyshny Volochyok, famous for its historic canal system. Agriculture focuses on dairy farming, flax cultivation, and livestock breeding, supported by the region's vast pastures.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region was the center of the Principality of Tver, which emerged as a powerful rival to the Grand Duchy of Moscow during the thirteenth and fourteenth centuries. Although Moscow eventually absorbed Tver in 1485, the region maintained its cultural and economic importance. Tver was home to Afanasy Nikitin, a fifteenth-century merchant who became one of the first Europeans to travel to and document India. During World War II, the oblast was the site of intense fighting, particularly the Battles of Rzhev, which resulted in massive casualties. Culturally, the region is known for its traditional wooden architecture, lace-making in Torzhok, and historic monasteries, such as the Nilov Monastery on Lake Seliger.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Tver\n* Approximate area: 84,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,200,000\n* Largest city: Tver\n* Signature features: The source of the Volga River and the scenic Lake Seliger.",
