    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nTomsk Oblast is located in the southeastern part of the West Siberian Plain, within the Siberian Federal District of the Russian Federation. It shares borders with Krasnoyarsk Krai to the east, Kemerovo and Novosibirsk oblasts to the south, Omsk Oblast to the southwest, and the Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug to the north and northwest. Its central location in Siberia makes it a key transit corridor, though much of its northern territory remains remote and accessible primarily by water or seasonal winter roads.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Tomsk Oblast is dominated by the vast, flat terrain of the West Siberian Plain. The region is heavily forested, with taiga covering approximately 60 percent of its territory. One of the most significant physical features is the Vasyugan Swamp, which is one of the largest wetlands in the world and occupies a substantial portion of the western and southern areas of the oblast. The primary hydrological artery is the Ob River, which flows from the southeast to the northwest across the region. Major tributaries of the Ob within the oblast include the Tom, Chulym, Ket, Tym, and Vasyugan rivers. These waterways are crucial for transportation, especially in areas lacking developed road infrastructure.\n\n## Climate\n\nTomsk Oblast experiences a continental climate, characterized by long, severe winters and short, warm summers. Average January temperatures range from minus 19 to minus 21 degrees Celsius, though extreme cold spells can push temperatures below minus 50 degrees Celsius. Summers are relatively warm but brief, with average July temperatures hovering around 17 to 19 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, averaging between 400 and 550 millimeters annually, with the majority falling during the warmer summer months. The ground remains covered with snow for approximately six months of the year, typically from late October to April.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Tomsk Oblast is heavily reliant on natural resource extraction, particularly petroleum and natural gas. The region possesses significant oil and gas fields, primarily located in its northern and western districts. Forestry and timber processing also constitute major industrial sectors due to the extensive taiga coverage. The administrative center, Tomsk, is a major scientific and educational hub, often referred to as the Athens of Siberia due to its high concentration of universities and research institutes. Other notable cities include Seversk, a closed city historically associated with nuclear materials production, and Strezhevoy, which serves as a center for the northern oil-producing region.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe region was originally inhabited by indigenous Siberian groups, including the Khanty, Selkup, and Ket peoples. Russian colonization accelerated after the founding of the Tomsk fortress in 1604 on the banks of the Tom River. Tomsk grew rapidly as a major trading post on the Siberian Route. In the nineteenth century, the city became a cultural and educational center with the establishment of Tomsk State University, the first university in Siberia, in 1878. The region's cultural heritage is reflected in its distinctive wooden architecture, particularly the ornate wooden houses preserved in the historic quarters of Tomsk.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Tomsk\n* Approximate area: 314,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,070,000 residents\n* Largest city: Tomsk\n* Signature features: The Vasyugan Swamp, which is one of the world's largest wetlands, and Tomsk State University, the oldest university in Asian Russia.",
    "summary": "Tomsk Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the southeastern West Siberian Plain, characterized by extensive taiga forests and the massive Vasyugan Swamp. Its economy relies heavily on oil and gas extraction, timber processing, and the scientific and educational institutions centered in its administrative capital, Tomsk. The region features a continental climate with severe winters and is historically notable for its early Siberian university and preserved wooden architecture.",
