    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nTula Oblast is a federal subject of the Russian Federation, positioned in the Central Federal District of the European part of the country. It lies in the center of the East European Plain. The oblast is landlocked and shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. To the north and northeast, it borders Moscow Oblast. To the east, it is bounded by Ryazan Oblast. Lipetsk Oblast lies to the southeast, while Oryol Oblast borders it to the southwest. To the west and northwest, Tula Oblast shares a border with Kaluga Oblast. Its strategic location places it close to the Moscow metropolitan area, which significantly influences its transport networks and economic integration.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Tula Oblast is characterized by a hilly plain, as it is situated in the northern part of the Central Russian Upland. The landscape is dissected by numerous river valleys, ravines, and gullies. The highest elevation in the region reaches approximately 293 meters above sea level. The oblast acts as a drainage divide between the basins of the Volga and Don rivers. The Oka River, one of the largest tributaries of the Volga, flows along the northwestern border of the oblast. The Upa River, a major tributary of the Oka, flows directly through the administrative center of Tula. The Don River originates within the territory of Tula Oblast, near the city of Novomoskovsk. Other notable rivers include the Krasivaya Mecha and the Shat. The northern part of the region features mixed forests, while the southern part transitions into fertile forest-steppe zones with rich chernozem soils.\n\n## Climate\n\nTula Oblast experiences a moderate continental climate, characterized by warm summers and cold, snowy winters. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is approximately minus ten degrees Celsius. In July, the warmest month, the average temperature is about nineteen degrees Celsius. The region receives moderate precipitation, averaging between 500 and 600 millimeters annually. Precipitation is unevenly distributed, with the highest amounts falling in the northwest and gradually decreasing toward the southeast. Snow cover typically forms in late November and persists until April, lasting for about 140 days.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Tula Oblast is highly industrialized, with a strong emphasis on heavy manufacturing, metallurgy, and chemical production. The administrative center, Tula, is historically famous for its metalworking and defense industries. Key enterprises include the Tula Arms Plant and the KBP Instrument Design Bureau, which produce military hardware and civilian firearms. The chemical industry is concentrated in Novomoskovsk, home to major mineral fertilizer plants such as Novomoskovsk Azot. Metallurgy is represented by facilities like Tulachermet. Agriculture is also highly developed, focusing on the cultivation of grains, sugar beets, and potatoes, alongside livestock farming. Tula is the largest city and administrative center. Other major urban areas include Novomoskovsk, Aleksin, Shchyokino, and Uzlovaya.\n\n## History & culture\n\nTula Oblast has a rich historical heritage that dates back to the medieval period. The Tula Kremlin, constructed in the early sixteenth century, served as a vital fortress along the southern defensive line of the Grand Duchy of Moscow. In 1380, the historic Battle of Kulikovo took place in the southern part of the modern oblast, where Russian forces led by Dmitry Donskoy defeated the Golden Horde, marking a turning point in Russian history. The region is globally renowned as the birthplace of writer Leo Tolstoy, whose estate, Yasnaya Polyana, is preserved as a museum. Culturally, Tula is famous for its traditional crafts, including the production of decorated metal samovars, accordions, and Tula gingerbread, a traditional sweet.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Tula\n* Approximate area: 25,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,480,000\n* Largest city: Tula\n* Signature features: Yasnaya Polyana estate of Leo Tolstoy, historic Tula Kremlin, and traditional samovar and gingerbread production",
