    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nNovgorod Oblast is located in the northwestern part of the European territory of Russia. It is part of the Northwestern Federal District. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. It is bordered by Leningrad Oblast to the north and northwest, Vologda Oblast to the east, Tver Oblast to the south and southeast, and Pskov Oblast to the southwest. The region is situated strategically between the two largest metropolitan areas of Russia, lying along the main transport corridor that connects Moscow and Saint Petersburg.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Novgorod Oblast is characterized by a mix of flat lowlands and rolling hills, as it lies within the East European Plain. The western portion of the oblast is dominated by the flat, marshy Ilmen Depression. In contrast, the southeastern part features the Valdai Hills, a morainic upland that forms a major drainage divide. The highest point in the oblast reaches approximately 296 meters above sea level in this hilly region.\n\nThe hydrographic network is extensive. Lake Ilmen is the central water body of the oblast, receiving major tributary rivers including the Msta, the Lovat, the Shelon, and the Pola. The Volkhov River is the sole outflow of Lake Ilmen, flowing northward into Lake Ladoga. Large areas of the oblast are covered by peat bogs and mixed coniferous-deciduous forests. Valdaysky National Park, located in the southeastern hills, protects a unique lake and forest ecosystem that is home to diverse flora and fauna.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a humid continental climate, influenced by its proximity to the Baltic Sea. Winters are moderately cold and snowy, with average January temperatures ranging from minus eight to minus ten degrees Celsius. Summers are short and mild, with average July temperatures hovering around eighteen degrees Celsius. Precipitation is distributed relatively evenly throughout the year, with an annual average of about 600 to 800 millimeters. Snow cover typically persists from late November until April.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Novgorod Oblast is diverse, with manufacturing, chemical production, and forestry playing primary roles. Veliky Novgorod, the administrative center and largest city, is the industrial heart of the region. A major chemical plant operated by the company Acron produces fertilizers and is one of the largest employers in the oblast. Other significant industries include metallurgy, food processing, and wood manufacturing.\n\nBeyond Veliky Novgorod, other notable urban centers include Borovichi, known for its refractory materials industry, and Staraya Russa, which is famous for its historic mineral spring spa. Chudovo and Pestovo are important centers for timber processing and manufacturing. Agriculture is primarily focused on dairy farming, poultry, and crop cultivation to support local consumption.\n\n## History & culture\n\nNovgorod Oblast holds a prominent place in Russian history. Veliky Novgorod is recognized as one of the oldest cities in the country, first mentioned in chronicles in the ninth century. It served as the capital of the medieval Novgorod Republic, a powerful merchant state that controlled vast territories from the Baltic Sea to the Ural Mountains. This republic was notable for its unique veche, a form of public assembly and early democratic governance.\n\nThe cultural heritage of the region is immense. The historic monuments of Veliky Novgorod and its surroundings are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. Key landmarks include the Novgorod Kremlin, also known as the Detinets, and the eleventh-century Saint Sophia Cathedral, which is the oldest church building in Russia proper. The Millennium of Russia monument, erected in 1862, stands inside the Kremlin to commemorate the traditional founding date of the Russian state.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Veliky Novgorod\n* Approximate area: 55,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 580,000\n* Largest city: Veliky Novgorod\n* Signature features: Lake Ilmen and the historic Novgorod Kremlin",
