    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nSmolensk Oblast is situated in the westernmost part of the Russian Federation, bordering the Republic of Belarus to the west and southwest. Specifically, it shares an international border with the Vitebsk and Mogilev regions of Belarus. Within Russia, the oblast is bordered by Pskov Oblast to the northwest, Tver Oblast to the north, Moscow Oblast to the east, Kaluga Oblast to the southeast, and Bryansk Oblast to the south. This strategic position makes the region a vital transport and transit corridor connecting Russia with Central and Western Europe.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Smolensk Oblast is characterized by the rolling hills of the East European Plain. The dominant topographic feature is the Smolensk-Moscow Upland, a morainic ridge formed by past glaciations. The highest elevation in the oblast reaches approximately 319 meters above sea level. The region serves as a major watershed division. The Dnieper River, one of the longest rivers in Europe, originates in the northern part of the oblast and flows southward. Other significant rivers flowing through the territory include the Desna, the Vazuza, and the Ugra. The northwestern part of the region features numerous glacial lakes, many of which are protected within the Smolenskoye Poozerye National Park, an area known for its dense forests and wetlands.\n\n## Climate\n\nSmolensk Oblast experiences a temperate continental climate. This climate is characterized by moderately warm summers and relatively cold, snowy winters. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, is approximately minus 9 degrees Celsius. In July, the warmest month, the average temperature is about 18 degrees Celsius. The region receives moderate precipitation, averaging between 600 and 700 millimeters annually, with a significant portion of the rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November until early April.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Smolensk Oblast is driven by manufacturing, energy production, and agriculture. Key industrial sectors include machine building, metalworking, chemical manufacturing, and food processing. The Smolensk Nuclear Power Plant, situated near the town of Desnogorsk, is a critical source of electricity for both the oblast and the wider central Russian grid. Agricultural activities focus primarily on dairy and beef cattle farming, grain cultivation, and the traditional growing of fiber flax. Smolensk is the administrative center and largest city. Other major urban and industrial centers include Vyazma, Roslavl, Yartsevo, Safonovo, and Gagarin.\n\n## History & culture\n\nFirst mentioned in historical chronicles in 863, Smolensk is one of the oldest cities in Russia. Historically, the region was a crucial stronghold on the trade route from the Varangians to the Greeks. Because of its western location, Smolensk Oblast has historically served as a shield for Moscow against western invasions. The region was the site of fierce fighting during the Napoleonic Invasion of 1812 and the Battle of Smolensk during World War II. Cultural landmarks include the Smolensk Kremlin, built between 1595 and 1602, and the Assumption Cathedral. The oblast is the birthplace of several prominent historical figures, including the composer Mikhail Glinka and the first human in space, Yuri Gagarin.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Smolensk\n* Approximate area: 49,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 860,000\n* Largest city: Smolensk\n* Signature features: The historic Smolensk Kremlin fortress walls and the glacial lakes of Smolenskoye Poozerye National Park",
