    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nSverdlovsk Oblast is a federal subject of the Russian Federation located in the Urals Federal District. It is situated on the boundary between Europe and Asia, spanning both sides of the Ural Mountains, though the vast majority of its territory lies on the eastern, Asian side. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian subdivisions. It is bordered by Perm Krai to the west, the Komi Republic to the northwest, the Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug to the northeast, Tyumen Oblast to the east, Kurgan Oblast to the southeast, Chelyabinsk Oblast to the south, and the Republic of Bashkortostan to the southwest. The political status of Sverdlovsk Oblast as an integral first-level administrative division of the Russian Federation is undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Sverdlovsk Oblast is defined by the Ural Mountains, which stretch from north to south across the western part of the region. The highest point in the oblast is Mount Konzhakovsky Kamen, which reaches an elevation of approximately 1,569 meters. To the east of the mountains, the terrain flattens into the West Siberian Plain, characterized by extensive lowlands and wetlands. The region is drained by an extensive network of rivers belonging to the Ob and Volga basins. Major rivers include the Tavda, Tura, Iset, and Sosva, which flow eastward toward the Ob River system. The Chusovaya River is a notable exception, flowing westward across the Ural Mountains into the Kama River, a tributary of the Volga. Dense coniferous forests, or taiga, cover about 70 percent of the oblast, featuring species such as pine, spruce, fir, and larch.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a continental climate, characterized by long, cold winters and short, warm summers. Winters typically last from November to April, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 16 degrees Celsius in the south to minus 20 degrees Celsius in the northern mountainous areas. Snow cover is persistent and can reach significant depths. Summers are brief but moderately warm, with average July temperatures ranging from 16 to 19 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 500 and 600 millimeters, with the highest amounts falling on the western slopes of the Ural Mountains.\n\n## Economy & cities\nSverdlovsk Oblast is one of the most economically developed and heavily industrialized regions in Russia. It is particularly famous for its metallurgical industries, which process local and imported ores. The region contains rich deposits of iron, copper, bauxite, asbestos, and nickel, as well as precious metals and gemstones. Yekaterinburg, the administrative center, is the fourth-largest city in Russia and serves as a major transportation, financial, and industrial hub. Other major industrial cities include Nizhny Tagil, which is known for steel production and railway car manufacturing, Kamensk-Uralsky, a center for aluminum production, and Pervouralsk, which specializes in steel pipes.\n\n## History & culture\nRussian colonization of the region began in the late 16th century, accelerated by the campaigns of Yermak Timofeyevich. In the early 18th century, Peter the Great initiated the rapid industrialization of the Urals by establishing numerous ironworks and mining operations. Yekaterinburg was founded in 1723 as a factory-fortress. The region played a tragic role in Russian history as the site where Emperor Nicholas II and his family were executed by Bolshevik forces in 1918. During World War II, Sverdlovsk Oblast became a vital evacuation destination for factories and cultural institutions from western Russia, which greatly expanded its industrial capacity. The oblast retains its Soviet-era name, honoring Bolshevik leader Yakov Sverdlov, despite its capital reverting to Yekaterinburg in 1991.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Yekaterinburg\n* Approximate area: 194,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4.3 million people\n* Largest city: Yekaterinburg\n* Signature features: The geographical boundary between Europe and Asia, and the historic Demidov ironworks sites.",
