    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nVolgograd Oblast is a federal subject of Russia located in the southwestern portion of the country within the Southern Federal District. It borders Saratov Oblast to the north, Voronezh Oblast to the northwest, Rostov Oblast to the west, and Astrakhan Oblast and the Republic of Kalmykia to the southeast. To the east, the oblast shares an international border with Kazakhstan. It also shares a short border with the Luhansk region to the west, an area subject to ongoing international territorial disputes. The oblast occupies a strategic position, serving as a transport gateway to the Caucasus and the Caspian Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain is predominantly flat, situated within the southern part of the East European Plain. The Volga River flows from north to south, dividing the oblast into the hilly Volga Upland on the west and the flat Trans-Volga lowland on the east. The Don River also traverses the western portion of the oblast, approaching within 80 kilometers of the Volga, which enabled the construction of the Volga-Don Shipping Canal. Major water bodies include the Volgograd Reservoir and the Tsimlyansk Reservoir. Natural vegetation transitions from fertile feather-grass steppes in the northwest to dry semi-deserts in the southeast.\n\n## Climate\nThe region experiences a temperate continental climate characterized by cold winters and hot, dry summers. Average January temperatures range from minus 8 to minus 12 degrees Celsius, while July averages range from 22 to 25 degrees Celsius, with extreme summer temperatures occasionally exceeding 40 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation is relatively low, varying from roughly 450 millimeters in the northwest to less than 270 millimeters in the dry southeastern plains, which makes irrigation essential for local agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy is highly diversified, featuring metallurgy, chemical manufacturing, petroleum refining, and machine building. The Volga Hydroelectric Station, located near Volzhsky, is one of Europe's largest hydroelectric plants. Agriculture is highly developed, focusing on winter wheat, barley, corn, sunflowers, and mustard seeds. Volgograd is the administrative center and largest city. Other significant urban centers include Volzhsky, an industrial city on the Volga River, and Kamyshin, known for its textile industries and scenic cliffs along the reservoir.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically part of the Eurasian steppe corridor, the region was inhabited by nomadic groups and later by the Don Cossacks. Founded in 1589 as Tsaritsyn, the administrative center was renamed Stalingrad in 1925 and became the site of the Battle of Stalingrad during World War II, a major turning point in the global conflict. Today, the cultural landscape is defined by this military heritage, represented by the Mamayev Kurgan memorial complex and its colossal statue, \"The Motherland Calls.\"\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Volgograd\n* Approximate area: 113,900 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,500,000\n* Largest city: Volgograd\n* Signature features: The Volga-Don Shipping Canal and the Mamayev Kurgan memorial complex.",
    "summary": "Volgograd Oblast is a strategically located federal subject in southwestern Russia, bordered by Kazakhstan and divided by the Volga and Don rivers. The region features a temperate continental climate with dry steppes and a highly diversified economy centered on heavy industry, hydroelectric power, and agriculture. It is globally recognized for its historical significance as the site of the Battle of Stalingrad during World War II.",
