    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nYaroslavl Oblast is located in the northern part of the Central Federal District of Russia, situated in the European portion of the country. It shares borders with six other Russian federal subjects. To the north lies Vologda Oblast, while Kostroma Oblast borders it to the east. Ivanovo Oblast is situated to the southeast, Vladimir Oblast to the south, Moscow Oblast to the southwest, and Tver Oblast to the west. The region occupies a highly strategic position, situated relatively close to Moscow, which lies approximately 250 kilometers to the southwest of the administrative center.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Yaroslavl Oblast is predominantly flat or gently rolling, characteristic of the East European Plain. The landscape is shaped by glacial deposits, featuring low hills and plains. Notable elevated areas include the Uglich Highlands in the west and the Danilov Upland in the north. The primary hydrological feature of the region is the Volga River, which flows through the oblast from the west to the east. The river is heavily modified by human engineering, most notably by the Rybinsk Reservoir. This massive artificial lake, often referred to as the Rybinsk Sea, covers a significant portion of the northern territory. Other important water bodies include Lake Nero, a shallow lake near the ancient town of Rostov, and Lake Pleshcheyevo, located near Pereslavl-Zalessky. The region is largely covered by mixed and coniferous forests, which are interspersed with peat bogs and agricultural land.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a moderate humid continental climate, characterized by cold, snowy winters and warm, relatively short summers. The average temperature in January, the coldest month, ranges from minus ten to minus twelve degrees Celsius. July is the warmest month, with average temperatures hovering around eighteen degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation averages between 500 and 600 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November until April, playing a crucial role in the local hydrological cycle.\n\n## Economy & cities\nYaroslavl Oblast is a highly industrialized region with a diverse economy. The manufacturing sector is dominated by machine building, chemical production, and oil refining. The Yaroslavl Oil Refinery is one of the largest in Russia, processing crude oil transported via pipelines. The city of Rybinsk is a major industrial hub, known for manufacturing aircraft engines, gas turbines, and snowmobiles, as well as hosting the Rybinsk Hydroelectric Station. Yaroslavl, the administrative center, is the largest city and serves as a major transportation junction where railways and highways cross the Volga River. Other significant urban centers include Tutayev, Uglich, and Rostov, which support local manufacturing, food processing, and tourism.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region possesses a rich historical heritage, containing several of Russia's oldest cities, which form a core part of the Golden Ring tourist route. The administrative center, Yaroslavl, was founded in 1010 by Prince Yaroslav the Wise and features a historic center that is designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. Rostov, often called Rostov Veliky, was first mentioned in historical chronicles in 862 and is famous for its white-stone kremlin. Pereslavl-Zalessky, founded in 1152, is the birthplace of the legendary military commander Alexander Nevsky. These cities preserve outstanding examples of medieval Russian architecture, including ancient monasteries, cathedrals, and traditional wooden structures.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Yaroslavl\n* Approximate area: 36,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,200,000\n* Largest city: Yaroslavl\n* Signature features: The Volga River with the massive Rybinsk Reservoir, and several historic Golden Ring cities including Rostov and Pereslavl-Zalessky.",
