    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nVologda Oblast is located in the northwestern part of European Russia, within the Northwestern Federal District. It shares borders with eight other federal subjects. To the north, it is bordered by Arkhangelsk Oblast. It borders Kirov Oblast to the east, Kostroma Oblast to the southeast, and Yaroslavl Oblast to the south. To the southwest, it shares borders with Tver and Novgorod oblasts. Leningrad Oblast lies to the west, and the Republic of Karelia borders it to the northwest. This position places the oblast along major transport corridors connecting central Russia with the northern regions. There are no active territorial disputes regarding this region.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Vologda Oblast is characterized by the flat to gently rolling landscape of the East European Plain, shaped by past glaciations. The region features lowlands, morainic hills, and upland ridges, including the Andoma Hills in the northwest, the Vologda Uplands in the south, and the Northern Ridge in the east. The oblast is hydrologically active, containing thousands of lakes and an extensive river network. Major rivers belong to three drainage basins: the Arctic Ocean, the Baltic Sea, and the Caspian Sea. The Sukhona River flows northeastward to join the Yug River, forming the Northern Dvina, which drains into the White Sea. The Sheksna and Mologa rivers flow south toward the Volga River basin, feeding into the Rybinsk Reservoir. Lake Beloye and Lake Kubenskoye are the largest internal lakes, while the northern border touches the southern shores of Lake Onega. Swamps and peat bogs cover a significant portion of the territory, and dense taiga forests, dominated by spruce and pine, cover more than seventy percent of the land.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a humid continental climate, which transitions toward a subarctic climate in the far northern districts. Winters are long, cold, and snowy, typically lasting from November through March. Average January temperatures range from minus eleven degrees Celsius in the west to minus fourteen degrees Celsius in the east. Summers are short and relatively warm, with average July temperatures hovering around eighteen degrees Celsius. Precipitation is moderate, averaging about five hundred to six hundred millimeters annually, with the majority falling as rain during the summer months and snow during the winter. Snow cover persists for approximately one hundred and fifty days a year.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Vologda Oblast is highly industrialized, focusing on metallurgy, chemical production, and forestry. Cherepovets is the largest city and the primary industrial hub, outstripping the administrative center in population and economic output. Cherepovets houses the Severstal metallurgical plant, one of the largest steel mills in Russia, and major chemical facilities operated by PhosAgro. The administrative center, Vologda, serves as a transportation junction focusing on food processing, machinery, and light industry. Forestry and wood processing are widespread due to abundant timber resources. Agriculture is centered on dairy farming, and the region is famous for Vologda butter, a high-quality dairy product.\n\n## History & culture\n\nVologda Oblast has a rich historical heritage dating back to the medieval period when it served as a vital trade route between Novgorod, Moscow, and the northern seas. The region was a major center for monastic life. The Ferapontov Monastery, renowned for its medieval frescoes by the master Dionysius, is designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The Kirillo-Belozersky Monastery, founded in 1397, is one of the largest fortified monasteries in Europe. Culturally, the region is famous for traditional handicrafts, most notably Vologda lace, an intricate bobbin lace style produced since the nineteenth century, and traditional northern wood carving.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Vologda\n* Approximate area: 144,500 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,140,000\n* Largest city: Cherepovets\n* Signature features: Ferapontov Monastery frescoes and traditional Vologda bobbin lace",
