    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nMoscow is a first-level federal city located in the western, European part of the Russian Federation. It is situated entirely within the Central Federal District. Geographically, the federal city is an enclave within Moscow Oblast, which surrounds it on almost all sides. Following a major administrative expansion in 2012, known as the New Moscow project, the city territory expanded southwest to also share a border with Kaluga Oblast. The political status of Moscow as the capital and a federal subject of Russia is internationally recognized and undisputed.\n\n## Physical features\nThe city lies in the undulating landscape of the East European Plain. The terrain is characterized by the Smolensk-Moscow Upland to the west and the flat, marshy Meshchera Lowland to the east. The average elevation of Moscow is approximately 156 meters above sea level, with the highest point reaching about 255 meters at the Teplostanskaya Upland. The primary hydrological feature is the Moskva River, which winds through the city from northwest to southeast for about 80 kilometers. Other notable watercourses include the Yauza River and the Moscow Canal, which connects the Moskva River to the Volga River. Moscow is known for its extensive urban forestry, featuring large parks such as Losiny Ostrov National Park, Izmaylovsky Park, and Gorky Central Park of Culture and Leisure.\n\n## Climate\nMoscow experiences a humid continental climate, classified as Dfb under the Köppen climate system. The weather is characterized by warm, humid summers and long, cold winters. January is typically the coldest month, with average temperatures ranging from minus 6 to minus 10 degrees Celsius, though extreme cold waves can push temperatures below minus 20 degrees Celsius. July is the warmest month, with average temperatures of about 19 degrees Celsius. The city receives approximately 700 millimeters of precipitation annually, with the heaviest rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover typically persists from late November to mid-April.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAs the capital of Russia, Moscow is the dominant economic, financial, and industrial center of the country. It generates a substantial portion of the national gross domestic product. The city's diverse economy is driven by financial services, retail, telecommunications, and heavy industries. Key industrial sectors include food processing, mechanical engineering, metallurgy, and chemical manufacturing, alongside the Kapotnya oil refinery. Moscow is a major global transport hub, featuring four international airports, Sheremetyevo, Domodedovo, Vnukovo, and Zhukovsky, as well as nine major railway terminals. The Moscow Metro, famous for its rapid service and ornate architecture, serves as the backbone of municipal transit. While Moscow is a single unified city, it also serves as the administrative center for the surrounding Moscow Oblast.\n\n## History & culture\nMoscow was first mentioned in historical records in 1147 when Prince Yuri Dolgorukiy called for a meeting there. It grew from a small wooden fort into the capital of the Grand Duchy of Moscow and later the Tsardom of Russia. Although Peter the Great moved the capital to Saint Petersburg in 1712, Moscow remained the spiritual heart of Russia and was reinstated as the capital in 1918 following the Bolshevik Revolution. The city is home to iconic cultural landmarks, including the Moscow Kremlin, Red Square, Saint Basil's Cathedral, and the Bolshoi Theatre. Its architectural landscape is highly diverse, featuring medieval churches, Stalinist skyscrapers known as the Seven Sisters, and the modern glass towers of the Moscow International Business Center.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Federal city\n* Administrative center: Moscow\n* Approximate area: 2,511 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 13 million\n* Largest city if different from the administrative center: Not applicable\n* Signature features: The Moscow Kremlin and Red Square, the historic Moscow Metro system, and the iconic onion domes of Saint Basil's Cathedral.",
