    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nUlyanovsk Oblast is located in the European part of the Russian Federation, situated within the Volga Federal District. It lies in the middle reach of the Volga River basin. The oblast shares borders with several other Russian federal subjects. To the north, it is bordered by the Republic of Chuvashia and the Republic of Tatarstan. To the east, it shares a border with Samara Oblast. Saratov Oblast lies to the south, while Penza Oblast and the Republic of Mordovia border it to the west. This central location in the Volga region makes it an important transit corridor for transport routes connecting central Russia with the Ural Mountains and Siberia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe primary geographical feature of Ulyanovsk Oblast is the Volga River, which bisects the territory into two distinct regions. The right bank of the river, known as the Predvolzhye, is dominated by the northern portion of the Volga Upland. This area features rolling hills, deep ravines, and elevations reaching up to 350 meters above sea level. The Undory Hills, famous for their mineral springs and fossil deposits, are located in this western section. Conversely, the left bank, known as the Zavolzhye, is a flat, low-lying plain that gently slopes toward the east. The Kuybyshev Reservoir, one of the largest artificial reservoirs in the world, covers a significant portion of the Volga valley within the oblast. Other major rivers flowing through the region include the Sura, which forms part of the western border, and the Sviyaga, which flows parallel to the Volga but in the opposite direction.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a moderate continental climate, characterized by distinct seasonal variations. Winters are typically cold and snowy, with average January temperatures ranging from minus twelve to minus fourteen degrees Celsius. Summers are warm and relatively dry, with average July temperatures hovering around twenty degrees Celsius. The average annual precipitation varies between 400 and 500 millimeters, with the majority of rainfall occurring during the late spring and summer months. The climate supports a mix of forest-steppe and steppe vegetation, making the region highly suitable for agricultural activities.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Ulyanovsk Oblast is highly industrialized, with a strong emphasis on machine building, metalworking, and transportation equipment. The administrative center, Ulyanovsk, is a major industrial hub home to the UAZ automotive plant, which produces off-road vehicles, and Aviastar-SP, one of the largest aircraft manufacturing enterprises in Russia. Dimitrovgrad, the second-largest city in the oblast, is a prominent center for nuclear research, hosting the Research Institute of Atomic Reactors. Agriculture also plays a vital role in the regional economy, focusing on the cultivation of grains, sugar beets, and sunflower seeds, alongside livestock farming.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe region was originally inhabited by various Volga-Finnic and Turkic tribes before being integrated into the Russian state. In 1648, the fortress of Simbirsk was founded on the high right bank of the Volga to defend the eastern borders of Russia. The settlement grew into an important trading post and became the center of the Simbirsk Governorate in 1796. In 1924, the city of Simbirsk and the surrounding region were renamed Ulyanovsk in honor of Vladimir Ulyanov, widely known as Lenin, who was born there in 1870. The oblast was officially established in 1943. Culturally, the region is also celebrated as the birthplace of the famous Russian historian and writer Nikolay Karamzin.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Oblast\n* Administrative center: Ulyanovsk\n* Approximate area: 37,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,190,000\n* Largest city: Ulyanovsk\n* Signature features: Division by the Volga River into the elevated Volga Upland and flat Zavolzhye plain, and its status as a major Russian aerospace and automotive manufacturing center.",
