    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nSaint Petersburg is a federal city located in the northwestern region of the Russian Federation. It is situated at the eastern end of the Gulf of Finland, which is an arm of the Baltic Sea. The city serves as the administrative center of both the Northwestern Federal District and the surrounding Leningrad Oblast, although it remains politically distinct from the oblast as an independent federal subject. Saint Petersburg shares land borders exclusively with Leningrad Oblast to the north, east, and south, while its western boundary faces the waters of the Neva Bay within the Gulf of Finland. Its strategic maritime position historically earned it the description of Russia's window to Europe.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe physical geography of Saint Petersburg is defined by its low-lying, flat topography and its intricate network of waterways. The city is built across the delta of the Neva River, which flows from Lake Ladoga into the Gulf of Finland. The Neva River is relatively short, measuring about 74 kilometers, but it carries a massive volume of water. Within the city limits, the river splits into numerous branches, including the Bolshaya Neva, Malaya Neva, Bolshaya Nevka, and Malaya Nevka. These branches, along with artificial canals like the Griboyedov Canal and Fontanka River, divide the city into dozens of islands, such as Vasilyevsky Island and Petrogradsky Island. Because of its low elevation, the city has historically been highly susceptible to severe flooding. To mitigate this risk, the Saint Petersburg Dam was completed in 2011 across the Gulf of Finland.\n\n## Climate\n\nSaint Petersburg experiences a humid continental climate, classified as Dfb under the Köppen climate system. The climate is moderated by the Baltic Sea, which brings high humidity and frequent weather changes. Summers are typically short and cool to warm, with average July temperatures around 18 degrees Celsius. Winters are long and cold, though milder than inland Russian regions at similar latitudes, with average January temperatures around minus 6 degrees Celsius. The city receives about 660 millimeters of precipitation annually. A notable meteorological phenomenon is the White Nights, occurring from late May to mid-July, when the high latitude prevents the sun from sinking far enough below the horizon to allow complete darkness.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nAs Russia's second-largest city, Saint Petersburg is a major industrial, financial, and transport hub. The local economy is highly diversified, emphasizing shipbuilding, automotive manufacturing, aerospace engineering, and electronics. Major shipyards, such as the Admiralty Shipyard, produce commercial vessels and naval submarines. The city is also the headquarters of major Russian corporations, including the energy giant Gazprom. As a federal city, Saint Petersburg contains several distinct municipal towns within its administrative borders, such as Kolpino, Pushkin, Petergof, and Kronstadt. Kronstadt, located on Kotlin Island, serves as a historic naval base defending the sea approaches to the city.\n\n## History & culture\n\nFounded by Tsar Peter the Great in 1703, Saint Petersburg was established to secure a warm-water port and westernize the Russian Empire. It served as the imperial capital of Russia for more than two centuries, from 1712 to 1918. The city changed names multiple times, becoming Petrograd in 1914 and Leningrad in 1924, before reverting to Saint Petersburg in 1991. The historic center of the city is a UNESCO World Heritage site, renowned for its Baroque and Neoclassical architecture. Key cultural institutions include the Hermitage Museum, housed partly in the Winter Palace, and the Mariinsky Theatre.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Federal city\n* Administrative center: Saint Petersburg\n* Approximate area: 1,439 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.6 million residents\n* Largest city: Saint Petersburg\n* Signature features: The Neva River delta, the Hermitage Museum, and the annual White Nights phenomenon.",
    "summary": "Saint Petersburg is Russia's second-largest city and a vital federal subject located at the mouth of the Neva River on the Gulf of Finland. Founded in 1703 by Peter the Great as the imperial capital, the city is renowned for its complex network of delta islands, rich cultural heritage, and major industrial sectors like shipbuilding. Today, it remains a critical maritime gateway and a globally recognized cultural hub famous for its historic architecture and the White Nights phenomenon.",
