    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nChukotka Autonomous Okrug is the northeasternmost federal subject of Russia. It is located in the Far Eastern Federal District. It shares land borders with the Republic of Sakha, also known as Yakutia, to the west, Magadan Oblast to the southwest, and Kamchatka Krai to the south. To the east, across the Bering Strait, lies the United States territory of Alaska. Chukotka is bounded by the East Siberian Sea and the Chukchi Sea to the north, which are part of the Arctic Ocean, and the Bering Sea to the east and south, which is part of the Pacific Ocean. It is the only part of Russia that lies partially in the Western Hemisphere, as the 180th meridian passes directly through the region.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe landscape of Chukotka is dominated by mountainous terrain and tundra. The Chukchi Highlands occupy much of the central and eastern parts of the region, with the highest point being Mount Iskhodnaya. The Anadyr Highlands lie to the south. Major rivers draining the territory include the Anadyr River, which flows eastward into the Gulf of Anadyr, as well as the Omolon, Velikaya, and Amguema rivers. Lake El'gygytgyn, an impact crater lake of great scientific interest for paleoclimate research, is located in the central part of the peninsula. Wrangel Island, a UNESCO World Heritage site known for its biodiversity and as a major breeding ground for polar bears and Pacific walruses, lies off the northern coast in the Arctic Ocean.\n\n## Climate\n\nChukotka experiences a harsh subarctic and polar climate, heavily influenced by its high latitude and surrounding cold oceans. Winters are long, dark, and extremely cold, with temperatures frequently dropping below minus 35 degrees Celsius. Summers are short, cool, and wet, with average temperatures in July rarely exceeding 10 degrees Celsius. Strong winds, blizzards, and dense fog are common throughout the year, particularly along the coastal areas. Permafrost is continuous across almost the entire region, which severely limits soil development and vegetation growth, restricting the flora primarily to mosses, lichens, and low-growing shrubs.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Chukotka relies heavily on mining, particularly the extraction of gold, silver, tin, and coal. Major mining operations include the Kupol and Valunisty gold mines. The administrative center is Anadyr, which is also the largest town in the region. Other notable urban settlements include Bilibino, home to the Bilibino Nuclear Power Plant, which is the world's northernmost nuclear power station, and Pevek, a major port on the Northern Sea Route. Traditional economic activities remain vital for the indigenous population, including reindeer herding, fishing, and marine mammal hunting.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous peoples of Chukotka, including the Chukchi, Yupik, Even, and Koryak, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. Russian contact began in the mid-seventeenth century with the expeditions of Semyon Dezhnyov, who navigated the strait between Asia and North America. For centuries, the Chukchi resisted Russian subjugation, leading to a series of military conflicts before peaceful trade relations were established in the late eighteenth century. During the Soviet era, the region underwent forced collectivization and industrialization, and several Gulag labor camps were established. Today, efforts are made to preserve the unique cultural heritage, languages, and traditional lifestyles of the native populations.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous okrug\n* Administrative center: Anadyr\n* Approximate area: 737,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 47,000\n* Largest city: Anadyr is the largest town and administrative center\n* Signature features: Wrangel Island UNESCO World Heritage site, Bilibino Nuclear Power Plant, and the 180th meridian passing through the territory",
    "summary": "Chukotka Autonomous Okrug is Russia's northeasternmost federal subject, characterized by a harsh polar climate, mountainous tundra, and a strategic location bordering the Bering Strait. Its economy is driven by gold and silver mining alongside traditional indigenous activities like reindeer herding. The administrative center is Anadyr, and the region is notable for hosting the world's northernmost nuclear power plant in Bilibino.",
