    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Jewish Autonomous Oblast is located in the Russian Far East, bordering the Khabarovsk Krai to the north and east, and the Amur Oblast to the west. To the south and southwest, it shares an international border with the Heilongjiang province of China, which is demarcated by the Amur River. It is the only federal subject of Russia designated as an autonomous oblast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of the region is divided between mountainous terrain and flat lowlands. The northern and western portions of the oblast are dominated by the southern extensions of the Bureya Range, including the Pompeyevsky and Maly Khingan mountains. In contrast, the southern and eastern regions consist of the fertile but swampy Middle Amur Lowlands. The Amur River is the primary waterway, forming the entire southern boundary. Its major local tributaries include the Bira River and the Bidzhan River, which flow southwards through the oblast and give the administrative center its name.\n\n## Climate\nThe oblast experiences a monsoon-influenced humid continental climate, characterized by extreme seasonal temperature variations. Winters are cold, dry, and prolonged, influenced by the Siberian High, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 20 to minus 25 degrees Celsius. Summers are warm and humid, dominated by the East Asian monsoon, which brings the majority of the annual precipitation. July temperatures average around 20 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nBirobidzhan is the administrative, economic, and cultural center of the oblast. Other significant settlements include Obluchye, Smidovich, and Amurzet. The regional economy relies heavily on natural resource extraction, particularly the mining of iron ore, coal, tin, gold, and brucite. Agriculture is concentrated in the fertile Amur lowlands, where farmers cultivate soybeans, grain, and vegetables. The Trans-Siberian Railway runs directly through the oblast from west to east, serving as a vital transport link for both passengers and freight.\n\n## History & culture\nThe Soviet government established the Jewish Autonomous Oblast in 1934. Joseph Stalin intended the territory to serve as a secular, socialist alternative to Zionism, providing a homeland for the Jewish population of the Soviet Union. Although thousands of Jewish settlers arrived during the 1930s and late 1940s, the harsh climate, remote location, and political purges limited long-term growth. Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, a large portion of the Jewish population emigrated to Israel. Today, ethnic Jews make up less than one percent of the population, though Yiddish cultural influences remain visible in local media, street names, and public monuments.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous oblast\n* Administrative center: Birobidzhan\n* Approximate area: 36,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 150,000\n* Largest city: Birobidzhan\n* Signature features: The only autonomous oblast in Russia, and the Bira and Bidzhan rivers which run through its territory.",
    "summary": "The Jewish Autonomous Oblast is a unique federal subject of Russia located in the Russian Far East along the border with China. Established in 1934 as a Soviet homeland for Jewish people, its economy today relies on agriculture, mining, and transport along the Trans-Siberian Railway. The administrative center of Birobidzhan lies along the Bira and Bidzhan rivers, surrounded by a landscape of mountains and swampy lowlands.",
