    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nThe Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug is situated in the northern part of West Siberia, spanning the Arctic Circle. This first-level federal subject of the Russian Federation is administratively part of the Tyumen Oblast, though it retains significant autonomy. It shares borders with the Nenets Autonomous Okrug to the northwest, the Komi Republic to the west, the Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug to the south, and Krasnoyarsk Krai to the east. To the north, its extensive coastline meets the Kara Sea, which is a marginal sea of the Arctic Ocean. The territory includes major landmasses such as the Yamal, Gydan, and Taz peninsulas.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of the region is characterized by vast, flat lowlands, extensive wetlands, and thousands of lakes. The Polar Ural Mountains define the western border of the okrug, rising to elevations of over one thousand meters. The rest of the territory lies within the West Siberian Plain. The Ob River, one of the longest rivers in Asia, flows through the western portion of the region and empties into the Gulf of Ob, a massive estuary that opens into the Kara Sea. Other major river systems draining the region include the Nadym, Pur, and Taz rivers. Permafrost is continuous across most of the territory, shaping the hydrology and preventing deep root growth.\n\n## Climate\nThe region experiences a harsh subarctic climate in its southern portions and a polar tundra climate along its northern coasts and islands. Winters are long, dark, and extremely cold, lasting up to eight months. Temperatures regularly drop below minus fifty degrees Celsius. Summers are short, cool, and cloudy, with average July temperatures ranging from four to fifteen degrees Celsius. Strong winds, blizzards, and frequent fog are common due to the proximity to the Arctic Ocean.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug is centered on the extraction of hydrocarbons. The region contains more than half of Russia's natural gas reserves and significant oil deposits. Major gas fields like Urengoy, Yamburg, and Bovanenkovo fuel both domestic consumption and exports to Europe and Asia. The Yamal LNG project, centered at the port of Sabetta, has made the region a global hub for liquefied natural gas. The administrative center is Salekhard, which is notable as the only city in the world located directly on the Arctic Circle. The largest city by population is Novy Urengoy, followed closely by Noyabrsk, both of which developed as industrial centers for the gas and oil industries.\n\n## History & culture\nThe indigenous peoples of the region, including the Nenets, Khanty, and Selkup, have inhabited the area for millennia. The Nenets are famous for maintaining a nomadic lifestyle centered on large-scale reindeer herding, migrating hundreds of kilometers annually across the tundra. Russian contact began in the late sixteenth century, leading to the establishment of the fortress town of Obdorsk, now Salekhard, in 1595. The Soviet government established the national okrug in 1930. Industrialization and rapid population growth occurred in the late twentieth century following the discovery of massive natural gas fields.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous okrug\n* Administrative center: Salekhard\n* Approximate area: 750,300 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 512,000\n* Largest city: Novy Urengoy\n* Signature features: Massive natural gas reserves and traditional Nenets nomadic reindeer herding",
    "summary": "The Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug is a northern Russian region located in western Siberia along the Kara Sea, famed for its harsh subarctic climate and vast tundra landscapes. It serves as the powerhouse of Russia's natural gas industry while hosting the traditional nomadic reindeer-herding culture of the indigenous Nenets people. Its administrative center, Salekhard, is uniquely positioned directly on the Arctic Circle.",
