    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nAkita Prefecture is located in the northwestern part of the Tohoku region on Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It faces the Sea of Japan to the west. The prefecture shares land borders with four other prefectures. It is bordered by Aomori Prefecture to the north, Iwate Prefecture to the east, Miyagi Prefecture to the southeast, and Yamagata Prefecture to the south. The capital and largest city is Akita, situated on the western coast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Akita Prefecture is characterized by a mountainous interior and a coastal plain. The Ou Mountains run along the eastern border with Iwate Prefecture, while the Dewa Mountains occupy the central portion of the prefecture. Mount Chokai, an active volcano located on the southern border with Yamagata Prefecture, is one of the highest peaks in the region. The Oga Peninsula projects westward into the Sea of Japan. Major river systems include the Yoneshiro River in the north, the Omono River in the center, and the Koyoshi River in the south. Akita is home to Lake Tazawa, which is the deepest lake in Japan with a depth of roughly 423 meters. To the north, Lake Hachirogata, once the second-largest lake in Japan, was largely reclaimed for agriculture in the mid-twentieth century. Portions of the Towada-Hachimantai National Park lie within the northeastern borders of the prefecture.\n\n## Climate\nAkita experiences a humid climate with distinct seasonal changes, heavily influenced by its position on the Sea of Japan. Winters are cold and characterized by heavy snowfall, driven by seasonal winds blowing from Siberia across the sea. The mountainous areas receive particularly high accumulations of snow. Summers are relatively warm and humid, though cooler than in southern parts of Japan. Autumn and spring are transitional seasons with moderate temperatures.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Akita Prefecture is historically rooted in agriculture, forestry, and mining. Akita is one of the leading rice-producing regions in Japan, famous for the Akita Komachi rice variety. The extensive forests of the prefecture provide high-quality Akita cedar, which supports a traditional woodworking industry. Sake brewing is another major traditional industry, utilizing the local high-quality rice and clean spring water. Modern industries include electronic components, metal refining, and wind energy development along the coastline. The capital city, Akita, serves as the primary industrial and commercial hub. Other significant cities include Odate in the north, known for its timber industry, Yokote in the southeast, and Noshiro, a port city at the mouth of the Yoneshiro River.\n\n## History & culture\nDuring the Edo period, much of modern-day Akita was ruled by the Satake clan from Kubota Castle, located in the modern city of Akita. The town of Kakunodate in Senboku is famous for its well-preserved samurai district and historic merchant quarters. Akita is well known for its unique cultural traditions. The Namahage festival of the Oga Peninsula, where performers dressed as mountain demons visit homes to ward off misfortune, is recognized as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage. The Akita Kanto Festival, held in August, features performers balancing long bamboo poles laden with paper lanterns. The prefecture is also the place of origin for the Akita Inu, a historic Japanese dog breed.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Akita\n* Approximate area: 11,637 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 930,000\n* Largest city: Akita\n* Signature features: Lake Tazawa, the deepest lake in Japan, and the Namahage cultural tradition of the Oga Peninsula",
    "summary": "Akita Prefecture is a first-level administrative division located in the northwestern Tohoku region of Japan, bordered by the Sea of Japan and mountainous terrain. The region is characterized by heavy winter snowfall, a strong agricultural economy centered on rice production, and deep cultural traditions such as the Namahage festival. Its capital is the coastal city of Akita, and the prefecture is home to Lake Tazawa, the deepest lake in Japan.",
