    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nAomori Prefecture is the northernmost prefecture on Japan's main island of Honshu. It is bordered by Akita Prefecture to the south and Iwate Prefecture to the southeast. To the north, the Tsugaru Strait separates Aomori from the island of Hokkaido. The prefecture is bounded by the Sea of Japan to the west and the Pacific Ocean to the east. Mutsu Bay is a prominent body of water nearly enclosed by the Shimokita and Tsugaru Peninsulas, situated in the northern part of the prefecture.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Aomori is defined by its mountainous terrain and distinct peninsulas. The Ou Mountains run north to south, dividing the prefecture into eastern and western halves. The Hakkoda Mountains, a volcanic group, lie south of Aomori City. Mount Iwaki, an active stratovolcano often called the Tsugaru Fuji due to its symmetrical shape, is the highest peak in the prefecture at 1,625 meters. The Shirakami Sanchi mountain range, which contains the last pristine virgin forest of Siebold's beech in East Asia, spans the border between Aomori and Akita and is designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. Major rivers include the Iwaki River, which flows through the western Tsugaru Plain, and the Mabechi River in the east. Lake Towada, a large caldera lake shared with Akita Prefecture, is a major geographic feature in the south.\n\n## Climate\nAomori experiences a humid continental climate characterized by short, warm summers and long, extremely snowy winters. The western side of the prefecture, facing the Sea of Japan, receives massive amounts of snowfall due to seasonal winds blowing from Siberia across the warm Tsugaru Current. Aomori City is recognized as one of the snowiest major cities in the world, often receiving over seven meters of cumulative snowfall annually. Conversely, the eastern Pacific side of the prefecture experiences cooler summers and less winter snow, but is prone to the \"yamase\" cold winds during the summer months, which can occasionally damage agricultural crops.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAgriculture, forestry, and fisheries form the backbone of Aomori's economy. The prefecture is the leading producer of apples in Japan, primarily cultivated in the Tsugaru Plain around Hirosaki. Aomori is also a major producer of garlic, Chinese yams, and marine products, particularly scallops from Mutsu Bay. The capital and largest city is Aomori, which serves as a major transportation hub connecting Honshu to Hokkaido via the Seikan Tunnel. Other major cities include Hachinohe, an industrial port city on the Pacific coast known for its commercial fishing and manufacturing, and Hirosaki, a historic castle town and cultural center in the west. Misawa hosts a major joint military base.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, Aomori was part of Mutsu Province. The region has been inhabited since prehistoric times, as evidenced by the Sannai-Maruyama Site, a large Jomon period settlement located near Aomori City. During the Edo period, the Tsugaru clan ruled the western region from Hirosaki Castle, while the Nambu clan controlled the eastern region. This historical division persists in distinct local dialects and cultural traditions. Aomori is famous for the Nebuta Festival, held annually in August, featuring massive illuminated paper floats.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Aomori\n* Approximate area: 9,645 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,200,000\n* Largest city: Aomori\n* Signature features: Mount Iwaki, Shirakami Sanchi UNESCO World Heritage site, and the annual Nebuta Festival",
    "summary": "Aomori Prefecture is the northernmost prefecture on Japan's main island of Honshu, bordered by Akita and Iwate prefectures. It is characterized by its mountainous terrain, including the UNESCO-listed Shirakami Sanchi, and experiences some of the heaviest snowfall in the world. Economically, Aomori is Japan's leading producer of apples and is culturally famous for its historic Jomon sites and the vibrant Nebuta Festival.",
