    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nChiba Prefecture is located in the Kanto region of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is situated on the Boso Peninsula, which projects southwards into the Pacific Ocean. Chiba is bordered by Ibaraki Prefecture to the north, Saitama Prefecture to the northwest, and Tokyo Metropolis to the west. The western coast of the prefecture faces Tokyo Bay, while the eastern and southern coasts face the Pacific Ocean. The Tone River forms the northern border with Ibaraki, and the Edo River forms part of the western border with Tokyo and Saitama.\n\n## Physical features\n\nChiba is characterized by its exceptionally flat topography, having the lowest maximum elevation of any prefecture in Japan. The northern portion of the prefecture consists of the Shimosa Upland, a flat plateau composed of volcanic ash loam layers. The southern part is occupied by the Boso Hills, where Mount Atago stands as the highest point in the prefecture at approximately 408 meters above sea level. Major waterways include the Tone River, which is one of Japan's longest rivers, and the Edo River. The eastern coastline features Kujukuri Beach, a continuous sandy beach stretching for about 66 kilometers. Natural preservation areas include the Minamiboso Quasi-National Park, which protects scenic coastal landscapes in the south.\n\n## Climate\n\nChiba experiences a humid subtropical climate. The climate is moderated by the surrounding ocean waters, particularly the warm Kuroshio Current flowing along the Pacific coast. This maritime influence results in relatively mild winters with rare snowfall, and hot, humid summers. The southern Boso Peninsula enjoys warmer winter temperatures than the northern inland areas, which are more susceptible to cold winter winds from the Asian continent.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nChiba has a highly developed, dual economy that balances heavy industry with agriculture. The Keiyo Industrial Zone, stretching along the coast of Tokyo Bay, is a major national hub for petroleum refining, chemical manufacturing, and steel production. Conversely, Chiba is one of Japan's top agricultural producers, leading the nation in the production of peanuts, Japanese pears, and various vegetables. The administrative center and largest city is Chiba City. Other major cities include Funabashi, Matsudo, and Ichikawa, which function as major residential suburbs for the Tokyo metropolitan area. Narita International Airport, the primary international gateway to Japan, is located in the inland city of Narita. Additionally, Urayasu City hosts the Tokyo Disney Resort.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region of Chiba was divided into three distinct provinces: Shimosa in the north, Kazusa in the central region, and Awa in the south. During the Kamakura period, the Chiba clan established strong control over the area. In the Edo period, the region served as a vital agricultural and fishing supply zone for the capital city of Edo. The modern prefecture was created in 1873 through the merger of Kisarazu and Inba prefectures. Notable cultural sites include Naritasan Shinshoji, a major Buddhist temple complex founded in the tenth century, and the historic merchant district of Sawara in Katori City.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Chiba\n* Approximate area: 5,157 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 6,280,000\n* Largest city: Chiba\n* Signature features: Narita International Airport and Tokyo Disney Resort",
