    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\n\nNenets Autonomous Okrug is situated in the extreme northwest of the Russian Federation, lying almost entirely within the Arctic Circle. It is administratively incorporated as a first-level federal subject, though it also maintains a unique dual-subordination status as part of Arkhangelsk Oblast. The okrug is bordered by the Komi Republic to the south and southeast, the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug to the east, and Arkhangelsk Oblast proper to the southwest. Its northern boundary is defined by a long coastline along the Barents, Pechora, and Kara seas, which are marginal seas of the Arctic Ocean. The territory also encompasses several islands, most notably Kolguyev Island and Vaygach Island.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe landscape of the okrug is predominantly low-lying and flat, forming the northeastern extremity of the East European Plain. The Timan Ridge, a range of low, heavily eroded hills, extends into the western portion of the territory. In the extreme east, the northernmost slopes of the Ural Mountains mark the border with the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug. The Pechora River is the dominant hydrological feature, flowing northwards through the center of the okrug to empty into the Pechora Sea via a massive, ecologically rich delta. Other significant rivers include the Kara, Kolva, and Oma. Tundra vegetation, extensive peat bogs, and thermokarst lakes cover the majority of the terrain, underlain by continuous or discontinuous permafrost. The Nenets Nature Reserve protects the pristine wetlands of the Pechora delta.\n\n## Climate\n\nThe region experiences a harsh subarctic climate, which transitions to a polar climate on the northernmost islands and peninsulas. Winters are prolonged, windy, and severely cold, lasting from October to May, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 12 degrees Celsius in the west to minus 22 degrees Celsius in the east. Summers are brief, cloudy, and cool, with average July temperatures hovering around 10 degrees Celsius. Because of its high latitude, the okrug experiences the polar night during December and January, and the midnight sun during the peak of summer. Annual precipitation is modest, averaging between 350 and 500 millimeters, mostly falling as snow.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe modern economy is dominated by the extraction of fossil fuels, particularly petroleum and natural gas. The okrug contains substantial onshore reserves as well as offshore fields in the Pechora Sea, such as the Prirazlomnoye field. Traditional economic activities remain highly significant for the rural population, centering on large-scale reindeer husbandry, fishing, and marine mammal hunting. Naryan-Mar, the administrative center, is the only town in the okrug and serves as its primary river and sea port. Other settlements are small villages or specialized outposts, such as Amderma, a coastal settlement near the Kara Sea. Transportation infrastructure is highly limited, with no permanent year-round road or rail connections linking Naryan-Mar to the rest of Russia.\n\n## History & culture\n\nThe indigenous Nenets people, who speak a Samoyedic language, have inhabited the tundra for millennia, developing a nomadic culture centered on reindeer migration. Russian contact began in the medieval period when Novgorod merchants traded for furs. In 1499, the Russians established Pustozyorsk, the first Russian town north of the Arctic Circle, which served as a military and administrative outpost until its eventual abandonment. The Soviet government established the Nenets National Okrug in 1929, marking the first national district created for an indigenous group in the Soviet Union. Today, traditional Nenets culture coexists with the industrial oil sector, though industrial development presents ongoing challenges to traditional grazing lands.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Russian Federation\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous okrug\n* Administrative center: Naryan-Mar\n* Approximate area: 176,700 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 41,000\n* Largest city: Naryan-Mar\n* Signature features: The vast Pechora River delta and the preservation of nomadic Nenets reindeer herding traditions.",
    "summary": "Nenets Autonomous Okrug is a sparsely populated federal subject of Russia located in the Arctic region, bordered by the Barents, Pechora, and Kara seas. Its economy relies heavily on oil and gas extraction alongside traditional Nenets reindeer husbandry. The administrative center, Naryan-Mar, lies along the Pechora River, which is the region's primary waterway.",
