    "mainNotes": "## Location within Russia\nKhanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug, also known as Yugra, is located in the central part of the West Siberian Plain within the Ural Federal District of Russia. Although it is a fully functioning federal subject of the Russian Federation, it is administratively subordinated to Tyumen Oblast. Yugra shares borders with several other Russian subdivisions. It is bordered by the Yamalo-Nenets Autonomous Okrug to the north, Krasnoyarsk Krai to the east, Tomsk Oblast to the southeast, the southern portion of Tyumen Oblast to the south, Sverdlovsk Oblast to the southwest, and the Komi Republic to the west. The region occupies a strategic geographic position in the center of Russia's Siberian territory.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of the region is predominantly flat, characterized by the vast, low-lying West Siberian Plain. This terrain is heavily forested and contains extensive wetlands, bogs, and peatlands. The hydrographic network is highly developed and dominated by the Ob River and its major tributary, the Irtysh River, which meet near the administrative center of Khanty-Mansiysk. Other significant rivers include the Vakh, Agan, and Tromegan. Along the western border of the okrug rise the Ural Mountains, specifically the Subpolar Urals. The highest point in the entire Ural range, Mount Narodnaya, sits on the border between Khanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug and the Komi Republic, reaching an elevation of roughly 1,895 meters.\n\n## Climate\nThe region experiences a continental subarctic climate, categorized as Dfc under the Köppen climate classification. Winters are long, dark, and extremely cold, with average January temperatures ranging from minus 18 to minus 24 degrees Celsius. Summers are short, relatively warm, and humid, with average July temperatures between 16 and 18 degrees Celsius. Annual precipitation ranges from 400 to 600 millimeters, with most rainfall occurring during the summer months. Snow cover persists for roughly 200 days of the year, and discontinuous permafrost is present in the northernmost sectors of the okrug.\n\n## Economy & cities\nKhanty-Mansi Autonomous Okrug is the primary oil-producing region of Russia, making it one of the most economically vital subdivisions in the country. The local economy is heavily dominated by oil and natural gas extraction, refining, and pipeline transportation. Major Russian energy companies operate massive oil fields here, such as the Samotlor field near Nizhnevartovsk. While Khanty-Mansiysk serves as the administrative center, it is not the largest city. The largest city is Surgut, which acts as a major industrial and transportation hub on the Ob River. Other major industrial cities include Nizhnevartovsk, Nefteyugansk, and Kogalym.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region is the historical homeland of the Khanty and Mansi peoples, who speak Ob-Ugric languages belonging to the Uralic language family. Historically referred to as Yugra, the territory was known to medieval Novgorodians as early as the eleventh century. Russian control solidified following the campaigns of Yermak Timofeyevich in the late sixteenth century. The Ostyak-Vogul National Okrug was established in 1930, later renamed the Khanty-Mansi National Okrug in 1940, and designated an autonomous okrug in 1977. The discovery of massive oil reserves in the 1960s triggered a rapid influx of Soviet workers, transforming the demographic landscape and leaving the indigenous populations as a small minority.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Russia\n* Subdivision type: Autonomous okrug\n* Administrative center: Khanty-Mansiysk\n* Approximate area: 534,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.7 million\n* Largest city: Surgut\n* Signature features: The primary oil-producing region of the Russian Federation and the historical homeland of the Ob-Ugric Khanty and Mansi indigenous peoples.",
