    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nFukushima Prefecture is located in the southern part of the Tohoku region on the island of Honshu. It is the southernmost prefecture of Tohoku. It borders the Pacific Ocean to the east. It shares land borders with six other prefectures: Miyagi and Yamagata to the north, Niigata to the west, and Gunma, Tochigi, and Ibaraki to the south. It is the third-largest prefecture in Japan by area.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe prefecture is divided into three distinct regions from west to east by mountain ranges: Aizu, Nakadori, and Hamadori. The Ou Mountains run through the center of the prefecture, separating the inland Nakadori region from the western mountainous Aizu region. The Abukuma Highlands run parallel to the Pacific coast, separating Nakadori from the coastal Hamadori region. Significant peaks include Mount Bandai, an active volcano, and Mount Hiuchigatake, the highest point in the prefecture. Major bodies of water include Lake Inawashiro, one of the largest freshwater lakes in Japan, and the Abukuma River, which flows north through the Nakadori valley. Bandai-Asahi National Park covers a significant portion of the mountainous terrain.\n\n## Climate\n\nDue to its topography, Fukushima experiences three distinct climates. The coastal Hamadori region has a mild maritime climate with moderate winters and cool, breezy summers. The central Nakadori region has an inland climate with hot summers and cold, snowy winters. The western Aizu region experiences a heavy snow climate, influenced by winter monsoons from the Sea of Japan, resulting in deep snow cover that often persists into late spring.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nFukushima has a diverse economy. Historically, agriculture has been a major sector, known for fruit production, particularly peaches, cherries, and pears, as well as rice cultivation in the Aizu basin. The coastal region traditionally relied on commercial fishing and energy production, including nuclear and thermal power, though the 2011 earthquake and subsequent nuclear disaster severely impacted these industries. Manufacturing is concentrated in the Nakadori valley, focusing on electronic components, chemicals, and transport equipment. The administrative center is Fukushima City, located in the north of the Nakadori region. The largest city by population is Iwaki, located on the southern coast. Koriyama, situated in the center of Nakadori, serves as a major commercial and transportation hub.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region was part of Mutsu Province. During the Edo period, the Aizu domain was a powerful samurai stronghold loyal to the Tokugawa shogunate. The Boshin War of 1868 saw intense fighting here, particularly the Siege of Aizu Wakamatsu Castle, which remains a symbol of samurai resilience. Cultural traditions include the Soma Namaoi, an annual festival featuring horse-riding samurai, and Akabeko, a traditional red papier-mache cow toy believed to ward off illness. The prefecture is also famous for its sake production, frequently winning national awards for quality.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Fukushima\n* Approximate area: 13,783 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.8 million\n* Largest city: Iwaki\n* Signature features: Lake Inawashiro, Mount Bandai, and the historic samurai heritage of the Aizu region.",
    "summary": "Fukushima is Japan's third-largest prefecture, located in the southern Tohoku region of Honshu. It is divided into three distinct geographical zones, featuring a mountainous interior with Lake Inawashiro and a coastal plain along the Pacific Ocean. The prefecture is known for its agricultural output, historic samurai heritage in Aizu, and its ongoing recovery efforts following the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.",
