    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nFukui Prefecture is located in the Chubu region on the island of Honshu, facing the Sea of Japan. It is bordered by Ishikawa Prefecture to the northeast, Gifu Prefecture to the east, Shiga Prefecture to the south, and Kyoto Prefecture to the southwest. The prefecture stretches from northeast to southwest along the coast, forming a geographical bridge between the Hokuriku region and the Kansai region. The northern part of the prefecture historically corresponds to Echizen Province, while the southern part corresponds to Wakasa Province.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Fukui is characterized by a mountainous interior and a varied coastline. The Ryohaku Mountains run along the eastern border with Gifu and Ishikawa, featuring peaks such as Mount Arashima. The Kuzuryu River is the primary river system, flowing from these eastern mountains through the Fukui Plains into the Sea of Japan. The coastline is divided into two distinct sections. The northern Echizen Coast is rugged and rocky, while the southern Wakasa Coast is a highly indented ria coastline forming Wakasa Bay. This southern area includes the Five Lakes of Mikata, which are connected brackish and freshwater lakes. Lake Suigetsu, one of these lakes, is internationally famous in geochronology for its well-preserved annual sediment layers, or varves, which serve as a global standard for radiocarbon dating.\n\n## Climate\n\nFukui experiences a maritime climate typical of the Sea of Japan coast. It is characterized by high precipitation throughout the year, with particularly heavy snowfall during the winter months due to cold seasonal winds blowing from Siberia across the Sea of Japan. The mountainous eastern regions receive some of the heaviest snow accumulations in Japan. Summers are warm, humid, and relatively short, occasionally influenced by Foehn winds crossing the central mountain ranges, which can raise temperatures significantly.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe capital and largest city is Fukui, which serves as the administrative and commercial hub. Sabae is globally recognized for its precision manufacturing, producing over 90 percent of Japan's optical frames. The city of Katsuyama is a major center for paleontology, home to the largest dinosaur fossil excavation site in Japan. In the south, Tsuruga is an important port city and transportation choke point connecting the Sea of Japan with the Kansai region. The coastal area of Wakasa Bay hosts a high concentration of commercial nuclear power plants, which historically supplied a significant portion of the electricity for the Kansai metropolitan area. Traditional industries also remain vital, including Echizen washi paper, Echizen cutlery, and lacquerware.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region was divided into Echizen and Wakasa provinces. During the Sengoku period, the Asakura clan ruled Echizen from Ichijodani, the ruins of which are now a major archaeological site. Fukui is home to Eihei-ji, one of the two head temples of the Soto school of Zen Buddhism, founded by Dogen Zenji in 1244. Maruoka Castle, located in Sakai, features one of the oldest surviving original castle keeps in Japan, dating back to 1576. The prefecture's culinary culture is famous for Echizen crab and winter mizu-yokan, a soft red bean jelly.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Fukui\n* Approximate area: 4,190 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 760,000\n* Largest city: Fukui\n* Signature features: The Fukui Prefectural Dinosaur Museum in Katsuyama and the historic Eihei-ji Zen Temple.",
