    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nFukuoka Prefecture is located on the northern coast of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It borders Saga Prefecture to the west, Kumamoto Prefecture to the south, and Oita Prefecture to the east. To the north, it faces the Tsushima Strait, which separates Japan from the Korean Peninsula, and the Kanmon Straits, which separate Kyushu from Honshu, specifically Yamaguchi Prefecture. This geographic position makes Fukuoka a critical gateway between Honshu and Kyushu, as well as a historical point of contact between Japan and the Asian mainland.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe prefecture features a diverse landscape of plains, basins, and mountainous regions. The Tsukushi Mountains run through the center of the prefecture, dividing it into northern and southern regions. Notable peaks include Mount Hiko on the border with Oita and Mount Sefuri on the border with Saga. Major lowlands include the Fukuoka Plain in the west, the Chikugo Plain in the south, which is the largest agricultural plain in Kyushu, and the Kurate Plain in the north. The Chikugo River, the longest river in Kyushu, flows through the southern part of the prefecture and empties into the Ariake Sea. Other significant waterways include the Onga River and the Naka River. Fukuoka possesses three distinct coastlines: the Genkai Sea to the north, the Suo Sea to the northeast, and the Ariake Sea to the south. Genkai Quasi-National Park protects scenic coastal areas along the northern shore.\n\n## Climate\n\nFukuoka has a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm, wet summers and mild winters. Winters are generally mild, though cold winds blowing across the Sea of Japan can bring overcast skies and occasional light snowfall. Summers are hot and humid, with temperatures frequently exceeding 30 degrees Celsius. The prefecture experiences a distinct rainy season from June to July, known as the tsuyu. Typhoons are a regular occurrence in late summer and early autumn, bringing heavy rainfall and strong winds, particularly to coastal areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nFukuoka is the economic powerhouse of Kyushu, featuring a diverse economy driven by services, manufacturing, and agriculture. Fukuoka City, the administrative center, is a major commercial, retail, and startup hub, particularly strong in the service and technology sectors. Kitakyushu, the second-largest city, is a major industrial center that historically anchored Japan's heavy industry through steel production, and it has transitioned toward green technology and robotics. Kurume is known for rubber manufacturing, while Omuta was historically a major coal mining center. Agriculture thrives in the fertile Chikugo Plain, which is famous for producing Amaou strawberries, rice, and Yame green tea.\n\n## History & culture\n\nDue to its proximity to mainland Asia, Fukuoka has historically served as Japan's primary gateway for foreign trade and cultural exchange. In the late seventh century, the imperial government established Dazaifu as the administrative center for Kyushu to handle foreign relations with China and Korea. During the thirteenth century, Hakata Bay was the site of the Mongol invasions of Japan, prompting the construction of defensive stone walls known as Genko Borui. Hakata, now a ward of Fukuoka City, has a long history as a prosperous merchant port. Cultural traditions include the Hakata Gion Yamakasa festival, which features massive wooden floats, and the production of Hakata clay dolls. The local cuisine is highly regarded, featuring tonkotsu ramen, motsunabe, and mentaiko.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Fukuoka\n* Approximate area: 4,986 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.1 million\n* Largest city: Fukuoka\n* Signature features: The historic ruins of Dazaifu and the annual Hakata Gion Yamakasa festival.",
