    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nAichi Prefecture is located in the Chubu region of central Honshu, the main island of Japan. It occupies a strategic position connecting eastern and western Japan. Aichi is bordered by Mie Prefecture to the west, Gifu Prefecture to the north, Nagano Prefecture to the northeast, and Shizuoka Prefecture to the east. To the south, the prefecture faces the Pacific Ocean, with its coastline deeply indented by Ise Bay and Mikawa Bay.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Aichi is divided into two distinct regions. The western portion is dominated by the fertile Nobi Plain, which is the second-largest plain in Japan. This plain is drained by the Kiso Three Rivers, which are the Kiso, Ibi, and Nagara Rivers, as well as the Shonai River. In contrast, the eastern portion of the prefecture is characterized by the Mikawa Highlands and low mountains. Mount Chausu is the highest peak in Aichi, reaching an elevation of 1,415 meters on the border with Nagano Prefecture. The coastline features two prominent peninsulas. The Chita Peninsula extends south on the west side of Mikawa Bay, while the Atsumi Peninsula extends west on the south side, sheltering the bay from the open Pacific Ocean. Natural conservation areas include the Tenryu-Okumikawa Quasi-National Park and the Mikawa Wan Quasi-National Park.\n\n## Climate\nAichi Prefecture generally experiences a humid subtropical climate. Summers are hot and humid, with temperatures in Nagoya often exceeding 30 degrees Celsius due to the heat island effect and the surrounding topography. Winters are relatively mild and dry, though the western plains occasionally experience cold, strong winds known as Ibuki-oroshi, which blow from the northwest and can bring light snowfall. The mountainous northeastern region experiences cooler temperatures year-round and receives heavier snowfall during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAichi is the leading industrial prefecture in Japan, consistently ranking at the top in terms of manufactured goods shipment value. The prefecture is the global headquarters of Toyota Motor Corporation, which is located in the city of Toyota. Other major industries include aerospace, machine tools, and traditional ceramics, with Seto and Tokoname being historically famous for pottery. Nagoya is the administrative center and the largest city, acting as the economic hub of the Chubu region. The Port of Nagoya is one of the largest and busiest ports in Japan by cargo tonnage. Other major cities include Toyohashi, Okazaki, Ichinomiya, and Kasugai. Chubu Centrair International Airport, built on an artificial island in Ise Bay, serves as the primary international gateway.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the area of Aichi was divided into two provinces: Owari in the west and Mikawa in the east. The region is highly significant in Japanese history as the birthplace of the three great unifiers of the Sengoku period: Oda Nobunaga, Toyotomi Hideyoshi, and Tokugawa Ieyasu. Nagoya Castle, built in 1612 by Tokugawa Ieyasu, remains a central cultural landmark, famous for the golden shachihoko statues on its roof. Traditional cultural assets include Seto ware ceramics and Arimatsu tie-dyed textiles.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Nagoya\n* Approximate area: 5,173 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7,500,000\n* Largest city: Nagoya\n* Signature features: Global headquarters of Toyota Motor Corporation and the historic Nagoya Castle.",
    "summary": "Aichi Prefecture is a major administrative and industrial hub located in the Chubu region of central Honshu, Japan, centered around its capital city of Nagoya. The prefecture features a diverse geography of the fertile Nobi Plain, mountainous highlands, and two major peninsulas enclosing Mikawa Bay. It is globally renowned as the birthplace of Japan's three great historical unifiers and as the headquarters of Toyota Motor Corporation.",
