    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nEhime Prefecture is located in the northwestern part of Shikoku, the smallest of the four main islands of the Japanese archipelago. It is bordered by Kagawa Prefecture to the northeast, Tokushima Prefecture to the east, and Kochi Prefecture to the south. To the north, Ehime faces the Seto Inland Sea, which separates Shikoku from the main island of Honshu. To the west, it borders the Uwa Sea, a body of water connected to the Pacific Ocean. The Kurushima Strait and other narrow channels separate Ehime from Hiroshima Prefecture, though they are connected by the Shimanami Kaido bridge system.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Ehime is highly varied, characterized by steep mountains and a deeply indented coastline. The Ishizuchi Mountain Range dominates the central and eastern parts of the prefecture. Mount Ishizuchi, standing at 1,982 meters, is the tallest peak in western Japan and is considered a sacred mountain. In the west, the Sadamisaki Peninsula extends approximately 40 kilometers into the Seto Inland Sea, making it the narrowest and longest peninsula in Japan. Major rivers include the Hijikawa River, known for its dramatic morning mists, and the Shigenobu River, which waters the Matsuyama Plain. The coastal areas are part of two major national parks: Setonaikai National Park in the north and Ashizuri-Uwakai National Park in the southwest, the latter famous for its marine life and coral reefs.\n\n## Climate\n\nEhime generally experiences a mild, temperate climate, but regional variations exist due to its mountainous terrain. The northern coastal area along the Seto Inland Sea has a Mediterranean-like climate, characterized by warm temperatures, abundant sunshine, and relatively low annual rainfall. This dry, sunny weather is highly favorable for citrus cultivation. In contrast, the southern mountainous regions and the areas facing the open Uwa Sea receive significantly higher levels of precipitation and can experience heavy snowfall in the high-altitude zones during winter.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Ehime is diverse, balancing agriculture, manufacturing, and heavy industry. The prefecture is famous nationwide for its citrus production, particularly mikan (satsuma mandarins), which thrive on the sunny, terraced hillsides. Aquaculture is highly developed along the Uwa Sea coast, where red sea bream and pearls are farmed. Matsuyama, the administrative center and largest city, is a hub for administration, tourism, and light manufacturing. Imabari, located in the north, is renowned for its high-quality towel manufacturing and major shipbuilding industries. The cities of Niihama and Saijo form an industrial belt along the northern coast, hosting chemical plants, non-ferrous metal refineries, and machinery factories.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as Iyo Province, Ehime has a rich cultural heritage. During the feudal era, the region was divided into several domains, leaving behind historic castles such as Matsuyama Castle and Uwajima Castle, which feature original surviving keeps. The coastal waters were historically controlled by the Murakami Suigun, a powerful medieval naval clan often described as pirates who secured the shipping lanes of the Seto Inland Sea. Ehime is home to Dogo Onsen, located in Matsuyama, which is widely regarded as one of the oldest hot spring resorts in Japan, with references dating back over a thousand years. The prefecture is also a key segment of the Shikoku Pilgrimage, a 1,200-kilometer route visiting 88 Buddhist temples associated with the monk Kobo Daishi.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Matsuyama\n* Approximate area: 5,676 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,300,000\n* Largest city: Matsuyama (same as administrative center)\n* Signature features: Dogo Onsen hot spring, Mount Ishizuchi, and high-volume mikan citrus cultivation.",
    "summary": "Ehime Prefecture is located in northwestern Shikoku, bordered by the Seto Inland Sea and characterized by a mountainous interior featuring Mount Ishizuchi. The region is economically diverse, known for its heavy industry in the north, extensive citrus cultivation, and traditional aquaculture along the western coast. Its cultural highlights include the historic Matsuyama Castle and Dogo Onsen, one of Japan's oldest hot spring resorts.",
    "model": "gemini-3.5-flash"
