    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nGunma Prefecture is a landlocked first-level administrative division located in the northwestern corner of the Kanto region on the island of Honshu, Japan. It is bordered by five other prefectures: Tochigi to the east, Saitama to the south, Nagano to the west, Niigata to the north, and Fukushima to the northeast. Because of its shape on the map, Gunma is often compared to a crane in flight, a motif celebrated in local culture. Its central location on Honshu makes it a vital transit corridor connecting the Tokyo metropolitan area with the Sea of Japan coast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Gunma is highly mountainous, with over two-thirds of its land area covered by hills and mountains. The northern and western borders are defined by rugged ranges, including the Mikuni Mountains. Among the most prominent peaks are the Jomo Sanzan, or the Three Mountains of Jomo, which consist of Mount Akagi, Mount Haruna, and Mount Myogi. Mount Asama, an active complex volcano, sits on the border with Nagano Prefecture, while Mount Kusatsu-Shirane is another notable active volcanic peak. The Tone River, which has the largest drainage basin in Japan, originates in the northern mountains of Gunma and flows southward through the prefecture. Oze National Park, shared with neighboring prefectures, features high-altitude marshes and unique alpine flora.\n\n## Climate\nGunma experiences a wide variation in climate between its mountainous north and its southern plains. The southern region has a humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters. A defining meteorological phenomenon of the prefecture is the karakkaze, a strong, dry winter wind that sweeps down from the northern mountains across the Kanto Plain. In contrast, the northern mountainous areas experience a subarctic climate with heavy winter snowfall, making the region a major destination for winter sports. Summer afternoons in the plains often bring severe thunderstorms due to convective activity over the surrounding peaks.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Gunma is highly industrialized, particularly in the southern plains. It is a major center for transport equipment manufacturing, with Subaru operating several large production facilities in the city of Ota. Other key industries include chemical manufacturing, metal products, and food processing. In agriculture, Gunma is a leading producer of cabbage, particularly from the highland fields of Tsumagoi, and konjac, a gelatinous food product made from corm tubers. The administrative center is Maebashi, but the largest city by population is Takasaki, which serves as a critical railway hub where the Joetsu and Hokuriku Shinkansen lines diverge. Other major industrial cities include Kiryu, Isesaki, and Ota.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically known as Kozuke Province, Gunma was a prosperous region during the Edo period. It became a global center for sericulture and silk manufacturing during the Meiji Restoration. The Tomioka Silk Mill, established in 1872 as Japan's first modern steam-powered silk reeling factory, is designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Gunma is also famous for its traditional hot spring resorts, or onsen, with Kusatsu, Ikaho, Minakami, and Shima being among the most celebrated in Japan. Culturally, the prefecture is famous for producing Takasaki Daruma dolls, which symbolize perseverance and good luck.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Maebashi\n* Approximate area: 6,362 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,900,000\n* Largest city: Takasaki\n* Signature features: Tomioka Silk Mill and Kusatsu Onsen",
    "summary": "Gunma Prefecture is a landlocked, mountainous region in central Honshu known for its heavy industry, agricultural output, and historic silk production. It features prominent volcanic peaks, the headwaters of the Tone River, and world-famous hot spring resorts like Kusatsu. While Maebashi serves as the administrative capital, Takasaki is the largest city and a major transportation hub.",
