    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nHiroshima Prefecture is located in the southwestern part of Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It occupies a central position within the Chugoku region. The prefecture shares land borders with four other prefectures: Yamaguchi to the west, Shimane to the northwest, Tottori to the northeast, and Okayama to the east. To the south, Hiroshima faces the Seto Inland Sea, which separates Honshu from the island of Shikoku. The maritime border across this sea connects Hiroshima to Ehime Prefecture.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Hiroshima Prefecture is characterized by a mountainous interior and a deeply indented coastline. The Chugoku Mountains run along the northern border with Shimane and Tottori, with Mount Osorakan being one of the highest peaks in the prefecture at approximately 1,346 meters. The southern portion of the prefecture consists of coastal plains and the Seto Inland Sea, which contains over 140 islands belonging to Hiroshima, including Itsukushima and Kurahashi. The Ota River is the primary river system in the west, flowing south into Hiroshima Bay and forming a large delta that supports the capital city. In the east, the Ashida River flows through Fukuyama. The northern highlands drain partly into the Gono River, which flows northward into the Sea of Japan. Much of the coastal area is protected within the Setonaikai National Park.\n\n## Climate\nHiroshima Prefecture experiences two distinct climatic zones due to the Chugoku Mountains. The southern coastal region features a Seto Inland Sea climate, which is characterized by mild temperatures, low annual rainfall, and high numbers of sunny days throughout the year. In contrast, the northern mountainous region experiences a Sea of Japan climate. This northern area is subject to cold winds from the Asian continent, resulting in heavy winter snowfall, cooler average temperatures, and higher precipitation levels.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Hiroshima Prefecture is highly industrialized, with a strong emphasis on heavy manufacturing, automotive production, and shipbuilding. The prefecture is home to the global headquarters of the Mazda Motor Corporation, located in Fuchu and Hiroshima City. Kure is a historic center for shipbuilding and naval engineering, while Fukuyama, the second-largest city, is known for its massive steel production facilities. Agriculture and aquaculture also play vital roles, with Hiroshima being Japan's top producer of farmed oysters. The major urban centers are Hiroshima, Fukuyama, Kure, Higashihiroshima, and Onomichi.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the area of Hiroshima was divided into the provinces of Aki in the west and Bingo in the east. Hiroshima City was established as a castle town by the warlord Mori Terumoto in 1589. During the Meiji period, the region developed into a major military and industrial hub. On August 6, 1945, Hiroshima became the first city in history to be devastated by an atomic bomb. The post-war era saw the prefecture rebuild itself as a global symbol of peace. Hiroshima features two UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the Itsukushima Shrine on Miyajima, famous for its floating torii gate, and the Hiroshima Peace Memorial, also known as the Genbaku Dome.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Hiroshima\n* Approximate area: 8,479 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,800,000\n* Largest city: Hiroshima (same as administrative center)\n* Signature features: Hiroshima Peace Memorial Park and the Itsukushima Shrine floating torii gate",
    "summary": "Hiroshima Prefecture is located in the Chugoku region of western Honshu, bordering the Seto Inland Sea to the south and the Chugoku Mountains to the north. The prefecture is a major industrial hub known for automotive manufacturing, shipbuilding, and steel production, alongside its famous oyster aquaculture. It is globally recognized for its commitment to peace, symbolized by the Hiroshima Peace Memorial and the historic Itsukushima Shrine.",
