    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nIshikawa Prefecture is located on the coast of the Sea of Japan in the Chubu region of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It occupies a narrow strip of land running southwest to northeast. The northern portion of the prefecture consists of the prominent Noto Peninsula, which juts out into the Sea of Japan. Ishikawa is bordered by Toyama Prefecture to the east, Gifu Prefecture to the southeast, and Fukui Prefecture to the south. Its strategic coastal position historically connected it to maritime trade routes across the Sea of Japan.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Ishikawa is divided into two distinct regions: the mountainous, coastal Noto Peninsula in the north and the flatter Kaga region in the south. The Noto Peninsula features rugged coastlines, low hills, and marine terraces, with the Sosogi Coast showcasing dramatic rock formations. In contrast, the southern Kaga region is dominated by the Kaga Plain, which is bordered to the east by the Ryohaku Mountains. The highest peak in the prefecture is Mount Haku, also known as Hakusan, which stands at 2,702 meters on the border with Gifu Prefecture. Mount Haku is recognized as one of Japan's three holy mountains, alongside Mount Fuji and Mount Tate. Major rivers include the Tedori River, which flows from Mount Haku to the Sea of Japan, and the Sai River. Conservation areas include Hakusan National Park and Noto Hanto Quasi-National Park. Kenroku-en, located in Kanazawa, is celebrated as one of the Three Great Gardens of Japan.\n\n## Climate\n\nIshikawa experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm, humid summers and cold, snowy winters. The prefecture is part of the \"snow country\" region of Japan. During winter, cold seasonal winds blowing from Siberia pick up moisture over the warm waters of the Sea of Japan, resulting in heavy snowfall, particularly in the mountainous southern areas. Summers are warm and often rainy, influenced by the East Asian monsoon. Precipitation is high throughout the year, with no distinct dry season.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe capital and largest city of Ishikawa is Kanazawa, which serves as the economic and cultural hub of the prefecture. Other major urban centers include Komatsu, Nanao, Kaga, and Wajima. The economy is diverse, blending heavy manufacturing with traditional industries. Komatsu is globally famous as the birthplace and namesake of Komatsu Limited, a major manufacturer of construction and mining equipment. Textile manufacturing, particularly synthetic fibers, is another key industrial sector. Traditional crafts contribute significantly to the local economy. Kanazawa produces over 90 percent of Japan's gold leaf, while Wajima is renowned for its high-quality lacquerware, and the southern region is known for Kutani ware porcelain. Agriculture focuses on rice cultivation in the Kaga Plain, while coastal fisheries exploit the rich waters of the Sea of Japan.\n\n## History & culture\n\nDuring the Edo period, the region was the core of the Kaga Domain, ruled by the powerful Maeda clan. The domain was the wealthiest in Japan outside of the Tokugawa shogunate's direct holdings, fostering a rich cultural heritage. Because Kanazawa was largely spared from destruction during World War II, much of its historic architecture remains intact. This includes Kanazawa Castle, the historic Higashi Chaya geisha district, and preserved samurai residences. The prefecture is also famous for traditional performing arts, including Noh theater, and its distinctive culinary traditions that utilize fresh seafood and local vegetables.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kanazawa\n* Approximate area: 4,186 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,110,000\n* Largest city: Kanazawa\n* Signature features: The Noto Peninsula, Mount Haku, Kenroku-en Garden, and traditional gold leaf production.",
    "summary": "Ishikawa Prefecture is located on the Sea of Japan coast of Honshu island and is characterized by the rugged Noto Peninsula and the mountainous Kaga region. Its capital, Kanazawa, is a major cultural center famous for historic architecture, traditional crafts like gold leaf, and the Kenroku-en garden. The prefecture's economy relies on a mix of heavy machinery manufacturing, agriculture, and traditional artisan industries.",
    "model": "gemini-3.5-flash"
