    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nHokkaido is the northernmost and second-largest island of Japan, constituting its own first-level prefecture. It is surrounded by the Pacific Ocean to the east and south, the Sea of Japan to the west, and the Sea of Okhotsk to the north. The Tsugaru Strait separates Hokkaido from Honshu, the main island of Japan, to the south, though the two islands are connected by the undersea Seikan Tunnel. To the north, the La Perouse Strait separates the island from Sakhalin Island, Russia. To the northeast lie the Kuril Islands. Japan claims the four southernmost islands of this chain, which it refers to as the Northern Territories, though they are currently administered by Russia in a long-standing territorial dispute.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Hokkaido is characterized by a central mountainous spine running north to south. The highest peak is Mount Asahi, also known as Asahidake, which reaches an elevation of 2,291 meters within the Daisetsuzan volcanic group. Active volcanoes are common, feeding numerous hot springs throughout the prefecture. Major lowlands include the Ishikari Plain in the west and the Tokachi Plain in the southeast. The Ishikari River is the longest river on the island and the third longest in Japan, while the Teshio River flows north to the Sea of Japan. Hokkaido is also home to notable lakes, including Lake Toya, Lake Shikotsu, and Lake Saroma. Protected areas are vast, with Daisetsuzan National Park and the Shiretoko National Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site, preserving pristine wilderness.\n\n## Climate\nHokkaido experiences a humid continental climate, distinguishing it from the subtropical climate of southern Japan. The island does not experience the typical June rainy season, known as tsuyu, and summer humidity is low. Winters are long, cold, and snowy. Freezing winds from Siberia pick up moisture over the Sea of Japan, resulting in heavy snowfall on the western side of the island. Summers are short and mild, with average temperatures in August ranging from 17 to 22 degrees Celsius. The Sea of Okhotsk coast is famous for winter drift ice, which flows south from the Amur River basin.\n\n## Economy & cities\nHokkaido possesses a resource-rich economy. It is the agricultural heartland of Japan, producing a large share of the nation's dairy, wheat, potatoes, sugar beets, and onions. Forestry and commercial fishing are also highly developed, with major catches of salmon, crab, and kelp. Sapporo is the administrative center and largest city, acting as the primary economic and cultural hub. Other major cities include Asahikawa, a central industrial city, Hakodate, a historic southern port, and Kushiro, a major eastern fishing port. Tourism is a major economic driver, drawing visitors for winter sports, summer hiking, and hot spring resorts.\n\n## History & culture\nThe indigenous Ainu people are the original inhabitants of Hokkaido, possessing a distinct language and culture closely tied to the natural environment. Historically known to the Japanese as Ezo, the island was officially renamed Hokkaido in 1869 during the Meiji Restoration. The Japanese government established the Development Commission to actively colonize the island and exploit its resources. American advisors were brought in to introduce Western agricultural methods and urban planning, which is reflected in the grid system of Sapporo. The Ainu faced decades of forced assimilation, but recent legislation has officially recognized them as an indigenous people, prompting cultural preservation efforts.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Sapporo\n* Approximate area: 83,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.1 million\n* Largest city: Sapporo\n* Signature features: Heavy winter snowfall with world-class ski resorts, and the unique indigenous cultural heritage of the Ainu people.",
    "summary": "Hokkaido is Japan's northernmost and largest prefecture, characterized by its mountainous terrain, volcanic activity, and humid continental climate. The region has a resource-based economy centered on agriculture, fishing, and tourism, with Sapporo serving as its primary administrative and cultural hub. It is also historically significant as the homeland of the indigenous Ainu people.",
    "model": "gemini-3.5-flash"
