    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nIbaraki Prefecture is situated in the northeastern part of the Kanto region on Honshu, the main island of Japan. It faces the Pacific Ocean to the east, providing the prefecture with a long coastline. Ibaraki shares land borders with Fukushima Prefecture to the north, Tochigi Prefecture to the west, Saitama Prefecture to the southwest, and Chiba Prefecture to the south. The Tone River serves as a natural boundary separating Ibaraki from Chiba Prefecture. Its proximity to Tokyo, located just south of Chiba and Saitama, makes southern Ibaraki an important part of the Greater Tokyo Area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Ibaraki is characterized by a contrast between mountainous northern regions and flat southern plains. The northern third of the prefecture is occupied by the Yamizo Mountains, where Mount Yamizo stands as the highest peak at 1,022 meters. In the central-western region, Mount Tsukuba rises to 877 meters, featuring distinctive double peaks that make it a prominent landmark on the Kanto Plain. The southern and central areas belong to the flat, fertile Kanto Plain. Ibaraki is home to Lake Kasumigaura, which is the second-largest lake in Japan and a major source of irrigation and fishing. The Naka and Kuji rivers flow through the central and northern parts of the prefecture into the Pacific Ocean, while the Tone River drains the southern border.\n\n## Climate\nIbaraki generally experiences a humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and relatively cold, dry winters. The climate varies between the coastal areas and the inland mountainous regions. The northern mountains receive colder temperatures and occasional heavy winter snowfall. In contrast, the coastal areas are moderated by the Pacific Ocean, resulting in milder winters and cooler summer breezes. The average annual precipitation ranges from 1,300 to 1,500 millimeters, with the heaviest rainfall occurring during the summer monsoon season and the autumn typhoon season.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Ibaraki is highly diversified, balancing agriculture, heavy industry, and advanced scientific research. It is one of Japan's leading agricultural prefectures, producing large quantities of melons, sweet potatoes, lotus root, and pears. The city of Hitachi, located along the northern coast, is the historic birthplace of the global electronics conglomerate Hitachi, Ltd., and remains an industrial powerhouse. Kashima, in the southeast, features a large deep-water port and serves as a major hub for steel production and petrochemical industries. Tsukuba, located in the south, is designated as Tsukuba Science City, hosting dozens of national research institutes and Tsukuba University. Mito, the administrative center, serves as the commercial and political heart of the prefecture.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically known as Hitachi Province, the region played a significant role during the Edo period. The Mito Domain was ruled by the Mito branch of the Tokugawa clan, which was one of the three powerful branches eligible to produce a shogun. Mito is famous for Kairaku-en, a landscape garden built in 1842 by Tokugawa Nariaki. It is celebrated as one of the Three Great Gardens of Japan, particularly famous for its thousands of blooming plum trees in early spring. The prefecture is also famous for natto, a traditional fermented soybean dish originating from Mito. Mount Tsukuba has been celebrated in Japanese poetry for centuries, often contrasted with Mount Fuji.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Mito\n* Approximate area: 6,097 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.86 million\n* Largest city: Mito\n* Signature features: Lake Kasumigaura, Tsukuba Science City, and Kairaku-en Garden",
    "summary": "Ibaraki Prefecture is located in Japan's northeastern Kanto region, featuring a diverse landscape of northern mountains, the flat Kanto Plain, and the Pacific coastline. The prefecture is a major hub for agriculture, heavy industry, and scientific research, notably centered in Tsukuba Science City. Its capital is Mito, a city historically significant as the seat of the Mito Tokugawa branch and home to the famous Kairaku-en Garden.",
