    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nIwate Prefecture is located in the Tohoku region on the northeastern portion of Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It is bordered by Aomori Prefecture to the north, Akita Prefecture to the west, and Miyagi Prefecture to the south. The eastern boundary of the prefecture is defined entirely by its long coastline along the Pacific Ocean. Iwate is the second-largest prefecture in Japan by total area, surpassed only by Hokkaido, making it the largest prefecture on the main island of Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Iwate is characterized by two parallel mountain ranges running north to south. The Ou Mountains form the western border with Akita Prefecture and contain several volcanic peaks, including Mount Iwate, which is the highest point in the prefecture at 2,038 meters. To the east, the older, gentler Kitakami Mountains run parallel to the coast. Between these two ranges lies the fertile Kitakami River basin, where the majority of the population and agricultural land are concentrated. The Kitakami River flows south into Miyagi Prefecture. The eastern coastline, known as the Sanriku Coast, features dramatic geographical contrasts. The northern section consists of high sea cliffs, while the southern section is a classic ria coastline with deep inlets and narrow bays. This coastal area is preserved within the Sanriku Fukko National Park, while the volcanic highlands in the northwest are part of Towada-Hachimantai National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nIwate features a diverse climate influenced by its mountainous terrain and ocean currents. The inland basin experiences a humid continental climate with cold, snowy winters and hot, humid summers. The western mountainous areas receive heavy snowfall due to winter winds blowing from the Sea of Japan across the Ou Mountains. In contrast, the coastal region has a maritime climate. Summers on the coast are often kept cool by the Yamase, a cold easterly wind that can bring fog and lower temperatures, occasionally affecting agricultural yields. Winters on the coast are generally milder and experience much less snowfall than the inland areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Iwate relies on a mix of primary industries and modern manufacturing. The fertile central valley is a major producer of rice, apples, and livestock, particularly Maesawa beef. The Sanriku Coast is one of the world's richest fishing grounds, supporting a major commercial fishing and aquaculture industry focused on seaweed, oysters, and sea urchins. In recent decades, the Kitakami valley has developed into an industrial corridor, attracting semiconductor, automobile, and precision instrument manufacturing. Morioka, the administrative center and largest city, serves as the commercial and transport hub. Other major cities include Hanamaki, which hosts the regional airport, Kitakami and Ichinoseki in the industrial south, and Miyako and Kamaishi along the Pacific coast.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, Iwate was part of Mutsu Province. During the late Heian period, the Northern Fujiwara clan established a powerful, semi-independent realm centered in Hiraizumi. This city rivaled Kyoto in cultural sophistication, and its surviving temples and gardens, such as Chuson-ji and Motsu-ji, are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. Traditional crafts remain highly valued, notably Nanbu Tekki, a form of durable cast ironware produced in Morioka and Oshu. The prefecture is also famous for its culinary traditions, including Wanko Soba, a style of serving buckwheat noodles in rapid succession. Iwate is the birthplace of several influential cultural figures, including the early twentieth-century poet and children's author Kenji Miyazawa.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Morioka\n* Approximate area: 15,275 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,200,000\n* Largest city: Morioka\n* Signature features: The rugged Sanriku Coast and the UNESCO World Heritage historic monuments of Hiraizumi.",
    "summary": "Iwate Prefecture is the second-largest prefecture in Japan, located in the northern Tohoku region of Honshu with its capital at Morioka. Its geography is defined by the central Kitakami River valley situated between the Ou and Kitakami mountain ranges, ending in the dramatic Sanriku Coast to the east. The region is known for its rich agricultural and fishing industries, historic Heian-period temples in Hiraizumi, and traditional Nanbu ironware.",
