    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nKagoshima Prefecture is located at the southwestern tip of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It also encompasses a long chain of islands stretching hundreds of kilometers southwest toward Okinawa Prefecture. Kagoshima is bordered by Kumamoto Prefecture to the north and Miyazaki Prefecture to the northeast. Its extensive coastline faces the East China Sea to the west and the Pacific Ocean to the south and east. The prefecture occupies a strategic maritime position, historically serving as a gateway for trade and cultural exchange between Japan and the rest of Asia.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Kagoshima is highly volcanic and mountainous. The central feature of the prefecture is Kagoshima Bay, also known as Kinko Bay, which is dominated by Sakurajima, one of the most active volcanoes in the world. Sakurajima was formerly an island but became connected to the Osumi Peninsula following a massive eruption in 1914. To the north lies the Kirishima volcanic group, which features numerous crater lakes and active vents. The prefecture's territory includes several major islands, most notably Yakushima, which is famous for its ancient cedar forests and high peaks like Mount Miyanoura, the tallest mountain in Kyushu. The Amami Islands, located further south, feature coral reefs and subtropical ecosystems. Major rivers draining the mainland include the Sendai River in the northwest and the Kimotsuki River in the southeast.\n\n## Climate\n\nKagoshima experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by hot, humid summers and mild, relatively dry winters. The prefecture receives high annual precipitation, often exceeding 2,000 millimeters in the lowlands and much higher amounts in mountainous areas like Yakushima. Summers are marked by frequent typhoons, which regularly impact the region between July and October. Winter temperatures rarely drop below freezing in the coastal areas, though snowfall is common in the high mountain ranges of Kirishima and Yakushima.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kagoshima relies heavily on agriculture, food processing, and heavy industries. It is a leading producer of sweet potatoes, green tea, and radishes, particularly the giant Sakurajima radish. Livestock farming is highly developed, with Kagoshima being famous for its black pork, known as Kurobuta, and high-quality beef. The prefecture also hosts advanced technological facilities, including the Tanegashima Space Center and the Uchinoura Space Center, which are central to Japan's space exploration program. The capital and largest city is Kagoshima, which serves as the political, economic, and cultural hub. Other major cities include Kirishima, known for its hot springs and industries, Kanoya on the Osumi Peninsula, and Satsumasendai on the western coast.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as the Satsuma Domain, the region was ruled for centuries by the powerful Shimazu clan. Satsuma played a pivotal role in the Meiji Restoration of 1868, which ended the Tokugawa shogunate and modernized Japan. Prominent historical figures from Kagoshima include Saigo Takamori and Okubo Toshimichi. The cultural heritage of the prefecture is reflected in Satsuma ware, a distinctive style of Japanese pottery, and the traditional production of shochu, a distilled alcoholic beverage made from sweet potatoes.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kagoshima\n* Approximate area: 9,187 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,560,000\n* Largest city: Kagoshima (same as administrative center)\n* Signature features: Sakurajima active volcano, Yakushima UNESCO World Heritage site, and the Tanegashima Space Center.",
    "summary": "Kagoshima is a prefecture located at the southwestern tip of Kyushu, Japan, known for its volcanic landscape dominated by the active volcano Sakurajima. It features a subtropical climate, a strong agricultural economy famous for sweet potatoes and black pork, and key space exploration facilities on its southern islands. Historically known as the Satsuma Domain, the region played a crucial role in the modernization of Japan during the Meiji Restoration.",
