    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nKagawa Prefecture is located on the island of Shikoku, which is the smallest of the four main islands of Japan. It is situated in the northeastern corner of Shikoku. Kagawa is bordered by Ehime Prefecture to the west and Tokushima Prefecture to the south. To the north and east, it faces the Seto Inland Sea, which separates Shikoku from the main island of Honshu. The Great Seto Bridge spans this body of water, connecting Kagawa directly to Okayama Prefecture on Honshu. Kagawa is officially the smallest prefecture in Japan by land area, a status it has held since the reclamation of land in Chiba Prefecture altered previous rankings.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe geography of Kagawa is characterized by the Sanuki Mountains running along its southern border with Tokushima Prefecture. The highest point in the prefecture is Mount Ryuo, which rises to an elevation of 1,060 meters. North of these mountains lies the fertile Sanuki Plain, which slopes gently toward the Seto Inland Sea. The coastline is highly indented and features numerous islands, the largest of which is Shodoshima. Other notable islands include Naoshima, famous for its contemporary art installations. Notable rivers include the Doki River, which is the only first-class river system in the prefecture, and the Koto River. Due to the dry climate, Kagawa features thousands of historic irrigation ponds, with Manno Lake being the largest man-made irrigation reservoir in Japan. Yashima, a distinctive flat-topped volcanic plateau, projects into the sea near Takamatsu.\n\n## Climate\n\nKagawa experiences a Seto Inland Sea climate, which is characterized by mild temperatures throughout the year and low annual precipitation. The Chugoku Mountains on Honshu and the Shikoku Mountains shelter the region from major rain-bearing wind systems, such as the summer monsoons and winter snow storms. While this results in a high number of sunny days, it also makes the prefecture susceptible to water shortages and droughts. Summers are warm and humid, while winters are dry and cool, with rare snowfall.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nTakamatsu is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a major economic and transport hub for Shikoku. Other significant cities include Marugame, Sakaide, and Kan'onji. Sakaide is a major industrial center featuring coastal heavy industries, including oil refining, chemical manufacturing, and shipbuilding. Agriculture is highly developed despite the limited space. Shodoshima is famous as the cradle of olive cultivation in Japan. Kagawa is also renowned for its food processing industry, particularly the production of Sanuki udon, which attracts significant domestic tourism.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as Sanuki Province, Kagawa has a rich cultural heritage. The Battle of Yashima, a major naval clash of the Genpei War, took place off its coast in 1185. The prefecture is home to several stops on the famous Shikoku Pilgrimage, including Zentsu-ji, the birthplace of the Buddhist monk Kobo Daishi. Kotohira-gu, also known as Konpira-san, is a major Shinto shrine complex situated on the slopes of Mount Zozu. In Takamatsu, Ritsurin Garden is recognized as one of the most outstanding historical landscape gardens in Japan, dating back to the Edo period.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Takamatsu\n* Approximate area: 1,876 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 950,000\n* Largest city: Takamatsu\n* Signature features: Sanuki udon noodles, Ritsurin Garden, and the Great Seto Bridge",
