    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nKochi Prefecture is located on the southern coast of Shikoku, the smallest of Japan's four main islands. It faces the Pacific Ocean to the south, forming a deep, crescent-shaped coastline along Tosa Bay. Kochi is bordered by Ehime Prefecture to the northwest and north, and Tokushima Prefecture to the northeast. It does not share a land border with Kagawa Prefecture, which lies further north. Its location makes it relatively isolated from the main island of Honshu, though it is connected via transport networks traversing the neighboring prefectures.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Kochi is highly mountainous, with the Shikoku Mountains running along its northern border. Approximately 84 percent of the prefecture's total land area is covered by forests, giving it the highest percentage of forest cover among all Japanese prefectures. The highest peak in the prefecture is Mount Miune, which reaches an elevation of 1,894 meters on the border with Tokushima. Kochi is drained by several major river systems. The Shimanto River, often referred to as the last clear stream of Japan, flows through the western portion of the prefecture and is famous for its lack of dams. The Yoshino River originates in Kochi before flowing east into Tokushima, and the Niyodo River is renowned for its highly transparent, blue-tinted water. The southern coastline features dramatic cliffs, sandy beaches, and Cape Muroto in the east and Cape Ashizuri in the west, both of which are designated as part of national parks.\n\n## Climate\n\nKochi experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by hot, humid summers and mild winters. Due to its southern exposure to the Pacific Ocean and the influence of the warm Kuroshio Current, it is one of the warmest and wettest regions in Japan. The prefecture is highly susceptible to typhoons, which frequently make landfall or pass close to the coast during late summer and autumn, bringing torrential rainfall. Annual precipitation in the mountainous interior can exceed 3,000 millimeters, while the coastal areas receive around 2,500 millimeters annually.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kochi is heavily reliant on agriculture, forestry, and fisheries. Due to the warm climate, greenhouse agriculture is highly developed in the coastal plains, producing off-season vegetables such as eggplants, green peppers, and cucumbers for major metropolitan markets. Citrus fruits, particularly yuzu, are also major agricultural products. The forestry sector utilizes the abundant mountain timber, while the coastal fisheries target bonito and mackerel. Manufacturing is relatively small-scale, focusing on paper production, machinery, and food processing. Kochi is the capital and largest city, serving as the political, economic, and cultural hub. Other notable cities include Nankoku, Shimanto, and Kami.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as Tosa Province, the region played a crucial role in the modernization of Japan during the late Edo period and the Meiji Restoration. Prominent historical figures from Kochi include Sakamoto Ryoma, a key negotiator who helped overthrow the Tokugawa Shogunate, and Itagaki Taisuke, a leader of the Freedom and People's Rights Movement. The cultural heritage of Kochi is celebrated through the annual Yosakoi Festival, a highly energetic dance festival held in Kochi City every August. The prefecture is also famous for its culinary tradition of Katsuo no Tataki, which is lightly seared bonito served with garlic and green onions.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kochi\n* Approximate area: 7,103 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 660,000\n* Largest city: Kochi\n* Signature features: Shimanto River, highest percentage of forest cover in Japan, and the historic legacy of Tosa Province",
