    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nKanagawa Prefecture is located in the southern part of the Kanto region on Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is bordered by the Tokyo metropolis to the north, Yamanashi Prefecture to the northwest, and Shizuoka Prefecture to the west. To the east, Kanagawa faces Tokyo Bay, while its southern coast meets Sagami Bay, which opens into the Pacific Ocean. As part of the Greater Tokyo Area, it serves as a vital residential and economic corridor adjacent to the national capital.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Kanagawa transitions from flat coastal plains to rugged mountainous terrain. The eastern portion of the prefecture is relatively flat and forms the southwestern edge of the Kanto Plain. In contrast, the western region is dominated by the Tanzawa Mountains and the Hakone volcanic massif. Mount Hiru, the highest peak in the prefecture, rises to 1,673 meters in the Tanzawa range. The Miura Peninsula extends southeastward, separating Tokyo Bay from Sagami Bay. Significant water bodies include the Sagami River, which flows south through the center of the prefecture, and the Tama River, which defines much of the northern border with Tokyo. Lake Ashi, a scenic caldera lake, is located in the southwest within Fuji-Hakone-Izu National Park.\n\n## Climate\nKanagawa experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm, humid summers and cool, dry winters. The coastal areas, influenced by the Pacific Ocean and the Kuroshio Current, enjoy milder winter temperatures than the mountainous interior. Average annual precipitation is high, with the heaviest rainfall occurring during the summer monsoon season in June and July, as well as during the autumn typhoon season in September and October. The mountainous western districts receive significantly more precipitation and experience colder winter temperatures, occasionally resulting in heavy snowfall in areas such as Hakone.\n\n## Economy & cities\nKanagawa possesses one of the most powerful prefectural economies in Japan, driven by heavy industry, commerce, and advanced technology. Yokohama, the administrative center, is the second-most populous city in Japan and home to a major international shipping port. Kawasaki, situated between Tokyo and Yokohama, is a core industrial city specializing in petrochemicals, steel production, and electronics. Sagamihara, the third-largest city, is an inland hub for machinery and logistics. Major corporations, including Nissan Motor Company, maintain headquarters here. Tourism also plays a critical economic role, drawing millions of domestic and international visitors annually to the historic coastal town of Kamakura, the hot spring resorts of Hakone, and the beaches of the Shonan coast.\n\n## History & culture\nKanagawa has played a pivotal role in Japanese history. During the Kamakura period from 1185 to 1333, the city of Kamakura served as the political capital of the nation under the Kamakura shogunate. This era left a rich cultural legacy, including the Great Buddha of Kamakura and numerous Zen Buddhist temples. In 1859, the opening of the Port of Yokohama under the Treaty of Amity and Commerce ended decades of national isolation, transforming a small fishing village into Japan's primary gateway for Western trade, technology, and culture. Odawara Castle, located in the west, represents another historical landmark, having served as a stronghold for the Hojo clan during the Sengoku period.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Yokohama\n* Approximate area: 2,416 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 9.2 million\n* Largest city if different from the administrative center: Yokohama (which is the administrative center)\n* Signature features: The historic temples of Kamakura, the volcanic hot springs of Hakone, and the bustling Port of Yokohama",
    "summary": "Kanagawa Prefecture is a highly populated and industrialized region located directly south of Tokyo on Japan's main island of Honshu. It features a diverse landscape that ranges from the urbanized Kanto Plain and the major port city of Yokohama to the mountainous terrain of Hakone and the historic temples of Kamakura. The prefecture serves as a vital economic, cultural, and transport hub, bordered by Tokyo Bay to the east and Sagami Bay to the south.",
