    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nKyoto Prefecture is located in the Kansai region on the island of Honshu, Japan. It occupies a central position on the island, stretching from the Sea of Japan coast in the north to the Kansai plains in the south. It is bordered by Fukui Prefecture to the northeast, Shiga Prefecture to the east, Mie Prefecture to the southeast, Nara Prefecture to the south, Osaka Prefecture to the southwest, and Hyogo Prefecture to the west. Its elongated shape connects the Sea of Japan with the inland Kansai area.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe prefecture is divided geographically by the Tanba Mountains, which run through its center. This mountain range separates the northern maritime region, known as San'in, from the southern inland basin region, known as San'yo or the Kyoto Basin. The northern coast features the Tango Peninsula, which projects into the Sea of Japan, and Miyazu Bay, home to Amanohashidate, a famous pine-clad sandbar. Major rivers include the Yura River in the north, and the Katsura, Uji, and Kamo rivers in the south, which converge to form the Yodo River. The southern region is dominated by the Kyoto Basin, surrounded by mountains on three sides: the Higashiyama, Kitayama, and Nishiyama ranges.\n\n## Climate\n\nDue to its elongated shape and central mountain range, Kyoto Prefecture experiences two distinct climate zones. The northern coastal region has a Sea of Japan climate, characterized by heavy snowfall in the winter and high precipitation year-round. The southern basin region experiences an inland climate with hot, humid summers and cold winters, often marked by significant temperature fluctuations between day and night. The surrounding mountains trap heat and moisture in the summer, leading to humid conditions in the southern urban areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Kyoto Prefecture is highly diversified. The southern region, particularly around the city of Kyoto, is a major hub for high-technology industries, traditional crafts, and tourism. Companies specializing in electronics, precision machinery, and video games are headquartered here. Traditional industries include sake brewing in Fushimi, green tea production in Uji, and Nishijin textile weaving. The northern region relies more heavily on agriculture, forestry, and commercial fishing. The capital and largest city is Kyoto. Other major cities include Uji, known for its tea and historic temples, Kameoka, Maizuru, which serves as a major port and naval base on the Sea of Japan, and Fukuchiyama.\n\n## History & culture\n\nFor over a millennium, from 794 to 1869, the city of Kyoto served as the imperial capital of Japan under the name Heian-kyo. This long history left the prefecture with an extraordinary concentration of cultural heritage. The Historic Monuments of Ancient Kyoto, spread across Kyoto, Uji, and Otsu in neighboring Shiga, are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. This designation includes famous temples like Kinkaku-ji, Ginkaku-ji, and Kiyomizu-dera, as well as Nijo Castle. Traditional arts, including the tea ceremony, flower arranging, and Kabuki theater, flourished here and continue to be practiced.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kyoto\n* Approximate area: 4,612 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.5 million\n* Largest city: Kyoto\n* Signature features: Amanohashidate sandbar, historic temples of the former imperial capital, and Uji green tea production.",
