    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nMie Prefecture is located on the eastern coast of the Kii Peninsula in the Kansai region of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is bordered by Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture to the northeast, Shiga Prefecture to the northwest, Kyoto Prefecture to the west, Nara Prefecture to the southwest, and Wakayama Prefecture to the south. To the east, Mie faces Ise Bay and the Pacific Ocean. While Mie is traditionally grouped with the Kansai region due to historical and linguistic ties, it also maintains strong economic and infrastructural connections with the Chubu region, particularly the Nagoya metropolitan area.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Mie is highly diverse, stretching north to south in a long, narrow shape. The northern part of the prefecture is characterized by the Suzuka Mountains, which form a natural border with Shiga Prefecture. The central and southern regions are dominated by the rugged Kii Mountain Range, including Mount Odaigahara, one of the wettest areas in Japan. The eastern coastline features two distinct coastal landforms. In the north, the Ise Plain borders the shallow waters of Ise Bay, where major rivers like the Kiso, Ibi, and Nagara empty. In the south, the Shima Peninsula features a highly indented rias coastline, characterized by numerous bays, inlets, and islands, which are protected as part of the Ise-Shima National Park. The Yoshino-Kumano National Park also covers parts of southern Mie.\n\n## Climate\nMie Prefecture generally experiences a humid subtropical climate, though local conditions vary significantly due to topography. The northern plains and coastal areas have relatively mild winters and hot, humid summers. The mountainous interior, particularly the southern Kii Mountains, receives some of the highest annual rainfall in Japan, often exceeding 3,000 millimeters. This high rainfall is driven by warm, moisture-laden winds from the Pacific Ocean striking the steep mountain slopes. Winters in the mountainous regions can be cold with significant snowfall, whereas the southern coastal areas remain warm year-round due to the warming influence of the Kuroshio Current.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mie is a mix of heavy industry, agriculture, and tourism. The northern city of Yokkaichi is a major industrial hub, famous for its petrochemical complexes, semiconductor manufacturing, and port facilities. It is the largest city in the prefecture by population, surpassing the capital city of Tsu. Agriculture is highly developed on the Ise Plain, producing rice, green tea, and high-quality Matsusaka beef. The coastal waters support a productive fishing industry, particularly famous for pearls, spiny lobsters, and oysters. Mikimoto Pearl Island in Toba is renowned as the birthplace of cultured pearl aquaculture.\n\n## History & culture\nMie holds a central place in Japanese history and spiritual culture. It is home to the Ise Grand Shrine, dedicated to the sun goddess Amaterasu. This shrine complex is considered the most sacred Shinto shrine in Japan and has attracted pilgrims for over a thousand years. The ancient Kumano Kodo pilgrimage routes, which are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site, traverse the southern part of the prefecture. Historically, Mie was divided into several provinces, including Ise, Shima, Iga, and a portion of Kii. The mountainous Iga region is famous as one of the historical cradles of ninjutsu.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Tsu\n* Approximate area: 5,777 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.73 million\n* Largest city: Yokkaichi\n* Signature features: Ise Grand Shrine and the historical Iga ninja region",
