    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nKumamoto Prefecture is located in the center of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It shares land borders with Fukuoka Prefecture to the north, Oita Prefecture to the northeast, Miyazaki Prefecture to the east, and Kagoshima Prefecture to the south. To the west, Kumamoto faces the Ariake Sea and the Amakusa Sea, which separate it from Nagasaki Prefecture. The prefecture occupies a strategic transit position on Kyushu, connecting the northern and southern regions of the island.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Kumamoto features dramatic volcanic landscapes and intricate coastlines. The eastern portion is dominated by Mount Aso, one of the largest active volcanoes in the world. Its massive caldera measures approximately 25 kilometers by 18 kilometers and contains inhabited towns and active peaks like Mount Nakadake.\n\nTo the west, the Amakusa Archipelago consists of over one hundred islands in the Yatsushiro and Amakusa Seas. The prefecture is drained by several major rivers. The Kuma River, one of the three swiftest rivers in Japan, flows through the southern mountains. The Shirakawa River flows from the Aso caldera through the capital, while the Kikuchi River drains the northern plains. Protected areas include Aso Kuju National Park and Unzen-Amakusa National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nKumamoto has a humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and cool winters. Inland basins and mountains cause pronounced seasonal and diurnal temperature variations. Summers bring heavy precipitation, particularly during the rainy season in June and July, making the region prone to landslides. Typhoons are common in late summer. Winters are mild on the coast but cold with occasional snow in the highlands around Mount Aso.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy combines agriculture, manufacturing, and technology. Due to fertile volcanic soil and abundant groundwater, Kumamoto is a leading producer of tomatoes, watermelons, and tatami rush grass.\n\nIn manufacturing, Kumamoto is a key node in Kyushu's semiconductor industry, centered around recent developments in Kikuyo. Other major industries include automobile manufacturing, biotechnology, and food processing.\n\nThe capital and largest city is Kumamoto. Other significant cities include Yatsushiro, an industrial port, and Amakusa, the primary hub for the western islands.\n\n## History & culture\n\nDuring the Edo period, the region was ruled as the Kumamoto Domain by the Hosokawa clan. The historic centerpiece is Kumamoto Castle, built in the early seventeenth century by Kato Kiyomasa and famous for its defensive stone walls.\n\nThe western Amakusa region was a major center for early Japanese Christianity and the seventeenth-century Shimabara Rebellion. The hidden Christian sites in Amakusa are now UNESCO World Heritage sites. Cultural traditions include the Yamaga Lantern Festival and Higo inlay metalwork.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kumamoto\n* Approximate area: 7,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.7 million\n* Largest city: Kumamoto\n* Signature features: Mount Aso caldera and Kumamoto Castle",
    "summary": "Kumamoto Prefecture is located in central Kyushu, Japan, and is characterized by the massive caldera of Mount Aso and the scenic Amakusa Archipelago. The region features a strong economy driven by agriculture, semiconductor manufacturing, and historical tourism centered around Kumamoto Castle. It is also historically significant for its early Christian heritage and the seventeenth-century Shimabara Rebellion.",
