    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nMiyazaki Prefecture is located on the eastern coast of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It is bordered by Oita Prefecture to the north, Kumamoto Prefecture to the west, and Kagoshima Prefecture to the southwest. To the east, Miyazaki faces the Pacific Ocean along a stretch of water known as the Hyuga-nada Sea. The prefecture occupies a strategic coastal position, isolated from the western side of Kyushu by the rugged Kyushu Mountain Range. There are no active territorial disputes regarding Miyazaki Prefecture, which is universally recognized as an integral part of Japan.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Miyazaki is highly mountainous, with over 70 percent of its land covered by forest. The Kyushu Mountains dominate the northern and western borders, featuring prominent peaks such as Mount Sobo and Mount Katamuki. In the southwest, the volcanic Kirishima range contains active peaks and crater lakes. The Gokase River flows through the northern part of the prefecture, carving the dramatic basalt columns of the Takachiho Gorge. The Oyodo River is the largest river basin in the prefecture, flowing through the fertile Miyazaki Plain into the Pacific Ocean. The coastline features diverse geography, ranging from the rugged rias coast in the north to the sandy beaches of the central coast and the wave-cut rock formations of the Nichinan Coast in the south. Aoshima Island, located just offshore, is famous for its unique geological formations known as the Devil's Washboard. Protected areas include the Kirishima-Kinkowan National Park and the Sobo-Katamuki-Okue Quasi-National Park.\n\n## Climate\nMiyazaki experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by hot, humid summers and mild winters. The warm Kuroshio Current flows northward off the eastern coast, moderating temperatures and contributing to high annual precipitation. Miyazaki is one of the wettest and sunniest prefectures in Japan. The region is highly susceptible to typhoons, which regularly bring heavy rainfall and strong winds during the late summer and autumn months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Miyazaki relies heavily on agriculture, forestry, and food processing. The warm climate and abundant rainfall support the cultivation of rice, sweet potatoes, and specialty citrus fruits such as hyuganatsu and kumquats. Miyazaki is also a major producer of high-quality beef, pork, and broiler chickens. Forestry is highly developed, utilizing the abundant Obi cedar trees for timber. Manufacturing is concentrated in northern coastal cities like Nobeoka, which developed as a major center for chemical and textile industries under the Asahi Kasei corporation. The capital and largest city is Miyazaki, which serves as the administrative, commercial, and tourism hub. Other major cities include Miyakonojo, an agricultural and livestock center in the south, and Hyuga, a port city known for commercial shipping and lumber processing.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the region was known as Hyuga Province. It is deeply rooted in Japanese mythology and is considered the setting for many ancient legends recorded in the Kojiki and Nihon Shoki. The town of Takachiho is celebrated as the site where Ninigi-no-Mikoto, the grandson of the sun goddess Amaterasu, descended to Earth. Traditional culture is preserved through Kagura, a sacred theatrical dance performed at local shrines to secure bountiful harvests. Notable historical sites include the Udo Shrine, built inside a cliffside cave overlooking the ocean, and the Miyazaki Shrine, dedicated to Emperor Jimmu, the legendary first emperor of Japan.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Miyazaki\n* Approximate area: about 7,735 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: about 1.06 million\n* Largest city: Miyazaki\n* Signature features: Takachiho Gorge, Nichinan Coast, and Miyazaki beef",
