    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nHyogo Prefecture is located in the Kansai region on the island of Honshu. It occupies a unique geographical position as the only prefecture, besides those in the Tohoku and Chubu regions, to stretch from the Sea of Japan in the north to the Seto Inland Sea in the south. Hyogo shares land borders with Kyoto Prefecture to the east, Osaka Prefecture to the southeast, Okayama Prefecture to the west, and Tottori Prefecture to the northwest. To the south, across the Akashi Strait, lies Awaji Island, which is also part of the prefecture and connects to Tokushima Prefecture on Shikoku via the Naruto Bridge.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Hyogo is highly diverse due to its dual-coastline layout. The Chugoku Mountain Range runs east to west through the center of the prefecture, dividing it into northern and southern halves. Mount Hyo, rising to 1,510 meters, is the highest peak in the prefecture. In the south, the Rokko Mountains form a dramatic backdrop to the coastal city of Kobe. Major rivers include the Kako River, the longest entirely within the prefecture, and the Maruyama River, which flows north into the Sea of Japan. The northern coast features rugged cliffs and is part of the San'in Kaigan National Park, while the southern coast along the Seto Inland Sea is highly industrialized and forms part of the Setonaikai National Park.\n\n## Climate\nHyogo experiences two distinct climate zones. The northern area facing the Sea of Japan has a marine climate characterized by high precipitation, particularly in winter when cold winds from Siberia bring heavy snowfall. The southern region along the Seto Inland Sea enjoys a warm, temperate climate with low annual rainfall and high sunshine hours, sheltered by the Chugoku and Shikoku mountains. The central mountainous region acts as a transition zone, experiencing cooler temperatures and moderate precipitation throughout the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe southern coastline forms a key part of the Hanshin Industrial Region, one of Japan's primary economic hubs. Heavy industries, including shipbuilding, steel production, and machinery manufacturing, are concentrated in cities like Kobe, Amagasaki, and Akashi. Kobe is also a major international port. In contrast, the northern and central regions rely on agriculture, forestry, and fishing. Hyogo is famous for Tajima beef, the lineage behind Kobe beef, and the Nada-Gogo district is the leading sake-producing region in Japan. Major urban centers include Kobe, Himeji, Nishinomiya, and Amagasaki.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, Hyogo was formed by merging five ancient provinces: Harima, Tajima, Awaji, Tanba, and Settsu. This diverse heritage is reflected in its cultural landmarks. Himeji Castle, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is Japan's most famous surviving feudal castle. Kobe Port, opened to Western trade in 1868, introduced foreign influences that are still visible in the historic Kitano-cho district. In 1995, the prefecture was struck by the devastating Great Hanshin Earthquake, which led to significant urban reconstruction and the development of world-class disaster-mitigation research facilities.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Kobe\n* Approximate area: 8,400 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 5.4 million\n* Signature features: Himeji Castle, Tajima beef, and coastlines on both the Sea of Japan and the Seto Inland Sea.",
    "summary": "Hyogo Prefecture is a diverse Japanese territory in the Kansai region that uniquely stretches from the Sea of Japan to the Seto Inland Sea. Its capital, Kobe, is a major port city and industrial hub, while the prefecture's interior is defined by the Chugoku Mountains and historic sites like Himeji Castle. Hyogo is also famous for its agricultural products, including Tajima beef and Nada-Gogo sake.",
