    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nNagasaki Prefecture is located on the westernmost part of the island of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It is bordered by Saga Prefecture to the east, while its other sides are surrounded by water. Specifically, it faces the East China Sea to the west and south, the Tsushima Strait to the north, and the Ariake Sea to the east. The prefecture also includes a vast number of offshore islands, such as the Tsushima and Iki islands in the Korea Strait, and the Goto Islands to the west.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Nagasaki Prefecture is highly fragmented and mountainous, with very little flat land. It has one of the longest coastlines of any prefecture in Japan due to its numerous peninsulas, bays, and inlets, such as Omura Bay and Shimabara Bay. Major peninsulas include the Shimabara Peninsula, the Nagasaki Peninsula, and the Nishisonogi Peninsula. Mount Unzen, an active volcano located on the Shimabara Peninsula, is one of the most prominent peaks in the prefecture, reaching an elevation of about 1,359 meters. The prefecture contains several rivers, including the Honmyo River. Unzen-Amakusa National Park and Saikai National Park protect significant portions of the prefecture's volcanic landscapes and marine environments.\n\n## Climate\n\nNagasaki experiences a humid subtropical climate, characterized by warm, wet summers and mild winters. Due to its maritime location and the influence of the warm Tsushima Current, extreme temperatures are rare. However, the region is highly susceptible to heavy rainfall and typhoons during the summer and autumn months. Precipitation is abundant throughout the year, particularly during the Asian monsoon rainy season in June and July.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Nagasaki Prefecture is diverse, with major contributions from shipbuilding, fisheries, agriculture, and tourism. Sasebo and Nagasaki cities are major centers for shipbuilding and heavy industries. Sasebo also hosts a major United States Navy base and Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force facilities. Agriculture is prominent on the peninsulas, where terraced fields produce potatoes, loquats, and mandarin oranges. Pearl farming and marine fishing are vital coastal industries. The capital city is Nagasaki, which serves as the administrative, cultural, and economic hub. Other major cities include Sasebo, Isahaya, and Omura.\n\n## History & culture\n\nNagasaki has a unique history as Japan's primary window to the outside world during the isolation period of the Tokugawa shogunate. The artificial island of Dejima in Nagasaki harbor was the only place where trade with the Dutch and Chinese was permitted. This contact introduced Western science, medicine, and culture to Japan. The prefecture also has a deep history of Christianity, marked by the persecution and survival of Hidden Christians, whose sites are now recognized as UNESCO World Heritage. In modern history, Nagasaki is globally recognized as the second city to suffer an atomic bomb attack, on August 9, 1945.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Nagasaki\n* Approximate area: 4,130 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,300,000\n* Largest city: Nagasaki\n* Signature features: Mount Unzen active volcano and the historic island of Dejima",
    "summary": "Nagasaki Prefecture is a highly mountainous and coastal region located on the western tip of Kyushu, Japan, known for its extensive network of offshore islands like Tsushima and the Goto chain. Historically, it served as Japan's sole gateway to Western trade during the isolationist Tokugawa era and is globally remembered as the target of the second atomic bomb in 1945. Today, the prefecture's economy thrives on shipbuilding, agriculture, and tourism centered around its rich cultural heritage and volcanic landscapes.",
