    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nNagano Prefecture is a landlocked prefecture located in the Chubu region on the main island of Honshu. Positioned in the central part of Japan, it shares borders with more prefectures than any other in the country. Nagano is bordered by Niigata Prefecture to the north, Gunma and Saitama prefectures to the east, Yamanashi and Shizuoka prefectures to the south, and Aichi, Gifu, and Toyama prefectures to the west. Because of its central, elevated location, it serves as a critical geographical link between the eastern and western regions of Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\n\nOften referred to as the Roof of Japan, Nagano is characterized by its rugged, mountainous terrain. The prefecture contains the majority of the Japanese Alps, which are divided into three major ranges. The Hida Mountains, or Northern Alps, run along the western border. The Kiso Mountains, or Central Alps, run north to south through the center of the prefecture. The Akaishi Mountains, or Southern Alps, lie along the southeastern border. Mount Hotaka, rising to 3,190 meters on the border with Gifu Prefecture, is the highest point in Nagano.\n\nThe prefecture is the source of several major river systems. The Chikuma River, which flows north into Niigata Prefecture to become the Shinano River, is the longest river system in Japan. The Tenryu River flows south from Lake Suwa, the prefecture's largest lake, toward the Pacific Ocean.\n\n## Climate\n\nDue to its mountainous topography and inland location, Nagano experiences a climate with significant regional variations. The northern part of the prefecture experiences heavy snowfall during the winter, influenced by cold winds blowing across the Sea of Japan. In contrast, the southern valleys have a milder, more temperate climate. Most of the prefecture is characterized by a humid continental climate, featuring cold, snowy winters and warm, relatively dry summers. The high elevation of many settlements leads to cool summer nights and a wide diurnal temperature range, which is highly beneficial for certain types of agriculture.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Nagano is diverse, balancing manufacturing, agriculture, and tourism. The prefecture is renowned for its precision machinery industry, producing high-quality optical equipment, watches, and electronic components, earning it the nickname the Switzerland of Japan. In agriculture, Nagano is a leading producer of apples, grapes, lettuce, and buckwheat. The Azumino area is famous for its large-scale wasabi cultivation, supported by cold alpine spring water.\n\nThe administrative center and largest city is Nagano, located in the northern basin. Matsumoto, the second-largest city, is a major cultural and commercial hub located in the central valley. Other notable cities include Ueda, Okaya, and Iida. Tourism is a major economic driver, centered on ski resorts, hot springs, and hiking trails.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region of Nagano was known as Shinano Province. Its strategic mountain passes made it a vital corridor during the feudal era. The city of Nagano grew around Zenko-ji, a seventh-century Buddhist temple that remains one of the most important pilgrimage sites in Japan. Matsumoto Castle, located in Matsumoto, is one of the oldest surviving original castles in the country, dating back to the sixteenth century.\n\nIn 1998, Nagano hosted the Winter Olympic Games, which spurred infrastructure development, including the Hokuriku Shinkansen high-speed rail line. The local culinary culture is famous for Shinshu soba, made from local buckwheat, and oyaki dumplings.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Nagano\n* Approximate area: 13,562 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2,010,000\n* Largest city: Nagano\n* Signature features: The Japanese Alps and Zenko-ji Temple",
