    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nMiyagi Prefecture is located in the Tohoku region on the northeastern part of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It faces the Pacific Ocean to the east. It is bordered by Iwate Prefecture to the north, Akita Prefecture to the northwest, Yamagata Prefecture to the west, and Fukushima Prefecture to the south. The prefecture occupies a central position within the Tohoku region, making its capital, Sendai, the primary administrative and economic hub of northeastern Japan.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Miyagi is characterized by a contrast between its mountainous western border and its coastal eastern plains. The Ou Mountains run along the western border with Yamagata Prefecture, featuring volcanic peaks such as Mount Zao, which is famous for its crater lake, Okama, and its winter frost-covered trees. To the east lies the Sendai Plain, a fertile agricultural region drained by major rivers. The Kitakami River, one of the longest rivers in northern Japan, flows through the northern part of the prefecture before emptying into the Pacific Ocean. Other significant rivers include the Abukuma River in the south and the Naruse River. The coastline of Miyagi is highly varied. The northern coast features the southern portion of the Sanriku Coast, characterized by dramatic rias coastlines with steep cliffs and deep inlets. In contrast, the southern coast is relatively flat and sandy. Matsushima Bay, located in the central coast, is renowned for its hundreds of pine-clad islands and is traditionally ranked as one of the Three Views of Japan. Sanriku Fukko National Park covers parts of the northern coastal area.\n\n## Climate\n\nMiyagi Prefecture generally experiences a humid subtropical climate, though it transitions to a humid continental climate in the mountainous western regions. The climate is moderated by the Pacific Ocean. Summers are warm but rarely excessively hot, with average temperatures in August around 24 degrees Celsius. Winters are cold but milder than in neighboring prefectures on the Sea of Japan side, as the Ou Mountains block much of the heavy winter snow. Sendai receives far less snowfall than cities on the western coast of Honshu, though the western mountainous areas of Miyagi receive heavy snow accumulations, supporting several ski resorts.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Miyagi is diverse, balancing agriculture, fisheries, and manufacturing. The Sendai Plain is a major producer of rice, particularly high-quality varieties like Sasanishiki and Hitomebore. The coastal waters, where the warm Kuroshio Current meets the cold Oyashio Current, support a highly productive commercial fishing industry. Key fishing ports include Kesennuma, Ishinomaki, and Shiogama, which process large catches of bonito, mackerel, and oysters. Manufacturing industries are concentrated around Sendai and the Sendai Port area, focusing on electronic equipment, chemicals, food processing, and pulp and paper. Sendai is the administrative center and the only designated city in the Tohoku region, acting as the regional headquarters for many national corporations and government agencies. Other major cities include Ishinomaki, the second-largest city, and Osaki, located in the fertile northern plain.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region of Miyagi was part of Mutsu Province. In the early seventeenth century, the powerful daimyo Date Masamune established the Sendai Domain and constructed Sendai Castle. Under his rule, the region flourished through land reclamation, trade, and cultural developments. Date Masamune also dispatched a diplomatic mission to Europe led by Hasekura Tsunenaga. The cultural heritage of Miyagi is reflected in historic sites like the Zuigan-ji temple in Matsushima and the Osaki Hachiman-gu shrine in Sendai. Traditional festivals are highly prominent, most notably the Sendai Tanabata Festival held in August, which attracts millions of visitors with its massive, hand-crafted paper decorations. The prefecture was severely impacted by the Great East Japan Earthquake and tsunami on March 11, 2011, which caused extensive damage to its coastal communities, leading to a massive, ongoing reconstruction effort.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Sendai\n* Approximate area: 7,282 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.3 million people\n* Largest city: Sendai (the administrative center is the largest city)\n* Signature features: Matsushima Bay, Mount Zao, and the Sendai Tanabata Festival",
    "summary": "Miyagi Prefecture is located in the Tohoku region of northern Honshu, centered around its capital city of Sendai. The prefecture features a diverse geography ranging from the volcanic Ou Mountains in the west to the scenic rias coastline and Matsushima Bay in the east. Its economy relies on a mix of commercial fishing, high-quality rice cultivation, and manufacturing, while its history is closely tied to the legacy of the Date clan.",
