    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nNara Prefecture is a landlocked administrative division situated in the Kansai region on the Kii Peninsula, which is located in the central-western part of Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It is bordered by Kyoto Prefecture to the north, Osaka Prefecture to the west, Wakayama Prefecture to the southwest and south, and Mie Prefecture to the east. Because it is entirely landlocked, Nara has no direct coastline along the Pacific Ocean or the Sea of Japan.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Nara is characterized by a stark contrast between its northern and southern regions. The northern portion contains the Nara Basin, a relatively flat lowland area where the majority of the prefecture's population and agricultural activities are concentrated. In contrast, the southern region is highly mountainous, dominated by the rugged Kii Mountains. Mount Hachikyo, rising to 1,915 meters, is the highest peak in Nara and the entire Kansai region. Major water systems include the Yamato River, which drains the northern basin, and the Yoshino River, which flows westward through the mountainous south. Forested areas cover roughly 77 percent of the prefecture's total land area. Notable protected areas include parts of the Yoshino-Kumano National Park and several quasi-national parks.\n\n## Climate\nNara experiences a humid subtropical climate, but local conditions vary by topography. The northern Nara Basin has an inland climate characterized by significant temperature fluctuations between summer and winter, as well as between day and night. Summers in the basin are hot and humid, while winters are cold with occasional light snowfall. Precipitation in the north is relatively moderate. The southern mountainous region experiences a much wetter and cooler climate. High-elevation areas receive heavy rainfall during the summer monsoon season and substantial snowfall during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Nara is diverse, blending traditional industries, agriculture, and tourism. The southern Yoshino region is renowned for its forestry sector, producing high-quality Yoshino cedar and cypress timber. Agriculture in the northern basin focuses on rice, persimmons, strawberries, and green tea. Manufacturing includes traditional goods such as calligraphy inksticks, writing brushes, and socks, alongside modern electronics and machinery. Tourism is a vital economic pillar, drawing millions of visitors annually to historical sites. Nara is the capital and largest city. Other major urban centers include Kashihara, which holds historical significance as an ancient imperial site, Ikoma, a residential suburb of Osaka, and Tenri.\n\n## History & culture\nNara is widely regarded as the cradle of Japanese civilization. It served as the political and cultural heart of Japan during the Nara period from 710 to 784 AD, when the capital was established at Heijo-kyo, located in modern-day Nara city. The prefecture contains an exceptional concentration of historical treasures. It is home to three UNESCO World Heritage Sites, which include the Historic Monuments of Ancient Nara, the Buddhist Monuments in the Horyu-ji Area, and the Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range. Todai-ji temple houses the Great Buddha, one of the largest bronze statues in the world. Nara Park is famous for its hundreds of free-roaming sika deer, which are protected as national natural monuments.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Nara\n* Approximate area: 3,691 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,300,000\n* Largest city: Nara\n* Signature features: Todai-ji temple and the free-roaming sika deer of Nara Park",
    "summary": "Nara is a landlocked prefecture in Japan's Kansai region, characterized by a populous northern basin and a mountainous, forested southern region. Historically significant as the country's ancient capital during the eighth century, it is home to numerous UNESCO World Heritage Sites, including the Todai-ji temple. Today, Nara's economy relies on tourism, forestry, agriculture, and traditional crafts.",
