    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nOita Prefecture is located on the northeastern coast of Kyushu, the southernmost of Japan's four main islands. It shares land borders with Fukuoka Prefecture to the northwest, Kumamoto Prefecture to the southwest, and Miyazaki Prefecture to the south. To the north, Oita faces the Suo Channel and the western reaches of the Seto Inland Sea. To the east, it is bordered by the Bungo Channel, a strait that separates Kyushu from the island of Shikoku. The prefecture occupies a strategic maritime position, historically serving as a gateway between Kyushu and the main island of Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe terrain of Oita is highly mountainous, with plains limited to coastal pockets and river valleys. Volcanic activity has heavily shaped the landscape. Mount Kuju, rising to 1,791 meters, is the highest peak in Oita and the entire island of Kyushu. Other prominent peaks include Mount Yufu and Mount Tsurumi. The prefecture is renowned for its extensive geothermal activity, which feeds thousands of hot springs, most notably in the coastal city of Beppu and the inland basin of Yufuin. Major rivers include the Ono River and the Oita River, both of which empty into Beppu Bay, as well as the Yamakuni River in the north. Conservation areas cover a significant portion of the prefecture, including parts of Aso Kuju National Park, Setonaikai National Park, and Sobo-Katamuki-Okue Quasi-National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nOita experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm, humid summers and relatively mild winters. However, local topography creates distinct microclimates. The coastal regions along the Seto Inland Sea enjoy a milder, drier climate with high sunshine hours. In contrast, the mountainous interior experiences significantly cooler temperatures, with sub-zero conditions and heavy snowfall common on the higher peaks during winter. Precipitation is abundant throughout the prefecture, peaking during the summer rainy season in June and July, as well as during the autumn typhoon season.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Oita is diverse, balancing heavy industry, agriculture, and tourism. The capital city, Oita, is a major industrial hub featuring steel mills, chemical plants, oil refineries, and semiconductor manufacturing facilities. Nakatsu, located in the northwest, is a center for automotive manufacturing. Tourism is a vital economic driver, centered on the hot spring resorts of Beppu and Yufuin. In agriculture, Oita is a leading producer of kabosu, a sour citrus fruit, as well as dried shiitake mushrooms and greenhouse-grown mandarins. The coastal waters of the Bungo Channel support a productive fishing industry, famous for premium horse mackerel and chub mackerel, marketed as Seki-aji and Seki-saba.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the area of Oita was divided between Bungo Province in the south and a portion of Buzen Province in the north. During the Sengoku period, the region was ruled by the influential Christian daimyo Otomo Sorin, who promoted trade with Portuguese merchants and introduced Western medicine and culture. This international legacy is preserved alongside ancient Buddhist traditions, such as the Usuki Stone Buddhas, a collection of dozens of stone statues carved into cliff faces during the late Heian and Kamakura periods. The Kunisaki Peninsula is famous for Rokugo Manzan, a unique local religious culture that blends Buddhism, Shinto, and mountain worship.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Oita\n* Approximate area: 6,340 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,100,000\n* Largest city: Oita\n* Signature features: Highest volume of hot spring water discharge in Japan, Mount Kuju.",
    "summary": "Oita Prefecture is located on the northeastern coast of Kyushu, Japan, and is characterized by its highly mountainous, volcanic terrain. The region is famous nationwide for its geothermal activity, particularly the hot spring resorts of Beppu and Yufuin, alongside a diverse economy that spans heavy industry, agriculture, and tourism. Historically known as Bungo Province, Oita features rich cultural assets, including the ancient Usuki Stone Buddhas and a legacy of early trade with Europe.",
