    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nOkayama Prefecture is located in the western part of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It occupies the southeastern portion of the Chūgoku region. The prefecture shares land borders with Hyōgo Prefecture to the east, Tottori Prefecture to the north, and Hiroshima Prefecture to the west. To the south, Okayama faces the Seto Inland Sea. Across this body of water lies Kagawa Prefecture on the island of Shikoku. The Great Seto Bridge, a series of double-decked bridges, spans the inland sea to connect Okayama with Kagawa, serving as a vital transportation link between Honshu and Shikoku.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Okayama Prefecture transitions from mountainous terrain in the north to flat plains in the south. The northern border is defined by the Chūgoku Mountains, which separate Okayama from Tottori Prefecture. Below these mountains lies the Kibi Plateau, a hilly upland region that occupies the central portion of the prefecture. The southern region features the fertile Okayama Plain, formed by sediment deposited by major river systems and expanded through historical land reclamation. Three major rivers flow southward through the prefecture into the Seto Inland Sea: the Yoshii River, the Asahi River, and the Takahashi River. The southern coastline includes numerous islands within the Seto Inland Sea, many of which are protected as part of the Setonaikai National Park.\n\n## Climate\n\nOkayama is characterized by a Seto Inland Sea climate, which is mild and temperate throughout the year. The Chūgoku Mountains to the north and the Shikoku Mountains to the south shield the region from seasonal monsoons, resulting in low annual rainfall and a high number of sunny days. This dry, stable climate has earned the prefecture the popular nickname of the \"Land of Sunshine.\" However, regional variations exist. The northern mountainous areas experience lower temperatures and significant snowfall during the winter months, while the southern plains and coastal areas remain warm and dry.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Okayama Prefecture balances heavy industry, agriculture, and traditional crafts. The Mizushima Industrial Complex, located in the coastal city of Kurashiki, is a major hub for petroleum refining, chemical manufacturing, steel production, and automotive assembly. Kurashiki is also renowned for its textile industry, particularly the Kojima district, which is recognized as the birthplace of domestic Japanese denim. Agriculture thrives in the sunny climate, with Okayama being famous nationwide for high-quality fruits, particularly white peaches and Muscat of Alexandria grapes. The capital city, Okayama, is the administrative and commercial hub, serving as a major railway junction for the San'yo Shinkansen.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically, the region of Okayama was the core of the ancient Kibi Kingdom, a powerful rival to the Yamato court during the Kofun period. It was later divided into the provinces of Bizen, Bitchū, and Mimasaka. Okayama is deeply associated with the folklore of Momotarō, or the Peach Boy, a popular Japanese fairy tale. Cultural landmarks include Okayama Castle, also known as the \"Crow Castle\" due to its black exterior, and Kōraku-en, which is celebrated as one of the Three Great Gardens of Japan. The prefecture is also home to the Shizutani School, established in 1670 as the world's first public school for commoners, featuring distinctive Bizen ware roof tiles.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Okayama\n* Approximate area: 7,114 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1,880,000\n* Largest city: Okayama\n* Signature features: Kōraku-en Garden, Great Seto Bridge, and Kojima denim production.",
    "summary": "Okayama Prefecture is located in the Chūgoku region of western Honshu, bordered by the Chūgoku Mountains to the north and the Seto Inland Sea to the south. Known as the Land of Sunshine for its mild, dry climate, the prefecture is a major agricultural producer of high-quality fruits and a hub for heavy manufacturing and textile industries. Key cultural landmarks include the historic city of Kurashiki, Okayama Castle, and the famous Kōraku-en Garden.",
