    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nSaitama is a landlocked prefecture located in the Kanto region on the island of Honshu. It is bordered by Tokyo to the south, Chiba Prefecture to the east, Ibaraki and Tochigi prefectures to the northeast, Gunma Prefecture to the north, Nagano Prefecture to the west, and Yamanashi Prefecture to the southwest. Because of its position immediately north of Tokyo, Saitama serves as a vital transition zone between the capital metropolis and the mountainous interior of central Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Saitama is divided into two distinct regions. The eastern half of the prefecture is flat and forms part of the fertile Kanto Plain, which is highly urbanized and cultivated. In contrast, the western half is rugged and mountainous, dominated by the Chichibu Mountains. The highest peak in the prefecture is Mount Sanbo, rising to 2,483 meters on the border with Nagano Prefecture. Other notable peaks include Mount Kobushi and Mount Ryokami. Saitama is entirely landlocked and has no coastline. Its hydrology is dominated by two major river systems: the Tone River, which flows along the northern border, and the Ara River, which originates in the western mountains and flows southeastward toward Tokyo Bay. The Chichibu-Tama-Kai National Park protects much of the western mountainous wilderness.\n\n## Climate\nSaitama experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters. The flat eastern plains often experience extreme summer heat, with inland cities like Kumagaya frequently recording some of the highest temperatures in Japan. Winter weather is generally clear and sunny but dry, driven by cold seasonal winds known as Karakaze that blow from the north. The western mountainous areas have a cooler alpine-influenced climate, receiving significantly more rainfall in the summer and heavy snowfall during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Saitama is robust and closely integrated with the Tokyo metropolitan area. It functions as a major residential suburb, with a large portion of the population commuting to Tokyo daily. Major industries include automotive manufacturing, precision machinery, chemicals, and food processing. Agriculture remains productive in the rural sectors, famous for producing Sayama green tea and Fukaya spring onions. The capital and largest city is Saitama City, which was created in 2001 through the merger of Urawa, Omiya, and Yono. Other prominent cities include Kawaguchi, a major industrial center, Kawagoe, famous for its preserved historic architecture, and Tokorozawa.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, Saitama was part of Musashi Province. During the Edo period, the region served as an agricultural supplier to the capital city of Edo and hosted several busy post stations along the Nakasendo and Nikko Kaido trade routes. Kawagoe preserves the atmosphere of this era with its traditional clay-walled warehouse buildings. The prefecture is home to the Chichibu Night Festival, a major winter festival featuring ornate floats that is recognized as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage. Saitama City also hosts the ancient Hikawa Shrine, which dates back over two thousand years.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Saitama City\n* Approximate area: 3,797 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.3 million\n* Largest city: Saitama City\n* Signature features: Landlocked geography, Chichibu Mountains, and the historic town of Kawagoe",
    "summary": "Saitama is a landlocked prefecture in Japan's Kanto region that serves as a major residential and industrial hub bordering Tokyo. Its geography transitions from the flat, urbanized Kanto Plain in the east to the rugged Chichibu Mountains in the west. The prefecture is known for its historic cities like Kawagoe, its robust manufacturing economy, and the scenic Chichibu-Tama-Kai National Park.",
