    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nOsaka Prefecture is located in the west-central portion of Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is situated in the Kansai region, also known as the Kinki region. Osaka is bordered by Hyogo Prefecture to the northwest, Kyoto Prefecture to the north, Nara Prefecture to the east, and Wakayama Prefecture to the south. To the west, the prefecture opens up to Osaka Bay, which is part of the Seto Inland Sea. Osaka is the second smallest prefecture in Japan by land area, yet it is one of the most densely populated.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe topography of Osaka is characterized by a central lowland plain, the Osaka Plain, surrounded by mountains on three sides and Osaka Bay on the west. The Hokusetsu Mountains lie to the north, separating Osaka from Kyoto. The Ikoma and Kongo mountain ranges form the eastern border with Nara, featuring Mount Kongo as the highest peak in the prefecture at approximately 1,125 meters. To the south, the Izumi Mountains separate Osaka from Wakayama. The Yodo River is the primary waterway, flowing from Lake Biwa through Kyoto and Osaka before emptying into Osaka Bay. Other significant rivers include the Yamato River, which drains the southern part of the plain. The coastline is heavily modified by land reclamation, featuring major artificial islands such as the one hosting Kansai International Airport.\n\n## Climate\n\nOsaka experiences a humid subtropical climate, classified as Cfa under the Köppen climate system. The region features four distinct seasons. Winters are generally mild with infrequent snowfall, though cold winds can blow from the northwest. Summers are hot, humid, and often oppressive, with temperatures frequently exceeding 35 degrees Celsius in July and August. The prefecture experiences two main rainy periods: the Tsuyu plum rain season in June and July, and the typhoon season in late summer and autumn. The surrounding mountains provide some shelter from extreme weather, making Osaka relatively dry compared to the Pacific coast of eastern Japan.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nOsaka is a major economic engine for Japan and forms the core of the Keihanshin Metropolitan Area, which includes Kyoto and Kobe. Historically a merchant city, Osaka is a hub for commerce, finance, and heavy industry. Key industries include electronics, chemicals, pharmaceuticals, machinery, and metal fabrication. Major corporations such as Panasonic, Sharp, and Keyence have deep roots or headquarters in the prefecture. The administrative center and largest city is Osaka. Other major cities within the prefecture include Sakai, a historic port and manufacturing center known for its ancient keyhole-shaped tombs, Higashiosaka, known for light manufacturing, and Suita, which hosted the Expo '70 and is home to Osaka University.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as Naniwa, Osaka served as an imperial capital of Japan in the seventh and eighth centuries. During the Edo period, it became known as the 'Kitchen of the Nation' because it served as the central clearinghouse for rice and other commodities. Osaka Castle, originally built by Toyotomi Hideyoshi in the late sixteenth century, remains a central historical landmark. Culturally, Osaka is famous for its distinct dialect, Osaka-ben, and its performing arts, including Bunraku puppet theater and Kamigata rakugo comedy. The prefecture is also renowned for its food culture, popularized by the phrase 'kuidaore', meaning to eat until one drops, with signature dishes like takoyaki and okonomiyaki.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Osaka\n* Approximate area: 1,905 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 8.8 million\n* Largest city: Osaka\n* Signature features: Osaka Castle, Kansai International Airport, and the ancient Mozu-Furuichi Kofun Group.",
