    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\n\nShiga Prefecture is a landlocked, first-level administrative division located in the Kansai region on the island of Honshu, Japan. It is positioned in the central-western part of the island. Shiga is bordered by four prefectures: Fukui to the north, Gifu to the east, Mie to the southeast, and Kyoto to the west and south. Because of its central location, Shiga has historically served as a critical transit corridor connecting eastern and western Japan, linking the Kanto region with the Kansai metropolitan area.\n\n## Physical features\n\nThe defining geographical feature of Shiga is Lake Biwa, the largest freshwater lake in Japan. Lake Biwa occupies approximately one-sixth of the prefecture's total land area and sits in a central basin. The lake is fed by over 100 rivers, but it has only one natural outlet, the Seta River, which flows south and eventually becomes the Yodo River. The central basin is ringed by several mountain ranges. To the west lie the Hira Mountains, to the east are the Ibuki Mountains, which include Mount Ibuki, the highest peak in the prefecture at 1,377 meters, and to the southeast are the Suzuka Mountains. The mountainous terrain covers more than half of the prefecture's area, leaving the flat plains around the lake as the primary zones for agriculture and urban settlement.\n\n## Climate\n\nShiga experiences a temperate climate, but there is a stark contrast between the northern and southern regions. The northern part, bordering Fukui and Gifu, is influenced by the Sea of Japan climate patterns. This area experiences heavy snowfall during the winter, with some mountainous zones receiving significant accumulation. In contrast, the southern part, closer to Kyoto, has a milder humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and relatively cold winters with minimal snowfall. Lake Biwa itself exerts a moderating influence on the local climate, reducing temperature extremes in the surrounding lowlands.\n\n## Economy & cities\n\nThe economy of Shiga is highly industrialized, despite its reputation for natural beauty. It has one of the highest ratios of manufacturing output to total gross product in Japan. Major industries include the production of electronic components, transportation equipment, chemicals, and machinery. This industrial development is concentrated along the southern and eastern shores of Lake Biwa, benefiting from excellent rail and highway connections to Kyoto, Osaka, and Nagoya. Agriculture also plays a role, with rice being the primary crop. Traditional industries include Shigaraki ware, a famous style of Japanese pottery, and the production of Omi beef. Otsu, the administrative center, is located on the southwestern shore of Lake Biwa. Other significant cities include Kusatsu, Hikone, Nagahama, and Omihachiman.\n\n## History & culture\n\nHistorically known as Omi Province, Shiga was a vital strategic region. Control over Omi was considered essential for controlling Japan because of its position along major historical highways, including the Tokaido and Nakasendo. The prefecture contains numerous historical sites. Hikone Castle, located in the city of Hikone, is one of the few surviving original castles from the Edo period. On the border between Shiga and Kyoto lies Mount Hiei, home to Enryaku-ji, a historic Buddhist temple complex that served as the headquarters of the Tendai sect and is recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage Site.\n\n## Quick facts\n\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Otsu\n* Approximate area: 4,017 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.41 million\n* Largest city: Otsu\n* Signature features: Lake Biwa, the largest freshwater lake in Japan, and Hikone Castle, a designated National Treasure.",
    "summary": "Shiga Prefecture is a landlocked administrative division in Japan's Kansai region, centered around Lake Biwa, the nation's largest freshwater lake. The prefecture is highly industrialized, featuring major manufacturing sectors alongside historic sites like Hikone Castle and the mountain temple of Enryaku-ji. Its strategic location historically made it a vital transit corridor connecting eastern and western Japan.",
