    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nTochigi Prefecture is a landlocked administrative division situated in the northern portion of the Kanto region on Honshu, the main island of Japan. It is bordered by Fukushima Prefecture to the north, Gunma Prefecture to the west, Ibaraki Prefecture to the east, and Saitama Prefecture to the south. Because it is surrounded entirely by other prefectures, Tochigi has no coastline. Its strategic position connects the Tokyo metropolitan area with the Tohoku region to the north.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Tochigi is highly varied, transitioning from rugged mountains in the north and west to flat plains in the south and east. The mountainous regions are part of the Nasu Volcanic Belt. Notable peaks include Mount Shirane, which is the highest point in the prefecture at an elevation of about 2,578 meters, as well as Mount Nantai and the active volcano Mount Nasu. The southern and central areas form the northernmost extension of the fertile Kanto Plain. Important water bodies include Lake Chuzenji, a scenic caldera lake formed by the eruption of Mount Nantai. The lake drains into the Kegon Falls, one of Japan's most famous waterfalls. Major rivers flowing through the prefecture include the Kinugawa, the Naka, and the Watarase, all of which are vital for agriculture and industry.\n\n## Climate\nTochigi experiences a temperate climate that varies significantly by elevation. The southern plains have a humid subtropical climate characterized by hot, humid summers and cold, dry winters. The northern mountainous regions experience a continental or subarctic climate with heavy winter snowfall. Winters across the prefecture are marked by dry, cold winds known as karakkaze that blow from the northwest. During the summer, the convergence of warm air masses over the mountains frequently causes severe afternoon thunderstorms. Utsunomiya is particularly famous for these storms, earning it a reputation as a city with some of the highest lightning activity in Japan.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Tochigi is highly diversified, balancing agriculture, manufacturing, and tourism. The prefecture is the leading producer of strawberries in Japan, famous for the Tochiotome variety. Other key agricultural products include rice, barley, and kanpyo, which are dried gourd strips. In the industrial sector, Tochigi hosts major manufacturing hubs, particularly in the cities of Utsunomiya, Oyama, and Kaminokawa, where automotive, electronics, and precision machinery factories are located. Tourism is another major economic driver, centered primarily on the historic town of Nikko. Utsunomiya is the capital and largest city, serving as the commercial and transport hub. Other significant urban centers include Ashikaga, Tochigi City, and Sano.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically, the region of Tochigi was known as Shimotsuke Province. It holds deep historical significance, particularly due to the city of Nikko. Nikko is home to the Toshogu Shrine, the mausoleum of the shogun Tokugawa Ieyasu, which is designated as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The prefecture is also home to the Ashikaga Gakko, which is considered Japan's oldest surviving academic institution, dating back to the classical or medieval period. Cultural traditions include the manufacture of Yuki-tsumugi silk fabric, which is registered as an intangible cultural heritage. Local culinary culture is famous for Utsunomiya gyoza, which are pan-fried dumplings, and Sano ramen.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Utsunomiya\n* Approximate area: 6,408 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.9 million\n* Largest city if different from the administrative center: None\n* Signature features: Nikko Toshogu Shrine and Kegon Falls, top strawberry production in Japan",
