    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nTokyo is a first-level prefecture located on the eastern coast of Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It is situated in the Kanto region and faces Tokyo Bay to the southeast. The prefecture is bordered by Yamanashi Prefecture to the west, Kanagawa Prefecture to the south, Chiba Prefecture to the east across the Edogawa River, and Saitama Prefecture to the north. Tokyo also administers several outlying islands in the Pacific Ocean, including the Izu Islands and the Ogasawara Islands, which stretch over 1,000 kilometers south into the Pacific.\n\n## Physical features\nThe mainland portion of Tokyo is divided into the eastern lowlands and the western mountainous region. The eastern part lies on the fertile Kanto Plain, which is drained by major rivers such as the Sumida, Arakawa, Tama, and Edo rivers. The western portion rises into the Okutama Mountains, featuring rugged terrain and peaks such as Mount Kumotori, the highest point in the prefecture at 2,017 meters. This western region contains Chichibu-Tama-Kai National Park, which offers dense forests and deep valleys. The coastal area along Tokyo Bay has been heavily modified by land reclamation, creating artificial islands like Odaiba. The volcanic Izu and Ogasawara archipelagos feature unique marine ecosystems and rugged volcanic topography.\n\n## Climate\nTokyo features a humid subtropical climate, classified as Cfa under the Köppen climate system. It experiences four distinct seasons. Summers are hot, humid, and wet, influenced by the East Asian monsoon, with temperatures frequently exceeding 30 degrees Celsius in August. Winters are generally cool and dry, with sunny days and occasional light snowfall, though temperatures rarely drop far below freezing. Autumn and spring are transitional seasons with mild temperatures and periods of rain. The prefecture is also subject to typhoons, which typically occur between August and October, bringing heavy rainfall and strong winds.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTokyo is the economic, financial, and political heart of Japan. It hosts the headquarters of numerous multinational corporations, major financial institutions, and the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Key industries include finance, technology, publishing, manufacturing, and services. The prefecture is divided into 23 special wards in the east, which function as individual cities, and the Tama area in the west, which contains suburban cities like Hachioji, Tachikawa, and Musashino. The 23 special wards constitute the core of the Greater Tokyo Area, which is the most populous metropolitan area in the world. Major commercial and administrative hubs include Shinjuku, Shibuya, Chiyoda, and Chuo.\n\n## History & culture\nOriginally a small fishing village known as Edo, the settlement rose to prominence in 1603 when Tokugawa Ieyasu established the Tokugawa shogunate there. Although Kyoto remained the imperial capital, Edo became the de facto political center of Japan. In 1868, with the Meiji Restoration, the emperor moved to Edo, which was renamed Tokyo, meaning Eastern Capital. The city suffered massive destruction during the 1923 Great Kanto Earthquake and World War II but was rebuilt rapidly both times. Culturally, Tokyo blends historic traditions with ultra-modern lifestyle. Key cultural sites include the Imperial Palace, Sensō-ji Temple in Asakusa, Meiji Shrine, and Ueno Park, which houses several national museums.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Metropolis (To, a first-level prefecture)\n* Administrative center: Tokyo (specifically the Tokyo Metropolitan Government Building in Shinjuku)\n* Approximate area: 2,194 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 14 million (with over 37 million in the metropolitan area)\n* Largest city: The 23 special wards collectively form the core urban area, with Shinjuku serving as the administrative hub.\n* Signature features: Mount Kumotori, the Imperial Palace, the Shibuya Crossing, and the Ogasawara Islands UNESCO World Heritage site.",
    "summary": "Tokyo is a first-level prefecture of Japan located on the eastern coast of Honshu, serving as the nation's political, economic, and cultural center. The prefecture spans from the flat Kanto Plain and Tokyo Bay in the east to the mountainous Okutama region in the west, while also administering several Pacific island chains. It features a humid subtropical climate and stands as the core of the world's most populous metropolitan area.",
