    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nTokushima Prefecture is situated on the eastern part of Shikoku, the smallest of Japan's four main islands. It is bordered by Kagawa Prefecture to the north, Ehime Prefecture to the west, and Kochi Prefecture to the southwest. To the east and south, Tokushima faces the Kii Channel, the Harima Nada of the Seto Inland Sea, and the Pacific Ocean. The Naruto Strait separates Tokushima from Awaji Island, which is linked to the main island of Honshu. The Onaruto Bridge spans this strait, providing a direct road connection between Shikoku and the Kansai region of Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Tokushima is highly mountainous, with rugged highlands covering more than 80 percent of the prefecture's total land area. The Shikoku Mountains dominate the interior, featuring Mount Tsurugi, which rises to 1,955 meters as the second-highest peak on the island. The Yoshino River, often called Shikoku Saburo, is the primary river system. It flows from west to east through deep valleys, including the scenic Oboke and Koboke gorges, before emptying into the Kii Channel. Along the coast, the narrow Naruto Strait is famous for the Naruto whirlpools, which are created by rapid tidal currents. Environmental preservation is maintained through Setonaikai National Park and Muroto-Anan Kaigan Quasi-National Park.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of Tokushima is divided by the Shikoku Mountains into two distinct zones. The northern region, bordering the Seto Inland Sea, experiences a mild, temperate climate with relatively low annual rainfall. In contrast, the southern region facing the Pacific Ocean has a humid subtropical climate. This southern area receives heavy precipitation, particularly during the summer months, and is frequently affected by typhoons during the late summer and autumn seasons.\n\n## Economy & cities\nTokushima's economy is supported by a mix of agriculture, manufacturing, and technology. The fertile plains surrounding the lower Yoshino River are highly productive, yielding crops such as sweet potatoes, lotus root, and sudachi, a small green citrus fruit. The prefecture is also a major center for chemical manufacturing and advanced technology, notably LED development, with Nichia Corporation headquartered in the city of Anan. Tokushima City is the administrative capital and largest urban center. Other key cities include Naruto, which serves as a northern gateway, and Anan, a major industrial hub on the eastern coast.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically known as Awa Province, the region was historically famous for its production of high-quality indigo dye, known as Awa Ai, which generated substantial wealth during the Edo period. The cultural heritage of the prefecture is highlighted by the Awa Odori, a traditional dance festival held every August in Tokushima City that attracts over one million visitors. Additionally, Tokushima is the starting point for the Shikoku Pilgrimage, a historic Buddhist route visiting 88 temples. The first temple of the pilgrimage, Ryozen-ji, is located in Naruto.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Tokushima City\n* Approximate area: 4,146 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 720,000\n* Largest city: Tokushima City (same as the administrative center)\n* Signature features: Naruto whirlpools and the Awa Odori festival",
