    "mainNotes": "## Location within Japan\nWakayama Prefecture is located in the southwestern part of the Kii Peninsula on Honshu, the largest island of Japan. It is situated in the Kansai region. The prefecture shares its northern border with Osaka Prefecture, its northeastern border with Nara Prefecture, and its eastern border with Mie Prefecture. To the west, Wakayama faces the Kii Channel, which connects the Seto Inland Sea to the Pacific Ocean. The southern and southeastern coasts of the prefecture lie directly along the Pacific Ocean. Cape Shionomisaki, located at the southern tip of the prefecture, is the southernmost point of the island of Honshu.\n\n## Physical features\nThe terrain of Wakayama is highly mountainous, with the Kii Mountain Range covering over 70 percent of the prefecture's total land area. These rugged mountains slope steeply down to the coast, leaving very little flat land for agriculture or urban development. Major peaks include Mount Obako and Mount Ryujin. The prefecture is drained by several significant river systems, including the Kinokawa River in the north, the Aridagawa River, the Hidaka River, and the Kumano River, which forms part of the eastern border with Mie Prefecture. The coastline is highly indented, particularly in the south, featuring rias coastlines and dramatic rock formations like Hashigui-iwa. Yoshino-Kumano National Park protects much of the mountainous interior and southern coastal areas.\n\n## Climate\nWakayama experiences a humid subtropical climate characterized by warm, wet summers and mild winters. The climate varies significantly between the northern and southern regions. The northern part of the prefecture, sheltered by mountains, receives moderate rainfall and has weather patterns similar to the Seto Inland Sea region. In contrast, the southern mountainous areas and coastal zones receive some of the highest annual rainfall in Japan, often exceeding 3,000 millimeters, due to moist air masses coming off the Pacific Ocean. The warm Kuroshio Current flows along the southern coast, keeping winter temperatures relatively mild and preventing severe frosts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Wakayama relies heavily on agriculture, forestry, and heavy industry. It is Japan's leading producer of mandarin oranges, locally known as mikan, and Japanese plums, known as ume, which are cultivated on the terraced hillsides. Forestry is prominent in the mountainous interior, utilizing high-quality timber like Yoshino cedar. Heavy industry is concentrated in the northern coastal strip around the capital city of Wakayama, featuring steel mills, chemical plants, and petroleum refineries. The capital, Wakayama, is the largest city and the administrative center. Other key cities include Tanabe, the gateway to the southern pilgrimage routes, Shingu on the eastern border, and Hashimoto in the northeast.\n\n## History & culture\nHistorically known as the province of Kishu, the region was ruled by the powerful Kishu-Tokugawa clan during the Edo period. Wakayama is deeply associated with spiritual traditions. The Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, span the prefecture. This includes Mount Koya, also known as Koyasan, the headquarters of the Shingon sect of Buddhism founded by the monk Kukai in the early ninth century. It also includes the Kumano Sanzan, a network of ancient Shinto shrines. Nachi Falls, located near Nachi Primeval Forest, is the tallest single-drop waterfall in Japan and is revered as a sacred site.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Japan\n* Subdivision type: Prefecture\n* Administrative center: Wakayama\n* Approximate area: 4,724 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 910,000\n* Largest city: Wakayama (same as the administrative center)\n* Signature features: Mount Koya temple complex, Kumano Kodo pilgrimage routes, and Nachi Falls",
