    "mainNotes": "## Location within Canada\nQuebec is located in the eastern part of Canada. It is the largest province in the country by area. It shares land borders with the province of Ontario to the west, Newfoundland and Labrador to the northeast, and New Brunswick to the southeast. To the south, Quebec borders the United States, specifically Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont, and New York. The province has extensive maritime borders and coastlines along James Bay, Hudson Bay, and Ungava Bay to the west and north, as well as the Gulf of Saint Lawrence to the east. The territory of Nunavut lies across the northern marine borders.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Quebec is defined by three main geological regions. The Canadian Shield covers roughly ninety percent of the province, dominating the northern and central areas. This region is characterized by rocky terrain, dense boreal forests, and thousands of lakes and rivers. The Saint Lawrence Lowlands are located in the southern part of the province and feature flat, fertile terrain where the majority of the population resides. The Appalachian region extends through the southeastern part of the province, including the Gaspé Peninsula, and features rolling hills and worn mountain ranges. The Saint Lawrence River is the most significant waterway, connecting the Great Lakes to the Atlantic Ocean. Other major rivers include the Ottawa, Saguenay, and Rupert rivers. Lake Mistassini is the largest natural lake in the province, while the Manicouagan Reservoir is a massive crater lake.\n\n## Climate\nQuebec experiences three main climate regions. The southern and western parts of the province, where most major cities are located, have a humid continental climate. This area experiences four distinct seasons, with warm summers and cold, snowy winters. The central region features a subarctic climate, characterized by long, severely cold winters and short, cool summers. The extreme northern region of Nunavik has an arctic climate with tundra vegetation, featuring continuous freezing temperatures for most of the year and very brief, cool summers.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Quebec is highly diversified, with significant sectors in aerospace, information technology, biotechnology, and pharmaceuticals. The province is a major producer of hydroelectricity, managed by the provincial crown corporation Hydro-Québec. Natural resources play a large role, with extensive mining of iron ore, gold, and diamonds, alongside a massive forestry industry. Agriculture is concentrated in the Saint Lawrence Lowlands, where dairy production and maple syrup extraction are prominent. Montreal is the largest city and serves as the primary economic and cultural hub. Quebec City is the administrative center and the second-largest metropolitan area. Other significant cities include Laval, Gatineau, Longueuil, Sherbrooke, and Trois-Rivières.\n\n## History & culture\nPrior to European contact, the land was inhabited by various Indigenous peoples, including Algonquian, Iroquoian, and Inuit groups. French explorer Samuel de Champlain founded Quebec City in 1608, establishing the core of the French colony of New France. Following the Seven Years War, the territory was ceded to Great Britain in 1763 under the Treaty of Paris. Quebec is unique in North America for its distinct French-Canadian culture. It is the only Canadian province where French is the sole official language and where the majority of the population is francophone. The province also maintains a civil law system derived from the French tradition, unlike the common law system used in the rest of Canada.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Canada\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Quebec City\n* Approximate area: 1.5 million square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 8.9 million\n* Largest city: Montreal\n* Signature features: Predominantly francophone population, the Saint Lawrence River valley, and extensive hydroelectric infrastructure.",
    "summary": "Quebec is the largest province in Canada by area and is uniquely characterized by its predominantly francophone population and French-Canadian culture. Its geography is dominated by the vast Canadian Shield in the north and the fertile Saint Lawrence Lowlands in the south, where most of its population and economic activity are concentrated. The province has a highly diversified economy supported by abundant natural resources, aerospace manufacturing, and massive hydroelectric power generation.",
