    "mainNotes": "## Location within Canada\nThe Northwest Territories is a federal territory located in northern Canada. It shares land borders with the territory of Yukon to the west and the territory of Nunavut to the east. To the south, it borders the provinces of British Columbia, Alberta, and Saskatchewan. The northern edge of the territory features a coastline along the Arctic Ocean, specifically bordering the Beaufort Sea and the Amundsen Gulf. The territory also encompasses several islands in the western portion of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago, including Banks Island, Prince Patrick Island, and portions of Victoria Island and Melville Island.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of the Northwest Territories is defined by vast lakes, major river systems, and rugged mountain ranges. The Mackenzie River, which is the longest river system in Canada, flows north through the territory and empties into the Beaufort Sea. The territory contains two of the largest lakes in North America. Great Bear Lake is the largest lake located entirely within Canada, and Great Slave Lake is the deepest lake in North America. The western edge of the territory is dominated by the Mackenzie Mountains, which form a natural boundary with Yukon. The eastern portion of the territory sits on the Canadian Shield, characterized by exposed Precambrian rock and thousands of smaller lakes. Notable protected areas include Nahanni National Park Reserve, known for Virginia Falls and deep river canyons, and Wood Buffalo National Park, which extends into Alberta.\n\n## Climate\nThe Northwest Territories experiences two primary climate zones. The southern and central regions have a subarctic climate, which brings long, extremely cold winters and short, relatively warm summers. The northern coastal areas and the Arctic islands have a polar tundra climate, where winters are severe and summer temperatures rarely rise above freezing for extended periods. Precipitation is generally low across the territory, and many northern areas are classified as cold deserts. Permafrost, which is ground that remains completely frozen for at least two consecutive years, is widespread. This frozen ground heavily influences local ecosystems and requires specialized engineering for buildings and transportation infrastructure.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of the Northwest Territories relies heavily on the extraction of natural resources. Diamond mining is the most significant industry, with major operations located at the Ekati, Diavik, and Gahcho Kué mines. The territory also holds substantial reserves of oil and natural gas, particularly in the Mackenzie Delta and the Beaufort Sea regions. Tourism is a growing sector, driven by wilderness recreation and aurora borealis viewing. Yellowknife is the administrative center and the largest city, situated on the northern shore of Great Slave Lake. Other significant communities include Inuvik in the north, Hay River and Fort Smith in the south, and Norman Wells along the Mackenzie River.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples have inhabited the region for thousands of years. The population includes diverse groups such as the Dene, Inuit, Inuvialuit, and Métis. European exploration of the area began in the late sixteenth century and expanded when Alexander Mackenzie navigated the Mackenzie River to the Arctic Ocean in 1789. The region was historically part of Rupert's Land and the North-Western Territory, which the British Crown transferred to Canada in 1870. The borders of the Northwest Territories have been reduced several times to create other provinces and territories. The most recent change occurred in 1999 when the eastern half of the territory was separated to form the new territory of Nunavut. The territorial government recognizes eleven official languages, which include English, French, and nine Indigenous languages.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Canada\n* Subdivision type: Territory\n* Administrative center: Yellowknife\n* Approximate area: 1,346,000 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 41,000\n* Largest city: Yellowknife\n* Signature features: The Mackenzie River, Great Bear Lake, Great Slave Lake, and major diamond mining operations",
    "summary": "The Northwest Territories is a vast federal territory in northern Canada known for its extensive river systems, massive lakes, and significant diamond mining industry. Its geography ranges from the Mackenzie Mountains in the west to the Canadian Shield in the east, with a climate that varies from subarctic to polar tundra. Yellowknife serves as the administrative center for a diverse population that recognizes eleven official languages.",
