    "mainNotes": "## Location within Canada\nNewfoundland and Labrador is the easternmost province of Canada. It consists of two distinct geographical parts. Newfoundland is a large island in the Atlantic Ocean, and Labrador is located on the mainland of the North American continent. Labrador borders the province of Quebec to the south and west. To the east, Labrador faces the Labrador Sea, which is a branch of the Atlantic Ocean. The island of Newfoundland is separated from Labrador by the Strait of Belle Isle. To the southwest, the island is separated from the province of Nova Scotia by the Cabot Strait. The French overseas collectivity of Saint-Pierre and Miquelon lies just off the southern coast of the island of Newfoundland.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province features a rugged and diverse landscape. The island of Newfoundland is characterized by rocky coastlines, deep fjords, and numerous bays, such as Placentia Bay and Bonavista Bay. The Long Range Mountains form the western spine of the island and are a northeastern extension of the Appalachian Mountains. Gros Morne National Park, located in this mountain range, is known for its exposed ocean crust and deep glacial valleys. On the mainland, Labrador is part of the Canadian Shield, featuring ancient bedrock, vast boreal forests, and thousands of lakes. The Torngat Mountains dominate northern Labrador, containing Mount Caubvick, the highest point in the province at roughly 1,652 meters. Major rivers in Labrador include the Churchill River, which flows into the Atlantic Ocean and is a significant source of hydroelectric power.\n\n## Climate\nThe province experiences a range of climates due to its vast size and maritime location. The island of Newfoundland generally has a humid continental climate, heavily influenced by the ocean. The cold Labrador Current flows south along the eastern coast, keeping summer temperatures relatively cool and bringing frequent fog, especially when it meets the warm Gulf Stream over the Grand Banks. Winters on the island are relatively mild compared to the mainland but receive heavy snowfall. Labrador has a subarctic climate, with much colder, longer winters and shorter, cooler summers. Coastal areas of Labrador are moderated slightly by the ocean, while the interior experiences more extreme temperature variations.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Newfoundland and Labrador was historically based on the Atlantic cod fishery. Following the collapse of the cod fishery in the early 1990s, the province diversified its economy. Offshore oil and gas extraction on the Grand Banks is now a major economic driver. Mining is also significant, with large iron ore deposits in western Labrador near Labrador City and nickel mined at Voisey's Bay. Hydroelectric power generation, particularly the Churchill Falls generating station in Labrador, provides substantial energy and revenue. Tourism has grown, centered on the province's natural landscapes and historical sites. St. John's is the administrative center and largest city, located on the Avalon Peninsula of Newfoundland. Other important municipalities include Corner Brook on the western coast of the island, Mount Pearl near St. John's, and Happy Valley-Goose Bay in central Labrador.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples, including the Beothuk on the island and the Innu and Inuit in Labrador, have inhabited the region for thousands of years. The Norse established a brief settlement at L'Anse aux Meadows on the northern tip of Newfoundland around the year 1000, marking the earliest known European presence in North America. In 1497, John Cabot explored the coast, leading to centuries of seasonal fishing by European fleets. Newfoundland became a British colony and later a dominion. It remained separate from Canada until 1949, when it joined the confederation as the tenth province. The culture is heavily influenced by its English, Irish, and Indigenous heritage, noted for distinct dialects of English, traditional folk music, and maritime folklore.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Canada\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: St. John's\n* Approximate area: 405,212 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 538,000\n* Largest city: St. John's\n* Signature features: Gros Morne National Park, L'Anse aux Meadows Norse settlement, Grand Banks fishery, Torngat Mountains",
    "summary": "Newfoundland and Labrador is the easternmost province of Canada, comprising the island of Newfoundland and the mainland region of Labrador. The province is known for its rugged maritime landscapes, offshore oil and gas industry, and historical significance as an early site of European exploration in North America. St. John's serves as the administrative center and largest city, anchoring an economy that has transitioned from traditional fishing to energy and mining.",
