    "mainNotes": "## Location within Canada\nYukon is the westernmost of Canada's three federal territories, situated in the northwest corner of the country. It shares a domestic border with the Northwest Territories to the east and the province of British Columbia to the south. To the west, Yukon shares an international border with the United States, specifically the state of Alaska. The territory also features a small northern coastline along the Beaufort Sea, which is a marginal sea of the Arctic Ocean.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Yukon is defined by its rugged, mountainous terrain and extensive river systems. The territory is located within the North American Cordillera. The Saint Elias Mountains in the southwest contain Mount Logan. At roughly 5,959 meters, Mount Logan is the highest peak in Canada and the second highest in North America.\n\nThe territory takes its name from the Yukon River, the primary watercourse in the region. The river originates in British Columbia, flows northwest through Yukon, and continues into Alaska. Other major rivers include the Pelly, Stewart, and Peel rivers. Large lakes, such as Kluane Lake and Lake Laberge, are scattered throughout the valleys.\n\nYukon contains several protected areas. Kluane National Park and Reserve, located in the southwest, protects vast ice fields and mountain landscapes. In the north, Ivvavik National Park and Vuntut National Park preserve Arctic tundra and crucial caribou calving grounds. The vegetation transitions from dense boreal forests in the southern and central regions to treeless tundra in the northernmost latitudes.\n\n## Climate\nMost of Yukon experiences a subarctic climate, characterized by long, bitterly cold winters and short, mild summers. The far northern regions and high mountain elevations feature a tundra climate. Due to its high latitude, the territory experiences extreme variations in daylight, with midnight sun in the summer and polar night in the winter.\n\nPrecipitation is generally low across the territory, as the coastal mountains in neighboring Alaska block moisture from the Pacific Ocean. This creates a semi-arid environment in many interior valleys. Despite the low precipitation, winter snow accumulation is significant. The territory is known for extreme cold events. The village of Snag holds the record for the lowest recorded temperature in North America, reaching negative 63 degrees Celsius in 1947.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Yukon is heavily dependent on the mining industry. Historically focused on gold, modern extraction also includes zinc, lead, silver, and copper. Government services and administration form the largest sector of employment, supported by federal transfers. Tourism is another vital industry, drawing visitors for outdoor recreation, hunting, fishing, and viewing the aurora borealis.\n\nWhitehorse is the administrative center and the only incorporated city. It serves as the commercial and transportation hub, housing roughly seventy percent of the total population. Dawson City, located further north along the Yukon River, is the second largest municipality and a major historical site. Other notable communities include Watson Lake, Haines Junction, and Carmacks, which primarily serve as regional service centers along the highway network.\n\n## History & culture\nIndigenous peoples have inhabited the Yukon region for thousands of years. Today, Yukon First Nations make up a significant portion of the population and include groups such as the Gwich'in, Han, Kaska, Tutchone, and Tlingit. Many of these First Nations have signed comprehensive land claim and self-government agreements, giving them substantial autonomy.\n\nEuropean and Canadian presence increased in the nineteenth century through the fur trade. The region experienced a massive population boom during the Klondike Gold Rush of 1896, which brought tens of thousands of prospectors to the Dawson City area. This rapid influx led the Canadian government to separate Yukon from the Northwest Territories in 1898, establishing it as a distinct territory. During World War II, the construction of the Alaska Highway connected the territory to the North American road network, shifting the economic and demographic center from Dawson City to Whitehorse.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Canada\n* Subdivision type: Territory\n* Administrative center: Whitehorse\n* Approximate area: 482,443 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 44,000\n* Largest city: Whitehorse\n* Signature features: Mount Logan, Yukon River, Klondike Gold Rush history, extensive boreal forests and tundra.",
    "summary": "Yukon is the westernmost of Canada's three territories, known for its rugged mountainous terrain, subarctic climate, and rich Indigenous heritage. Its economy is largely driven by mining, government services, and tourism centered around its vast national parks and historical sites. The territory's population is highly concentrated in Whitehorse, which serves as the administrative and commercial hub.",
