    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nBavaria is located in the southeastern corner of Germany. It is the largest German state by land area. It shares international borders with Austria to the south and southeast, and the Czech Republic to the east. Domestically, it borders the German states of Baden-Württemberg to the west, Hesse to the northwest, Thuringia to the north, and Saxony to the northeast.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of Bavaria is diverse, ranging from high alpine peaks to rolling hills and river valleys. The Bavarian Alps dominate the southern border with Austria, featuring the Zugspitze, which is the highest mountain in Germany at roughly 2,962 meters. North of the Alps lies the Alpine Foreland, a relatively flat plateau dotted with glacial lakes such as Lake Starnberg, Ammersee, and Chiemsee. The Danube River flows west to east across the central part of the state, serving as a major geographic and commercial artery. Other significant rivers include the Main in the northern region of Franconia, and the Isar and Inn rivers in the south. The Bavarian Forest and the Bohemian Forest form a low mountain range along the eastern border with the Czech Republic, creating one of the largest contiguous forest areas in Europe.\n\n## Climate\nBavaria experiences a temperate continental climate. Winters are generally cold, with frequent snowfall, especially in the higher elevations of the Bavarian Alps and the Bavarian Forest. Summers are warm and can be humid. Precipitation is distributed throughout the year, though summer months often see the highest rainfall due to thunderstorms. The Alpine regions exhibit a distinct mountain climate with lower average temperatures and higher precipitation compared to the river valleys in the north. The Föhn wind, a warm and dry downslope wind, occasionally raises temperatures in the Alpine Foreland during the colder months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nBavaria has one of the largest economies in Europe. It transitioned from a largely agrarian state to a high-technology and industrial center after the mid-twentieth century. Major industries include automotive manufacturing, aerospace, mechanical engineering, and electronics. Munich is the administrative center and the largest city, serving as a hub for finance, technology, and insurance. Other major cities include Nuremberg, which is a center for manufacturing and logistics, as well as Augsburg, Regensburg, Ingolstadt, and Würzburg. Agriculture remains important in rural areas, with significant production of dairy, hops, and barley. Tourism is also a major economic sector, drawing visitors to the alpine resorts and historic towns.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by Celtic tribes and later incorporated into the Roman Empire. The Duchy of Bavaria emerged in the sixth century and eventually became a kingdom in 1806. It joined the German Empire in 1871 while retaining a distinct cultural identity. Bavaria is culturally divided into three main regions: Old Bavaria, Franconia, and Swabia. It is known for its strong Catholic heritage, which influences local traditions and public holidays. Traditional attire, such as lederhosen and dirndls, is still worn during festivals. The state is widely known for Oktoberfest, an annual festival held in Munich, and for its historic architecture, including Neuschwanstein Castle commissioned by King Ludwig II.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Land)\n* Administrative center: Munich\n* Approximate area: 70,550 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 13.3 million\n* Largest city: Munich\n* Signature features: The Bavarian Alps, Neuschwanstein Castle, and Oktoberfest",
    "summary": "Bavaria is the largest state in Germany, located in the southeastern part of the country and known for its diverse geography that includes the Bavarian Alps and the Danube River. Its economy is a major European industrial and technological hub centered around its capital, Munich. The state retains a distinct cultural identity famous for historic castles, traditional festivals like Oktoberfest, and strong regional traditions.",
