    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nBaden-Württemberg is a state located in the southwestern corner of Germany. It shares international borders with France to the west and Switzerland to the south. Within Germany, it is bordered by Rhineland-Palatinate to the northwest, Hesse to the north, and Bavaria to the east. The western and southern borders are largely defined by the natural boundaries of the Rhine river and Lake Constance.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Baden-Württemberg is characterized by diverse landscapes, including forested mountains, river valleys, and fertile plains. The Black Forest is a prominent mountain range in the western part of the state, running parallel to the Rhine valley. The highest peak in the Black Forest is the Feldberg, which reaches an elevation of 1,493 meters. To the east lies the Swabian Jura, a limestone plateau known for its karst topography and extensive cave systems. The state is shaped by several major rivers. The Rhine forms the western border, flowing through the Upper Rhine Plain. The Neckar river flows through the central part of the state, passing through Stuttgart and Heidelberg before joining the Rhine. The Danube river originates in the Black Forest and flows eastward through the southern part of the state. Lake Constance, situated in the south, is shared with Switzerland and Austria.\n\n## Climate\nBaden-Württemberg experiences a temperate seasonal climate, with variations largely dependent on elevation. The Upper Rhine Plain is one of the warmest and sunniest regions in Germany, featuring mild winters and warm summers that support viticulture. In contrast, the higher elevations of the Black Forest and the Swabian Jura have a cooler climate with lower average temperatures and higher precipitation. During the winter months, these mountainous areas frequently receive snowfall, while the lower river valleys experience rain. Average summer temperatures in the plains hover around 20 degrees Celsius, whereas winter temperatures often drop below freezing in the uplands.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe state possesses one of the strongest economies in Europe, heavily focused on manufacturing, engineering, and technology. The automotive industry is a major economic driver, with companies like Mercedes-Benz and Porsche headquartered in Stuttgart. Other significant sectors include mechanical engineering, electronics, and information technology, with the software company SAP based in Walldorf. Stuttgart is the administrative center and the largest city. Other major urban centers include Mannheim and Karlsruhe, both located in the Rhine valley and known for their industrial and research facilities. Freiburg im Breisgau is situated near the Black Forest and is noted for its environmental research. Heidelberg and Tübingen are historic university towns, while Ulm is situated on the Danube river.\n\n## History & culture\nBaden-Württemberg was established in 1952 through the merger of three post-World War II states: South Baden, Württemberg-Baden, and Württemberg-Hohenzollern. Historically, the region was part of the Duchy of Swabia within the Holy Roman Empire. The cultural landscape is divided primarily between the Alemannic traditions in the south and west, and the Swabian traditions in the center and east. The state is known for specific regional dialects, including Swabian and Alemannic German. Traditional cultural exports include the cuckoo clock, which originated in the Black Forest, and culinary items such as Black Forest gateau, Maultaschen, and Spätzle. The region also contains numerous historical sites, including Hohenzollern Castle and the Maulbronn Monastery.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Bundesland)\n* Administrative center: Stuttgart\n* Approximate area: About 35,750 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: Roughly 11.1 million\n* Largest city: Stuttgart\n* Signature features: The Black Forest, Lake Constance, and a heavy concentration of automotive and engineering industries.",
    "summary": "Baden-Württemberg is a highly industrialized state in southwestern Germany known for its strong automotive and engineering sectors. Its diverse geography includes the Black Forest, the Swabian Jura, and the origins of the Danube river. Formed in 1952, the state blends Swabian and Alemannic cultural traditions with major urban centers like Stuttgart, Mannheim, and Karlsruhe.",
