    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nBremen is a city-state located in the northwestern part of Germany. It is the smallest of the sixteen German states by both area and population. The state consists of two non-contiguous territories. These are the city of Bremen and the coastal city of Bremerhaven. Both of these territories are completely enclaved by the state of Lower Saxony. Bremerhaven is situated roughly sixty kilometers to the north of the city of Bremen. The state is positioned along the Weser River, which provides direct access to the North Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe state of Bremen lies entirely within the North German Plain. The terrain is exceptionally flat, with very little variation in elevation. The highest natural point in the state reaches only about thirty-two meters above sea level at Friedehorst Park. The dominant geographic feature is the Weser River. The river flows northwest through the city of Bremen, widening significantly as it reaches Bremerhaven and forms an estuary before emptying into the North Sea. The landscape surrounding the urban areas consists largely of marshlands and wet meadows. The Wümme River, a tributary of the Weser, flows through the northern and eastern parts of the city of Bremen, creating a nature reserve area known as the Blockland. Urban green spaces are prominent, with the Bürgerpark serving as one of the largest privately funded city parks in Germany.\n\n## Climate\nBremen experiences a temperate oceanic climate. The proximity to the North Sea heavily influences the weather patterns. Winters are generally mild, with average January temperatures hovering just above freezing. Summers are moderately warm, with July temperatures averaging around twenty-three degrees Celsius. Precipitation occurs relatively evenly throughout the year, with no distinct dry season. Coastal winds are common, particularly in Bremerhaven, where the maritime influence is strongest. Snowfall is infrequent and rarely accumulates for extended periods.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe state comprises only two municipalities, which are the city of Bremen and the city of Bremerhaven. The economy is heavily industrialized and historically rooted in maritime trade. The ports of Bremen and Bremerhaven form one of the largest port complexes in Europe, handling significant volumes of container traffic and automobile imports and exports. Beyond shipping, the state is a major center for the automotive and aerospace industries. A large Mercedes-Benz plant operates in Bremen, while companies like Airbus and ArianeGroup maintain substantial aerospace manufacturing and research facilities. The food and beverage sector is also prominent, featuring major coffee roasting operations and the historic Beck's Brewery. In recent years, Bremerhaven has developed a growing offshore wind energy sector.\n\n## History & culture\nBremen has a long history of autonomy, dating back to its membership in the Hanseatic League during the Middle Ages. This legacy of independence is reflected in its official name, the Free Hanseatic City of Bremen. The historic market square in the city of Bremen features the Town Hall and the Roland Statue, both of which are designated as a UNESCO World Heritage site. These monuments symbolize the civic liberty and trading rights of the city. The state is also famous for the Brothers Grimm fairy tale about the Town Musicians of Bremen, commemorated by a bronze statue near the Town Hall. Following the Second World War, Bremen was established as an enclave of the American occupation zone within the surrounding British zone, which allowed it to retain its status as an independent state in modern Germany.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State\n* Administrative center: Bremen\n* Approximate area: 419 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 680,000\n* Largest city: Bremen\n* Signature features: Two non-contiguous enclaves, Hanseatic League history, major European port complex",
    "summary": "Bremen is the smallest state in Germany, consisting of two non-contiguous cities, Bremen and Bremerhaven, which are completely surrounded by Lower Saxony. Situated along the Weser River near the North Sea, the state has a strong maritime economy supported by major port facilities, aerospace manufacturing, and automotive industries. Its long history of independence is rooted in its legacy as a prominent member of the Hanseatic League.",
