    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nNorth Rhine-Westphalia is situated in the western part of Germany. It shares domestic borders with Lower Saxony to the north and northeast, Hesse to the southeast, and Rhineland-Palatinate to the south. Internationally, the state borders the Netherlands to the west and northwest, specifically the provinces of Limburg, Gelderland, and Overijssel. To the southwest, it shares a border with Belgium, specifically the Walloon region.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of North Rhine-Westphalia is divided into two primary regions. The northern half is part of the North German Plain, characterized by the flat topography of the Westphalian Lowland. The southern and eastern parts of the state transition into the German Central Uplands. Notable highland areas include the Eifel in the southwest, the Bergisches Land, the Sauerland, and the Teutoburg Forest. The highest elevation in the state is the Langenberg in the Rothaargebirge, reaching roughly 843 meters above sea level.\n\nThe state is defined by its major river systems. The Rhine flows from south to north through the western part of the state, serving as a significant inland waterway. Its major tributaries within the state include the Ruhr, the Lippe, and the Sieg. The Ems river originates in the Senne region and flows northward, while the Weser river forms a portion of the eastern border with Lower Saxony.\n\n## Climate\nNorth Rhine-Westphalia experiences a temperate oceanic climate, which gradually transitions into a more continental climate toward the eastern and southeastern highlands. Winters are generally mild, and summers are moderately warm. Precipitation occurs year-round. The lowland areas along the Rhine valley are typically the warmest parts of the state. In contrast, the mountainous regions, such as the Sauerland and the Eifel, experience lower average temperatures and higher annual precipitation, including significant snowfall during the winter months.\n\n## Economy & cities\nNorth Rhine-Westphalia is the most populous state in Germany and possesses the largest state economy in the country. Historically, the state was the industrial heartland of Germany, driven by coal mining and steel production in the Ruhr valley. Over the past several decades, the economy has transitioned toward the service sector, high technology, media, and advanced manufacturing.\n\nThe Rhine-Ruhr metropolitan region is a major European population and economic center. Düsseldorf serves as the administrative center and is a hub for telecommunications, fashion, and finance. Cologne is the largest city in the state, recognized for its media industry, chemical manufacturing, and automobile production. Other major cities include Dortmund, Essen, and Duisburg. Duisburg is notable for operating the largest inland port in the world. Additional significant urban centers include Münster, Bielefeld, and Aachen.\n\n## History & culture\nThe modern state of North Rhine-Westphalia was established in 1946 by the British military administration following World War II. It was created by merging the northern portion of the Prussian Rhine Province with the Prussian Province of Westphalia. The former Free State of Lippe was incorporated into the state in 1947.\n\nThe cultural landscape is diverse, reflecting the historical division between the Rhineland and Westphalia. The Rhineland is recognized for its annual Carnival celebrations, particularly in Cologne and Düsseldorf. The state contains several prominent historical landmarks, including multiple UNESCO World Heritage sites. Aachen Cathedral was the coronation site for German kings, Cologne Cathedral is a major example of Gothic architecture, and the Zollverein Coal Mine Industrial Complex in Essen preserves the industrial history of the Ruhr region.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Bundesland)\n* Administrative center: Düsseldorf\n* Approximate area: 34,100 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 18.1 million\n* Largest city: Cologne\n* Signature features: Rhine-Ruhr metropolitan region, Cologne Cathedral, Ruhr valley industrial heritage",
