    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nSaxony-Anhalt is a landlocked state located in the central-eastern part of Germany. It shares borders with four other German states. To the northwest lies Lower Saxony, while Brandenburg is located to the northeast. The state of Saxony borders it to the southeast, and Thuringia is situated to the southwest. The state occupies a geographical transitional zone between the North German Plain and the Central Uplands.\n\n## Physical features\nThe landscape of Saxony-Anhalt is geographically diverse, divided broadly into the flat northern plains and the hilly or mountainous southern regions. The Altmark in the north is a sparsely populated, low-lying area characterized by heathlands, pine forests, and bogs. South of the Altmark is the Magdeburger Börde, a region noted for its exceptionally fertile loess soils. The southwestern part of the state is dominated by the Harz Mountains. The Brocken is the highest peak in the Harz and in Saxony-Anhalt, reaching an elevation of 1,141 meters. The state is intersected by several major rivers. The Elbe River flows from southeast to northwest, serving as a primary waterway. Its major tributary, the Saale River, flows northward through the southern part of the state, joined by other rivers like the Unstrut and the Bode.\n\n## Climate\nSaxony-Anhalt experiences a temperate climate that represents a transition between the maritime climate of Western Europe and the continental climate of Eastern Europe. Summers are generally warm, and winters are moderately cold. Precipitation varies significantly across the state due to the topography. The Harz Mountains receive the highest amounts of rainfall and snow, as they intercept moisture-laden winds from the west. This creates a rain shadow effect to the east of the mountains. Consequently, the central plains, including the Magdeburger Börde and the area around Halle, are among the driest regions in Germany.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Saxony-Anhalt relies on a mix of heavy industry, chemical manufacturing, agriculture, and renewable energy. The southern region around Halle, Merseburg, and Bitterfeld is historically known as the Central German Chemical Triangle, which remains a major hub for the chemical and plastics industries. The fertile soils of the Magdeburger Börde support intensive agriculture, with primary crops including sugar beets, wheat, and barley. The state is also a significant producer of wind and solar energy. Magdeburg is the administrative center and a major inland port on the Elbe River. Halle is the largest city by population and serves as an important cultural and educational center. Other notable cities include Dessau-Roßlau and Wittenberg.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has played a central role in European history, particularly during the Protestant Reformation. The theologian Martin Luther lived and worked in Wittenberg, and he was born and died in Eisleben. Both towns contain UNESCO World Heritage sites related to his life. The state is also known for its architectural heritage. The city of Dessau is famous for the Bauhaus school of design, which operated there in the 1920s and early 1930s and heavily influenced modern architecture. Following World War II, the area became part of the German Democratic Republic. Saxony-Anhalt was re-established as a state in 1990 during the reunification of Germany.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Land)\n* Administrative center: Magdeburg\n* Approximate area: 20,450 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.18 million\n* Largest city: Halle (Saale)\n* Signature features: The Harz Mountains and Brocken peak, Martin Luther heritage sites in Wittenberg and Eisleben, Bauhaus architecture in Dessau",
    "summary": "Saxony-Anhalt is a landlocked state in central-eastern Germany known for its diverse geography, ranging from the flat northern plains to the Harz Mountains in the southwest. Its economy is driven by the chemical industry, agriculture in the fertile Magdeburger Börde, and renewable energy. The state holds significant historical importance as the birthplace of the Protestant Reformation and a center for Bauhaus architecture.",
