    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nHamburg is a city-state situated in northern Germany. It is completely surrounded by two other German states. The state of Schleswig-Holstein borders it to the north, and the state of Lower Saxony borders it to the south. Hamburg is located at the head of the funnel-shaped estuary of the Elbe River, which flows into the North Sea roughly 110 kilometers to the northwest.\n\n## Physical features\nHamburg is situated on the North German Plain, and its terrain is predominantly flat and low-lying. The Elbe River is the primary geographic feature, dividing into the Northern Elbe and Southern Elbe before rejoining to form a large island called Wilhelmsburg in the center of the city. The Alster River, a tributary of the Elbe, has been dammed to create two artificial lakes within the city center: the Binnenalster and the Außenalster. Another significant tributary is the Bille River. The region features numerous canals and bridges. The Wadden Sea National Park of Hamburg is a small exclave located at the mouth of the Elbe River in the North Sea. This exclave features tidal mudflats and includes the small islands of Neuwerk, Scharhörn, and Nigehörn.\n\n## Climate\nHamburg experiences an oceanic climate. The proximity to the North Sea and the Atlantic Ocean brings maritime influences, resulting in mild winters and relatively cool summers. Average temperatures in January are roughly 2 degrees Celsius, while July averages around 18 degrees Celsius. Precipitation is distributed evenly throughout the year, with an annual average of about 770 millimeters. The city frequently experiences overcast skies and breezy conditions. Occasional strong winds and storm surges occur during the winter months, requiring extensive flood protection systems along the Elbe.\n\n## Economy & cities\nHamburg is a single municipality that also functions as a federal state. It has a highly developed economy. The Port of Hamburg is the third-largest port in Europe, serving as a major hub for international trade, logistics, and shipping. The city is also a major center for the aerospace industry, hosting significant Airbus manufacturing and assembly facilities. Other key economic sectors include media, publishing, financial services, and renewable energy. Hamburg is divided into seven administrative boroughs, including Hamburg-Mitte, Altona, Eimsbüttel, Hamburg-Nord, Wandsbek, Bergedorf, and Harburg.\n\n## History & culture\nHamburg has a long history as a trading center. It was a leading member of the Hanseatic League, a medieval commercial and defensive confederation of merchant guilds and market towns. This legacy is reflected in its official name, the Free and Hanseatic City of Hamburg. The city suffered severe damage during the Great Fire of 1842 and heavy bombing during World War II, leading to extensive postwar reconstruction. Notable cultural and architectural landmarks include the Speicherstadt, a large historic warehouse district recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage site. The Elbphilharmonie is a modern concert hall built on top of an old warehouse near the harbor. The Reeperbahn in the St. Pauli district is a historic entertainment area.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (City-state)\n* Administrative center: Hamburg\n* Approximate area: 755 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 1.9 million\n* Largest city: Hamburg\n* Signature features: Port of Hamburg, Speicherstadt warehouse district, Alster lakes",
    "summary": "Hamburg is a German city-state located on the Elbe River, serving as one of Europe's most important port cities and logistical hubs. Known for its extensive network of canals, the historic Speicherstadt warehouse district, and its Hanseatic legacy, the state features a flat, low-lying landscape with an oceanic climate.",
