    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nThuringia is a landlocked state located in the central part of Germany. Due to its central position and dense forest cover, it is frequently referred to as the green heart of Germany. It shares borders with five other German states. Lower Saxony lies to the northwest, Saxony-Anhalt to the north and northeast, Saxony to the east and southeast, Bavaria to the south, and Hesse to the west. This central location has historically made it an important transit region within Central Europe.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Thuringia is characterized by a mix of low mountain ranges, river valleys, and fertile basins. The most prominent physical feature is the Thuringian Forest, a heavily wooded mountain range stretching across the southern and southwestern parts of the state. The highest peak in this range is the Großer Beerberg, which reaches an elevation of about 983 meters. To the north of the forest lies the Thuringian Basin, a wide and fertile lowland area used extensively for agriculture. The state is drained by several major rivers. The Saale flows through the eastern part of the state, while the Werra runs along the western border. Other notable rivers include the Unstrut and the White Elster. Thuringia is also home to Hainich National Park, which protects one of the largest continuous broadleaf forests in Central Europe and is recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage site.\n\n## Climate\nThuringia experiences a temperate seasonal climate that represents a transition zone between the maritime climate of Western Europe and the continental climate of Eastern Europe. The weather is heavily influenced by elevation. The Thuringian Basin generally has a drier and warmer climate with lower annual precipitation. In contrast, the Thuringian Forest and other upland areas receive significantly more rainfall and experience cooler temperatures year-round. Winters in the mountainous regions are cold enough to support winter sports, with frequent snowfall. Summers across the state are generally warm, with average July temperatures in the lower elevations reaching roughly 18 to 20 degrees Celsius.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Thuringia is diverse, relying on manufacturing, technology, agriculture, and tourism. The state is known for its specialized industries, particularly in optics, precision engineering, and microelectronics. The city of Jena is a major hub for the optical industry, historically associated with the Carl Zeiss corporation. Automotive manufacturing and metalworking are also significant economic drivers. The administrative center and largest city is Erfurt, which serves as a center for logistics, administration, and horticulture. Other major cities include Gera, known for its historical textile industry, and Weimar. Agriculture remains important in the Thuringian Basin, where farmers cultivate wheat, barley, sugar beets, and rapeseed.\n\n## History & culture\nThuringia has a complex political history, having been divided into numerous small sovereign states and duchies for centuries. This fragmentation left a legacy of numerous castles and palaces. The state is deeply connected to German cultural and intellectual history. Wartburg Castle, located near Eisenach, is where Martin Luther translated the New Testament into German in 1521. The city of Weimar was the center of the Weimar Classicism movement in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries, home to literary figures such as Johann Wolfgang von Goethe and Friedrich Schiller. Following World War I, the German national assembly met in Weimar to draft the constitution for the Weimar Republic. The Bauhaus architectural movement was also founded in Weimar in 1919. After World War II, Thuringia became part of East Germany until the reunification of Germany in 1990.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Land)\n* Administrative center: Erfurt\n* Approximate area: 16,171 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.1 million\n* Largest city: Erfurt\n* Signature features: The Thuringian Forest, Wartburg Castle, and the cultural heritage of Weimar",
    "summary": "Thuringia is a landlocked state in central Germany known for its heavily forested mountains and historical significance. Its economy is driven by manufacturing, optics, and agriculture, with major urban centers including the capital Erfurt, Jena, and Weimar. The state is culturally renowned for its associations with Martin Luther, the Weimar Classicism movement, and the founding of the Bauhaus.",
