    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nGauteng is a landlocked province located in the northeastern part of South Africa. It is the smallest of the nine provinces by land area but holds the largest population. The province shares borders with four other South African provinces. Limpopo lies to the north, Mpumalanga to the east, the Free State to the south, and the North West province to the west. The southern boundary is largely defined by the Vaal River, which separates Gauteng from the Free State.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province is situated on the Highveld, a high-altitude plateau that dominates much of the South African interior. Elevations generally range between 1,400 and 1,800 meters above sea level. The most prominent geological feature is the Witwatersrand, a rocky ridge that runs east to west through the center of the province. This ridge is notable for containing the largest known gold reserves in the world. To the northwest, the Magaliesberg mountain range forms a natural boundary, featuring rugged quartzite peaks and deep ravines. The Vaal River is the primary watercourse, supplying water to the densely populated urban areas through a system of dams, including the Vaal Dam located just outside the provincial borders. The Cradle of Humankind, a World Heritage site containing a complex of limestone caves, is located in the western part of the province.\n\n## Climate\nGauteng experiences a subtropical highland climate. Because of the high elevation, temperatures are generally milder than other regions at similar latitudes. The province has distinct wet and dry seasons. Summers occur from October to April and are characterized by warm days, frequent afternoon thunderstorms, and the majority of the annual rainfall. Winters last from May to August and are typically dry and sunny. Winter days are mild, but nighttime temperatures can drop below freezing, resulting in occasional frost. Snow is extremely rare in the province.\n\n## Economy & cities\nGauteng is the economic center of South Africa, contributing a significant portion of the national gross domestic product. The economy was historically built on gold mining along the Witwatersrand, but it has since diversified into finance, manufacturing, technology, and services. Johannesburg is the administrative center of the province and the largest city in South Africa, serving as a major financial hub for the African continent. Pretoria, located in the northern part of the province within the City of Tshwane Metropolitan Municipality, serves as the national administrative capital of South Africa. Other major urban centers include Ekurhuleni, which hosts OR Tambo International Airport, and the industrial areas of the West Rand and Sedibeng.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a long history of human habitation. The Sterkfontein Caves in the Cradle of Humankind have yielded some of the oldest hominid fossils ever discovered. In the late nineteenth century, the discovery of gold in 1886 triggered a large influx of prospectors and laborers, leading to the rapid establishment of Johannesburg. During the twentieth century, the province was a central site in the struggle against apartheid. The township of Soweto, located southwest of Johannesburg, was the site of the 1976 Soweto uprising, a pivotal event in South African history. Today, Gauteng is highly urbanized and culturally diverse. The population speaks a wide variety of languages, with Zulu, Sesotho, English, and Afrikaans being among the most widely used. The name of the province itself translates to \"place of gold\" in the Sotho-Tswana languages.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Johannesburg\n* Approximate area: 18,178 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 16,000,000\n* Largest city: Johannesburg\n* Signature features: The Witwatersrand gold reef, the Cradle of Humankind paleoanthropological site, and the economic hub of Johannesburg.",
    "summary": "Gauteng is the smallest but most populous province in South Africa, serving as the economic and financial hub of the country. Centered around the cities of Johannesburg and Pretoria, the region's development was historically driven by the discovery of gold along the Witwatersrand. The province is located on the high-altitude Highveld plateau and features significant cultural and historical sites, including the Cradle of Humankind.",
