    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nKwaZulu-Natal is a province located on the eastern coast of South Africa. It shares international borders with three countries. Mozambique lies to the far northeast, Eswatini is situated to the north, and Lesotho borders the province to the west. Domestically, KwaZulu-Natal is bordered by the South African provinces of Mpumalanga to the north, the Free State to the west, and the Eastern Cape to the southwest. The entire eastern boundary of the province is formed by a long coastline along the Indian Ocean.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of KwaZulu-Natal is highly diverse, rising from the coastal plains in the east to the high escarpment in the west. The western border with Lesotho is dominated by the Drakensberg, which is the highest mountain range in South Africa. This range includes the uKhahlamba-Drakensberg Park, a UNESCO World Heritage site, and features Tugela Falls, one of the tallest waterfalls in the world. The central region consists of the rolling hills of the KwaZulu-Natal Midlands. The northern area features the Lebombo Mountains and the Maputaland coastal plain. Major rivers include the Tugela River, which is the largest river in the province, as well as the Pongola and Umgeni rivers. The coastline includes the iSimangaliso Wetland Park, another World Heritage site known for its extensive estuary systems and diverse wildlife.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of KwaZulu-Natal varies significantly depending on elevation and distance from the ocean. The coastal region experiences a humid subtropical climate with hot, humid summers and mild, dry winters. The warm Agulhas Current in the Indian Ocean heavily influences this coastal climate. Inland, the Midlands region has a more temperate climate with cooler temperatures and occasional winter frost. The mountainous Drakensberg region in the west experiences an alpine climate, characterized by cold winters and regular snowfall at higher elevations. Most of the province receives the majority of its rainfall during the summer months, often accompanied by heavy thunderstorms.\n\n## Economy & cities\nKwaZulu-Natal has the second largest economy in South Africa. The coastal city of Durban is the largest city in the province and serves as a major economic hub. The Port of Durban is the busiest container port in sub-Saharan Africa. Richards Bay, located further north on the coast, is another crucial port city specializing in bulk exports like coal and features a large aluminum smelting industry. Pietermaritzburg is the administrative center and a center for timber, aluminum, and agricultural processing. The province has a strong agricultural sector. The coastal belt is heavily utilized for sugar cane cultivation, while the inland areas support dairy farming, forestry, and maize production. Newcastle, in the northwest, is an industrial center known for coal mining and steel production.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region has a complex history shaped by various groups. In the early nineteenth century, King Shaka consolidated numerous Nguni chiefdoms to form the powerful Zulu Kingdom. During the 1830s, Boer Voortrekkers arrived and briefly established the Natalia Republic before the British annexed the territory as the Colony of Natal in 1843. The late nineteenth century saw the Anglo-Zulu War, which included significant battles at Isandlwana and Rorke's Drift. During the British colonial period, thousands of indentured laborers were brought from India to work on sugar plantations. Today, KwaZulu-Natal is the traditional home of the Zulu people, who make up the majority of the population. The province also has the largest population of Indian descent outside of India, contributing significantly to the cultural and culinary landscape of the region.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Pietermaritzburg\n* Approximate area: 94,361 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 11.5 million\n* Largest city: Durban\n* Signature features: The Drakensberg mountain range, the Port of Durban, and the historical legacy of the Zulu Kingdom.",
    "summary": "KwaZulu-Natal is a diverse coastal province in eastern South Africa known for its major ports, the towering Drakensberg mountains, and a strong agricultural economy. It serves as the traditional homeland of the Zulu people and contains a large population of Indian descent. The province is economically anchored by Durban, which hosts the busiest container port in sub-Saharan Africa, while Pietermaritzburg serves as the administrative center.",
