    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nMpumalanga is a landlocked province located in the eastern part of South Africa. It shares international borders with two countries, meeting Mozambique to the east and Eswatini to the southeast. Domestically, it is bordered by the South African provinces of Limpopo to the north, Gauteng to the west, the Free State to the southwest, and KwaZulu-Natal to the south. The province was created in 1994 from the eastern portion of the former Transvaal province.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Mpumalanga is defined by a sharp division between two distinct topographical regions. The western half consists of the Highveld, an elevated plateau characterized by rolling grasslands. The eastern half is the Lowveld, a lower-altitude region of savanna and woodland. These two areas are separated by the northern section of the Drakensberg escarpment.\n\nThis escarpment creates significant geological formations. The Blyde River Canyon, also known as the Motlatse Canyon, is one of the largest green canyons in the world and a major geographical landmark. The Barberton Makhonjwa Mountains in the southeast contain some of the oldest exposed rocks on Earth. Several major rivers flow through the province, including the Crocodile River, the Olifants River, and the Komati River. The southern half of Kruger National Park, a massive wildlife reserve, occupies a large portion of the eastern Lowveld.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate varies significantly depending on the elevation. The Highveld experiences a temperate climate with warm summers and cool winters. Winter temperatures on the plateau frequently drop below freezing at night, resulting in frost. The Lowveld has a subtropical climate, characterized by hot, humid summers and mild, dry winters. Mpumalanga receives the majority of its precipitation during the summer months, typically between October and April, often in the form of afternoon thunderstorms.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Mpumalanga relies heavily on mining, agriculture, and tourism. The province produces roughly eighty percent of South Africa's coal. This coal mining industry is centered around the city of eMalahleni, formerly known as Witbank. The abundance of coal supports numerous power stations, making the province the primary generator of electricity for the country. Agriculture is also highly productive. The Highveld produces maize and wheat, while the Lowveld specializes in citrus fruits, sugar cane, and macadamia nuts. Extensive commercial forestry plantations operate in the escarpment region.\n\nMbombela, formerly Nelspruit, serves as the administrative center and the largest city, acting as a hub for the citrus industry and regional commerce. Other significant urban centers include Middelburg, an industrial and agricultural center, and Secunda, which hosts a large synthetic fuel plant. Tourism is a major economic driver, supported by Kruger National Park and the scenic Panorama Route along the escarpment.\n\n## History & culture\nThe name Mpumalanga means \"the place where the sun rises\" in the Swazi, Xhosa, Ndebele, and Zulu languages. The region has a long history of human habitation, evidenced by ancient San rock art and Iron Age settlements. In the late nineteenth century, the area experienced a gold rush, leading to the establishment of mining towns like Pilgrim's Rest and Barberton. Today, the province is culturally diverse. It is home to a large population of Swazi people, particularly near the Eswatini border. The Ndebele people, known for their distinctively painted houses and intricate beadwork, also form a significant cultural group within the province.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Mbombela\n* Approximate area: 76,495 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4.7 million\n* Largest city: Mbombela\n* Signature features: Blyde River Canyon, southern Kruger National Park, extensive coal mining industry",
