    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nLimpopo is the northernmost province of South Africa. It shares international borders with three countries. Zimbabwe lies to the north, Mozambique to the east, and Botswana to the west. Within South Africa, Limpopo is bordered by the North West, Gauteng, and Mpumalanga provinces to the south. The province takes its name from the Limpopo River, which forms its northern and western boundaries.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of Limpopo is defined by diverse landscapes, including mountains, bushveld, and subtropical forests. The Limpopo River is the most prominent watercourse, flowing along the international borders before turning toward the Indian Ocean. The Waterberg Massif, a large geological formation and biosphere reserve, dominates the western part of the province. In the north, the Soutpansberg mountain range stretches from east to west. The eastern escarpment of the Drakensberg mountains extends into the province, separating the central plateau from the low-lying Lowveld region. The Lowveld encompasses the northern half of the Kruger National Park, a major wildlife reserve. The central area consists largely of the Bushveld, a sub-tropical woodland ecoregion.\n\n## Climate\nLimpopo experiences a predominantly subtropical climate. The region has hot summers and mild, mostly frost-free winters. It is a summer rainfall area, with the majority of precipitation occurring between October and March. The Lowveld region in the east tends to be hotter and more humid than the rest of the province. In contrast, the mountainous areas, such as the Soutpansberg and Waterberg, experience cooler temperatures and higher rainfall. The western and far northern parts of the province are semi-arid and are prone to occasional droughts.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Limpopo relies heavily on mining, agriculture, and tourism. The province contains a significant portion of the Bushveld Igneous Complex, which holds vast reserves of platinum group metals. Mining operations also extract diamonds, coal, copper, and iron ore. Agriculture is another major sector, benefiting from the subtropical climate. Farmers produce citrus, mangoes, avocados, papayas, and macadamia nuts. Game farming and forestry are also prominent.\n\nPolokwane serves as the administrative center and the largest city in the province. Other important urban centers include Tzaneen, an agricultural hub, and Phalaborwa, a mining town located near the Kruger National Park. Musina is a key border town facilitating trade with Zimbabwe, while Thohoyandou serves as a commercial center in the northeast. Tourism is driven by wildlife reserves, particularly the Kruger National Park, Marakele National Park, and numerous private game lodges.\n\n## History & culture\nLimpopo has a deep archaeological and historical record. The Mapungubwe World Heritage Site preserves the remains of an ancient African kingdom that thrived between 1000 and 1300 CE. This society engaged in extensive trade with regions as far away as India and China, exchanging gold and ivory for glass beads and ceramics. The Makapansgat Valley is another crucial site, containing hominid fossils that provide insight into early human evolution.\n\nThe province is culturally diverse. The population primarily consists of Northern Sotho, Tsonga, and Venda speakers. Northern Sotho is the most widely spoken language in the province. Traditional leadership structures continue to play a role in local governance, particularly in rural areas.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Polokwane\n* Approximate area: 125,754 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 6.3 million\n* Largest city: Polokwane\n* Signature features: Limpopo River, northern Kruger National Park, Mapungubwe World Heritage Site",
    "summary": "Limpopo is the northernmost province of South Africa, bordered by Botswana, Zimbabwe, and Mozambique. Its economy is largely driven by mining in the Bushveld Igneous Complex, subtropical agriculture, and ecotourism centered around the Kruger National Park. The province is known for its rich archaeological history, including the ancient kingdom of Mapungubwe, and its diverse cultural heritage.",
