    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nThe Eastern Cape is a province located on the southeastern coast of South Africa. It shares borders with several other provinces, including the Western Cape to the west, the Northern Cape to the northwest, the Free State to the north, and KwaZulu-Natal to the northeast. Additionally, it shares an international border with the independent nation of Lesotho to the northeast. The southern and southeastern edges of the province feature a long coastline along the Indian Ocean.\n\n## Physical features\nThe geography of the Eastern Cape is diverse, ranging from arid plains to rugged mountain ranges and coastal forests. The Great Escarpment runs through the province, featuring the Sneeuberge and the Winterberg ranges, while the southern reaches of the Drakensberg mountains lie along the border with Lesotho. The province is intersected by several significant rivers, including the Great Fish River, the Kei River, and the Mzimvubu River. The coastline is notable for its distinct sections, such as the Sunshine Coast in the west and the rugged, undeveloped Wild Coast in the east. Protected areas include Addo Elephant National Park and the Tsitsikamma section of the Garden Route National Park, which preserve native flora and fauna.\n\n## Climate\nThe climate of the Eastern Cape varies significantly depending on the region and elevation. The western interior, part of the Great Karoo, experiences a semi-arid climate with low rainfall and extreme temperature fluctuations between summer and winter. The coastal areas enjoy a more temperate climate in the west, transitioning to a humid subtropical climate further east toward KwaZulu-Natal. The eastern coastal regions receive higher annual rainfall, supporting dense vegetation and forests. In the high-altitude mountainous areas, winters are cold, and snowfall is common.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of the Eastern Cape relies heavily on the automotive manufacturing industry. The province is a major hub for vehicle assembly and component production, with large facilities located in Gqeberha, formerly known as Port Elizabeth, and East London. Agriculture is another major sector. The province produces significant quantities of wool, mohair, dairy, and citrus fruits. The coastal ports of Port Elizabeth, Ngqura, and East London facilitate international trade and shipping. Tourism is also an important economic driver, centered around wildlife reserves and coastal resorts. The administrative center is Bhisho, while Gqeberha is the largest city. Other notable urban centers include East London, Makhanda, and Mthatha.\n\n## History & culture\nThe Eastern Cape is the traditional heartland of the Xhosa people, who make up the majority of the provincial population. The region was the site of the Xhosa Wars, a series of conflicts between the Xhosa, British colonial forces, and Boer settlers during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. During the apartheid era, the region contained the nominally independent homelands, or Bantustans, of Transkei and Ciskei. These territories were reintegrated into South Africa in 1994 to form the current Eastern Cape province. The province is historically significant as the birthplace of numerous prominent anti-apartheid leaders, including Nelson Mandela, Oliver Tambo, Steve Biko, and Thabo Mbeki.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Bhisho\n* Approximate area: 168,966 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.2 million\n* Largest city: Gqeberha\n* Signature features: The rugged Wild Coast, Addo Elephant National Park, and the birthplace of Nelson Mandela",
