    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nNorth West is a landlocked province located in the northern part of South Africa. It shares an international border with the Republic of Botswana to the north and northwest. Domestically, it is bordered by the South African provinces of Limpopo to the northeast, Gauteng to the east, the Free State to the southeast, and the Northern Cape to the south and southwest. Its proximity to Gauteng, the economic hub of the country, heavily influences its transport and trade networks.\n\n## Physical features\nThe landscape of North West consists primarily of flat or gently undulating plains. The eastern part of the province features the Magaliesberg mountain range, which extends from Pretoria in neighboring Gauteng to Rustenburg. The far western region transitions into the semi-arid scrubland of the Kalahari Desert. Major watercourses include the Vaal River, which forms the southern boundary with the Free State. In the north, the Marico River and the Crocodile River are significant waterways that eventually join to form the Limpopo River. A prominent geological feature is the Pilanesberg, an alkaline ring complex formed by an extinct volcano, which now houses a major national park.\n\n## Climate\nThe province experiences a predominantly semi-arid climate, with variations depending on elevation and proximity to the Kalahari. The eastern areas receive more rainfall and have a temperate to subtropical climate, while the western areas are significantly drier. Precipitation occurs almost exclusively during the summer months, typically between October and April, often in the form of late afternoon thunderstorms. Summers are generally hot, with temperatures frequently exceeding thirty degrees Celsius. Winters are dry and cool, with sunny days and cold nights. Frost is common during the winter months, particularly in the southern and western regions.\n\n## Economy & cities\nMining is the dominant economic sector in North West. The province sits on the Bushveld Igneous Complex, one of the richest mineral deposits in the world. It produces a significant portion of the world's platinum, along with gold, uranium, diamonds, and chromite. Rustenburg and Brits are the primary centers for the platinum mining industry. Agriculture is also vital, with the province being a major producer of white maize and sunflowers. Cattle ranching and game farming are prevalent in the drier western regions. Tourism is a growing industry, anchored by the Sun City casino and resort complex, Pilanesberg National Park, and Madikwe Game Reserve. Mahikeng serves as the administrative center, while Rustenburg is the largest city by population. Other notable urban centers include Potchefstroom, known for its large university, and Klerksdorp, a historic gold mining town.\n\n## History & culture\nNorth West was established as a province in 1994 following the end of apartheid in South Africa. It was created by merging parts of the former Transvaal and Cape provinces with the majority of Bophuthatswana, a former designated homeland for the Tswana people. Today, the Tswana make up the vast majority of the provincial population, and Setswana is the most widely spoken language. The region has a notable colonial history. Mahikeng, historically known as Mafeking, was the site of the Siege of Mafeking during the Second Boer War. The province also contains a portion of the Cradle of Humankind World Heritage Site at the Taung skull fossil site, where the first Australopithecus africanus specimen was discovered in 1924.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Mahikeng\n* Approximate area: 104,882 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 4.1 million\n* Largest city: Rustenburg\n* Signature features: Extensive platinum mining operations, Sun City resort, Pilanesberg National Park, and a predominantly Tswana-speaking population",
    "summary": "North West is a landlocked province in South Africa known for its vast platinum mines and semi-arid plains. It borders Botswana to the north and features major tourist destinations like the Sun City resort and Pilanesberg National Park. The province was formed in 1994 and is predominantly home to the Tswana people, with Mahikeng serving as its administrative center.",
