    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nThe Free State is a landlocked province located in the geographic center of South Africa. It shares borders with six other South African provinces. To the north lie North West, Gauteng, and Mpumalanga. KwaZulu-Natal is located to the east, the Eastern Cape to the south, and the Northern Cape to the west. Additionally, the Free State wraps around the western and northern edges of Lesotho, which is an independent, landlocked country.\n\n## Physical features\nThe province consists primarily of broad, flat plains known as the Highveld, which sit at an elevation of roughly 1,200 to 1,500 meters above sea level. The eastern landscape becomes increasingly rugged as it approaches the Maluti and Drakensberg mountain ranges along the Lesotho border. Golden Gate Highlands National Park is situated in this eastern region and is recognized for its deeply eroded sandstone cliffs. Two major rivers define the boundaries of the province. The Vaal River forms the northern and northwestern borders, separating the Free State from North West, Gauteng, and Mpumalanga. The Orange River forms the southern boundary with the Eastern Cape and Northern Cape. The Wilge River and the Caledon River are also prominent waterways within the province.\n\n## Climate\nThe Free State experiences a continental climate that ranges from semi-arid in the west to temperate in the east. Summers are generally warm to hot, while winters are cold and dry. Because of the high elevation, winter temperatures frequently drop below freezing at night, bringing widespread frost to the region. Snowfall is rare on the plains but occurs occasionally in the eastern mountains. Most of the province receives its precipitation during the summer months, typically in the form of brief, intense afternoon thunderstorms. Annual rainfall averages roughly 600 millimeters in the east and decreases to about 300 millimeters in the drier western areas.\n\n## Economy & cities\nAgriculture and mining are the primary drivers of the Free State economy. The province is often referred to as the breadbasket of South Africa because it produces a large portion of the country's maize, wheat, and sunflowers. Livestock farming, including cattle and sheep, is also a principal agricultural activity. The mining sector is concentrated in the northern and western regions. The Free State Goldfields, centered around the city of Welkom, have historically been a major source of gold. Diamond and coal mining also contribute to the regional economy. The city of Sasolburg in the north is a central hub for the petrochemical industry. Bloemfontein is the administrative capital of the province and serves as the judicial capital of South Africa. Other notable urban centers include Kroonstad, Bethlehem, and Phuthaditjhaba.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by San hunter-gatherers and Khoikhoi pastoralists, followed by Sotho-Tswana agriculturalists. During the early nineteenth century, the area experienced severe upheaval during a period of conflict and migration known as the Mfecane. In the 1830s, Boer settlers known as Voortrekkers arrived from the Cape Colony. They established the Orange Free State as an independent republic in 1854. The republic was annexed by the British Empire in 1902 following the Second Anglo-Boer War. It became a province of the Union of South Africa in 1910 and was renamed Free State in 1995. Today, Sesotho is the most widely spoken language in the province, followed by Afrikaans and isiXhosa.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Bloemfontein\n* Approximate area: 129,825 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.9 million\n* Largest city: Bloemfontein\n* Signature features: Golden Gate Highlands National Park, major maize and gold production",
    "summary": "The Free State is a landlocked province in central South Africa known for its broad agricultural plains and significant gold mining industry. Bounded by the Vaal and Orange rivers, it surrounds the western edge of Lesotho and features a continental climate with summer thunderstorms and cold, frosty winters. Its administrative center, Bloemfontein, also serves as the judicial capital of South Africa.",
