    "mainNotes": "## Location within Germany\nSchleswig-Holstein is the northernmost state of Germany. It is situated on the southern half of the Jutland Peninsula. The state is bordered by Denmark to the north. To the south, it shares borders with the German states of Lower Saxony, Hamburg, and Mecklenburg-Vorpommern. The western boundary is formed by the North Sea, while the eastern boundary is formed by the Baltic Sea.\n\n## Physical features\nThe landscape of Schleswig-Holstein is generally flat, characterized by coastal lowlands, marshes, and gentle moraines left by Ice Age glaciers. The highest elevation is the Bungsberg, reaching roughly 168 meters above sea level. The western coast along the North Sea features the Schleswig-Holstein Wadden Sea National Park, an extensive tidal flat ecosystem. Offshore lie the North Frisian Islands, including Sylt, Föhr, and Amrum, as well as the more distant island of Heligoland. The eastern Baltic coast is highly indented with fjords and bays, such as the Kiel Fjord and the Flensburg Fjord, and includes the island of Fehmarn. Major rivers include the Eider, the Trave, and the Elbe, which forms a portion of the southwestern border. The Kiel Canal is a major artificial waterway that cuts across the state, linking the North Sea to the Baltic Sea.\n\n## Climate\nThe state experiences a maritime oceanic climate, classified as Köppen Cfb. The proximity to two major bodies of water heavily influences weather patterns, resulting in moderate temperatures year-round. Summers are generally mild and sometimes cool, while winters are relatively temperate compared to inland regions of Germany. Wind is a constant feature, particularly along the western coast. Precipitation is distributed fairly evenly throughout the year, with high humidity and frequent cloud cover being typical for the region.\n\n## Economy & cities\nThe economy of Schleswig-Holstein is heavily tied to its maritime geography. Shipbuilding, port logistics, and naval operations are concentrated in coastal cities. The state is also a major producer of renewable energy, particularly onshore and offshore wind power. Agriculture remains significant, with dairy farming prevalent in the marshlands and crop cultivation, such as cabbage in the Dithmarschen district, common in the interior. Tourism is a major economic driver, drawing visitors to the North Sea islands and Baltic coastal resorts. Kiel is the administrative center and largest city, known for its deep-water harbor and maritime industries. Lübeck is the second-largest city, recognized for its medieval Hanseatic architecture and port facilities. Other notable urban centers include Flensburg and Neumünster.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was historically divided into the Duchy of Schleswig in the north and the Duchy of Holstein in the south. For centuries, these territories were closely associated with the Danish crown. Following the Second Schleswig War in 1864, the region was annexed by Prussia. After World War I, the Schleswig Plebiscites of 1920 determined the modern border, with Northern Schleswig voting to join Denmark and Southern Schleswig voting to remain in Germany. Today, the state is home to recognized Danish and North Frisian minority populations, who maintain their own cultural institutions and languages. Low German, or Plattdeutsch, is also widely spoken and promoted alongside standard German.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: Germany\n* Subdivision type: State (Bundesland)\n* Administrative center: Kiel\n* Approximate area: 15,800 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 2.9 million\n* Largest city: Kiel\n* Signature features: The Kiel Canal, the Wadden Sea tidal flats, and the historic Hanseatic city of Lübeck.",
