    "mainNotes": "## Location within South Africa\nThe Western Cape is a province located in the southwestern extremity of South Africa. It is bordered by the Northern Cape province to the north and the Eastern Cape province to the east. The province features extensive coastlines along two major oceans. The Atlantic Ocean lies to the west, and the Indian Ocean lies to the south. These two oceans officially meet at Cape Agulhas, which is the southernmost point of the African continent.\n\n## Physical features\nThe topography of the Western Cape is highly varied, dominated by the Cape Fold Belt. This mountain range system includes the Cederberg, Langeberg, Swartberg, and Outeniqua mountains. The most famous landform is Table Mountain, a flat-topped mountain overlooking the city of Cape Town and the Cape Peninsula. The Cape of Good Hope is a prominent rocky headland on the Atlantic coast. Inland from the coastal mountains lies the Karoo, a vast semi-desert region divided into the Great Karoo and the Little Karoo. Major rivers draining the province include the Breede River, the Berg River, the Olifants River, and the Gourits River. Protected areas include Table Mountain National Park, West Coast National Park, and sections of the Garden Route National Park.\n\n## Climate\nThe Western Cape is unique in South Africa for having a predominantly Mediterranean climate, particularly in the southwestern coastal regions. This climate is characterized by cool, wet winters and warm, dry summers. The interior regions, such as the Karoo, experience a semi-arid climate with more extreme temperature variations between day and night. The southern coastal area, known as the Garden Route, has a temperate maritime climate and receives rainfall throughout the year.\n\n## Economy & cities\nCape Town is the administrative center of the Western Cape and serves as the legislative capital of South Africa. Other significant urban centers include Stellenbosch, Paarl, George, and Worcester. The provincial economy is highly diversified. It relies heavily on agriculture, tourism, manufacturing, and financial services. The agricultural sector is famous for the Cape Winelands, which produce a large portion of the country's wine. Farmers in the province also cultivate deciduous fruits, citrus, and wheat, while sheep farming is common in the drier inland areas. The fishing industry is a major economic contributor along the Atlantic west coast.\n\n## History & culture\nThe region was originally inhabited by indigenous Khoekhoe and San hunter-gatherers and pastoralists. In 1652, the Dutch East India Company established a maritime supply station at the Cape of Good Hope, leading to European settlement. The British Empire took control of the region in the early nineteenth century, eventually forming the Cape Colony. In 1994, following the end of apartheid, the historic Cape Province was divided into three new provinces, creating the modern Western Cape, Eastern Cape, and Northern Cape. The province has a diverse cultural landscape. Afrikaans, isiXhosa, and English are the primary languages spoken by residents. The region is also home to the Cape Malay community, which has significantly influenced the local cuisine and architecture.\n\n## Quick facts\n* Country: South Africa\n* Subdivision type: Province\n* Administrative center: Cape Town\n* Approximate area: 129,462 square kilometers\n* Approximate population: 7.4 million\n* Largest city: Cape Town\n* Signature features: Table Mountain, Cape of Good Hope, Cape Winelands, Cape Agulhas",
